<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Markets West - Emerging Growth</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#C0C0C0><CENTER><IMG SRC="mw.gif" ></CENTER><HR>
<p>
<center><font size=6><b>EMERGING GROWTH
STOCKS</b></font><br>
<font size=3><i>Covering the V.S.E. , Junior Gold Stocks, and
Special Situations - Volume V, No. 2</i></font></center>
<hr>
<center><h3>MARKET COMMENTARY<br>
-Voisey Bay Fever Strikes V.S.E.-</h3></center>
The market soared in the second half of April, fuelled by Voisey
Bay and diamond fever, as investors scrambled to jump aboard these
two area plays (Diamond Fields and Mountain Province's respective
mineral discoveries).  Trading expanded through month end,
finishing on a high note, with a 24 point (3%) rally on the highest
volume recorded so far this year, and taking the composite index
back up through 800, up 17% from the lows recorded in March.<p>
Throughout May and June, the market consolidated these gains, and
digested the many news reports and analysis in the media on these
two emerging area plays.  Apart from all the background noise, we
view April's strength as further confirmation that, at least on a
technical basis, the V.S.E. market index is the healthiest it's
looked in well over a year, and appears to be setting the stage for
the next bull run.  We view the current sideways activity as a
normal consolidation, and see at least four bullish signals in the
charts below.<ol>
<li>Recent index high is higher that    previous one (Dow
Theory).<p>
<li>Index trading well above it's short-term (10 week) Moving
Average.<p>
<li>Index recently challenging its long term (40 week) Moving
Average.<p>
<li>R.S.I. (Rel. Strength Index) recently broke into a positive 
area from negative.</ol><p>
The same applies to the stocks in Calgary.  While this exchange
does not have the exposure to Voisey Bay that Vancouver does, it
seems that the entire oil and gas sector took a huge hit last year,
and also looks ready for a big move.<p>
A low priced example from this sector with positive cash flow and
excellent growth potential is enclosed in this issue (Wayburn Oil
and Natural Gas, WON.C, $0.34C).<p>

<center><h3>AREA PLAY SPECULATING<br>
-Voisey Bay-</h3></center>
No doubt, Diamond Fields has hit upon the most important North
American metal discovery in decades, and Discovery Hill (the
precise location of the huge and extremely rich nickel-copper-
cobalt deposit), Voisey Bay is destined to become one of the
world's great mining camps.  The discovery is still not well known
outside Canada and I believe the play has a lot of steam left to
it, which is why you probably want to be involved in some way.  The
question remains for potential investors, just how to approach
Voisey Bay at this stage, while reducing the potential risks
associated with investing (really speculating) in all area
plays.<p>

With regard for overall timing, this seems a good time to take a
limited position (limited due to the very high risk).  While the
initial staking rush in Labrador and buying spree on Howe Street
has subsided for now, my guess is the whole area will get very hot
again later this summer, as news on exploration results starts
coming out in earnest.  Many of the stocks that ran up in March and
April after announcing property acquisitions are now pulling back,
some by as much as 50% and are poised to move again.  Just
remember, those marginal players that don't hit pay dirt this
summer could fall right back to their 52 week lows this winter.<p>

As far as which stocks to buy, it is the nature of a wildcat play,
especially at its' early stages that it is impossible to tell who
will get lucky, so I really hesitate to recommend anything.  I'll
just mention a few I am watching - <b>NDT Ventures</b> (NDE.V -
$4.00) is the largest claim holder in the area and therefore a good
barometer of the play, <b>Freeport Resources</b> (FRI.V $1.40 to
$2.00) apparently has the serious interest of numerous seniors in
it's holdings, maybe a buy at $1.40, and my low priced issue is
<b>Fairhaven Resources</b> (FRH.V $0.30 to $0.40), previously a
dormant Pezim shell company, recently refinanced and in on a
property with another large Pezim company,<b>Prime Equity</b>
(PQE.V $2.36).  The Fairhaven issue has warrants to buy the stock
at $0.46, currently trading at around $0.07, good for almost a
year.  Results from an airborne survey should be released in the
near future.<p>
<hr><center><h1><i>WAYBURN OIL AND NATURAL GAS</i></h1></center>
<center><table border>
<tr><td>Recent Price</td><td>: $ 0.34</td></tr>
<tr><td>52 Week High</td><td>: $ 0.58 (07/94)</td></tr>
<tr><td>52 Week Low</td><td>: $ 0.20 (02/95)</td></tr>
<tr><td>A.S.E. Symbol</td><td>: WON</td></tr>
<tr><td>Shares Issued</td><td>: 4.3 million</td></tr>
<tr><td>Approx Float</td><td>: 1.5 million</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cash Flow</td><td>: $28,000. per month</td></tr>
<tr><td>Corp Headquarters</td><td>: Vancouver,
B.C.</td></tr></table></center><p>
<h3>-Summary-</h3>
Wayburn is an exceptional, low-risk emerging producer I have been
following since it started trading in January, 1994.  The company
is debt free, has positive cash flow, and inspite of excellent
results in the oil patch, I have remained neutral on the stock for
technical and market reasons, until this time.  These conditions
have reversed, and now I am giving Wayburn my strongest buy
recommendation for it's outstanding value and growth prospects over
the next six to twelve months.<p>

<h3>-Development History-</h3>
Wayburn concentrates on low risk, high yield in-fill drill projects
that provide a high degree of success.  The company used it's
financing to fund a seven well drilling program which <b>garnered
five producers, all located in Southern Saskatchewan</b>.  Wayburn
has interests ranging from 25% to 10%, and is netting around 100
Bbl/d which translates into an average cash flow of $28,000 per
month.<p>
<center><table border>
<caption align=bottom><font size=1>(Taking $22.50 per Barrel, at
the wellhead, this translates<br>into $2137.50 per day gross cash
flow, netting Wayburn an average of $28,000 per
month)</font></caption>
<tr><th colspan=4  align=center>-April Production-</th></tr>
<tr><th rowspan=2 align=left>Well<br>(type: V = vertical H =
horizontal)</th><th rowspan=2> WON%</th><th colspan=2>Bl/d-
April/95</th></tr>
<tr><th>Net</th><th>Gross</th></tr>
<tr><td>Queensdale.H</td><td align=center>20%</td><td
align=center>28</td><td align=center>140</td></tr>
<tr><td>Queensdale.H</td><td align=center>12%</td><td
align=center>19</td><td align=center>178</td></tr>
<tr><Td>Weyburn.H</td><td align=center>20%</td><td
align=center>27</td><td align=center>135</td></tr>
<tr><td>Weyburn.H</td><td align=center>10%</td><td
align=center>15</td><td align=center>150</td></tr>
<tr><td>Bromhead.V</td><td align=center>20%</td><td
align=center>6</td><td align=center>30</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Totals</b></td><td>&nbsp;</td><td
align=center>95</td><td
align=center>633</td></tr></table></center><p>
Now, Wayburn is actively evaluating larger acquisition prospect
that would bring in anywhere from $1 to $5 million (CND), and
provide a maximum 3 to 3.5 year payout from cash flow.  They have
retained the services of accomplished 30 year veteran Landman, Mr.
Larry Blonde to assist in locating and acquiring new projects, and
are considering more than 50 packages that are currently on the
market (Canadian and US).<p>
<h3>Goldston, Saskatchewan<br>
-Fall Drilling Planned-</h3>
On April 26, 1995, Wayburn's management successfully negotiated a
low risk drilling program in Goldston, Saskatchewan, Canada on a
1/3 before pay out and 1/4 after pay out basis.  The operator is a
well-known private company, Postell Energy.  The letter of intent
outlines a project which has the potential of becoming a multiple
well development project.  Drilling is scheduled to begin no later
than fall 1995.<p>

The program consists of 3 wells initially and has the capability of
a maximum of 12 wells, depending on results obtained.<p>

The plan is to begin with a low risk vertical infill well expected
to cost $300,000 (CDN) and which is projected to yield at least 60
- 75 BOPD initial production.<p>

<h3>-FINANCIALS-</h3>
Cash flow from current operations (which should expand sharply
before year end) amounts to about $340,000 per year, or about $0.08
per share.  Therefore, at the current price of $0.34 per share, the
stock trades for  about 4 times cash flow.  At this time, the
company is reserving over 60% of its cash flow for new production
acquisition, and carries no debt.<p>
<h3>-CAPITAL STRUCTURE-</h3>
The company went public with an IPO of 1,500,000 shares at $0.55 in
January, 1994, which raised $825,000 and was used for drilling and
exploration expenses.  Of the 4.3 million shares currently
outstanding, 2.2 million are held by directors and insiders, and
are escrowed until 1998.  There are no shares due to become
eligible for trading from previous financing, and there are
approximately 200,000 options outstanding, priced at $0.35 and
$0.32.<p>

<h3>-MANAGEMENT-</h3>
What impresses me most about Wayburn is Management's ability, and
determination to grow the company and add shareholder value just as
rapidly as possible, but without exposing shareholders to undue
risk, or causing heavy stock dilution.  For example, the president
works long hours but forgoes a regular cash salary, and elects
instead to get paid in stock.  Cash flow is reserved for expansion,
and the company sticks to low-risk drilling projects.  I guess this
should come as no surprise, as management has a large stake in the
company, and has every reason to want to see it, and the share
price grow.<p>

<h3>-TECHNICALS-</h3>
The stock had a rough aftermarket, no doubt in large part dragged
down by the rest of the oil and gas sector.  The stock had been in
a steady decline until it hit bottom at $0.20, first in January,
and then again in late February, forming a double bottom.<p>

In March it broke through the major trend line and moving averages,
and made a recent high of $0.38.  Support is forming at $0.30 and
the stock has now clearly reversed it's previous decline and turned
decidedly bullish.<p>
<h3>-RECOMMENDATION-</h3>
With cash flow where it is today, the stock is cheap at $0.40 or
less by industry standards, and should probably fetch more, $0.50
to $0.60.  I expect however, we will see substantial increases in
cash flow in the coming months and year for Wayburn - 70% to 100%
by year end, and between 3 and 5 times current levels or more in
the next 12 months.  Given a conservative price to cash flow ratio
of 5- I have targets of $0.70 by year end (higher on speculation)
and $2.00 to $4.00 longer term.<p>
<hr>
For subscription or other information,<br>
Please contact:<p>
Mr. Louis Paquette<br>
Tel: +1 (604) 687-5772<br>
Toll Free: +1 (800) 265-3455
