<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>HOT STOCKS FLASH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
George Chelekis' HOT STOCKS REVIEW -- Copyright 1996 
<P>
<I>George Chelekis'</I>
<P>
<H1><CENTER>HOT STOCKS FLASH</CENTER></H1>
<P><CENTER><I><STRONG>October 18, 1996</STRONG></I><BR>
<BR>
ADVERTISING SALES/CIRCULATION: (813) 254-5599<BR>
FAX: (813) 254-4142 * RECORDED HOTLINE:813-251-0030<BR>
<P>
</CENTER>
<P>
Area plays in Indonesia and Voisey's Bay continue to appear like SELL situations.
While the DJIA and TSE 300 Index continue to set new highs, most lightweight
speculators continue to avoid the high-risk western Canadian stocks. The
senior markets continue to follow the &quot;October trend&quot; found in
the previous US presidential election, whereupon these markets rise until
election day (this year it's November 5th) and then quickly retreat during
November. <BR>
<BR>
That &quot;cautious optimism&quot; has not translated into the western Canadian
markets. Technically, the VSE index showed a sell on September 27th. It
appears that the VSE Index will sink below its July 24th low, before we
see any upturn in these markets, probably around January 10, 1997. The speculative
markets depend upon the unsophisticated low net-worth &quot;gambler&quot;
to fuel any appreciation and most gamblers are avoiding them. Last week's
FBI sting caused many to hesitate before plodding into the thinly traded,
highly manipulated OTC Bulletin Board marketplace.<BR>
<BR>
Fighting against such odds, one must become EXTREMELY selective in their
speculations over the next 90 days. More than likely, you will see a substantial
retreat in many of your speculations. Now is the time to phone each of the
CEOs of the companies in which you have invested and find out what their
plans are, throughout the latter part of October and November, with regards
to earnings projections or drilling plans. Should you find anyone hesitating
in their responses.........run for the exits.<BR>
<BR>
One example is High Grade Ventures (VSE:HGV), which has had a spectacular
runup since July, after hiring MarketMedia to provide a &quot;shareholder
enhancement program.&quot; Technically, HGV is overbought. Further, Patrick
Kephart, owner of HGV's PR firm, was previously employed by Atlantic Capital
Corporation, which was recently accused by the SEC for paying bribes to
various stockbrokers in three states in a stock-touting scheme. (Bribing
stockbrokers can be hazardous to a stock promoters' health.) The Atlantic
case involves even more bribe money than the recently announced FBI sting!<BR>
<BR>
Another example is Coral Gold (VSE:CLH), which has seen their share price
collapse from well above C$6/share to nearly C$3/share since their &quot;imminent&quot;
takeover by a major failed to immediately materialize in late July or early
August. Their news release of the &quot;Rothschild agreement&quot; seemed
to coincide with a desperate attempt to prevent their share price from sinking
further. Newsletter recommendations from Dines, Sarnoff and Wheeler to buy
CLH have miserably failed. It could be a long hard winter for CLH, before
they see the light of day.<BR>
<BR>
Yet another example is Gold Canyon (VSE:GCU), whose joint venture partner
(Santa Fe Gold) walked away from the Springpole project. Aside from the
PR spin on their recent news release, with the appointment of a new president,
one should carefully study GCU's news release and realize that GCU is liable
for the recently completed summer drill program and all on-going costs associated
with this project. Recommendations, again from Sarnoff and Wheeler, should
come to no positive result for GCU.<BR>
<BR>
The point I am making is this: Results, not promotion, will fuel a stock's
depreciation or demise. Study your companies with an even more jaundiced
eye over the next 3-4 months. (Please note that each of the above companies
paid HSR various amounts to be reviewed in previous editions of HSR -- see
HSR website for disclosure information.)<BR>
<P>
<P>
<H2><CENTER>BEST BETS....</CENTER></H2>
<P>
I have avoided issuing any sort of &quot;Best Bet&quot; selections over
the past seven months, for various reasons. At a time when the speculative
markets look exceptionally weak, I continue to emphasize looking for the
underlying value in each company. This vague term, underlying value, may
be defined the company's checkbook balance, their management team, their
geologist, their stock promoter(s) or the product or service offered by
the company. Best Bets are not the &quot;flavor of the month&quot; and do
not mean they will necessarily skyrocket for a quick flip. At a time when
I foresee a painful short-term future in the speculative markets, I like
the following speculations. Unless otherwise specified, one should understand
that each of the companies below have previously purchased a $9800 advertisement
in the print version of Hot Stocks Review, unless otherwise noted. Those
who have long followed HSR have come to realize that companies which offer
the most potential, receive the most coverage while others do not, irregardless
that each paid the same amount for the same advertisement. Risk factors
such as market collapse (bid off) or the collapse in gold (or another commodity)
are not taken into account in compiling this list.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #1</B>: Vior Exploration (Montreal:VIO). The area play in the
Sept-Iles region of northeastern Quebec, plus other factors, demonstrate
that VIO may attract wide global interest throughout the fourth quarter
and possibly beyond. VIO has never paid for advertising in HSR.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #2</B>: Fairmile Gold (Alberta:FLA). No surprise here. The
size of the Buffalo Valley project, the amount of FLA's successful shallow
drilling in that area and the possibility of the motherlode on their deep
drilling continue to make me a believer.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #3</B>: Transformation Processing (OTC BB:TPII). If this company
does what they have been saying they are going to do, then TPII might make
the Wall Street Journal before the year is out.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #4</B>: Strathmore Resources (VSE:SMR). Uranium is going to
make news during 1997. SMR is strongly positioning itself to attract the
interest of a major, both in potential acquisitions of uranium reserves
and in building up their board &amp; management team.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #5</B>: Sino-Forest (TSE:TRE.A). Flippers can stay away from
this stock. Their recent financing confirms that they are back on track.
John Thompson's previous play, Pembridge (TSE:PEM), has nearly tripled since
I first featured PEM in HSR. Sometimes, slow but sure is better.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #6</B>: Asquith Resources (CDN:ASQH). Both the size of their
gold property and the grades they've been finding hint that perhaps the
next Bre-X Minerals could be in Africa. ASQH could be the biggest surprise
of 1997.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #7</B>: Enterprise Development (Alberta:ED). A recent acquisition,
a new trading range and new coverage on this tiny oil exploration company
make me feel bullish on their prospects. Once their story is widely told,
ED should attract very strong interest. Large outstanding share position
bothers me.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Numbers #8, #9 and #10</B>: These slots remain blank as these three
companies could quickly move to the top of the list. They will be featured
in the upcoming NEW email service in November for all paid HSR subscribers.
Who knows? They may or may not be any one of those listed in the WILD CARD
section below.<BR>
<P>
<P>
<H2><CENTER>WILD CARDS</CENTER></H2>
<P>
I've been following these companies very closely for months and months.
Any one of these companies could move onto the &quot;Best Bet&quot; list,
but have various flaws, at this time, which keep them off that list. Abrupt
changes are expected in the high-risk spec arena and one never knows when
exactly a company WILL hit on a drill or land a major contract that could
bring them earnings. So, I created this list of companies which you should
begin closely following or inquiring about.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #1</B>: Miranda (VSE:MAD). There is a reason why the stock
has not retreated further since mid-August. Why is that? There is something
in the works.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #2</B>: Primo Resources (VSE:PRI). Drilling is around the corner.
Their Argentinean joint venture appears to be turning out better than initially
expected. I don't see how PRI has more than two dimes of risk at the current
level versus a potential triple in rewards.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #3</B>: Anvil Resources (Alberta:ANV). I interviewed ANV's
geologist, overseeing their Yalakom Mountain copper/gold project, and read
Paul Hawkins' report on this property. Watch and see why I included ANV
in this list. Historically, flippers have failed to lose on ANV when they
purchase the shares under C$0.70 and exit above C$1/share. Perhaps this
time, there may be an extra surprise.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #4</B>: Abitibi (VSE:ABB). When they drill in west Timmins,
I'll feel more comfortable about this company. Their joint venture in the
Cranbrook area, though, gives ABB longevity.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #5</B>: First Choice (VSE:FSD). I like Peter Dasler and his
exploration plans on Knob Hill (Vancover Island). Drilling to start soon
<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #6</B>: Interactive Processing (OTC BB:IAPI). If IAPI survives
the winter, and turns the corner, then this tiny company could become a
success.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #7</B>: Nu-Dawn Resources (VSE:NDN). NDN could be six months
away from their &quot;dream come true.&quot; When, and if, this occurs,
NDN would move right to the top of the Best Bets list.<BR>
<BR>
<B>** Number #8</B>: Prior Resources (Alberta:PQL). Drilling on their Mexican
property could turn up the goods. That alone would probably cause one insider
to buy back all the stock he used to own. Assays forthcoming any day now
-- from what I've been told, PQL may soon announce infill drilling, which
is a very positive sign.<BR>
<P>
