<P>
<A NAME="Ad"><H2>Adrian Resources</H2>
Nasdaq Symbol:  ADLRF      TSE & VSE Symbol:  ADL<BR>
 $ US $3.75,  CDN $ 4.60<BR>
<P>
Adrian Resources currently owns a 52% interest in one of the world's largest undeveloped copper and gold deposits: 
<P>
<B>The Petaquilla Mineral District in Panama.</B> The total geologic resource stands at 3.74 billion tons containing 31.8 billion pounds of copper, 9.8 million ounces of gold, and 962 million pounds of molybdenum. A scoping study conducted by Flour Daniel Wright has estimated the present value of the concession to be US$955 million at US$1.00lb copper. Adrian trades on the Toronto & Vancouver Stock Exchange under the symbol, ADL and on the Nasdaq, symbol ADLRF.
<P>
<I>Two respected financial institutions, Bunting Warburg and Yorkton Securities, were retained by Adrian's management to identify the most effective way to leverage the growing interest on the part of the senior mining community for Adrian's share of the Petaquilla project and to maximize the value for shareholders. A report with their strategic recommendations is due to be released within the next month.  Teck Corporation, which has an option to participate in the Petaquilla project, continues to make progress on its bankable feasibility study and is expected to release this important report in November.</I>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="Bo"><H2>Boron Chemicals International</H2>
Vancouver, Symbol: BHI<BR>
C$ 2.10<BR>
<P>
Boron is scheduled to become a leading supplier of industrial minerals when it takes its Aguas Blancas concession in Northern Chile into production in 1998. This concession contains the world's largest proven deposits of high grade iodine, and large quantities of sodium sulfate and sodium nitrate, the later being used in the manufacturing of upscale potassium fertilizers. Revenues in its first year of operation are estimated to be US$51 million. Latinvest Securities Limited, a specialist investment bank, is serving as financial advisors with the goal of raising US$60 million to construct Boron's iodine, sodium sulfate, and potassium nitrate processing plant on the Aguas Blancas property.
<P>
<I>The company reports continued progress on the US$60 million financing package for its Aguas Blancas project. Boron's Chairman of the Board, Adolf H. Lundin, has been able to move the negotiations to the point where it is anticipated that the necessary financing will be completed before the end of 1996, with mine construction to commence in early 1997 and production to follow in 1998.</I>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="Ch"><H2>Chase Resources / Delta Gold Mining Corp</H2>
Chase: Toronto, Symbol: CQS, Delta: Vancouver, Symbol; DTG.<BR>
Chase (CGS): C $ 3.80,   Delta (DTG): C $ 1.90 
<P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Chase Resources and its affiliated exploration company, Delta Gold Mining Corp., have engaged in an intensive exploration and land acquisition program in the Philippines, Chile and, most recently, Indonesia. This has paid off with the acquisition of a number of highly prospective properties, including the Cikondang Gold Mine in Indonesia and the Taysan copper-gold deposit in the Philippines. Taysan alone is estimated to contain an estimated resource of 2.5 million ounces of gold and 3.6 billion pounds of copper. By September 1996, Chase and Delta will be amalgamated into a single company. Mining giant BHP is a major shareholder in Chase/Delta and is involved in the joint development of the Taysan deposit. For more information, call Chase's Audio Text Number, 1-800-836-4012.
<P>
<I>The official merger of Delta Gold Mining into Chase Resources is on track to occur in the first half of September. Once the merger is complete, the "new" company will retain the name of Chase Resources and a listing will be sought on the NASDAQ. In advance of the merger, Delta Gold Mining announced an update on its seven active exploration projects, including the most advanced of these projects, the Cikondang Gold Mine in Indonesia,  which has been allocated an exploration budget of $1 million. Recent additional evaluation by management has reinforced their belief that Cikondang will become a gold producer and provide the company with sustainable cash flow.</I>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="Go"><H2>Goldbelt Resources</H2>
Vancouver, Symbol: GDB<BR>
C $ 1.27<BR>
<P>
<P>
Since 1992, Goldbelt Resources has, through a series of strategic partnerships, built a substantial presence in the mineral rich former Soviet Republic of Kazakstan. With three primary concessions in the 
company's coffers, and the financing of production facilities at their Leninogorsk gold project in its final stages, investors can look for Goldbelt to transition from an exploration company into a sizable producer within the next 18 months. For more information, call Goldbelt's Audio Text Service, 1 -800-836-4013.
<P>
<I>Goldbelt's price has steadily recovered from a set-back suffered when, to satisfy a legal judgment, a court awarded 3.1 million shares of its stock to another mining company. For investors, the important factors are (a) that these shares had been issued prior to the judgment, so that no dilution of existing shareholders resulted, and (b) the fundamentals of the company have not changed. If anything, they have gotten better as the company has greatly expanded the scope of its drilling program in Kazakstan. Watch for results of this expanded drilling program to be released this fall.</I>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="Gu"><H2>Guyana Gold Corporation</H2>
Toronto, Symbol: GUY<BR>
C $ 0.98<BR>
<P>
<P>
Guyana Gold Corporation is a moderate-sized producer from its Sabi Gold Mine in Zimbabwe. An upgrade is underway, slated for completion by 1998, that will increase production to a significant 40,000 ozs a year at a projected cost of less than $226  per ounce. The company has also begun an exploration program on its Sabi concession designed to double the resource of 1,200,000 ounces during six months of drilling. For an audio update on Guyana, call their Audio Text Number, 1-800-334-2191. Or, visit their web site at: <B>HTTP:\\WNN.GUYANAGOLD.COM.</B>
<P>
<I>The company is pleased that its stock price has recovered substantially from what management termed a "drastic overreaction" to the announcement of amicable discussions being conducted between the company and the government of Zimbabwe regarding their partnership on the Sabi Mine. There has been no interruption in the company's production at the Sabi Gold Mine.</I>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="In"><H2>International Panorama Resources</H2>
OTC.BB, Symbol: IPNRF; Vancouver, Symbol: ILP<BR>
C $ 3.85<BR>
<P>
<P>
International Panorama is a Canadian exploration firm with a global portfolio of highly prospective properties, including the recently acquired Kambove and Kakanda tailings projects in Zaire (see below). Other concessions include: over 30,000 acres in Canada's Voisey Bay region, near the site of the massive nickel discovery by Diamond Fields Resources; the Union of Myanmar (formerly Burma), where the company has been granted exclusive exploration rights to an area covering 1,400 sq. km., potentially rich in gold; and in the United States. An updated Corporate Profile is available with more details on the company's exciting Zairian acquisition. To receive your free copy, call 1-800-485-0108.
<P>
<I> In a long awaited development, the company announced the completion of its joint venture agreement on the massive cobalt/copper tailings near the concentrators at Kambove and Kakanda in the Shaba Region of Zaire. The government of Zaire, which has formally ratified the agreement, will be the 49% joint venture partner through Gecamines, the state run mining company.  Gecamines has reported that the Kambove and Kakanda tailings contain a combined 61,174,000 tonnes of ore grading an average of .98% copper and .19% cobalt. The company is currently preparing a bankable feasibility study which is due to be complete by Spring 1997.</I>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="Si"><H2>Silver Standard Resources.</H2>
(Nasdaq, Symbol: SSRIF, Vancouver, Symbol: SSO)<BR>
C $ 7.10<BR>
<P>
<P>
Silver Standard is a silver exploration company with a mission to secure a group of properties with a minimum total defined in-ground resource of 250,000,000 ounces of silver by 1997, and to become a significant silver producer within four years. Silver Standard, which has multi-million ounce concessions in Bolivia, Mexico and the Russian Far East is a top recommendation of a number of leading analysts including Doug Casey, Jim Blanchard, Adrian Day and Rick Rule.
<P>
<I> Within the near future results will be released from drill programs being conducted across the company's growing inventory of silver properties. Investors will want to watch for (by the end of September) results from drilling at their Dios Padre and San Miguel properties in Mexico.  Drilling will start at the El Asiento in Bolivia at the same time.  By the end of October, the company expects to release a bankable feasibility study on the Lunnoe property in the Russian Far East. This property, Silver Standard's most advanced, has proven and probable reserves of 120 million ounces of silver and 500,000 ounces of gold.</I>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="Yu"><H2>Yuma Gold Corp.</H2>
Vancouver, Symbol: YUM<BR>
C $ 3.32<BR>
<P>
<P>
The first stage of the strategic plan is to make the first payment towards the purchase of the Dona Ada copper cement facility, thus giving Yuma a 100% ownership of the plant with estimated profits of approximately $200,000 per month. Concurrently Yuma will commence construction of copper sulphate fertilizers at Tuina and at the recently acquired Sierra Miranda mine site.
<P>
The second part of the plan construction of a Solvent Extraction Electrowinning (SX-EW) plant at Sierra Miranda for the production of copper cathodes will commence. Once the SX-EW plant is operational, the copper sulphate plant at Sierra Miranda will be moved to Dona Ada. Both Dona Ada and Tuina will continue to produce copper sulphate crystals for shipment to Sierra Miranda and conversion into copper cathodes. Total production of copper cathodes at the Sierra Miranda plant is estimated at 40,000 tonnes (85 million pounds) per annum.
<P>
<I> Yuma's management reports that the company is on schedule to begin producing copper at its Dona Ada mine this September. To provide working capital and fund its obligations at its Chilean mining operations, the company recently announced a private placement of up to 2 million ``units at $2.57 per unit. Each unit consists of one share and one warrant, which entitles the holder to purchase an additional share at $2.57 during the first year, and at a price of $3.00 during the second year.</I>
<P>
<P>
