<P>
<H1>KAISER EXPRESS # 96 -- 12</H1>
<P>
Commentary by John Kaiser  ------  November 13, 1996<BR>
<P>
<H1>Juniors Starting to Break Out of Bottom</H1>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="#Ju">Juniors Starting to Break Out of Bottom</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Us">US election outcome pulls speculators from the sidelines back onto the field</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Jn">$1-5 juniors destined to post biggest gains in the Year of the Blowoff</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Ca">Canadian stock market poised to outperform US markets </A><BR>
<A HREF="#Tw">Two Bottom-Fishing Windows: Now, and again when tax-loss selling switches to tax-gain selling</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Un">Unkind chalk mark commentary on truth machine verdicts</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Ke">Keep an eye on First Choice</A><BR>
<A HREF="#To"><font size=+1>Two Sportsfishing Picks for 1997: Energold and Sonoma</font size></A><BR>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Ju">The buyer's strike that has plagued Canadian juniors since June started to end last week. As you may recall, the reality checks delivered by the Timbuktu and Cartaway disasters helped push speculators to the sidelines, a move reinforced by the senior market's micro-correction in July. Despite a rising chorus of bearish warnings that the longest running bull market in history was on the verge of collapse, New York has since charged ahead to a record high of 6,219 as of Friday, November 8. While investors have largely ignored the bears, these warnings did not go unheeded by speculators, whose phenomenal success with Canadian juniors in 1996 satiated greed and calmed the usual desperation for big and quick profits that characterizes speculation. From June until now speculators have kept a nervous eye on the "dangling sword" that the senior market's apparent toppiness represented, while they awaited liquidity for the $10 billion bonanza delivered in 1996 by Diamond Fields, Bre-X and Arequipa. While partial recycling of these hard value profits fueled the junior stocks during the first half, it appears that the proceeds from the Diamond Fields and Arequipa takeover bids have stayed on the sidelines. Bre-X itself has not been taken over, but the stock has traded so heavily in the $15-25 range ($150-250 pre-split, with retail investors on board below $25 pre-split) that it is safe to conclude that much of the Bre-X paper has shifted from retail shareholder accounts to institutional accounts. That institutional money has been sucked from conservative capital pools invested in mutual funds whose managers as a group have allocated the minor spec component into high profile juniors like Bre-X. Retail investors have been reluctant since June to reinvest their windfall profits in other junior stocks because those profits carry a big capital gains tax liability and the junior market was not only trapped in the downtrending "cup-half-empty" phase of the seasonal cycle, but vulnerable to getting whacked if New York did keel over. Retail speculative buying is driven by the expectation of profits "tomorrow", not "next year". The thinking that set in was "hey, if I buy this stock now it means my tax burden next April will be even worse, and with the trend going against me, I'm at risk of "losing" either way". Sounds perverse, but keep in mind that Americans resist paying down mortgages because they like to claim the interest as a tax deduction.
<P>
<A NAME="Us"><font size=+1>US election outcome pulls speculators from the sidelines back onto the field
</font size>
<P>
As always happens when buyers go on strike, speculators have encountered liquidity problems trying to sell their Canadian juniors, especially during the past two months. The high-flyers of 1996 have consequently pulled back sharply, putting many speculators in specific loss positions, but not in overall net loss terms. The smarter ones have already cut their losses by taking their losses to offset earlier gains. The downtrend, however, has reached a standstill, which is evident in the large bid-ask spreads on many juniors. This condition implies that prices have dropped low enough to defuse the "dump at any cost" mood. Normally I would say it is still too early in the tax loss selling season for bottom-fishers to switch from lurking at the bid to reaching for the offer, but this year the turnaround trigger lies in the US election, which gave the market exactly what it wanted: a Republican controlled house and senate that ensures ongoing fiscal conservatism, and a Democrat president to veto the loonier initiatives launched by Republican extremists. The outlook for continuing moderate growth and subdued inflation suits investors just fine. It is clear that in the post-election debate over the economy's and market's direction the bulls are beating the bears as a vision of "a 10,000 Dow before a 3,000 Dow" settles in. I do not care to comment on the wisdom of this mentality, but I am prepared to predict it will nail that "dangling sword" securely to the wall for at least another six months in the eyes of speculators. With only two months to go before the arrival of 1997, "tomorrow's spec profits" are rapidly becoming "next tax year's profits". The timing is right for speculators to move their money from the sidelines back into Canadian juniors, particularly ones that do not have a heavy overhang of shareholders underwater at much higher prices. Juniors that spent 1996 treading water in terms of stock performance but got things accomplished in terms of fundamentals are ready to rocket out of the bottom into the new year with hardly an interruption. As this group turns the VSE index into a visible uptrend, the 1996 high-flyers will follow suit. But you should be aware that this group of "underwater" stocks is very likely to suffer a setback in mid-December as the Johnny-come-latelies realize they should do some tax loss selling and switch the proceeds into "fresh" stories. I think the tax-loss selling pressure on most of the Canadian juniors is over, but not for that small group of heavily traded stocks down 50% or more from their 1996 peaks. This latter group will also be vulnerable to the annual year-end shuffle of institutional window-dressing as fund managers purge losing positions from the portfolio so that they don't show up in next year's mutual fund prospectus.
<P>
<A NAME="Jn"><font size=+1>$1-5 juniors destined to post biggest gains in the Year of the Blowoff
</font size>
<P>
My recommendation is to avoid 1996's high profile stocks until mid-December, but bottom-fish aggressively now for the also-ran juniors who are set to capitalize on a surge in market interest in 1997. I think the senior market is good for at least one more major leg in 1997, during which speculative interest in Canadian exploration juniors will soar, especially as new major discoveries lurch onto the scene. I believe juniors in the $1-$5 price range with strong management, capital and a diverse portfolio of projects at various stages of exploration will post the biggest gains in 1997, shooting for double digit dreamland. The promise of liquidity and information flow coupled with promotional infrastructure will draw large audiences of speculators to these stocks. Cheaper stocks are not likely to be as rewarding, because if management hasn't already got its act together, it is probably too late to participate in the giant 1997 Blowoff that is brewing. Calling 1997 the Year of the Blowoff may be a harsh and cynical way of putting it, but with the longevity of the senior bull market an open question, and the poor odds that as many world class discoveries will be made as there are serious juniors looking for them, you can bet that the "industry" will be focused on shifting its paper into the hands of new audiences attracted by the exceptional recent track record of Canadian juniors. The accompanying promotion campaigns aren't likely to kick in until the new year, so speculators already familiar with how the systems work would be wise to take their positions during the next two months. In short, what I am saying is the upward ramping chart pattern popularly known as the January Effect is now underway two months early. The downside risk lies in the large profits that are still embedded in the Canadian juniors. I would venture that many stocks have been able to sustain hefty market caps for the simple reason that shareholders who bought positions at lucrative prices using Bre-X style profits have held off taking profits until the new tax year arrives. Unless new capital is injected into the Canadian juniors through takeover bids of stocks like Adrian, Farallon, Intl Curator and Aber, or through the arrival of new audiences, the tax-gain selling pressure that will greet the higher profile juniors in the new year may force them into a downtrend one might call a Reverse January Effect. Such a development could spill over into the rest of the market.
<P>
<A NAME="Ca"><font size=+1>Canadian stock market poised to outperform US markets</font size>
<P>
I have been talking about the Canadian spec market from the domestic perspective of Americans, as though their moods about their own stock market and economy dictate the trend of Canada's stock market. There is reason to think that a sneeze in the United States won't necessarily cause Canada's stock market to catch a cold this time around. Canada's central bank has been dropping the prime rate relentlessly over the past two years in an effort to stimulate an economy whose unemployment rate is stuck at 10% compared to 5.2% in the United States. As a result the prime rate stands at 4.75%, a level that hasn't been seen since the fifties. Even though the US prime rate stands at 8.25%, the Canadian dollar has risen to about $0.75 and is still regarded as undervalued. Canada's inflation hovers at 1.5%, half that in the United States. From the American perspective it now looks like Canada's economy should soon start to respond positively and offer an excellent window for investment growth before inflation creeps back into the picture. If you ignore the potential for a Quebec induced currency crisis, and consider that interest rates can't be pushed too much lower, the Canadian dollar is set to rise. The stage has been set for a boom in Canadian equities as Canadian investors move their money into stocks in search of better returns, followed by American capital which sees the comparative uptrend in Canadian markets supercharged with the potential for a currency exchange gain. Over the past few years Canadian stocks have suffered from the opposite perception. This special attractiveness of the Canadian stock market would offset the fallout from a near-term correction in American equity markets, provided such a correction does not spiral out of control into a devastating shock to the system. Given the recent track record of junior resource stocks, this sector is a natural destination for both investment and speculation dollars. (To appreciate the scale of the accomplishments, just ask yourself when the global news has ever before covered a story involving the extortion bid by a dictator's kid for a $1 million monthly nose-picking retainer and a 10% carried interest in a multi-billion dollar gold discovery by a Canadian junior? Frankly, I find the affair quite disgusting, and would not be surprised if it becomes the symbolic lever that helps the Indonesian people toss out the sleazebag military once Suharto joins his wife. Bre-X already has about 50 million ounces gold, and the extra 100 million ounces it might still find are worthless because they won't see the light of day for another 50 years. There are limits to how much ore a single mining operation can process, so unless Busang's grade improves, Bre-X stock has limited upside in net present value terms. In terms of comparative value and potentially higher gold prices, 50 million ounces in a single deposit is nowhere near as valuable as 50 million ounces in five deposits. I don't expect speculators to hang around with Bre-X positions once we are in the new tax year.) The only thing missing from the equation is an uptrend in commodity prices, a development that does not presently form part of anybody's expectation set. If prices for metals like copper, gold, silver, and, heaven forbid, zinc, started heading up, Canadian resource stocks would become the hottest investment on the planet.
<P>
<A NAME="Tw"><font size=+1>Two Bottom-Fishing Windows: Now, and again when tax-loss selling switches to tax-gain selling</font size>
<P>
If I am correct in calling the turnaround out of the bottom for Canadian junior resource stocks as happening right now, the publication of my 100 bottom-fish picks for 1997 in early December will not be very good timing for bottom-fishing purposes. The September-October issue of the Kaiser Bottom-Fishing Report, which is a complete review of my 100 bottom-fish picks for 1996, went to the printer on October 29, but did not get into the mail until November 5 thanks to a pile of last minute election propaganda that slipped into the queue ahead of me. Although I hinted in that issue that the breakout from the bottom was coming early this year, I am now sufficiently convinced to make a point of telling my Kaiser Express subscribers that the timeliness of the stocks classified as bottom-fish or seasonal buys is immediate. Most are comparable in quality to the leading new candidates on my 1997 bottom-fish short list. Read my September-October issue carefully and act now to avoid the crowd and higher prices in December. On the other hand, if we do get back to back rounds of tax-loss selling in late December and tax-gain selling in early January, bottom-fishers could experience a welcome market lull during which they will have ample time to take advantage of the 100 Bottom-Fish Picks for 1997.
<P>
<A NAME="Un"><font size=+1>Unkind chalk mark commentary on truth machine verdicts</font size>
<P>
The truth machines have been whittling away at a number of my Kaiser Express picks over the past year, in particular <b>Peruvian Gold (PVO-V: $2.57), Teuton Resource Corp (TUO-V: $0.87), Gerle Gold (GGL-V: $1.12)</b> and <b>Cons Callinan Flin Flon (CFF-V: $1.42).</b> The chalk marks have already delivered rather nasty verdicts on these stocks, even though the fat lady's turn to sing isn't even in the lineup yet. At this point I would suggest that tax loss considerations be the only logic in contemplated sales, for these stocks are close to a bottom. I am working on getting clear pictures of the truth machine verdicts, and will publish my conclusions in a future Kaiser Express. As for the Voisey's Bay East play, it looks like any extension of the Eastern Deeps is going to be very deep, if it exists at all. <b>Columbia Yukon (CYR-C: $0.46)</b> and <b>Intl Canalaska (ICA-V: $0.60)</b> drilled through uninspired geology to a depth of 860 metres before packing it in for the season. The Voisey's Bay East play isn't dead yet, but I regard Columbia Yukon's short term value primarily in tax mitigation terms. Speculators who had the fortune of ignoring Columbia Yukon should regard our liquidation binge as a bottom-fishing opportunity. Those who chose <b>Lucero Resource Corp (LCR-V: $1.15)</b> as their Eastern Deeps Extension hedge made the better choice and will soon be very happy. Lucero is in the process of nailing down a land package in Mexico that Jim Dawson thinks has exceptional potential. We are still three weeks away from knowing whether or not Lucero is on track with a Farallon style "district" story. I own shares in Gerle, Peruvian Gold, Columbia Yukon and Lucero.
<P>
<A NAME="Ke"><font size=+1>Keep an eye on First Choice</font size>
<P>
One stock to put on your watch list is Peter Dasler's <b>First Choice Industries (FSD-V: $0.31)</b>, which is busy drilling the Knob Hill prospect in northern Vancouver Island. The target here is an El Indio type high sulphidation gold deposit within the upper levels of a porphyry system. First Choice has drilled several short holes that have yielded sulphides over 300 ft, with lead-zinc-copper and arsenopyrite mineralization evident. The gold grade, invisible until assayed, will make or break this play. Dasler, who is the underlying owner of the prospect under option 65% to First Choice, is pretty excited about the core, but not enough to have sent it in for rush assaying. His optimism is based on an associated arsenic-gold soil anomaly, which suggests to him that this stuff will run a decent gold grade. If it does, and assays are expected within a week, First Choice is sitting on a major new discovery. The stock is somewhat of an orphan whose key supporters have been back-dooring each other over the past year. But the company does have one large shareholder whose paper doesn't free up until late December. This individual operates his own PR machine, which you can bet will be hooked up to First Choice if the core assays gold. At this stage I suggest nobody buy the stock, just watch it closely for assay results and be prepared to act swiftly if we get long intersections of 1 g/t gold or better. It is preferable to own this stock at higher prices when we know the company has the goods. First Choice can be reached at (800) 473-9444. I own a small position in First Choice.
<P>
<A NAME="To"><font size=+2>Two Sportsfishing Picks for 1997: Energold and Sonoma</font size>
<P>
Two juniors of the variety that I think will do very well in 1997 are <b>Energold Mining Ltd (EGD-V: $1.48)</b> and <b>Sonoma Resource Corp (SNA-V: $1.64).</b> Energold is a graduate from my 1996 Bottom-Fish List and Sonoma is a graduate from the 1995 list. Neither had a major play in 1996, but did spend the year straightening out organizational matters, raising money and preparing for a big exploration year in 1997. Energold is the more illiquid of the two, but both stocks appear to have resistance at the $2 level and accordingly speculators should not chase these stocks beyond $2 until there are further corporate developments. I own a small position in Sonoma.
<P>
<font size=+2><b>Energold</b>: Dominican Republic Country Play</font size>
<P>
<b>Energold Mining Ltd (EGD-V)</b> maintained a fairly low profile during 1996 while management waited for the outcome of elections in the Dominican Republic and for the Eldorado-Gencor-HRC reorganization deals to close. Energold had been created in 1994 by Fred Davidson and Walter Sellmer, whose Latin American quest ended in 1995 when Eldorado assigned to Energold an option to acquire a package of concessions in the Dominican Republic which Canyon and Battle Mountain had assembled and wished to unload because of political uncertainty. Eldorado became a key shareholder in Energold, and boosted its equity stake to a current 42% interest in April 1996 when it bought out an offshore venture capital group's 3.2 million Energold shares. Eldorado has been a passive investor; although the Davidson/Sellmer group control only 20% of Energold's 13.4 million fully diluted shares, they run the company and control the board with 3 directors compared to Eldorado's 2 directors. The relationship is friendly, and buttressed by investments Eldorado insiders have made in Energold.
<P>
The centrepiece of Energold's property portfolio is the EL Centenario gold deposit on the El Higo concession, a shallow epithermal system estimated to host 1,094,000 tonnes of 6.7 g/t (0.2 opt) gold or about 220,000 ounces on the basis of 35 holes drilled by Canyon/Battle Mountain. Drilling late last year was interrupted when environmentalists prodded a jurisdictional dispute between the mines and forestry departments over six trees that the drilling contractor had chopped down. Management suspects that the fuss was related to political posturing for the upcoming election in 1996. One year later (Sept 26/96) Energold received permission to begin a 50 hole reserve delineation drill program expected to take 3-4 months. Management concedes that El Centenario is not a world class contender, and thinks the upside limit for a gold reserve is about 400,000 ounces.
<P>
The Dominican Republic covers the eastern two-thirds of the Hispaniola Island in the Caribbean. Since the arrival of Columbus in the 15th century DR has suffered a sordid history of foreign military occupations and internal dictatorships. The proximity to Cuba and the United States has ensured repeated political intervention by the USA during the past century. In 1966 Joaquin Balaguer was elected president and for the next 30 years succeeded in being "elected" to seven presidential terms totalling 22 years during which he imposed his conservative "law and order" philosophy that required suppression of the opposition. Balaguer's election rigging efforts failed in 1978 when a moderate leftist became president, who was replaced by a social democrat in 1982. During the eighties DR fell victim to inflation and a debt crisis that enabled Balaguer to be re-elected in 1986. With the aid of election fraud he was re-elected in 1990 and again in 1994, but the last affair caused such a domestic and international uproar that his term was cut in half and new elections scheduled in mid-1996. The May 16 election and the June 30 runoff between Leonel Fernandez and Jose Francisco Pena Gomez may represent a watershed in DR politics. Although Fernandez beat Gomez by less than 3%, the loser graciously acknowledged defeat (unprecedented in DR history) and outside observers confirmed that there was virtually no evidence of electoral fraud. Fernandez, who is only 43 years old and grew up in New York before returning to DR to train as a lawyer, is described as "slightly right of centre" (outgoing president Balaguer voted for him) and committed to free-market economies. The loser, Gomez, has formed an alliance between his PLD party and Balaguer's old party, the PRSC, to control DR's senate and lower house in a situation that appears similar to the United States. Gomez, described as "slightly-left-of-centre", however, also favours free markets and foreign investments. During the past two months a change in political atitude has become obvious, in particular with regard to the mining sector, which the new government sees as a major way to boost the agriculturally based economy.
<P>
For Energold, which ventured into the Dominican Republic when political risk was still spelled with capital letters, this development promises to attract investor interest. Two other earlybirds, Falconbridge and BHP, have been joined by MIM in a "staking" rush. Energold itself has amassed over 180,000 ha, and because of restrictions on the number and size of concessions a single party can control, has been busy farming projects out to others while retaining rights to back in for 60% by reimbursing expenditures. The real story, however, which will put the Dominican Republic on the institutional map is a proposal by Eldorado and Gencor to test a proprietary extraction technology on the refractory sulphide ore at the Pueblo Viejo Mine. Pueblo Viejo is a world-class deposit Eldorado estimates has a geologic resource of about 464 million tonnes of 2 g/t (0.058 opt) gold using a 1 g/t cutoff. Between 1975-1992 the state mining company, Rosario Dominicana SA, has produced 5 million ounces gold and 22 million ounces silver by open-pit mining the over-lying oxide ore which is now largely depleted. The refractory nature of the sulphide ore has meant that the underlying 32 million ounce gold reserve is non-commercial. If Gencor/Eldorado can demonstrate commercial extraction with Gencor's BIOX bacterial oxidation technology, they will make a unique development proposal to the Dominican Republic.
<P>
If mining Pueblo Viejo's sulphide ore is feasible and a development deal is struck, the spotlight will shine on the remaining relatively unexplored potential of the Dominican Republic. When investors realize that the Hispaniola Island is an accretion of numerous island-arc terranes assembled from the Cretaceous period onward, and that the Pueblo Viejo deposit is hosted by sedimentary rocks within a maar crater diatreme complex, they are going to recognize the language of Kalimantan and Busang. Falconbridge was present because DR hosts nickel deposits, but the arrival of two Australian mining giants and their acquisition campaign in the vicinity of Pueblo Viejo suggest they recognize certain similarities with the geology that turned Bre-X into a household name. While the region has likely been scoured for exposed oxide deposits, the potential for hidden sulphide deposits similar to Pueblo Viejo is relatively untouched. Once it becomes apparent that Pueblo Viejo's refractory problem is solvable, Energold's large adjacent land position will become an especially hot exploration target.
<P>
Energold presently has about $2.5 million working capital that includes proceeds from a recent private placement of 923,077 shares at $1.30 that was taken down by a number of prominent promoters, brokers and newsletter writers. Energold's Fred Davidson is not known as a strong promoter, but the elite audience he has cultivated ensures that when the timing is right there will be no shortage of market support. The feedback I get from Eldorado is that it perceives Energold as an exploration company specializing in Central America and the Caribbean. The acquisition efforts in the Dominican Republic over the past year were guided by Energold management, but it would not be unreasonable to expect Eldorado to steer a flow of potential projects toward Energold in 1997. At this point Energold does not have an institutional shareholder base, but with Eldorado as a shareholder anchor, it is just a matter of time. The stock is thinly traded, and hard to buy at current levels. It has no overhang of "underwater" paper, but selling from impatient shareholders should materialize around the $2 level. Energold can be reached at (604) 681-9501.
<P>
<font size=+2> Sonoma: a play on Argentina and the Cerro Toro prospect</font size>
<P>
It's taken Pat McCleery longer than he expected, but he finally has <b>Sonoma Resource Corp (SNA-V)</b> properly financed and positioned to become a major Argentina play in 1997. Over the past few years Jim Keighley and Ron Brown have pooled their collective knowledge of Argentina and satellite imagery data to assemble a million acre land package consisting of 30 prospects in six regions of Argentina. The top priority is the 2,000 ha Cerro Toro project in Argentina's San Juan province. Located on the Argentine side of the El Indio gold belt, Cerro Toro hosts a north south striking colour anomaly of 3,500 m by 1,000 m that Ron Brown first discovered in 1982 while working for St Joe Minerals. Sampling work late last year revealed a series of high grade polymetallic vein swarms in the Central Zone that appear to repeat themselves over a width of 300-400 metres and a strike length of 1,350 metres. One channel sample yielded 16 ft grading 32.2% zinc, 19 opt silver, 2,26% copper, 0.46 g/t gold and 0.5% lead. Because the Central Zone is littered with talus Sonoma decided early this year to build a road into the property in order to bring in heavy equipment, but by the time the road was finished the southern hemisphere's winter had arrived. Although Cerro Toro itself has an elevation of 3,000-3,500 metres and can be worked year round, the main road climbs a 5,000 metre pass that is closed during winter from June through September. Sonoma's bulldozers have been ripping open the Central Zone since October as part of a 10,000 metre trenching program. While the individual high grade veins are only 1-2 metres wide, they appear to be set within a stockwork of disseminated mineralization that represents an El Tambo style bulk tonnage target of 50-100 million tonnes. Trenching and IP geophysical survey results are expected in January, at which point Sonoma expects to be ready to drill the Central Zone. Geophysics is also underway on the South Zone, which, on the basis of fine grained mineralization, Sonoma believes to be the uplifted portion of a major copper-gold porphyry system speculated to underly the Cerro Toro prospect. Sonoma believes it has made a major new grassroots discovery. Because Sonoma is well financed and owns Cerro Toro 100%, confirmation would turn Sonoma into a huge success story.
<P>
Sonoma has projects in San Juan, Cordoba, San Luis, Rio Negro, Chubut and Santa Cruz provinces, any one of which could lurch onto the front burner as a result of ongoing field work. For now the focus, however, is on Cerro Toro. Fully diluted Sonoma has 22.8 million shares, of which about 17.1 million are presently issued. Of these 5 million trade as special warrants under the symbol SNA.WT.L. Each special warrant consists of one share and a 1/2 warrant which were sold in October by Loewen Ondaatje through a brokered private placement of 5 million special warrants at $1.10. Sonoma has about $2.5 million working capital, plus $5 million in escrow pending prospectus qualification of the special warrants, expected to take 2-3 months. Full dilution would inject another $8.4 million into the treasury. Sonoma has a well rounded management that includes Dan Kunz as president, Pat McCleery, Chet Idziszek, and Bill Rand. They have attracted a strong shareholder base that includes the likes of Adolf Lundin and Doug Casey. If results over the next six months let Cerro Toro live up to its potential, Sonoma will be a major play in 1997. Sonoma can be reached at (800) 763-3255.
<P>
