<BODY BGCOLOR=#C0C0C0><CENTER><IMG SRC="../mw.gif" ></CENTER><HR>
<P>
<H1>KAISER EXPRESS # 96 -- 11</H1>
<P>
Commentary by John Kaiser  ------  September 23, 1996<BR>
<P>
<H1> Gerle finally hits kimberlite!</H1>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="#Ga">Gerle finally hits kimberlite!</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Vo">Voisey's Bay East: hey look, a troctolite!</A><BR>
<A HREF="#In">Indonesian Hype: flying on skimpy evidence</A><BR>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Ba"><b>Gerle Gold Ltd</b>(GGL-V: $1.46) announced on September 18 that 15 out of 98 shallow reverse circulation holes had intersected kimberlite. Apparently Gerle has been sitting on this information for more than a week, though judging by Gerle's recent sell-off to $1.35 and Wednesday's lacklustre market action, this secret has had a tight lid on it. The news release provides no details about the type and size of the kimberlite. A winterized camp is being established in the "area of interest" and diamond core drilling is expected to begin in about a week. Meanwhile results of a ground geophysics survey are being studied and kimberlite samples will be sent for caustic fusion analysis.<BR>
<P>
I talked to Gerle's Ray Hrkac Wednesday afternoon, and was able to glean the following additional information about the discovery. Precise details were not forthcoming because Monopros is unwilling to make any disclosure until it has a better understanding of the discovery. The RC holes were drilled to a maximum depth of 100 ft. The 15 holes that hit kimberlite are within what Hrkac describes as an "extensive area" close to the head of the indicator mineral train on the North/Central claims of the Doyle Lake project south of Mountain Province's 5034 pipe. When I pressed Hrkac about the meaning of "extensive", the best I could get was that it is considerably larger than the area encompassed by the 5034 pipe. Some of the holes stopped in kimberlite, others passed through it into granite. Kimberlite holes were also interspersed with non-kimberlite holes. The kimberlite material appears to be uniform in all the holes. Its facies type has not yet been classified (ie crater, diatreme, hypabyssal). At this stage Monopros does not know whether it is dealing with a large crater facies, a cluster of small diatremes, or a fissure system. Hrkac stated that the lack of outcrop within the "area of interest" clashes with the density, size and texture of the train's indicator minerals, though he did concede that the area includes a number of untested "gaps" in the form of lakes and swamps as well as places where overburden is so thick the RC drill failed to reach bedrock. No indicator mineral analysis has yet been done which would allow a comment on the relationship of the kimberlite's chemistry with the excellent chemistry of the indicator mineral train. Even in the area of the kimberlite intersections the geophysics is too confusing to distinguish between kimberlite and country rock.<BR>
<P>	
About the most I can express about this discovery is that Gerle has finally hit kimberlite. We can't say 'pipe' until Gerle has drilled several deep holes into a kimberlite body. And we can't say diamondiferous until the RC samples are processed. Hrkac was unable to give me a time frame, but did indicate Monopros was treating it on a rush priority basis. This kimberlite discovery is only the beginning. Apparently on the basis of indicator mineral distribution in terms of type and size within the general train, Gerle's consultant, Felix Kaminsky, feels that several distinct sources have fed the train, which travels westward as far as the Noble Peak/Southerena/Monopros JV. My optimism in Gerle's Doyle Lake project, which admittedly had started to flag in the face of the company's inability to hit kimberlite, has been restored. Below $2 the stock is a strong buy. I would be reluctant to pay more until diamond drilling gives us a sense of what sort of kimberlite body (ie tonnage implications) we are dealing with, and to what degree the kimberlite is diamondiferous. However, the Second NWT Diamond Wave I talked about in the March-April 1996 issue of the Kaiser Bottom-Fishing Report appears to be underway, and may blow the lid off market valuations of key NWT diamond plays. Aber's continuing success in establishing grade and value for the A154, A418 and A21 pipes is pushing that play ever closer to the point where RTZ must make a decision about buying out <b>Aber Resources Ltd (ABZ-T: $23.65)</b>. On September 17 <b>Mountain Province Mining (MPV-V: $5.10)</b> announced a special warrant financing of 3,075,000 units at $4.90 to be brokered by Eagle Partners on a best efforts basis. Eagle is where diamond analyst John Hainey hangs his hat these days. Hainey is quite capable of doing his homework, and probably has not missed the rumours that values won't be reported for the carat parcel from the 113 tonne bulk sample, whose final grade results are imminent. So when the results are finally reported and come nowhere near the original 5 ct/t and $100/ct fantasies of certain offshore tout sheets, I don't expect Mountain Province's price to tank and Eagle to wave the "market out clause" flag. With many of the key NWT diamond plays now operating on an all-season basis, the arrival of winter marks the beginning of the next speculative cycle for NWT diamond stocks.<BR>
<P>
<A NAME="Vo"><font size=+1> Voisey's Bay East: hey look, a troctolite!</font size>
<P>
The Voisey's Bay East play received a bit of a shot in the arm recently when <b>NDT Ventures (NDE-V: $1.00)</b> and <b>Lucero Resources Corp (LCR-V: $1.11)</b> announced that a gravity survey on Project 122 just east of the VBE-1 project of <b>Columbia Yukon (CYR-C: $1.22)</b> and <b>Intl Canalaska (ICA-V: $1.26)</b> revealed a structure interpreted as a "200 metre thick ultramafic/troctolite body at a depth of approximately 300 metres below surface". A map published by the JV shows this structure entering from the VBE-1 claim in the north, swinging southwards, and then exiting the property about midway eastwards onto <b>Absolut's (ALR-C: $1.10)</b> property, where it appears to coincide with a deep east-west fjiord that likely coincides with one of the strong east-west fault structures that cut the Voisey's Bay region. The NDT/Lucero news release throws in "ultramafic" as an alternative to "troctolite", but this appears to have been thrown In for the cause of conservatism. The way I heard the story the original troctolite interpretation was made by an individual who has done extensive work interpreting the gravity surveys on the main Voisey's Bay block for Diamond Fields. In other words, the 122 project probably does host a troctolite body. Anywhere else in Labrador such a claim would hardly even deserve a yawn. But in the Voisey's Bay East area the hypothesis has been floated that the geological system that hosts the Eastern Deeps ore may extend much farther east from the original Ovoid discovery than even Diamond Fields' wildest optimists imagined when they stopped staking to the east where dull-looking anorthositic rocks replaced the troctolitic/gneissic rocks that hosted the discovery mineralization. The NDT/Lucero news is the first published evidence that the third dimension may be much more interesting than initially thought, though we are still a long way off from seeing evidence of nickel-copper massive sulphides. None of this has kept the price of NDT from sliding lower, though this may be largely due to the likelihood that the key players behind NDT blew off most of their paper earlier in the year on the back of the Project 44 drill play with Takla Star near Nain. Columbia Yukon and Intl Canalaska meanwhile have finally obtained a drill permit for the VBE-1 claim and will soon begin drilling the first of a several deep geological holes. From what I have heard this hole is in the northern part, and may be aimed at the western extension of the "troctolite" NDT/Lucero have interpreted on their property. At this stage the Voisey's Bay East play is still a wild gamble, but the news from NDT/Lucero leaves me optimistic that drill logs may soon cause this play to catch fire.
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="In"><font size=+1>Indonesian Hype: flying on skimpy evidence</font size>
<P>
Two of my bottom-fish, <b>Borneo Gold Corp (BNO-V: $11.25 halted)</b> and <b>Goldstake Explorations (GXP-T: $2.75)</b> exploded to new highs on extraordinary volume this week. Borneo gapped up on Monday after announcing that a 800 metre by 2,000 metre porphyry breccia intrusive known as the Monsan Prospect had been identified as the lode source of alluvial gold being mined in the area. The news release featured enough qualitative geological detail mixed with talk about visible gold to get any geologist dreaming about the project's exploration potential, but it provided no quantitative details in the form of assays and mineralization extent to explain why the stock suddenly deserved a $300 million market cap based on the 30 million or so fully diluted Borneo shares. In a followup news release prompted by the VSE Borneo confessed that actual sampling had only just begun and that the presence of high grade gold had only been visually observed. The VSE has decided that Borneo should stay halted until Borneo has had opportunity to put all these "bonanza grade ore shoots" into a quantitative perspective based on assays and sample distances. Given the slow pace of exploration work in Indonesia, Borneo may be off the board for a long time. Investors who sold probably have less reason to fret than those who didn't.<BR>
<P>
The following day on September 17 Goldstake produced a feeble news release that "caused" the stock to charge from Monday's $1.18 close to a high of $4.70 before settling back to $3.55 on mind-boggling volume of 6.6 million shares. The news release stated that grades ranging from 0.29 opt gold to 3.38 opt gold had been obtained, but neglected to mention whether these were grab samples, trench samples or drill core assays. The news release also alleged that the work had extended the mineralization in the Ann and Joy Zones from 400 metres to 2,400 metres. The remaining 75% of the news release was devoted to a geological lesson on the Lihir type gold deposit, which Goldstake's geologists think could be the model for the Soreang concession on Java. But consider the wording: "the discovery is a major step toward confirming that the Soreang concession could host a Lihir-type deposit". Sloppy readers may think that Goldstake was sitting on a Lihir deposit, but in reality it is a confession that Goldstake does not yet have sufficient evidence to make the claim that the Soreang's geological setting fits the Lihir model.
<P>
Probably under pressure from the TSE Goldstake provided a more detailed news release on September 18 that mainly regurgitated previous data reported last December about the property's "massive epithermal sulphide" bodies (ie high grade polymetallic stringers and veinlets). Goldstake revealed that the only results it had were four chip samples taken randomly from "unmapped" old trenches and mine workings along strike from the Ann and Joy Zones. This is not a new property. It was worked during the eighties by an Australian company called Pelsart, and at one time was under option by Andrew Milligan's Camino Resources. Based on the vague information so far produced, this recycled Java prospect is hardly deserving of the $100 million market cap based on 30 million or so fully diluted shares. Incidentally, Goldstake has yet to report that any of the private placement financings announced earlier this year have actually closed. This stock is a trading opportunity for speculators who think they are good at playing the greater fool game. For the rest of us it should be sold or avoided.
<P>
<P>
