<P>
<H1>KAISER EXPRESS # 96 -- 10</H1>
<P>
Commentary by John Kaiser  ------  September 5, 1996<BR>
<P>
<H1>Mansfield & Corriente & Voisey's Bay East</H1>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="#Ma"> Mansfield & Corriente: a good time to sell both</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Hi"> <b>Highwood:</b> chronic beryllium disease lawsuits spell trouble for Brush Wellman</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Vo"> <b>Voisey's Bay East:</b> stirring the pot with unsubstantiated rumours</A><BR>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Ma"><b> Mansfield Minerals Inc</b>(MDR-V: $8.80)  Investors who have been betting that the company's Cerro Samenta copper prospect in Argentina's Salta province may turn out to be a multi-billion dollar clone of the La Escondida deposit 100 km to the west in Chile (2.2 billion tonnes 1.6% copper) received a rude shock on August 27 when Bob Bishop issued Fax Alert #61. The night before <b>Corriente Resources Inc</b> (CTQ-T: $4.40) had announced the staking acquisition of 60,000 ha adjacent to Mansfield's Cerro Samenta property. What caught Bishop's attention was an option to acquire 100% of 6,000 ha from a private party for 2 million shares and US $1,350,000 cash in stages. A payment of $150,000 was due September 4, with anything further "subject to confirmation of satisfactory claim title". Beyond a statement that these claims cover an "area of known porphyry copper mineralization" there was nothing in the release to indicate that it was something special. But after talking to both Corrien! te and Mansfield Bishop concluded that Mansfield's "Escondida" lookalike prospect was actually owned by a local prospector who had optioned it to Corriente. In other words, Corriente was a buy because it had latched onto title to what had been touted by Mansfield and Teck as a major copper discovery, and Mansfield, whose price already implied a project valuation of $400 million for Cerro Samenta, was a sell because it probably lacked title to the grassroots discovery the Leask brothers had made as a result of the regional exploration program initiated in 1994. Bishop's Fax Alert caused Mansfield to plunge before the VSE halted trading and forced Mansfield to make a release on the property dispute. In Kaiser Express 96-8 I suggested that Mansfield could emerge as another major success story for the Canadian juniors, though I felt that the stock's price was ahead of the facts, which consisted of two large geophysical anomalies, a copper-porphyry geological setting, some high grade s! urface samples, and undisclosed trench values. Mansfield was featured as a $0.50-0.75 bottom-fish in the Nov-Dec 94 issue of the Kaiser Bottom-Fishing Report, and to those individuals who still held a position I suggested that they hang on for a homerun. This new property dispute, however, requires me to reassess the wisdom of hanging onto Mansfield.
<P>
I have talked to Mansfield's Gordon and John Leask as well as Corriente's Ken Shannon. I was unable to obtain an articulate description from Ken Shannon about the dispute, and came away with the impression that the Samenta option is somebody else's idea. As of July Corriente management owned only 738,000 shares (Shannon = 604,000) out of 19.6 million fully diluted shares, plus options on a further 980,000 shares. There are no 10% or bigger shareholders. Last March Corriente completed a private placement of 3 million units at $3.50 brokered by James Capel and First Marathon. My guess is that it was not Ken Shannon, whose strength lies in the technical arena, who talked this financing into existence. While mineral exploration is a dog-eat-dog business, it is out of character for a straight-shooter like Shannon to embark on a deposit snatch campaign without having an intimate understanding of the case, or, if he does, be unwilling to convey it. I don't know from whom Bob Bisho! p got his version, and why at this stage he sides so heavily with Corriente, but the details he has presented collide seriously with the version I obtained from the Leask brothers. Truth lies in the coherence of details, and the most detailed side of the story has come from the Leask brothers, though I must confess that I found their sketchiness on certain names and dates perturbing. I am not convinced that I have the full story, but I do believe the presentation below accurately depicts the story as told to me by the Leask brothers. Since I cannot verify any part of it, acceptance will have to be based on a judgement about the integrity of the Leask brothers. At the very least, I hope it will coax greater details from both sides of the dispute so that investors can intelligently take sides.
<P>
According to Mansfield's John Leask, the Cerro Samenta property was discovered late 1994 when the exploration crew found copper exotica float while walking a road cut in Argentina's Salta province. Upon further investigation Mansfield discovered porphyry style copper mineralization in two areas now known as the North and South Cerro Samenta properties. Mansfield checked out the title status, discovered that the area covered by the North Cerro Samenta showing was open, and made successful cateo application in November 1994. Mansfield noted that the South Cerro Samenta area was covered by a claim held by an individual whose identity Leask could not recall off the top of his head (personally, if I were in his shoes and possibly standing on a multi-billion dollar Escondida lookalike, such details would be etched into my memory). Mansfield also noticed that the government map showed a cateo applied for in February 1994 by a Jorge Darocca directly on top of the South Cerro Sament! a area. Mansfield checked out the coordinates and discovered that the map location of Darocca's cateo was inconsistent with the cateo's documented description. An official informed them that the claim location maps were notoriously unreliable. In any case, and this is a key aspect of Mansfield's claim that Corriente has zero chance of securing title to South Cerro Samenta, the ground to which Darocca supposedly laid claim in February 1994 was at that time controlled by a valid cateo held by a third party (the Mystery Man) and thus was not available. The Leasks decided to monitor the status of the underlying cateo, which apparently was cancelled in late 1995. Mansfield promptly applied for a cateo to cover the South Cerro Samenta area. This waiting game appears to be a key reason why Mansfield's enthusiasm for Cerro Samenta was muted until early 1996. According to the Leasks Darocca did not start kicking up a fuss until July 1996 when he connected with a North American predator who!  specializes in claim disputes. This group, whose desire to keep its identity secret the Leasks inexplicably feel obliged to respect, did its due diligence and apparently concluded that Darocca's claim was a non-starter. Once it became clear that Darocca was determined to pursue his claim, arrangements were made for a government survey to establish the actual claim locations. Because Mansfield had verified its claim location with GPS coordinates, there was no question that Mansfield's South Cerro Samenta claim was properly located. Darocca, however, did not use GPS to verify his coordinates. The government official's unofficial interpretation of the reference points used by Darocca placed his claim at best within 700 metres of Mansfield's South Cerro Samenta, and at worst 4.6 km away. In this respect Bishop's Fax Alert has the problem backwards: it is the reference points for Darocca's cateo that are in question, not those for Mansfield. Nobody disputes that Darocca's cateo is valid. The dispute boils down to the actual physical coordinates of the cateo. Darocca appears to believe that the map defines the location, but apparently it is the written description that defines the location. At this stage the  "judge's" decision is not yet official, but the innuendo has already been floated by the Corriente camp that the decision was fixed in the Argentine tradition of corruption. For Corriente to win control of South Cerro Samenta via its option on Darocca's 6,000 ha cateo, at least two things have to be established: one, Darocca's cateo actually covers the area of South Cerro Samenta, and, two, this ground was open when Darocca made application for a cateo. Unfortunately, and I find this quite annoying, neither Mansfield nor Corriente is willing or able to provide claim maps depicting their respective perceptions of reality.<BR><BR>
<P>
One conclusion I can draw at this stage is that even if Darocca's version of his claim location turns out to be correct, it apparently covers only the South Samenta anomaly. The property has two IP high, Mag low, resistivity anomalies. The North Samenta has dimensions of about 1 km by 1.6 km, with an exposed window of supergene chalcocite mineralization at the southern end. Trench samples from this area were sent in for assaying in mid-May. The second anomaly has a similar intensity with dimensions of 1 km by 2 km, located 4 km to the south of the North Samenta anomaly. This area has a known copper showing which may have been the target of Darocca's staking effort in early 1994. The geological model is that the Cerro Samenta hosts two possibly connected copper porphyry systems that have extensively leached caps. The theory is that the leaching process led to supergene enrichment below the low grade leach cap (ie the initial chalcopyrite copper mineralization was dissolved b! y percolating water and precipitated out as chalcocite at a deeper level), and the hope is that Cerro Samenta hosts a thick blanket of high grade chalcocite similar to that at Escondida, whose thickest section ran 250 metres of 3% copper. If the IP anomalies represent thick, high grade copper mineralization, and Darocca's cateo is verified in Corriente's favour, then Mansfield would end up with the northern half and Corriente with the southern half. In other words, the worst case scenario for Mansfield does not leave Mansfield and Teck (earning 60%) out of the picture.
<P>
On August 30 Mansfield finally released assays for the 11 trenches sampled earlier this year. 8 trenches were barren because they exposed the copper-depleted leached capping. Trenches 98E and 100N, which are perpendicular to each other, cut the "potassic core" and averaged 123 m of 0.51% copper and 93 m of 0.47% copper respectively. This mineralization, whose grade is probably subeconomic, is not the target. Trench 93N yielded 48 m of 0.45% copper, which represents an average of both leached capping and supergene enrichment. Grades for 3 metre intervals reached as high as 1.6% copper where supergene material was present. The trench results look disappointing, but at this stage they are meaningless. What Cerro Samenta needs is drill holes that establish the presence of a chalcocite blanket with a meaningful thickness grading 1% or higher copper. A drilling program is expected to begin in mid-September. In the case of drilling the Escondida prospect in 1981, significant miner! alization was not hit until the sixth hole. Given the high expectations already built into Mansfield's price, a market that has already become leery about Teck's tortoise-like assaying and results releasing policies, and the title uncertainty that clouds at least part of the Cerro Samenta prospect, it is my view that profit-taking above the $5 level would be a prudent strategy. As for Corriente, if the "judge" makes his survey interpretation official, which reportedly favours Mansfield, it will require lengthy litigation to establish title. Because of the deal Corriente cut with Darocca, its only exposure will be the $150,000 payment and direct legal costs. Because Corriente does not have any other prospects that obviously justify the $80-100 million market cap the stock is presently sporting, I expect Corriente to pursue this issue indefinitely to keep shareholders from unloading Corriente in favour of cheaper Latin American alternatives. Until a much clearer picture emerges about the legal potential of Corriente's Darocca option, shareholders should use the current market strength to lighten up on Corriente. 
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Hi"><font size=+1> <b>Highwood:</b> chronic beryllium disease lawsuits spell trouble for Brush Wellman</font size>
<P>
Readers of the August 25 New York Times may have noted an article by Barry Meier entitled "The Dark Side of a Magical Metal" which spanned nearly two full pages. The focus of the article was chronic beryllium disease, a respiratory ailment caused by exposure to airborne beryllium particles. Beryllium is the specialty metal that <b>Highwood Resources Ltd</b> (HWD-T: $1.14, HIWDF-NASDAQ) hopes to bring into production. The merger between Mountain Minerals and Highwood has been completed and has put Royal Oak in firm control of the Thor Lake beryllium deposit. The NYT article is relevant to Highwood because its target is <b>Brush Wellman Inc</b> (BW-N: $19, 15.9 million issued), the world's largest producer of pure beryllium and beryllium alloys with sales of $370 million in 1995. Exposure to beryllium is harmless except for about 1-5% of the population which has an immunological vulnerability to beryllium believed to have a genetic root. In 1949 the United States established a maximum work! place standard of 2 micrograms per cubic metre on which Brush Wellman has leaned heavily ever since. Actual cases of CBD have been treated as caused by exposure through accident or negligence. But by the mid-eighties evidence had begun to emerge that factory employees such as secretaries who never came physicially in contact with beryllium nevertheless had developed beryllium sensitivity and in some cases come down with CBD. Sensitivity to beryllium causes scar tissue to build up in the lungs that reduces the ability to absorb oxygen and eventually kills the victim. The NYT article featured a picture of three victims with tubes up their noses permanently attached to oxygen tanks. By 1990 Brush Wellman was aware that the federal standard may be inadequate. Since then victims have launched a spate of lawsuits claiming compensation. The official party line is that the resolution of these cases will have no material affect on the company. Indeed, a class action suit filed April 2, 1996 was dismissed on July 12, 1996, though the time limit for filing an appeal has not expired. However, the thrust of the NYT article was that Brush Wellman ignored the warning signs and may not escape substantial liability claims. My interpretation of the situation is that the potential for ballooning CBD compensation claims is not going to go away. In a worst case scenario Brush Wellman may find itself in financial jeopardy, a development that would help break its dominant grip on the beryllium marke! t. But even if this does not happen overnight, the liability threat may soften up the vicious circle that has prevented alternative beryllium producers from breaking into the market. That vicious circle is the reluctance of industrial users to sign supply contracts with would-be producers for fear that failure of the alternative production to come on stream could leave the user stranded without a secure supply of beryllium. The inability to secure purchase commitments, not economic feasibility, was the reason Hecla decided in 1990 not to proceed with development of Thor Lake. To some degree Brush Wellman's control of the market is already under siege, as indicated by an anti-dumping complaint it filed against a Kazakhstan producer. Against this backdrop of offshore production and Brush Wellman's contingent liability problems, industrial users will likely be less afraid to offend Brush Wellman by entertaining purchase commitments for beryllium from new potential producers like High! wood. Highwood recently visited the Thor Lake property and has initiated permitting for removal of a bulk sample presently stored on the site. Highwood plans to use the sample for metallurgical testing and marketing. Should we be worried about the CBD liability risk the Thor Lake deposit may pose for Highwood? Not really. Genetic screening can identify most individuals who should never be near the stuff. As for airborne exposure, tougher standards will be developed and implemented. For litigation to be successful against Brush Wellman, the plaintiffs will have to prove that Brush Wellman suppressed information and knowledge that the federal standards were inadequate. Success will hinge on legal theories about the extent of Wellman's obligation to investigate the inadequacy of federal standards, and during the course of such investigations to warn employees that they may have a serious CBD risk even though all health and safety standards are being met.
<P>
Highwood has 18.1 million (20.1 million fully diluted) shares issued. The sloppiness in the market is typical of a merger where shareholders of one of the companies suffered a rollback. Between now and the end of the year I expect the stock to creep towards $2. Management will not promote the Thor Lake story until it has reached a deal with owners of a 30% reversion right. If Thor Lake is not in production by 2000, which it definitely will not be,  a 30% working interest reverts to a pair of offshore investors who funded Highwood during its early days. Since this group is not interested in contributing costs, and is a sizable shareholder in Highwood, a deal which leaves them with some sort of carried interest and assures fast-track development is a sensible course. Once such a deal is announced, we can expect Highwood to acquire a much higher profile. Highwood now has a solid base as an industrial minerals producer, a beachhead in China where it is exploring various rare ea! rth and specialty metal opportunities, the flagship beryllium Thor Lake deposit, and the 100% owned Ilimaussaq yttrium deposit in Greenland it also plans to develop. This Nasdaq-listed package is bound to be an easy sell; subscribers of the Premium Kaiser Express should take a serious look at Highwood before it rises onto the radar screen of American brokers.
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Vo"><font size=+1><b>Voisey's Bay East:</b> stirring the pot with unsubstantiated rumours</font size>
<P>
<b>Columbia Yukon</b> (CYR-C: $1.00) and <b>Intl Canalaska</b> (ICA-V: $1.14) came to life Friday August 22 on rumours that Diamond Fields (Inco) had intersected massive sulphides at about a 600 metre depth only 500 metres from the Columbia Yukon boundary. Although this rumour generated plenty of buying activity, it could not be confirmed. At this stage all that can be said is that grid lines for geophysical surveys have been cut right to the boundary. Columbia Yukon hopes to have permits in hand shortly to begin drilling a 3,000 ft hole in mid-September. Because of the recent interest by the likes of Falconbridge and Inco in optioning ground to the east of the main Voisey's Bay block, intense curiousity has developed about what the rocks do in the third dimension. This first of six proposed holes by Columbia Yukon will be watched very closely, not for broad intersections of massive sulphides, but for geological variety revealing that a lot more is going on at depth to the east than the older anorthosites on surface might suggest. If the drill logs showed the presence of gneisses and troctolite at depth, speculation would build rapidly about how far eastwards the Eastern Deeps nickel-copper ore does extend. That explains the market's strong response to the "500-metres-from-the-boundary" rumour. While Columbia Yukon indicates that potential suitors for the VBE-1 block appear to have gone away, rumours persist that <b>NDT Ventures</b> (NDE-V: $1.25) and <b>Lucero Res Corp</b> (LCR-V: $1.16) are wrangling with Inco on a farmout deal. By now no junior will do a deal with Inco that does not include an anti-inventory clause, typically in the form of no vesting of any interest unless the property is in commercial production by a certain date. If indeed a deal between Inco and Lucero/NDT does materialize over the next month or so, it would likely be a very aggressive one. For a while at least the notion that Inco was sandbagging the VBE-1 claims would send Columbia Yukon and Intl Canalaska soaring. However, there is another way to interpret an aggressive Inco deal. At best such a deal would secure Inco a 60% interest, less than the 75:25 split of the Voisey's Bay ore it shares with Voisey's Bay Nickel Co. Inco has enough nickel ore to do serious damage to the nickel market. Without a doubt it will do its best to squeeze its competitors by flooding the market with low-cost Ovoid ore, thought not to such an extreme as to render its other nickel operations hopelessly sub-economic. Any scenario which forces Inco to replace Ovoid ore with more expensive ore from another property would be contrary to Inco's interest. But this scenario would still be preferable to one where a competitor gets hold of Voisey's Bay East ore and cranks it into production at ma! ximum throughput. An aggressive deal need not mean that Inco is convinced that the Eastern Deeps extends beyond the main DFR block. Inco may think that there is probably nothing on this ground, but as a form of insurance it is tying up the ground long enough to rule out the remote possibility that high grade ore is present. In other words, Inco views the "need" to get vested as only a small risk, which it nevertheless must take on. This subtlety, however, will be lost on most investors, who will greet such a deal as a powerful endorsement of the Voisey's Bay East hypothesis. Columbia Yukon would be the primary beneficiary, because its right to earn 70% by carrying the property to production makes it the obvious takeover target if ore was found on the VBE-1 claim. Over the next eight weeks Columbia Yukon will emerge as a hot trader, especially if initial drilling on VBE-1 demonstrates that this area has very interesting geological potential for nickel-copper ore, either in the form!  of mineralization hosted by basal remnants of a magma chamber or feeder dyke extensions. The best way to play Voisey's Bay East is to tuck away cash-rich Lucero for the long haul, and buy Columbia Yukon as a short-term speculation. At current prices the market isn't putting too much Voisey's Bay faith in Lucero, so the damage from a flop is minimal. In the case of Columbia Yukon, the downside risk is serious, but the upside leverage is exceptional. Both stocks are strong contenders to at least double before the end of the year. Contrarians might take a look at NDT, which is finally in a price range where the leverage is reasonable. NDT has sufficient working capital to generate fresh news on other fronts, or tag along in the Staghorn lake area if the Cdn States/Cartaway drilling lucks into some significant massive sulphides. NDT can easily bounce back from its current oversold position and yield a double.
<P>
<P>
<b>Brief updates on other fronts</b>
<P>
Wedge drilling by <b>Cons Callinan Flin-Flon</b> (CFF-V: $2.35) is closing in on another down-hole geophysics target the company expects to hit by the end of the first week of September. We are still looking for 20 metre plus intersections of high grade copper. With <b>Fancamp Resources Inc</b> (FNM-V: $1.47) on the rise, <b>Freewest Resources Canada</b> (FWR-TM: $1.14) looks like a smart buy, especially in view of a recent announcement that it has staked a new copper-nickel-cobalt prospect in Quebec 275 km northeast of Chibougamau. High grade copper-nickel-cobalt showings were discovered through followup prospecting of geophysical anomalies identified within a 40 km by 5 km corridor of layered anorthosite.<b> Arizona Star</b> (AZS-V: $12.85) and <b>Bema Gold</b> (BGO-T: $10.50) have enjoyed a good run thanks to further results from the Cerro Casale copper-gold porphyry deposit in northern Chile. However, the copper grade is low, as is the gold grade outside the high grade breccia zone. I have not had a chanc! e yet to look at results in detail, but it strikes me that building ounces out of 0.2-0.3% copper and 0.01-0.03 opt gold mineralization and applying the $50/oz valuation yardstick may be inappropriate. Profit-taking is advisable, though keep in mind that we may be on the threshold of a mania where major mining companies are taking over juniors with increasingly aggressive logic (ie Barrick's takeover of Arequipa).
<P>
