<P>
<H1>KAISER EXPRESS # 96 -- 9</H1>
<P>
Commentary by John Kaiser  ------  July 24, 1996<BR>
<P>
<H2>Beware the Dangling Sword</H2>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="#Ba">Barrick's Takeover Bid for Arequipa another feather in the Canadian junior cap</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Br">Brace yourself for a flood of special warrant conversions.</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Ne">Nearly $10 billion frozen in limbo, waiting to be unleashed by the last quarter.</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Te">Teuton & Minvita: keeping a lid on the Clone Project</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Fa">Fancamp & Freewest: Probing the Great Red Spot</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Ge">Gerle Gold: pipes, come out from wherever you are!</A><BR>
<P>
<P>
In recent weeks I have frequently heard two notions that I believe are dead wrong. One is that a major senior market setback never happens during a US election year, and the other is that the Canadian juniors will enjoy a September rally once the summer doldrums are behind us. I do not believe speculative juniors have any chance of a broad-based revival until New York's Dow Jones index has settled into the 4600-4800 range, and while I cannot predict how swiftly and when this breakdown will happen, I am convinced it will happen before the election. On the assumption that New York will find solid support in the 4600-4800 range, a breakdown below which signals a long term general bear and a terminal prognosis for speculative markets, I think this year August-October will turn out to be prime bottom-fishing season, with a strong spec market rally breaking out in November and carrying into the new year with a boom that may make the first half of 1996 appear like a warmup exercise.<BR>
<P>
While we may credit the likes of Timbuktu and Cartaway with triggering the evaporation of the bull market in speculative juniors, the real culprit keeping speculators on the sidelines is not loss of confidence in the Canadian exploration initiative, but rather anxiety about the fate of the senior equity bull market. The pullback in NASDAQ stocks parallels the Canadian spec market, and has nothing to do with the reasons given for the Canadian bear market. Net mutual fund inflows during the first half of 1996 exceeded the total for 1995, but have now turned negative. The warnings about a major correction are now too obvious to miss, and the cassandras prophecizing an all out redemption run fueled crash are no longer dismissed as a lunatic fringe. From a speculator's viewpoint the prospect of a market meltdown is akin to a sword dangling precariously from a hook on the wall. If your head is exposed and the sword falls, your head will be lopped off.
Count on the September Rally to be a no-show.
<P>	
Last year's Voisey's Bay driven spec market was interrupted by a similar fear I labelled downdraft anxiety. Last year, however, we were treated to a September rally, an annually predicted event that only occasionally materializes. The September rally theory is premised on the idea that brokers and investors go on holiday during the summer while the juniors head into the field to conduct work programs. The absence of results and market interest is explained as the summer doldrums. When people go back to work in September and results start to flow, market activity is supposed to rekindle. The problem with the Canadian exploration juniors is that the seasonal half-full to half-empty cycle is a very powerful pattern. By definition a September rally is shortlived. The cups must be emptied before they can be refilled to the half-way mark for the next year's cycle. Anticipation of this psychological necessity inevitably turns the "September Rally" into a selling binge. In years where everybody has their pink tickets ready for the September Rally, it turns into a no-show. This year's September Rally is shaping up to be a no-show because the junior spec market did not crash, but simply disappeared. The bids disappeared so quickly everybody was hung before they knew it. Daily volume on the VSE has dropped below 20 million shares and brokers are grumbling about how dead things are. At today's close of 1104 the VSE Composite Index is still up 39% for the year, but we might as well accept that it will not take much for the VSE to be back in the bottom-fishing range of 750-800. The lack of liquidity has kept the Canadian juniors from collapsing, but this is an illusion that a senior market meltdown would shatter as it prompts investors to seek liquidity at any price. Speculators are now in the mode of waiting patiently for bids to reappear which they can fill.<BR>
<P>
What the Canadian juniors need is the sword off the wall and on the floor. This is where the supposed election year sanctity of the stock market becomes troublesome, for if true, we speculators are in for a long bear market. There seem to be two reasons why Americans have great faith the market will not crash during an election year. One is the empirical observation that it has never done so and thus never will, and the other is that the President is so powerful he can actually control the stock market's behaviour. Both reasons are nonsense. The stock market is an organism that not only responds to external stimuli, but also generates stimuli that spawn feedback loops with potentially chaotic outcomes. It is precisely because the market is conscious of its own patterns, some of which are at odds with the market's interest and thus undesirable, that the market's behaviour can become unpredictable. When the market achieves a high degree of self-consciousness, as it now has, even the contrarians have to throw up their hands in despair. This year we have witnessed a struggle between the market's awareness of being over-valued and the belief that it will not respond negatively to this condition until after the presidential election. However, once the election has happened this struggle no longer exists, and unless the market no longer feels itself over-valued by conventional yardsticks, the market should be expected to head downwards big time. Because the market is well aware of this destiny, it will discount this outcome well before its time has arrived. This is the sword speculators have been anxiously eyeing for several months now.<BR>
<P>	
What makes the sword so troubling is the concern that a market correction may spiral out of control into a vicious circle of asset deflation and corresponding recessionary economic behaviour. If New York breaks below 4600 the next stop is 4000, by which time speculation in Canadian exploration juniors will be a vague memory. A rapid move to 4600, however, will likely mobilize the central bank to inject liquidity by slashing interest rates and re-establishing stability. The US Fed has indicated that it believes the strength of the US economy is attributable to the undue economic confidence the equity bull market has instilled among investors. During the eighties consumers spent on the basis of inflated real estate values. During the nineties they are spending on the basis of inflated investment portfolios. Greenspan's agenda is likely to cool down investment growth as an engine of inflationary economic growth, not destroy it. If during the next three months we see a rapid decline in the Dow to the 4600-4800 level accompanied by a successful stabilization effort, it will translate into the turning point for speculative Canadian juniors. If this happens before the election, then no matter who is president, 1997 will see a resumption of the long run equity uptrend. The next president, barring a tragedy, will usher in the next millenium. We should not overlook the psychological impact the millenium countdown could have for both the stock market and economy, on a global scale. Resource stocks have not yet had their day in the sun.
<P>
The collapse of copper and the return of gold to its trading rut have tempered enthusiasm for resource exploration plays, but these are short term developments of relevance only to producers and near-producers. The importance of the Canadian exploration juniors is that they find valuable new orebodies. In addition to the world-class success stories of Diamond Fields, Bre-X, and Dia Met, we now can add Arequipa Resources. While Arequipa's Pierina deposit in Peru is not yet a proven world-class orebody, Barrick's $27 per share cash takeover bid certainly is world-class. The $915 million bid is an aggressive move by Barrick I hope is not driven by the same jilted bride thinking that moved Placer Dome to buy out Mt Milligan after failing to lock up Eskay Creek through its bid for Stikine. Barrick is rumoured to have snubbed Bre-X during its early days, and to have been in turn snubbed by Bre-X when it later informally offered 5-6 Barrick shares for 1 pre-split Bre-X share.<BR>
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Ba"><font size=+1>Barrick's Takeover Bid for Arequipa another feather in the Canadian junior cap</font size>
<P>
Since it is unlikely another gold major will slug it out with Barrick for the right to find the missing root of the decapitated Pierina deposit, the takeover bid will likely be accepted. I suspect that the only reason Arequipa has not yet publicly embraced the $27 offer is because certain shareholders would prefer the option of a tax free rollover into Barrick stock. The one ploy Arequipa may pursue is to convince Barrick to allow Pierina to be separated from the rest of the property portfolio assembled by David Lowell, such as Mac Watson did with Freewest and Harker-Holloway. I suspect, however, that Barrick is paying the big premium for the whole works, not just Pierina. If so, it will signal how important the Canadian junior exploration effort has become in the eyes of the majors. This will not be a case of a major having to buy out a $5 billion nickel-copper deposit from a junior which had the good luck of listening to an accountant who argued it would look better if a US $88,000 option payment was made just before year end so that a $500,000 exploration expenditure could remain on the books. It would be a tribute to the ingenuity and agility of juniors in assembling prospects in third world frontiers.
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Br"><font size=+1>Brace yourself for a flood of special warrant conversions</font size>
<P>	
The Canadian junior spec market is presently suffering from a severe lack of liquidity that I fear will not be remedied before the last quarter. Until the senior market sword has clanged harmlessly to the floor, I recommend  a defensive strategy of selling both winners and losers while keeping stocks with limited downside and projects that won't be made or broken until next year. I expect at least one more major downward lurch in the juniors coinciding with a further senior market decline before a true bottom is created. A bottom in September and October followed by a rally in November would be a deviation from the typical pattern, and certainly inconvenient for my upcoming November-December 1996 Bottom-Fish List. Speculators should be preparing their own bottom-fish wish lists right now and be ready to start accumulating them as their downtrending chart patterns bottom out into troughs. In particular they should watch well-financed and still expensive juniors who loaded their treasuries during the first half with special warrant financings. Many of these stocks have tiers of cheaper private placements that are now coming free trading, and, in the style of Essex, we can expect this paper to drive prices lower before the institutions get their special warrants converted. It appears that institutional investors have to carry their special warrants at cost until they are converted to free trading paper through the receipting of a qualifying prospectus. That was a curse during the uptrend when the mutual fund's NAV was not permitted to show paper profits, but is a blessing as stock prices head underwater. However, now that the spec market is bearish and mutual fund holders are turning cranky, you can bet that fund managers will be eager to get losing positions off the books before anybody notices and starts asking the manager about what possessed them to buy this stock at that price. While the managements of junior companies are generally not anxious to speed the prospectus along, they now have reason to get the job done and the sell-offs over with while there is still a crummy bear market to blame for the lack of liquidity.
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Ne"><font size=+1>Nearly $10 billion frozen in limbo, waiting to be unleashed by the last quarter</font size>
<P>	
There are a couple other reasons for my forecast that the spec market is due for a rally in the last quarter when it would normally be under pressure from tax-loss selling and the empty cup blues. The current slump is giving investors plenty of time to generate losses to match their profits. The quest for offsetting losses will help stocks lower during the next few months. Consider also that between Diamond Fields, Bre-X and Arequipa there is about $10 billion in new hard wealth that is sort of frozen. The Diamond Fields/Inco merger is on hold until at least August 31 pending resolution of the Exdiam lawsuit. Inco's Mike Sopke, ridiculed for being outwitted by Friedland, has had the last laugh as he watches Friedland twist in the wind. Under the pretense that a Texas lawsuit might actually succeed in its claim that everything anybody ever did for Diamond Fields was really for the benefit of Exdiam Corp, in which Jean Boulle's family has a 23.5% interest, and not for the benefit of Diamond Fields shareholders, Inco has refused to close its merger with Diamond Fields. To ensure its dominant role in the world nickel market Inco is paying a 200-300% strategic premium for Voisey's Bay. The longer control of Voisey's Bay stays out of anybody else's hands without Inco having to pay anything, the better off is Inco. Even in a worst case scenario where a Texas jury awarded Voisey's Bay to Exdiam, Inco has nothing to worry about because it is unlikely the Canadian government, smarting over the imperialistic ambitions of the Helms-Burton anti-Cuba law, would allow a Canadian deposit scooped by a US court to be turned into a cash cow that would destroy a Canadian icon like Inco. The Exdiam legal dispute has escalated into a battle of titanic egos that is beyond an out-of-court settlement. When it becomes apparent that the Exdiam lawyers cannot extract a payoff to go away, they will likely drop the Voisey's Bay deposit ownership claim from the suit and concentrate on winning some or all of the paper Boulle and Friedland own. While just about everybody's hackles are raised by Exdiam's broader claim, only a handful care about the outcome of a dispute between Friedland/Boulle and Exdiam. How much beyond August 31 Inco can stall the merger is unclear, especially since Falconbridge has recently rattled its chains to indicate that it is still interested in acquiring Voisey's Bay. But I am confident the Exdiam litigators will pave the way enabling the merger to close.<BR>
<P>
I expect Diamond Fields shareholders to get liquidity by the last quarter of 1996. By then Bre-X may also have entered an arrangement which gives Bre-X shareholders security that the entire value of their investment is not at risk of going up in smoke thanks to a political conflagration in Indonesia. The Arequipa deal will also have put nearly $1 billion into the jeans of shareholders, many of whom will be Canadian residents with a sudden need for flow-thru deductions. All this liquidity could arrive on the scene just when the Canadian juniors are breaking out of a bottom. Assuming the US Fed's stock market tinkering doesn't wreck both the economy and the market, the stage will have been set for an extraordinary year in 1997. Meanwhile, all we can do is wait and keep are powder dry. 
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Te"><font size=+1>Teuton & Minvita: keeping a lid on the Clone Project</font size>
<P>	
One of the nice things about bear markets is that market activity tends to be driven by results, not trends. It is much easier to spot unusual activity possibly indicative of good news leaking out. Several weeks ago Teuton Resources Corp (TUO-V: $2.40) and Minvita Enterprises (MVE-V: $2.35) spiked up at a time when most of the market was hurrying south. It looked very much like excited drill crew coming out of the bush hoping to make a quick buck but oblivious to the fact that the wind was blowing the wrong way. The stocks pulled back but stabilized and did not develop the downtrend characteristic of this market. A news release on July 19 indicated that 28 holes comprising 12,000 ft had been drilled, of which 5,000 ft was at the lab for assaying. The release was prompted by a bizarre Navarre release reporting that "rumours of...GOBS OF GOLD are to be heard in the bars, cafe's, in the grocery stores and at the gas stations all over town (Stewart)". Teuton's Dino "the Clam" Cremonese was not very helpful beyond saying that 7% shareholder Homestake was happy. While it is likely that visible gold was intersected at the Clone Project, the real story here is zone structure, with the assays of almost secondary significance when they eventually arrive. I think the Clone project will be a big newsmaker during the next four months and suggest that it would be a good idea to nibble at the stocks below $2.50, with preference, subject to liquidity, given to Minvita.
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Fa"><font size=+1>Fancamp & Freewest: Probing the Great Red Spot</font size>
<P>
Fancamp Resources Ltd (FNM-V: $1.25) and. Freewest Resources Canada (FWR-T: $1.10) have completed airborne magnetic surveys over 370 km of the Kalahari Suture Zone in Botswana. According to Fancamp's Peter Smith much of the KSZ has been interpreted to have a 200-400 metre cover of sediments and Kalahari Sands, not as shallow as we might have wished, but certainly not as deep as Smith might have feared. MPH's analysis has identified numerous targets interpreted as potential ultramafic intrusives or carbonatites, confirming the theory of Bob Mason and Peter Smith that the KSZ represents perhaps the greatest untested mineral frontier in the deposit rich continent of Africa. Fancamp's Botswana Elephant Hunt may turn out to be the coup of the next century. Beyond speculative geophysical interpretation the only exploration tool is drilling, and because of the sheer quantity of targets and expense of prospecting with a drill, Fancamp and Freewest plan to carve the KSZ into segments and farm out exploration to majors and possibly other juniors. One phenomenal target on the 50:50 Fancamp/Freewest Central Block that consists of an intense 10 by 13 km magnetic feature will not be farmed out. Dubbed the "Great Red Spot", this target sits at the juncture of the KSZ and the Zambezi Rift, a prime location for a layered intrusive complex. The target happens to straddle the boundary of a claim block acquired by Falconbridge last year after it spent six weeks reviewing data Fancamp supplied supporting the theory that the KSZ may be highly prospective for base metal deposits. Readers of the January-February 1996 issue of the Kaiser Bottom-Fishing Report may recall that Falconbridge considered this a brilliant idea it intended to pursue for its own account, though it did ungenerously offer Fancamp the opportunity to earn an interest in any ground Falconbridge would acquire by assuming the exploration funding burden. As it turned out, thanks to Mac Watson's Freewest poor Smith and Fancamp weren't as down and out as Falconbridge may have thought. They managed to scoop most of the KSZ before Falconbridge made its move, and would have acquired the two blocks Falconbridge did get if it hadn't been for a misunderstanding about the availability of this ground. The Great Red Spot may be just a big blob of iron, or it could be a monster deposit that puts Voisey's Bay to shame. Fancamp and Freewest plan to drill several deep geological holes into this target before yearend in an effort to obtain a better understanding of the underlying formation. Because of the anomaly's size investors should not hold their breath in expectation of a discovery hole into the guts of an orebody. Just a bit of base, precious or platinum metals smoke will be sufficient to drive speculators and the majors wild. In light of the airborne magnetic survey results I am very optimistic that eventually Fancamp and Freewest will make a major discovery in the KSZ. However, it may take years to make or break this story. At this stage every speculator should make an effort to have at least some exposure to the KSZ play either through Fancamp or Freewest, and then hope that these stocks go down in price. A rule of thumb for the current market is to buy or hold only stocks you wish would go down so that you can own more at a cheaper price. The only juniors which qualify for this strategy are those whose medium term work programs are funded, whose story is not at risk of being destroyed by near term results, and which have the potential to become very expensive overnight thanks to the arrival of results or a highly receptive audience. In the case of the Botswana elephant hunt, it is worth noting that Fancamp and Freewest have yet to benefit from investors who have cashed in their Diamond Fields chips for solid Inco paper.  I see no urge to chase either Fancamp or Freewest above $1.30, and will be personally hoping the stocks drift down to the $0.60-0.70 level between now and the end of the year. 
<P>
<P>
<a name="Ge"><font size=+1>Gerle Gold: pipes, come out from wherever you are!</font size>
<P>	
Investors have not taken kindly to the failure of Gerle Gold Ltd (GGL-V: $1.35) to intersect kimberlite this summer. On June 26 Gerle announced that it had killed 32 out of 40 priority geophysical targets by drilling or surface inspection. The market, thinking that Gerle was moving from high priority to low priority targets, was not happy. What many investors did not appreciate is that because kimberlite is softer than the country rock in the Slave Craton, glaciers will have preferentially gouged out the kimberlite to form holes that show up as lakes or swampy depressions in the NWT. Land-based geophysical targets thus have a lower probability of being kimberlite. So why did Gerle start picking off land-based targets instead of angle drilling lake targets? By the time Gerle mobilized in May, the ice was too soft for ski-equipped planes to transport a heavy diamond drill. So Monopros told Gerle to fly in a lighter reverse circulation drill and, instead of having the crew twi!
 ddle its thumbs, dispatch the crew on what amounted to a condemnation campaign. I interpret this decision as a sign of how serious Monopros is about Gerle's Doyle Lake project. By July the lakes in the NWT were free of ice and Gerle was able to fly in a diamond drill rig using a float equipped plane. Gerle has not revealed how many lake targets it has angle drilled and what degree of success it has obtained. Reading between the lines I suspect Gerle has come up empty. So from where do the indicator minerals come from? It may be that the geophysical techniques so far applied are irrelevant. Gerle has indicated it is still experimenting with different geophysical approaches. It also appears that Monopros is pursuing a strategy of ever more closely spaced sampling in an effort to pinpoint threads and their terminals within the overall paintbrush-like swath. In the end Gerle may have to drill fences until it hits kimberlite. If this is the case and there are pipes on the property, it is only a matter of time before a discovery is made. However, the not so pleasant scenario that has started to haunt me is the possibility that small dykes may have shed the indicator minerals on Gerle's property. A diamond studded dyke is not likely to be regarded by Monopros as an economic resource. What I don't know is whether small dykes can shed the sort of train Gerle has identified. Until we hear Gerle has explained its indicator minerals through a series of small dykes, there is still hope for an overnight breakthrough. The cup is certainly half-empty for Gerle and seems on an unveering course towards emptiness. At this stage all I can say is hold your positions and hope the stock's price gets real cheap so that we can load up just before the stock gets halted.  No statement or expression of opinion, or any other matter herein, directly or indirectly, is an offer to buy or sell the securities mentioned.  While we believe the sources of information to be reliable, we in no way represent or guarantee the accuracy thereof, nor the statements contained herein.<BR>
<P>
