<P>
<H1>KAISER EXPRESS # 96 -- 8</H1>
<P>
Commentary by John Kaiser  ------  June 24, 1996<BR>
<P>
<H2>A Junior Spec Market In need of Leadership</H2>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="#Mo">Mountain Minerals: buy now if you fear a hurricane</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Ge">Gerle Gold: Boyd Warner ownership uncertainty to continue.</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Mou">Mountain Province: under Timbuktu pressure.</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Pe">Peruvian Gold and Laramide </A><BR>
<P>
<P>
A delayed reaction to the Cartaway and Timbuktu disasters slammed the Canadian juniors in early June. The chart pattern for the VSE index and virtually every active junior turned into a cliff-hanger as the seller's strike broke and buyers went on strike. The fallout from these examples of speculative frenzy completely out of control combined with two other serious trend reversals. Copper, whose recent volatility and inexplicable price strength during the past year had confounded metals analysts, broke down when it was revealed that a Sumitomo trader had racked up $1.8 billion in losses and a hoard of copper inventory in an apparent scheme to manipulate the copper market. Gold also broke down below $390 when inflation data showed that inflationary pressure was not yet apparent in the US economy, which was clicking along very nicely in terms of job creation. Since the latter must inevitably give rise to inflation, the conclusion is that interest rates can only head higher, ma! king comparative equity and debt yields as well as bottom-lines poorer. Add to that the andecdotal stories about stock buying waiters and cabbies, "this time is different" and "long live equities" ballads, and the unchecked proliferation of Cartaway style debacles in the NASDAQ market, and you have a hurricane-of-the-century warning for the overall stock market. Because the Canadian junior stock market is a small world with widespread media coverage that ensures nobody misses the message, this sector has taken its reality check to heart early and scurried to the sidelines.<BR>
<P>
What do we do now? The answer is not obvious because the Canadian juniors are usually the last to crash. The speculation game for Canadian juniors is not over until we have a crash on a par with the October 1987 crash. In other words, it's not over until the senior market wails its death song. That song is not scheduled until late this year, though such events are notorious for their unscheduled arrival. Speculators have never successfully pre-empted their own demise. But they are now using the Canadian market's lull as an excuse to do nothing. The summer doldrums are around the corner, and who knows, New York may crash when everybody is on vacation.<BR>
<P>
If you are sitting on big winners like Diamond Fields, Bre-X and Arequipa, now is the time to take profits and use them to pay down mortgages, buy things you can enjoy, add up next April's tax liabilities, and put enough money aside in T-bills to take care of that problem. Then restructure what remains of your portfolio. The most optimistic outlook is that the senior market will demonstrate that the predictions of its imminent demise are completely wrong, even if the US Fed notches up its interest rates. As New York pushes toward 6,000, worries about a crash will subside (not necessarily with justification), and speculators will begin to chase after Canadian resource juniors once more, provided leadership emerges in this market. Right now the Canadian resource junior market is missing a positive trend. Most of the high-flyers have pulled back from their May highs, and now face a host of shareholders muttering: "when it gets back to where it was, I'll sell". The high flyers ! like Arequipa, Farallon and Valerie Gold still have bad risk-reward leverages and cannot head higher without stunning results except in the context of greater fool spirals. To get this chilled out market to warm up, the leadership must come from unexpected quarters.Arizona Star and Mansfield: tomorrow's market kick-starters?<BR><P>
Two examples of potential leaders are Arizona Star Resources Corp (AZS-V: $6.60) and Mansfield Minerals (MDR-V: $9.70). Arizona Star and 50:50 partner Bema Gold have discovered that a huge gold-enriched sulphide copper porphyry resource underlies the Cerro Casale deposit in the Maricunga District of northern Chile. Hole 19 graded 1,805 ft of 0.066 opt gold and 0.68% copper, including 794 ft of 0.123 opt gold and 1.14% copper within breccia, which in turn included a bonanza zone of 188 ft of 0.329 gold and 1.12% copper. Hole 18, 660 ft northeast of #19, intersected 1,037  ft of 0.027 opt gold and 0.12% copper in oxides, and then carried on 972 ft in sulphides that graded 0.024 opt gold and 0.4% copper. Previous drilling had concentrated on an oxide resource to a depth of about 800 ft where a 2 million ounce low grade gold resource had been established. 17 earlier holes had bottomed in copper-gold porphyry mineralization over an area of 2,600 ft by 1,150 ft. What the first tw! o deep holes, #18 and #19, now tell us is that a) Arizona Star has a gold-enriched copper porphyry deposit of the sort seen in the Philippines and Indonesia, and, b) the porphyry contains significant breccia zones that carry high gold grades. The presence of a large copper-gold sulphide resource (100-200 million tonnes) completely changes the focus for Arizona Star, whose oxide gold deposit looked like a marginal production situation. The oxide resource will have to be stripped to get at the sulphide resource, but instead of being a capital cost, it can pay for itself and more while the sulphide resource is developed. A 40,000 ft drill program is now underway to establish grade and tonnage for the sulphide resource. At 42 million fully diluted Arizona Star's $6.60 price implies a project cap of $550 million. Its parent, Bema Gold (BGO-T: $5.45), controls about 30% of Arizona Star and will likely pursue an amalgamation as the project becomes further developed. Arizona Star is heading higher, and should be bought with a $10 near term price target in mind. Bema, which is going through its Refugio producing pains, is a safer alternative. <BR>
<P>
Mansfield Minerals (MDR-V: $9.70), a bottom-fish from my 1995 list, has traded as high as $13 on speculation that it has made a grassroots discovery of an Escondida style copper deposit (2.1 billion tons 1.6% copper) in northern Argentina. Last December Teck optioned 50% of the Cerro Samenta prospect for $9.1 million in cash and exploration over 5 years, with Mansfield having the option of dropping to 40% in exchange for Teck arranging production financing. Teck's Bill Meyer has recently been quoted in the Canadian media as declaring Cerro Samenta as the best copper porphyry prospect he has ever seen. The prospect was discovered in November 1994 when Mansfield's Gordon Leask insisted on walking a fresh roadcut during a regional exploration program. The discovery of "exotica" float led to the discovery of two chalcocite porphyry zones with surface grades as high as 1.5%. The showing was previously undocumented and the company did not make a big deal about the discovery until!  after permit concessions were granted In late 1995. Based on a 50 metre deep canyon that cuts one of the zones, Mansfield estimates that a chalcocite copper enrichment blanket at least 50 metres thick is present on the property. The zones correlate with two distinct geophysical anomalies. Trenching is now underway and rumours suggest that high grade values are being obtained. At 17.2 million fully diluted Mansfield and its 50% interest imply a project cap of $333 million. This may be rich considering that no holes have yet been drilled, but cheap if Cerro Samenta's enrichment blanket ends up having a thickness of 200-250 metres in the style of Escondida 55 miles to the west. Teck hopes to be drilling within a month. I am loathe to recommend buying a stock with a $300 million project cap prior to any drill holes, but I feel comfortable telling anybody who owns it to hang on until we get drill results. Mansfield is an elephant shot that is a strong candidate for the Canadian Junior Icon Club. More so than Arizona Star, Mansfield's success would give the market a big boost. While this may sound like a broken record, a strategic alternative to Mansfield is Lucero Resource Corp (LCR-V: $1.19), Mansfield's former partner in the Argentine exploration initiative. Lucero is still sitting on 350,000 Mansfield shares which will be released from pool in quarterly installments. Lucero has al! ready built its warchest to $6-7 million, so doesn't need to sell the Mansfield paper when it comes free. Lucero has more upside than downside, so owning this stock makes good defensive sense.<BR>
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Mo"><font size=+1>Mountain Minerals: buy now if you fear a hurricane</font size>
<P>
While we wait for the likes of Arizona Star and Mansfield to restore the market's faith in the Canadian junior exploration boom and trigger a resumption in the speculation boom by late summer, the best strategic buy right now which is virtually immune from a market crash are Mountain Minerals (MIM-T: $0.37) and Highwood Resources ltd (HWD-T: $1.32). MIM and HWD have just announced that the merger terms will be 3.521 MIM for 1 HWD. That is worse than a Highwood shareholder such as myself would have preferred, but it is excellent for MIM shareholders. Information circulars have been mailed out and the AGM will be July 31. Royal Oak's John Smrke has indicated that the only source of potential resistance, a pair of Swiss investors who own 1.1 million shares of Highwood, are on side. A deal with them regarding the 30% interest in the Thor Lake project that reverts to them in 2000 is also in the works. The merged company will survive as Highwood, which also trades on NASDAQ under!  HIWDF. I discussed the two companies in the May-June issue of the Kaiser Bottom-Fishing Report (went in the mail June 14) and in Kaiser Express 96-4 on March 29. The outlook is pretty much unchanged, so suffice it for me to say that Royal Oak's goal is to build the merged company into a specialty metals powerhouse. This process will take several years, but the important thing to keep in mind is that Highwood's success will not "happen" because something is "found"; its success will be "made to happen". That is the formula that works best in a bear market. If you don't for a second believe that the best of times for the junior spec boom are still to come, then Mountain Minerals and Highwood are perfect for you. They are at rock bottom and carry virtually no paper overhang. Because Mountain Minerals is by far more liquid, and the merger ratio is only 3.521:1, the best strategy for anybody seeking size is to buy Mountain Minerals to a limit of $0.50. Mountain Minerals can be reached!  at (403) 261-3999 or Royal Oak at (206) 822-8992. Environmental review panel gives nod to Canada's first diamond mine<BR>
<P>
On Friday morning June 21 the Canadian government's NWT environmental assessment review panel released its recommendation that the Dia Met/BHP diamond mine at Lac de Gras be permitted to proceed subject to certain conditions. These conditions appear to be mainly the creation of monitoring bureaucracies to ensure that environmental and socioeconomic impacts do not exceed expectations. The review panel also urges the federal government to get on with land claims settlements and come up with a system to establish when an exploration project is advanced enough to ensure exclusion from settlement selection (the latter is of importance to the overall NWT diamond hunt). The panel also recommends that the government set up procedures for diamond valuation, probably to ensure that NWT diamond production doesn't escape taxation. A formal goahead decision won't be rendered until Cabinet sits again, which won't be until August. From a practical perspective diamond mining in the NWT has!  been given the green light, which should be a boost for other juniors in the region. Given that not much has gone right for the Canadian resource juniors during the past couple months (ie Cartaway, Timbuktu, copper's price collapse, gold's southward trek, extortion lawsuits and the chilling out of Canadian junior spec fever), there has been a sense of caution best described as a tribute to the notion that "when it rains, it pours".<BR>
<P>
One interesting note is a comment in the June 10 Northern Miner which states that the capital cost is now pegged at US $750 million. The BHP and Dia Met agreement says that BHP will arrange financing up to US $500 million. An earlier agreement between Dia Met, Chuck Fipke and Stu Blusson decrees that the latter individuals have a carried interest. The implication is that Dia Met will have to fund 49% of capital costs above $500 million. Dia Met has suffered a low profile because it lacked a fiscal sponsor for the simple reason it didn't need such backing. A window may now be opening for the brokerage industry to get behind Dia Met. The Northern Miner article also stated the hitherto unrevealed $89 carat value for the 0.33 ct/t Leslie Pipe. This value confirms that cash flow for the final 15 years of BHP's 25 year mining plan will pale compared to the first ten years as the plant is fed $34 rock from the Fox and $29 rock from the Leslie pipes. However, two new pipes, the Jay!  and Sable, have emerged as substitute candidates. A 1,096 t bulk sample yielded a grade of 0.98 ct/t and an average value of $64/ct. If a 9 ct gem stone valued at US $17,556 is removed from the parcel, the Sable pipe's value drops to $48/ct. The stones from the Jay pipe, which yielded 2.01 ct/t from 476.8 tonnes, have yet to be evaluated. Nothing has been said about tonnages. BHP has also revealed that the values it publishes represent a 10% discount from the commercial dealer valuations it has obtained. In other words, for the sake of comparison with values reported by other companies, BHP's diamonds should be marked up 11%. The 10% discount is likely intended to reflect the 10% "marketing" fee the CSO collects for handling a producer's rough diamond supply.<BR><P>
Now that the risk of government rejection of the mining plan has been largely eliminated, purchase of Dia Met Minerals (DMM.B & DMM.A - T) shares is timely. Dia Met's A shares at $21 continue to trade at a discount to the more liquid B multiple voting shares at $23. Because both classes participate equally, and future financings are likely to be in the form of the A shares, investors should favour the cheaper class for the long run. With about 28.7 million fully diluted shares for the combined classes, the market is presently valuing the Dia Met/BHP at about $2.1 billion (CAD) or US $1.5 billion. Based on published data the diamond mine will initially be churning out about US $400 million worth of rough diamonds per year. BHP has not revealed internal operating cost estimates, but I estimate that during the first ten years they will run 20-30% of gross revenues. Payback should be within several years and Dia Met will then become a cash cow. The stock has not had much hype d! uring the past two years, and although it has doubled this year, this reflects more a rebound from last year's review panel uncertainty and accompanying subdued information flow than excessive speculation. Investors looking for a strategic place to park their speculative capital while they wait out the hurricane warnings should give Dia Met a serious look.<BR>
<P><P>
<A NAME="Ge"><font size=+1>Gerle Gold: Boyd Warner ownership uncertainty to continue.</font size>
<P>
Gerle Gold (GGL-V: $2.60) is busy drilling on its Doyle Lake project south of Mountain Province's Kennedy Lake project. So far Gerle has killed 10 out of 40 initial targets either by drilling or surface inspection. As Winspear found at Snap Lake and Mountain Province is finding at its Carl Hicks anomaly, geophysics is proving to be ineffective as a target definition tool. A new round of indicator mineral sampling has been completed and is being processed by Monopros on a rush basis. I have heard that a section 84 appeal has been filed in Ottawa on the cancellation of the Boyd Warner claims. Gerle, pointing at the weak and unsworn defence provided to the NWT Mining Recorder by Golden Rule, the purported owner of the Boyd Warner claims, plans to carry on exploration as if its ownership is secure. Gerle shareholders worried about an adverse decision six months or later down the road should not consider Golden Rule as a hedge. Last year an attempt was made to assign ownership o! f the Boyd Warner claims to John Dupuis' Inukshuk Capital. Whatever agreement underlay this transfer attempt is probably still intact, and at the least represents a potential lawsuit for Golden Rule if the latter should try to keep whatever Gerle may find on the Central claims. Golden Rule, incidentally, makes no mention in its annual report that it is the beneficial owner of the Boyd Warner claims. Because lawyers automatically exhaust every avenue of appeal, Golden Rule's section 84 appeal could be the company just going through the motions. Nevertheless, Gerle investors should keep the ownership risk in mind. If it is any comfort, Boyd Warner, who comes from a respected and honourable NWT family, verbally informed the NWT Supervising Mining Recorder, Annette McRobert, that "he was contracted to stake this ground for Tyler". McRoberts gives no weight to this statement because it was not provided in writing. But she does report it as an aside in her decision, something she is unl! ikely to have done if she regarded Warner as "mixed up" or a flake. Until Gerle hits a kimberlite, it is a hold.<BR>
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Mou"><font size=+1>Mountain Province: under Timbuktu pressure.</font size>
<P>
Diamond speculators should keep a close eye on Mountain Province Mining (MPV-V: $5.40). The stock has based out in the $5-5.50 range where it dropped from the $8 level when it revealed that the first 24.6 tonne bulk sample graded 3.09 ct/t, or 2.28 ct/t counting only stones with one dimension 2 mm or greater. Although the new president, Jan Vandersande, indicated to me that he wanted a 200 ct parcel before shipping the stones off for appraisal, rumours have it that he is in Europe obtaining valuations right now. The market's negative reaction probably prompted this plan change, as has talk that the stones are now expected to average $50/ct. That would still give a value of $100-150/t. If reports of a 20 million tonne resource with an unusually high degree of stone distribution homogeneity hold up under further bulk sampling, and the values come in as expected, investors will soon start paying much closer attention to MPV and the 5034 pipe. At $5.40 the Kennedy Lake project ! has a value of only $256 million compared to Gerle's $154 million. In comparing the valuations one must keep in mind that MPV must foot 50% of all costs, whereas Gerle is carried through production. Because of the uncertainty of funding dilution, MPV is better compared to Aber, presently sporting a project cap of $1.5 billion. The best explanation for the price weakness of MPV is that the company has become dependent on Lytton's backers for financial support. One of the biggest buyers of MPV until recently has been Ron Brimacombe's Yorkton Calgary office. This is the same office that buried itself in Timbuktu, settlement of which trades has resulted in liquidation of other positions. I would venture that control of MPV's destiny is shifting back into the market place, and given Vandersande's determination to plug the information leaks that have in the past plagued MPV and undermined its credibility, the stage has been set for new financial backers to arrive on the scene. MPV has b! een courted by a number of majors, but at this stage a farmout that gives 50% to a major would be a giveaway, even if MPV gets carried to production with favorable payout rates during the payback period. One sensible route for MPV is to let a major get its toe wet through a private placement. A representative of the major should join the board, and the stock should become part of a voting trust in favour of management. A merger with Camphor on arithmetic terms that reflect capitalization and property interest should be pursued. This would create a 60% controlling stake in Kennedy Lake that it would make sense for a major to acquire through a takeover bid. On the assumption that MPV's funding strategy is drifting in this direction, the stock below $6 is a strategic buying opportunity that takes advantage of the Timbuktu factor. As for concern that MPV is a one-pipe wonder, I am convinced that it is only a matter of time before one or more pipes is found in the vicinity of the Carl Hicks anomaly.<BR>
<P>
<P>
<A NAME="Pe"><font size=+1>Peruvian Gold and Laramide </font size><P>
Peruvian Gold (PVO-V: $3.80) has settled back into the range of $3.50-4.00 after the predictable cancellation of the $10 million financing First Marathon had promised to broker. Given the market's reality check and subsequent reluctance to assume the third dimension for surface showings, Peruvian is no longer itching to go to $10. The company has about $3 million working capital, more than enough to complete a proposed drill program. Heavy monsoon rains have halted work now, but David Henstridge expects to be back on the site no later than August. The length and strength of the rainy season varies, but once the rain stops, it is only a 6 hour drive from Quito and 10 minute helicopter sling job to get a drill on site. Peruvian is also considering an underground adit to sample and drill the sheeted vein system at El Encanto in Ecuador. For now the stock is a hold, and those who sold should watch for buying opportunities triggered by a general market crisis.<BR>
<P>
Investors should regard any private placement announced before June with suspicion until the company confirms that it has closed. With the cup now half empty instead of half full, institutions and other investors are applying much more critical standards before agreeing to put money in a junior's treasury. In cases like Laramide Resources Ltd (LAM-T: $1.36), which has just announced a private placement of 4 million special warrant units at $1.10 by Newcrest Capital and Griffiths McBurney, the non-closing risk is much lower. While First Marathon is destined to become a lame duck in the arena of institutional financings for junior resource companies thanks to Cartaway, others like Newcest, Griffiths and Whalen are emerging as funding leaders. Laramide, which I featured in the May-June issue as one of my anti-promoter flow-thru picks, is a much stronger buy to the $1.50 limit now on the assumption this financing closes.No statement or expression of opinion, or any other matter herein, directly or indirectly, is an offer to buy or sell the securities mentioned.  While we believe the sources of information to be reliable, we in no way represent or guarantee the accuracy thereof, nor the statements contained herein.<BR>
<P>
This issue of the Kaiser Express is intended for the exclusive use of Premium subscribers until the Bargain release date posted above.<BR>
