<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Kaiser</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#C0C0C0><CENTER><IMG SRC="../mw.gif" ></CENTER><HR>
<P>
<H1>KAISER EXPRESS #96 -- 7</H1>
<P>
Commentary by John Kaiser ----- May 23, 1996<BR>
<P>
<H2>"Hey Waiter,the menu said octopi, not calamari!"</H2>
<P>
<P>
<P>
For several days last week during the burgeoning hype about the giant nickel-copper octopus Cartaway was hauling up from the depths of its Cirque property in the Okak Bay area of Labrador, the VSE made successive daily volume records. On Thursday Cartaway galloped to $26 on news that hole #3 had intersected 67.5 metres containing four zones of "heavy" sulphide mineralization estimated to contain 5-10% chalcopyrite, a copper sulphide which should have a corresponding grade of 1.5-3.5% copper. This time around the presence of pentlandite, the nickel sulphide, was also observed. While the first two holes of net-textured to massive sulphide mineralization with "significant visible chalcopyrite", of which according to Walter Nash massive sulphides represented only a few 3-4 metre intervals, left only fools dreaming about Voisey Bay ovoid style grades and intervals, hole 3 looked like the real thing. In fact, it had one infamous risk-reward arbitrager who had just dusted 1.2 mill! ion shares probably wondering if he had once again blown the big one. But only for a bit. On Friday May 17 the fun ended abruptly when Cartaway was halted and the satellites sold off sharply on rumours the assays needed rechecking. What, so good like Timbuktu's they couldn't be true? No, laddy, so bad they couldn't be true.
<P>
The biggest interval of 32 metres from hole #2 graded a pathetic 0.166% copper, 0.087% nickel, and 0.045% cobalt. The budget conscious, surplus proud ASE, still smarting from the "rube capital" title it earned for its handling of the Timbuktu affair, watched its trading facility choke on the onslaught of Cartaway sell orders and demonstrated it was really only suited for the peanut league when it stopped Cartaway trading to prevent a total system crash. It's a good thing so few people take seriously the assays for the Franklin Lakes project of Naxos, which imply one of the richest mineral deposits in the world. The really bad news for Cartaway came on Tuesday when the company announced that the richer intervals in hole #3 graded no better than 0.23% copper, 0.189% nickel and 0.082% cobalt. When trading resumed on May 21 Cartaway opened at $2, down a whopping $21 or 93% from Thursday's $23 close. The fury with which Cartaway paper was blown out says only one thing: instituti! onal fund managers caught with the most hideous embarassment of their careers on their books wanted only one thing: Cartaway off their books before anybody noticed. The stock subsequently bounced back to $4 before settling out at $2.78, reflecting once more its previous classification as an expensive junior with a large portfolio of grassroots Labrador properties.
<P>
Four primary questions have come my way during the past few days.<BR>
<P><UL>
<LI>How could experienced geologists over-estimate the copper sulphide ? <BR> 
<LI>Content in core by more than factor of ten? What does this mean ? <BR>
<LI>For the Labrador play ?  What does this mean for the flow of institutional money into Canadian juniors? <BR><LI>And what does this mean for the future of the biggest spec boom in juniors in 15 years?<BR>
</UL><P>
On the first question the blame is being placed on a field geologist who logged the core and provided estimates of the chalcopyrite content. Walter Nash and no doubt quite a number of independent experts are rushing to take a peek at the infamous core. Was the chalcopyrite estimate reasonable in terms of visual appearance? If so, was it reasonable to apply visual standards to previously unassayed mineralization? The market wants an explanation that reassures it no deliberate deception was made.
<P>
On the question of Labrador, it is obvious that the cup has abruptly gone from half-full to half-empty. When Cartaway grabbed hold of the Cirque tentacle and made noises it had grabbed hold of something big, the market rushed to the table expecting a feast of octopi. Instead, chefs Nash and Ivany served up calamari. This pattern of great Voisey Bay expectations followed by disappointing reality, all accompanied by the blowoff of paper created last year, was predicted. What hadn't been predicted was that it would happen on such an extravagant scale. The consequence is that investors will greet Labrador rumours and news releases with suspicion for the rest of the exploration season. It is possible that further drilling of the Cirque anomaly may lead to better results, but next time around the market will want to see a number of high grade intersections that spell out a 3-dimensional body with an economically significant volume and grade before it starts to assign world-class ! orebody valuations. For the Labrador play the best dedicated exploration bets beside Cartaway (CWA-C) continue to be Castle Rock (CTP-V), United Compass (UCR-V), Columbia Yukon (CYR-C) and NDT Ventures (NDE-V). The best strategy, however, continues to be to monitor these plays for positive field developments and hold the secondary plays like Eastfield (ETF-V), Lucero (LCR-V), Aranlee (ARB-V), Birchwood (BIR-V) and Freewest (FWR-T) which have a primary focus elsewhere. As for Layfield (LAY-V), the company will seek shareholder approval in June for a 5:1 stock consolidation. Had the Cirque delivered the goods, the rollback plan would likely have been cancelled to preserve Layfield as a highly liquid ersatz Cartaway play. However, now that the Cirque's potential has dropped to no better than any other prospect in the area, Layfield is little more than a widely distributed stock that will fall victim to the fate of most junior rollback candidates: after the 5:1 rollback the stock will drift from its post-rollback level of $2-2.50 back to $0.30 where new insiders will create fresh paper to motivate them to find a new life for Layfield. Judging from NDT's inability to say anything interesting about the Layfield property, there probably isn't any compelling reason to own the stock on its own merits.
<P>
On the question of what effect the Cartaway debacle will have on the institutional money that has been pouring into the Canadian juniors, I think it will be very positive. Not positive in the sense that more will come chasing into the market, but positive in the sense that it will be deployed more prudently within a risk-reward context. The quest for the next Bre-X or Diamond Fields is foremost in the minds of both retail and institutional investors. What people have been forgetting is that good exploration results are the exception to the rule, not the norm. And extraordinary discoveries like Busang or Voisey's Bay are extraordinary exceptions to the rule. Equity fund managers continue to experience a heavy inflow of money, are under pressure to deliver high returns, but are hamstrung by a yo-yo senior market that one week is destined for 6,000 and beyond, and the next week slipping toward 5,000 and oblivion. Meanwhile the worldwide exploration landscape is being altered b! y an explosion of well financed junior exploration companies staffed by geological talent pools frequently drawn from the folds of major mining companies. They are being funded by retail and institutional investors as well as major companies, which are effectively shifting exploration to the public market driven juniors while they concentrate on their core business: acquiring, developing and mining orebodies. The institutional money has recognized the enormous leverage that these juniors represent, and so long as the juniors pursue a formula of raising more money than they need and constantly replenishing their property portfolios with new prospects to replace the duds, the downside risk is slow and gradual. Since these juniors are mainly companies trying to conjure an economic asset out of thin air, in other words prove that a heap of rocks is really a valuable orebody, their valuation boils down to relating the risk of finding nothing to the reward of finding something valuable. Investors who got burned by Cartaway did so because they ignored the fact that while the reward implicit in the stock's price grew, there was no corresponding decline in the risk that no reward would be delivered. Fear and gr! eed that they were missing the next Diamond Fields drove investors into Cartaway. The disastrous result translates into a reality check that will also break the "seller's strike" that has permitted market valuations to soar.
<P>
Cartaway has done the junior exploration market a big favour because it reminds investors to assess speculative stocks in terms of their risk-reward leverage. At $26 Cartaway sported a $800 million project valuation without any assays in hand, not even from surface sampling or trenching. Exploring a deposit is a gradual process that can involve some results based quantum leaps in valuation, but rarely does exploration produce one giant leap from nothing to world class orebody. That does not mean plays like Arequipa and Fortune Minerals won't yield multi-billion dollar deposits. But just because they have this potential does not mean investors should be willing to price these stocks as though extensive drilling has already turned the potential into reality. This year we have seen heavy price inflation for a number of high-powered stocks so that 12% of VSE listings represented 58% of the VSE's entire market capitalization. I believe the Cartaway experience will help reverse t! his trend, which is the stock equivalent of an ever smaller segment of the population controlling an ever larger portion of the total wealth. Both retail and institutional investors will start looking for smaller deals where the market cap has plenty of room for upside if the company starts delivering the promised reward. If I am correct both retail and institutional money will continue to flow into the Canadian resource exploration juniors, but they will do so at the lower market cap end of the spectrum. The rebellion against all risk-no reward plays has begun.
<P>
The diversification of investor interest is very healthy for this market because it will result in a broader base of companies who get sufficiently financed to carry on the orebody hunt. Cartaway's fall from grace will help this process because the Masters of the Universe behind Cartaway, a small group of First Marathon brokers who owned most of the very cheap 14 million shares which came free trading on May 5, have had their feathers clipped. Thanks to their involvement with Diamond Fields, this group had emerged as a dominant financing force in this market that had tremendous influence over institutions. During the height of the Cartaway hype these Masters of the Universe were personally up over $200 million on paper, and dreaming about being up $1 billion. While they probably won't spend too much time in the penalty box for sharing those feelings with their institutional clients, it may be long enough for other, less influential brokerage firms to pick up the ball and in! troduce product from a broader field to the institutional money. Such a development would make this market's destiny less vulnerable to the whims, fortunes and woes of a very small elite. In terms of the big picture, New York has just made a new high at 5,700 and is in no immediate danger of melting down. The emergence of a new breed of junior exploration companies with healthy treasuries in excess of $5 million earmarked for serious exploration around the world has created a foundation that will bring forth a parade of discoveries, many of them modest, a few world-class. Should New York fail us and unleash a hurricane, these companies will see their prices flattened. But like reeds when the wind has stopped blowing they will snap back. The attitude is developing among investors that while a senior market driven setback is inevitable, its timing is uncertain and irrelevant, for the junior driven global hunt for mineral deposits has become a fixture of the future.
<P>
Two juniors that I feel are ripe for institutional funding are Major General Resources (MGJ-V) and Rio Amarillo Mining (RIO-V). Rio Amarillo is currently awaiting results from hole 10 on the Aicha tourmaline breccia target in Peru. This target has been a real teaser for Rio's Hal Waller, who had just about given up that the Bellota Pipe would yield any significant tonnage of polymetallic mineralization when hole 10 produced a 142 metre intersection that should have been only 7-10 metres long. Except for a 50 metre section of massive pyrite Waller expects to be barren, much of this intersection is expected to run gold, silver, copper and zinc grades, albeit not spectacular grades. Rio Amarillo now thinks there is a lot more going on at depth than initially expected and plans to carry on drilling. While Aicha may at best lead to a medium sized underground mining operation, the blue-sky for Rio Amarillo investors sits with the Portovelo prospect in Ecuador which Rio has starte! d to drill. This property covers an old gold vein mining camp where Rio hopes to discover a large disseminated stockwork gold deposit. With 14.3 million fully diluted, working capital of $3.5-4 million, an excellent geological talent pool, and a range of properties in Ecuador, Bolivia, and Peru, Rio Amarillo at $1.51 is a steal. You cannot yet put your finger on what will make this company a winner, but it is the sort of stock you should have and could have easily bought all year. After unsuccessfully pursuing a cheapskate strategy of waiting for the stock to get cheaper, I finally took the plunge last week and bought a small position in the $1.55-1.65 range. Investors should not be afraid to own the stock up to $2, where its market cap is still only $30 million. Once the stock has broken through $2 it will likely attract an institutional audience and will be in a price bracket where management is confortable raising additional funds.
<P>
Major General is another stock whose cheapness has worked to its detriment. Major just raised $1.4 million at $0.80 through a private placement that took no time to sell out. By now the company has at least 28 million shares fully diluted, and is or was owned by just about everybody who has heard the by now tiresome "irons-in-the-fire" touts from Bob Bishop and myself. The biggest problem with Major has been the absence of leadership since late 1994 when Bill Coulter was appointed interim president. He stepped down late last year for health reasons. Dick Atkinson is finally looking for an aggressive new president, and if one is found, the market will no doubt applaud. Companies trading at distressed prices thanks to missing pieces that could easily be filled are excellent buys. Major plans to spend a good part of the money on a 20 hole drill program on the new Orion gold zone discovered west of the 150,000 oz high grade Hammerdown gold deposit on the Rendall-Jackman propert! y in Newfoundland. Bernie Kahlert thinks Orion is the fault offset and upfaulted deeper portion of the system that fed the Hammerdown veins and is optimistic that a substantial medium-grade gold resource can be developed. Rendall-Jackman needs a bigger gold reserve to make a standalone mining operation feasible. Major has been described as a Canadian mutual fund, but it may soon be known as a Greenland diamond play. Last year while sampling for heavy metals like nickel and copper, Major started picking up kimberlite indicator minerals. This constituted the first evidence that kimberlite emplacement occurred in Greenland. So far only a handful of indicator minerals have been found, of which only G9's have been identified. Major has beefed up its land position to 2,300 sq km.
<P>
While in Vancouver last week I had a chance to review the diamond indicator mineral data for Major General, Mountain Province and Gerle Gold. On May 10 the NWT Supervising Mining Recorder had released her decision on the Boyd Warner claims, which was to cancel them and allow the overlying Central claims of Gerle and Kidme claims of Major General and Southernera to stand. Golden Rule has until June 10 to file a Section 84 appeal in Ottawa. An appeal would be surprising, especially considering that Golden Rule and Tyler did not trouble to make "sworn" responses to the Mining Recorder's request for submissions nor provide supporting documentation. From what I saw in Vancouver, I can make two predictions: Mountain Province will find a diamondiferous kimberlite on the Carl-Hicks anomaly it is presently drilling, and Gerle will find at least two diamondiferous kimberlites on its claims. Major has two distinct mineral trains that cross its property in a northeasterly direction. On! e clearly originates from MPV's Carl Hicks anomaly. The other leads directly to the cluster of anomalies on Gerle's ground. Gerle is presently mobilizing for a drilling program that will carry on all summer. An attempt will be made to drill targets on Phantom Lake before winter breakup, but I wouldn't hold my breath. Major has a 24% interest in the Kidme claims, which are not part of the Misty Lake JV with Monopros. The Gerle train has a spur on the Kidme claim between the Misty and Central blocks that could well indicate a pipe. Part of Phantom Lake, through which the main train passes, sits on the Kidme claim. At current prices of $2.75-3.00 Gerle without a diamondiferous kimberlite is overpriced. So was Dia Met in early 1992 when the only published information was the Point Lake micro counts. That is why I am holding Gerle for the long haul. Major General will be a wonderful ersatz play for Gerle because its ground may be very strategic, and I can think of a half dozen other reasons to own the stock at current prices. Major General should be accumulated to the $1.30 level and watched for some event that would trigger a breakout. No statement or expression of opinion, or any other matter herein, directly or indirectly, is an offer to buy or sell the securities mentioned.  While we believe the sources of information to be reliable, we in no way represent or guarantee the accuracy thereof, nor the statements contained herein.
<P>
