<P>
<H1>KAISER EXPRESS #96 -- 6</H1>
<P>
Commentary by John Kaiser  ------  May 10, 1996<BR>
<P>
<P>
<H2>Cartaway's Cirque Discovery</H2>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="#Co">Cons Callinan: still in hanging wall stratigraphy </A><BR>
<A HREF="#Pe">Peruvian: 870 metre strike length established for high grade gold.</A><BR>
<P>
<P>
<font size=+1>Cartaway's Cirque Discovery</font size><BR><P>
One year ago VSE daily volume hit 50 million shares on the back of the Voisey Bay nickel-copper discovery. I predicted in Kaiser Express 95-3 we were on the threshold of the biggest spec boom in 15 years and that we
would hit 100 million share days before the year was over. Naturally, the rest of the year saw only lower daily volumes. On Thursday May 9 the VSE hit 67.4 million shares on the back of the Cirque nickel-copper (maybe) discovery. This time I am keeping my mouth shut. Next week I will be in Vancouver to attend the Vancouver International Mining Investment Conference, which runs at the Hotel Vancouver from 
May 12-14.<P>
<P>
<B>Cartaway: serving up another Voisey's Bay deposit?</B><BR><P>
Results are now driving the speculative resource stock market. The biggest splash was made by Timbuktu Gold, which published assays for a hole that switched from anomalous gold in the first 100 ft to grades 
of 1-5 opt gold over the next 200 ft. It did not occur to the ASE, the brokerage firm sponsors of Timbuktu, 
nor the company's management to halt trading immediately until these numbers could be confirmed. Now the ASE, which has shunned the development of information systems comparable to the VSE because of "budget and manpower constraints" while building up a $12 million surplus, looks like the rube capital of the stock business. The biggest rubes are the brokers who fell for those glorious numbers, suspecting neither a methodology problem nor, heaven forbid, a salt job. After churning $50 million or so worth of paper the stock is now halted while the hole is redrilled with a diamond drill. The rumblings are that the news will not be happy. So, of course, the first question people ask when Cartaway catapults to a $300 million project valuation on about $36 million worth of trading is whether investors are being loaded onto another cattle car destined for Timbuktu.
<P>
While I may have my beefs about the way the brokers behind Cartaway Resources Corp (CWA-C: $9.50, 
33 million fully diluted) manage the allocation of risks and rewards among themselves and their clients, I have 
never doubted the credibility of the people running Cartaway. When you have Noranda's former eastern Canada exploration manager, Walter Nash, running the exploration program and writing the news releases, you have no doubts that the information is presented in anything but the utmost professional manner. 
May 8 Cartaway announced the first two of six holes planned for the 100% owned Cirque property south of Okak Bay and northwest of Alliger Lake in northern Labrador. The target was an elliptical magnetic-EM anomaly 400 by 250 metres. This target has been interpreted as a pipe-like,  southeasterly plunging sulphide body. There is no mineralized outcrop, and though float that graded nickel-copper-cobalt had been found in the area,  the target was regarded as a blind target. Optimism that it might represent another Voisey Bay style deposit was drawn largely from its proximity to the nearby Canadian States property, where arrow nickel-copper massive sulphide mineralization had been intersected last fall.
<P>
Cartaway's first hole nipped the western edge of the anomaly and yielded several short sections of network-textured to coarse-grained massive sulphides. The second hole was drilled vertically from the same setup and
intersected 4 zones of net textured to massive sulphide mineralization to a depth of 123 metres, including 
32 m between 9.5 - 41.5 m depth. The news release does not reveal the extent of "massive" intervals, but does
emphasize "significant visible chalcopyrite" mineralization within the zones. I did not have the opportunity to talk to Walter Nash before writing this Express, but I presume that he did not mean he spotted copper within a
few narrow massive sulphide bands here and there. Although the sulphides are mainly pyrrhotite, the sulphide found most often in conjunction withthe nickel sulphide, pentlandite, no mention of the latter was made.
I have heard that the chalcopyrite has been eyeballed at 5%, meaning it should grade 1-2% copper, and that nickel is present. At this stage the $300 million market valuation is premature. We need assays to establish grade and more holes to give us some geometry to estimate tonnage. The geophysical anomaly would suggest a 10-15 million tonne body to a depth of 50 metres. Anything deeper is open to the imagination. There does not seem to be any doubt the Cirque zone will run nickel and copper. The question is what the grade will be.
<P>
If the Cirque turns out to be a large high grade nickel-copper deposit, it will signal that the Voisey Bay deposit Inco is buying for about $5 billion is not an isolated freak occurrence within the Nain Province. 
That should certainly attract the attention of Falconbridge, which has a $100 million war chest as a consolation price for losing the takeover battle for Diamond Fields. Despite the implications of the discovery for Labrador in general, market interest will tend to concentrate in the immediate area of the new discovery as investors dream about how big this octopus may be and how far its tentacles reach. The area of interest will be what I last year called Kingurutik North, which stretches about 30 km east and west of the Cirque discovery and is bounded by the exempt mineral lands at Okak Bay to the north and at Alliger Lake to the south. Cartaway's immediate neighbours  will receive heavy market attention. To the south is the 50:50 JV between NDT Ventures (NDE-V: $3.70) and Layfield Minerals (LAY-V: $$0.79). 
<P>
<B>Layfield</B>, which has about 26-30 million shares fully diluted, traded over 12 million shares on Thursday. A private placement of 4 million shares and 4 million warrants brokered last year to a Howe Street Who's Who list has come free trading. The liquidity of Layfield and its location just south of the Cirque discovery promises to make this stock the market's ersatz Cartaway play. Because Layfield's market action will track that of the pricier Cartaway, speculators can treat it as a sort of Cartaway option. I purchased Layfield on Thursday for this reason. 
<P>
<B>Eastfield Resources</B> (ETF-V: $1.50) will be the flagship for the ground to the east of the Cirque property. Eastfield shares 25% of the Alliger West block with each of Athbaska Gold (AHB-T: $0.85), Warner Ventures (WVL-V: $0.98) and Island-Arc (IAR-V: $1.50). The most leveraged stock immediately to the east is Warner Ventures, with about 6 million fully diluted.  Eastfield et al will be releasing results early next week from a six hole program completed on the Alliger West block. Drilling of a geophysical target intersected massive magnetite. Management does not have high expectations for this core, but is optimistic it will run minor nickel and copper. The geophysical survey used to identify targets last year on the Alliger group had the capacity to penetrate only about 50 metres. Deep EM surveys have been undertaken on the project and results are expected in a few weeks. If they reveal deeper targets, this group of stocks should heat up in anticipation of a summer drill play.
<P>
<B>NDT Resources</B> and its other Staghorn Lake partners, Aranlee Resources (ARB-V: $1.50), Birchwood Ventures 
(BIR-V: $0.90), Essex Resources (ESX-V: $4.15) and Lumina Investments (LMI-V: $0.80) have properties in the vicinity of the Cirque which will likely attract attention. Essex has pretty much become a Bolivian play, and Aranlee will likely develop its Argentina focus with the help of two recent appointments, Tony Williams and Clive Johnson. That leaves Birchwood as the most uncommitted participant. Columbia Yukon 
(CYR-C: $2.37) and partner Silverstone Resources (SVT-V: $0.94) quietly announced several short sulphide intervals from drilling on the ML 1506 claim that adjoins Cartaway to the north. Columbia Yukon describes them as "nickel bearing", so these holes should be watched. Castle Rock (CTP-V:$1.59) and United Compass 
(UCR-V: $2.76) expect to be drilling by the end of May on their Okak Bay property further to the north. One pair of companies further to the east that bear watching are Ivory Oil (IVY-V:$1.10) and Spokane Resources (SKN-V: $1.05), which are joint ventured 55:45 on the Tasiuyak Bay property. They have traced a north-south troctolite dyke with up to 60 metre widths over 2 km. This dyke carries anomalous copper and nickel values and could be interpreted as a "tentacle". Last  year Diamond Fields supposedly expressed interest in this dyke, but never followed through. I have not heard that there are any important EM anomalies associated with this dyke, so its potential will have lie deep.
<P>
<font size=+1><A NAME="Pe" >Peruvian: 870 metre strike length established for high grade gold</font size>
<P>
Peruvian Gold (PVO-V: $5.60) reported trench results for #5 and #7 on Thursday that confirmed the company may be sitting on a million ounce plus gold deposit. Trench 5 yielded 37.2 ft of 0.13 opt gold and Trench 
7 yielded 77.4 ft of 0.61 opt gold. This establishes medium to high grade gold mineralization over a strike length of 870 metres, with widths ranging 11-52 metres. The next stage will be to drill test the zone. The sensible thing for Peruvian to do now is to hit up its financial backers for a private placement of 2 million or so units at the $5 level. The stock is itching to push towards the $10 target, but needs a financing to turn the
light green.<BR>
<P>
<font size=+1><A NAME="Co">Cons Callinan: still in hanging wall stratigraphy</font size>
<P>
The eleventh hour is turning out to be a very long hour for Cons Callinan Flin-Flon (CFF-V: $3.19). Based on interpretation of the April 26 to hit the target within 40-100 metres. Instead, the drill punched through 
44 metres of weak sulphides with minor copper and zinc mineralization before carrying on in what is still being described as hanging wall stratigraphy. This mineralization was unexpected at this level of the stratigraphic sequence, which remains identical to that which hosts the Callinan zones presently mined by HBMS. The failure to hit the target has been explained through the recognition that the stratigraphy's dip has
steepened from 45B0 to 65B0. The latest projection is that the target horizon will be interesected 
80-100 metres deeper. Drilling has slowed down to 10 metres per day when it hasn't stopped altogether due to equipment failure. At this rate we can stop worrying about Callinan for another 1-2 weeks. Until word gets out that the Callinan footwall has been penetrated without intersecting massive sulphides, the game will still be on. In  addition to the two massive sulphide zones alluded to by Minorco in its 1994 annual report, Callinan now has hopes that the unexpected 44 metre disseminated sulphide zone is related to a third zone that later wedge drilling can probe. At this point investors should decide to hang on for the end or bail out.
<P>
This issue of the Kaiser Express is intended for the exclusive use of Premium subscribers until the Bargain release date posted above.<BR>
<P>
Annual subscriptions to the Premium Kaiser Express are $300.00 US and can be ordered from:<BR>
<CENTER>
Canspec Research<BR>
PO Box 6488,<BR>Moraga, CA, 94556<BR>
<P>Tel: (510) 299-0214<BR>
Fax: (510) 299-1286<BR><P>
KAISER EXPRESS 96-6<BR>
Premium Release:May 10, 1996<BR>
Bargain Release:May 8, 1996<BR>
<P>
Tel: (510) 299-0214   Written by John Kaiser<BR>
Fax: (510) 299-1286   (C) 1996 Canspec Research<BR></CENTER>
<P>
No statement or expression of opinion, or any other matter herein, directly or indirectly, is an offer to buy or sell the securities mentioned.  While we believe the sources of information to be reliable, we in no way represent or guarantee the accuracy thereof, not the statements contained herein.  This issue of the Kaiser Express is intended for the exclusive use of Premium subscribers until the Bargain release date posted above.  Annual subscriptions to the Premium Kaiser Express are $300.00 US and can be ordered from Canspec Research at PO Box 8488, Moraga, CA, 94556.<BR>
