<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Kaiser</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#C0C0C0><CENTER><IMG SRC="../mw.gif" ></CENTER><HR>
<P>
<H1>KAISER EXPRESS # 96 -- 5</H1>
<P>
Commentary by John Kaiser  ------  April 26, 1996<BR>
<P>
<H2>Awaiting Good News on Several Fronts</H2>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="#La">Labrador: a summer of trading opportunities</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Ge">Gerle Gold: waiting for NWT Mining Recorder decision any day.</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Pe">Peruvian Gold: medium tonnage high grade deposit new target model.</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Ma">Mazenod Lake and Olympic Dam Mania</A><BR>
<P>
<P>
Cons Callinan Flin-Flon (CFF-V: $3.80) is 40-100 metres away from intersecting Flin Flon's Sister. Drilling was suspended at 1,610 metres on Tuesday to allow for a downhole geophysics probe to take a look. The probe indicates that a massive body lies dead ahead somewhere between 40-100 metres. Drilling has now resumed, and at the recent rate of 18 metres per shift, two shifts per day, the target should be intersected by Friday or at the latest by Monday. The market had weakened earlier in the week as investors got the eleventh hour jitters amidst delays caused by broken drill rods. CFF has been drilling steadily since November 22 except for a three week break in late December. Callinan believes that the 300-330 metre wide 100% owned War Baby claim covers the down-plunge projection of the stratigraphy that hosts the Callinan deposit presently being mined by HBMS.  Callinan has a 6 2/3% net profits interest in the Callinan claim north of 
the War Baby claim. Within days we may get confirmation that a second world-class deposit sits underneath downtown Flin-Flon.
<P>
I introduced the Callinan story on Sept 18, 1995 in Kaiser Express 96-10 ($2.25 buy limit, $5 12 month target), where I argued that circumstantial evidence and rumours suggest that HBMS had discovered a significant new zone down plunge from the known Callinan reserves. HBMS is controlled by Minorco, a unit of South African controlled Anglo American. HBMS has been doing substantial underground development and exploratory work on a project it claims is subeconomic. It has refused to disclose any information to 
Callinan, even though the parent, Minorco, a multi-billion dollar company, disclosed in its 1994 annual report that two new zones of copper and zinc mineralization had been found at the Callinan Mine. In Minorco's words, "these new zones occur significantly deeper but in the same sequence of rocks that host the current Callinan mining operations". Callinan's Mike Muzylowski believes that HBMS may have found a deep orebody comparable to the now depleted 70 million ton Flin Flon deposit. The War Baby claim straddles the Callinan stratigraphy projected about 3,000 ft down plunge from the known Callinan zone, and covers about 1,600 ft of plunge. The stratigraphy dips at about 45 B0. HBMS has drilled two deep holes, one on the northern, up-plunge border of the War Baby claim, and another on the southern, down-plunge border of War Baby where the Callinan stratigraphy is projected to be at a depth of about 7,000 ft. For the past 12 months HBMS has been wedging off both holes, drilling a fan of holes to define "something". These are expensive holes, and you can bet your life HBMS is not conducting an academic study. Rumours have indicated that spectacular zinc-copper core has been pulled from these holes. Given that a Flin-Flon style volcanogenic massive sulphide deposit will be stratigraphically controlled, the obvious conclusion is that the War Baby claim covers the middle of a very important zone. Callinan expects its intersection to represent a true width of the deepest third of the body that lies within the War 20baby claim boundaries, and is hoping to get 30 metres or better of massive sulphide core. Once it has intersected the zone, it plans to back up and wedge drill a fan of holes to define the geometry of the zone.
<P>	
What should Callinan shareholders do in the eleventh hour? For those who bought Callinan last year when I recommended it and have stuck it out, hold your positions. If massive sulphide core is hit, the town of Flin Flon will know about it instantly, the stock price will spike up before management knows about the hit, and trading will be halted for disclosure. When trading resumes there will be heavy speculation based on visual "assays" of  the core. I expect the stock to shoot through $5. To go higher will depend  on the width and grade of the intersection. With only 14 million shares fully diluted, Callinan could head into double digits upon receipt of strong assays. Given HBMS's perseverance on both sides of War Baby, it is unlikely the grades will be sub-economic. Speculators will be hoping that the grades are very high, ie 5%+ zinc, 5%+ copper, and gold credits. When more data is available I will try to put the value potential into perspective. If drilling intersects weak sulphide mineralization, the stock will likely gap down to the $1.50-2.00 level. Callinan will drill at least 4 wedges before giving up. However, downhole geophysics has indicated an off-hole anomaly at 1,550 m hole depth. This may represent a separate zone. At the end of this program Callinan would  have $3 million working capital and be in good shape to find itself a new life.
<P>
The purpose of this drill hole is to give Callinan the leverage needed to force HBMS to renegotiate the deal on the main Callinan property. Callinan is pushing for a formal audit of the accounting HBMS uses to render the 
Callinan Mine uneconomic. HBMS has never said there is nothing there on the Callinan ground. It has simply hidden behind the extremely high threshold of what is material for one of the world's biggest mining companies. I suspect that once the cat is out of the bag, HBMS management will have to sit down at the negotiating table to hammer out a deal that consolidates the War Baby "zone" with the rest of the ore. Speculators willing to gamble on this hole, or interested in exploiting the volatility that will accompany the mystery associated with the information flow during the next few weeks, may want to grab a position before the stock breaks $4.00. Those who prefer a bird in the hand over two in the bush should take their 
100% profit. CFF: (604) 669-5598
<P>
<font size=+1><A NAME="La">Labrador: a summer of trading opportunities</font size>
<P>
Speculation about the Labrador nickel-copper hunt is starting to heat up on rumours that Diamond Fields is hitting massive sulphides on new targets. Last week local investors got all worked up about rumours that Diamond Fields had made a discovery very close to the eastern border of the main Voisey's Bay block. This brought substantial buying into Intl Canalaska (ICA-V: $1.20), which owns 100% of the VBE-1 property that adjoins to the east. JV partner Columbia Yukon (CYR-C: $1.89), which has less fully diluted stock out and stands to earn 70% of the VBE-1 property by carrying all costs to production, was largely ignored. Subsequent rumours placed the new DFR discovery about 5 miles east of the ovoid, or about halfway between 
 the ovoid and the Intl Canalaska border. That cooled off the market. Right now the metaphor for the Voisey's Bay deposit is that of a deeply buried octopus. Confirmation of a discovery well east of Eastern Deeps would be significant because it would signal the existence of another octopus whose tentacles might extend under the VBE-1 claims and possibly even the claim NDT and Lucero own 50:50 east of VBE-1. Canalaska has found encouraging smoke on the VBE-1 claims which it plans to follow up with deep EM geophysical surveys in mid-May and drilling in June.
<P>
The general exploration strategy this year in Labrador's Nain Province is to search for deep-seated octopi like the Eastern Deeps deposit using deep EM geophysics and deep drilling. Last year's exploration pass pretty well killed the potential for another near-surface deposit like the 30 million tonne ovoid zone. Short near surface intersections of magmatic sulphide mineralization will be treated as possible tentacles of a deeper octopus to be followed up with downhole geophysics and deeper drilling. This stage will be accompanied by lots of hype. Investors should realize that key Labrador players like Castle Rock (CTP-VB: $1.47), Cartaway (CWA-V: $3.50), and NDT Ventures (NDE-V: $3.00), as well as their smaller JV partners, have huge quantities of paper hanging over the market. The only discoveries that count will be ones that have copper and nickel grades better than 1% and tonnages in excess of 20 million tonnes. Inco is not likely to accept mill 
feed from smaller deposits. To have an economic nickel-copper deposit in Labrador, it will have to be big. Unless spectacular holes of 50 metres plus and high grades are pulled, the significance of drill results will be 
an open question. You can bet that the existing shareholders who got papered up last year will be selling into volume generated by encouraging results. Speculators should treat the 1996 Labrador exploration season as a 
 trading play. Buying and holding for elephant confirmation will be the most effective way to lose your money. Better to buy back at a higher price when size potential has been confirmed than get suckered into the trap of not wanting to miss the next Diamond Fields. I expect that majors like Falconbridge, RTZ and Gencor who got skunked in the DFR takeover game will be watching very closely and will be eager to do farm-in deals. I do think that if any juniors pull very good results that clearly indicate a sizable discovery, the majors will move much more quickly to take equity positions. But be forewarned that there will be lots of false rumours about takeover bids. One possible new wrinkle that may change the complexion of the Labrador play this summer is the emergence of platinum group mineralization. The Voisey's Bay deposit does include platinum group credits, but they have been ignored by DFR because their recoverability is likely incompatible with nickel-copper recovery processes. Platinum group metals tend to be associated more with disseminated sulphides than massive sulphides. It is quite possible that some layered sulphide intersections that don't look too promising for nickel or copper sulphides may kick back important platinum group grades. The economics of a platinum deposit would be a new ballgame unaffected by the size of the Voisey's Bay deposit. Nobody is talking about platinum group targets, but keep this prospect in mind as a wild card.
<P>
The action in the next while will likely centre in the Okak Bay area where,Cartaway Resources Corp 
(CWA-C) will soon start drilling the 100% owned Cirque property. This property adjoins the Alliger West property owned 25% each by Eastfield Resources Ltd (ETF-V: $1.16) and Warner Ventures 
(WVL-V:$0.97), both bottom-fish that popped up several weeks ago on news that magmatic segregation style mineralization had been intersected. The core,  however, was high on magnetite but low on sulphides. Assays are several weeks away and are not expected to be barnburners. The target was identified with geophysics that had a maximum 50 metre penetration. A new grid of geophysics with a 200 metre depth penetration is planned to see if Eastfield et al have the tentacle of an octopus. Success by Cartaway next door would certainly boost optimism in the Eastfield camp. Eastfield appears to be much more excited about a target in Alliger Lake on the Alliger South block it shares 75:25 with Mongolia Gold (MGR-V: $1.39). Initially dismissed as a lake bottom sediment anomaly, this target is now believed to contain a significant linear magnetic feature that the planned geophysics program will further illuminate. Of the bunch Eastfield remains the most strategic buy because it has interests ranging 25-75% in all three Alliger blocks and has a life beyond Labrador. Work on the 50:50 JV with Prism Resources (PRN-V: $0.85) on the Tonopah Gold Project in Nevada has begun. This program is geared towards bringing the low grade gold resource of 250,000-300,000 ounces on the Three Hills/Hill of Gold property to the feasibility stage by this fall and testing for new reserves. Eastfield 
recently completed a private placement of 1,200,000 units at $0.79. There is no hurry to buy Eastfield, but below $1.30 it is a good indirect bet on Okak Bay with lots of gold-related upside. Also in the Okak Bay area, to the northwest of Alliger Lake on the ML 1506 block, Columbia Yukon and Silverstone (SVT-V) are starting a drill program to follow up on nickel-copper-cobalt showings. (JK owns shares in WVL) 
ETF:  (604) 681-7913
<P>	
If you want exposure to Labrador but don't want to be a trader of stocks like NDT, Cartaway and Castle Rock, the perfect stock right now is Lucero Resources Corp (LCR-V: $1.18). NDT has indicated that it plans to follow up with more work on ten claim blocks, including the one east of VBE-1. Lucero has $2.9 million working capital and owns 670,000 shares of Mansfield Minerals (MDR-V: $3.80) worth about $2.3 million which Lucero is free to sell after May 31. A 10,000 ft drill program is planned in late July for the Wolf project in central British Columbia. The program is designed to make or break the epithermal gold potential of this prospect on which Lucero has worked since 1987. Insiders recently reloaded with restricted stock through a private placement of 1,000,000 units at $0.60. And the company has been actively looking for copper and gold prospects in Chile.  Lucero has 14.4 million fully diluted, working capital of about $5 million that could be boosted by $1.2 million through the exercise of 806,250 warrants at $1.50 by June 29, 1996, exposure to Labrador, and the blue-sky of a new exploration focus in South America. The timing is right for 
 judicious positioning in the $1.00-1.50 range during the next four weeks.   LCR: (604) 682-7041
<P>
<font size=+1><A NAME="Ge">Gerle Gold: waiting for NWT Mining Recorder decision any day</font size>
<P>	
The latest buying surge in Gerle Gold (GGL-V) is likely due to a strong recommendation it received in the March-April issue of the Kaiser Bottom-Fishing Report. Dated April 15 and mailed April 20, this issue is devoted to the NWT Diamond Hunt. In it I argue that the second exploration wave is underway in the NWT diamond play and that the Lac de Gras pipes of Dia Met and Aber may not be the richest and most valuable pipes in the NWT.  Based on indicator mineral data Gerle believes its North and Central claims cover a cluster of diamond pipes. A decision by the NWT Mining Recorder on the Boyd Warner/Central claims is expected any day. If the ruling goes in Gerle's favour, it means Gerle will own the entire cluster, not just part of it. Gerle plans to start drilling by mid-May and intends to drill throughout summer. Apparently there are no large lakes on Gerle's ground, and the targets are at worst associated with small lakes that can be drilled from shore. Subscribers who bought Gerle as a result of my March 6 Kaiser Express 96-3 should definitely hold their positions. Weakness due to an adverse decision by the Mining Recorder should be treated as a buying opportunity. (JK owns shares in GGL) GGL: (604) 688-0546
<P>
<font size=+1><A NAME="Pe">Peruvian Gold: medium tonnage high grade deposit new target model</font size>
<P>
The latest trench assays for Peruvian Gold (PVO-V: $3.75) spell bad news for hopes that the 60% optioned El Encanto project in northern Ecuador hosts a bulk tonnage gold deposit. The distribution of mineralization is showing that there is some sort of control to the gold within the system of porphyry veining. The good news is that instead of a 100 million ton deposit of 0.05-0.07 opt gold, we are likely looking at a medium tonnage deposit of 5-10 million tons of 0.1-0.3 opt gold. Trench 1 yielded 0.15 opt gold over 171.4 ft.  Trench 3, 100 metres upslope of Trench 1, yielded 23 ft of 1.33 opt gold. Trench 2, about 35 m downslope from Trench 1, yielded only 49.2 ft of 0.11 opt gold and was the basis for concern during the past few weeks. However, trenches 2A and 2B just above and below trench 2 yielded 29 ft of 0.85 opt gold and 47.7 ft of 0.17 opt gold. Trenches 4 and 6 failed to expose enough bedrock to sample. The key to the El Encanto project will be trench 5, 300 metres downslope from trench 2, and trench 7, 600 metres downslope from trench 2. These two trenches have provided broad sampling widths. Assays are expected within two weeks. If these two trenches have values similar to trenches 1-3, we will have a zone with a minimum 800 metre strike length, widths ranging 15 to 50 metres, and a vertical drop of 400 metres. An extensive drill program will be required to confirm grade consistency and establish depth. I suspect that drilling of this gold zone will yield the sort of long and high grade intersections that this market is eager to go nuts about. Bottom-fishers who bought cheaply should take this opportunity to sell at least 25% of their position. More aggressive speculators and traders should hang on for much 
higher prices on the heels of positive results for trenches 5 and 7 in about two weeks. (JK owns shares
in PVO). PVO: (604) 681-0110
<P>
<font size=+1><A NAME="Ma">Mazenod Lake and Olympic Dam Mania</font size>
<P>	
Fortune Minerals (FORM-CDN) was halted at $27 on Thursday. I have not seen the news, but hear Fortune has intersected the right type of mineralization on its Olympic Dam prospect in the NWT. Satellites were up on heavy trading: Avalon Ventures (AVL-V: $1.35), GMD Res Corp (GMD-V: $6.30), Alto Industries
(ATO-V: $0.90), Starcore (SOE-V: $1.05) and Moss Resources (MRS-T: $1.05). Fortune clearly has the best ground, while the rest have strategic ground in the belt. Moss, which has optioned 40% of 31,758 claims 
 from WMC, has the best mystery ground because its claims have extensive Paleozoic cover that hides the sort of evidence that makes the Fortune property exciting. If Fortune has a big Olympic Dam style deposit, the most likely location for another one, based on what can already be seen on the rest of the claims in the belt, is on the Moss ground. More on the Mazenod Lake play as it evolves. (JK owns MRS shares) 
MRS: (416) 363-4376
<P>
