<P>
<H1>KAISER EXPRESS # 96 -- 4</H1>
<P>
Commentary by John Kaiser  ------ March 29 , 1996<BR>
<P>
<H2>Highwood Resources Ltd:  Under New Management</H2>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="#Mo"> Mountain Minerals: buy before it stops being a bore </A><BR>
<P>
<P>
<B<Highwood Resources Ltd:  Under New Management</B>
<P>
Most people including myself missed a news release on February 27, 1996 that Mountain Minerals Co Ltd (MIM-T: $0.30) had bought 2,758,771 shares (34.7%) of Highwood Resources Ltd (HWD-T: $1.10, also HIWDF on NASDAQ) at $1.233 each from Conwest Exploration. Conwest is an oil & gas company which had inherited control of Highwood during the eighties when its mining subsidary funded exploration on Highwood's Thor Lake property in the NWT. Conwest was run by ultra-conservatives obsessed with cash flows and returns on equity, and seemingly oblivious to the dynamics of speculative venture capital markets. As a result Highwood has been a market dog since 1988 when Gren Thomas lost control and the push to turn Thor Lake into a beryllium producer fizzled out. Strangely, the market greeted the change of control as a turn for the worse, and sold Highwood down back to its cash breakup level of about $0.80. The stock has since bounced back to the $1.10 level on the strength of accumulati! on by investors such as myself who find it hard to believe that the arrival of new management spells anything but a brighter future for Highwood. After some further digging I have concluded that Highwood is an exceptional buy all the way to the $2 level. Because the stock is relatively illiquid at current prices and has not traded above $2 during the past six years, it is impossible to predict when and where stock will come out. New management is still sorting out its plans for Highwood, but has indicated that dilution of Highwood stock is not on the near-term agenda. I regard Highwood as an important medium-term component of any speculative portfolio, especially for investors concerned that a market crash will ambush this junior bull market later this year. With its focus on rare earths and specialty metals as well as its new home under the wing of the aggressive Royal Oak organization, Highwood is the sort of stock that would flourish in a post-crash bear market when investors a! re eager for exotic plays. The best strategy for investors is to buy some stock up to a $2 limit, wait for the self-fulfilling prophecy to wear itself out, and then do some serious accumulation. Management is not ready to push any buttons yet that will bring new audiences into Highwood's orbit (when and how remains Peggy Witte's secret), but I am confident Highwood will be launched on a double-digit moonshot sooner than later.
<P>
<B>What makes me so bullish on Highwood?</B> At the minimum Highwood is a clean, cash rich shell with intact TSE and NASDAQ listings. We are experiencing the strongest junior resource market in more than a decade, so it makes sense to press this vehicle into service sooner than later. The TSE listing will make institutional financings a piece of cake, and the NASDAQ listing ensures that American brokers can start recommending Highwood to their clients immediately without worrying about penny stock rule paperwork and blue-sky registrations. With working capital of $6.3 million and only 8.2 million fully diluted shares, Highwood at $2 would have a market cap of only $16 million, which is peanuts compared to the pie-in-the-sky valuations of today's hot exploration plays. Peggy Witte and her Royal Oak management team have a reputation for aggressive growth strategies. Royal Oak, which prefers to be a known as a gold producer, holds a 43% equity stake in Mountain Minerals (19.5 million!  shares). Mountain Minerals, in turn, appears to be Royal Oak's vehicle for the development of non precious and base metal assets. Because Royal Oak's upside has become pretty much a function of gold price trends, the American network that helped build Royal Oak is due for a blue-sky distraction. Furthermore, Mountain Minerals, perceived as a plodding industrial minerals producer, would benefit through the appreciation and eventual sale of its investment in Highwood.
<P>
Highwood also happens to be more than a cash-rich shell. The company owns 100% of the Thor Lake property about 100 km southeast of Yellowknife in the Northwest Territories of Canada. Highwood acquired the property in 1976 and together with Placer established a resource of 70 million tons of 0.03% tantalum, 0.4% niobium, 3.5% zirconium and 1.7% combined rare earths before Placer pulled out during the early eighties. By the mid-eighties the focus had shifted to the beryllium potential of the T-Zone within the larger complex, where 497,000 tons of 1.4% beryllium oxide and 1.3 million tons of 0.66% BeO have been outlined. In late 1986 Hecla optioned 50% and spent $4 million on a feasibility study that included metallurgical and marketing research. Hecla dropped the option in early 1990 when it became apparent it could not secure purchase commitments for future production. The beryllium market is dominated by Brush Wellman, whose Spor Mountain open-pit mine in Utah accounts for ! more than half the world's production. Optimism that Thor Lake would soon be in production evaporated when the peace dividend arising from the collapse of communism resulted in major cutbacks in the defence and aerospace industries, both major consumers of specialty metals. Further price weakness in the rare earth/specialty metal sector materialized as Chinese production came on stream. Highwood and others have spent at least $11.5 million on Thor Lake, and Highwood still carries on its books $6.26 million of its own expenditures. For the past five years the market has discounted Thor Lake as a long term sleeper. It appears that Royal Oak is eager to take a fresh look at turning Thor Lake into a commercial production situation.
<P>
The rare earth/specialty metals market is dominated by a few major producers such as Molycorp and Brush Wellman who have both the supply and supply contracts locked up. Two key forces will help new producers break into this market: one is demand driven by new applications, the other is technological breakthroughs in processing. Although the defence and aerospace cutbacks that followed the end of the Cold War hurt demand for rare earth and specialty metals such as beryllium, new demand for consumer and industrial applications will develop as the military declassifies top secret information about the properties of these elements. At the same time the users are demanding higher purities. Owners of existing deposits who can develop cost-effective techniques that yield higher grade concentrates from their particular style of mineralization will have a wedge that can help them secure supply contracts. While breaking into this market is normally a "chicken-and-the-egg" problem for!  newcomers, a window of opportunity may be opening up for companies like Highwood. Peggy Witte's metallurgical background may be no small factor in Royal Oak's decision to secure control of Highwood through Mountain Minerals. The beachheads Royal Oak has established in China through Asia Minerals and Mountain Minerals also open up possibilities of deals to exploit abundant rare earth/specialty metal deposits in the Inner Mongolia region of China. A precise game plan does not yet exist, but management has confirmed my speculations are on the right track.
<P>
<font size=+1><A NAME="M0">Mountain Minerals: buy before it stops being a bore</font size>
<P>
What about Mountain Minerals, which has 45.3 million shares issued and 60.9 million fully diluted?
<P>
Mountain Minerals used to be called Trader Resource Corp, which listed in the VSE in 1983 and spent the first phase of its life exploring the Yellow Giant gold prospect on Banks Island in British Coilumbia under the guidance of Bob Dickinson. The Yellow Giant had seen decades of earlier exploration that yielded numerous high grade zones, but Dickinson's goal was to test the property's bulk tonnage potential. Financed by European institutions, Trader churned out wonderful high grade gold intersections which attracted the mining arm of Australia's Elders IXL Ltd. Elders pumped $4.5 million into the treasury in 1987 and emerged as the new boss of Trader, which achieved its TSE listing on May 28, 1987. After the 1987 market crash Trader lost its focus and bounced around as various groups squabbled over its destiny. In 1993 Royal Oak emerged with control and arranged in March 1994 ! for Trader to acquire an industrial minerals producer called Mountain Minerals Co Ltd for $7.4 million. The stock surged from the pennies in 1993 to the $1 level, where First Marathon brokered a private placement of 11,977,000 units at $0.90 on March 1, 1994 to fund the acquisition. The institutional placees probably never knew what hit them, for the stock promptly headed south, eventually bottoming at $0.15 in late 1995. On Jan 3, 1995 Trader changed its name to Mountain Minerals Co Ltd.
<P>
This "boring" industrial minerals producer, which is expected to eke out earnings of about $500,000 and cash flow of about $1 million on revenues of $10-11 million for the year ending Dec 31/95, is a classic bottom-fish emerging from a period of transition. Most of the revenue comes from three divisions: a) barite, which is used as a filler by the automotive and paint industries, and as a drilling mud component for the oil & gas industry, b) silica, which is supplied to Consumers Glass in southern BC, and c) limestone, which is supplied to the central Alberta market. While these operations can be tweaked to improve the bottom-line somewhat, they cannot contribute to significant earnings and revenue growth. The latter must come from new acquisitions and progress in two other divisions. MIM has a Chinese JV that sources barite feedstock from mom & pop operations and produces a filler product for Asian markets. After a bumpy start this project appears to be on track. MIM contr! ols two zeolite deposits near Kamloops, British Columbia that have been undergoing testing for two years. Mine permitting has been completed and MIM plans to market zeolite as a feed and fertilizer additive for the agricultural industry.
<P>
If speculators are to get excited about Mountain Minerals, it certainly won't be about what the company is already doing. Industrial mineral companies only catch the attention of investors when they exhibit a strong growth pattern. But based on the rumblings I am hearing from Royal Oak's Graham Eacott and MIM's new president, Garry Lynkowski, the company will soon stop treading water. If MIM plans to build shareholder value through a growth by acquisition strategy, it will need higher stock prices. As of Sept 30/95 MIM had working capital of $2.2 million, long term debt of $2.4 million and a book value of $13.4 million ($0.30/share). In anticipation of a growth by acquisition campaign, investors should feel comfortable buying Mountain Minerals to the $0.60 level. If MIM negotiates any major acquisitions, it will likely obtain bridge debt financing through its parent, Royal Oak. If the market likes the value added implications of the acquisition, a cash injection in the form!  of 11,977,000 warrants (held by institutions) exercisable at $1.00 until August 15, 1996 becomes a realistic possibility. The key to a higher profile for Mountain Minerals will likely be Highwood. For further information call Royal Oak's Graham Eacott at (206) 822-8992 or Mountain Minerals' Garry Lynkowski at (403) 261-3999. John Kaiser owns shares in Highwood.  No statement or expression of opinion, or any other matter herein, directly or indirectly, is an offer to buy or sell the securities mentioned.  While we believe the sources of information to be reliable, we in no way represent or guarantee the accuracy thereof, nor the statements contained herein.
<P>
