<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Information Literacy and Library Literacy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H1>Library Literacy</H1></CENTER>
<P>
<B>Contents:</B>
<A HREF="#what">What is Information Literacy?</A> |
<A HREF="#whatliblit">What is Library Literacy?</A> |  
<A HREF="#why">Why be Concerned about Them?</A> | 
<A HREF="#imp">Implications for Higher Education and Scholarship</A> |
<A HREF="#more">How to Become Library Literate</A> |
<P>
<hr size=3>
<P>

<DL>
<DT><A NAME="what"><STRONG>What is Information Literacy?</STRONG></A>
<P>
<DD>Information literacy is the ability to locate, evaluate, manage, and use information from a 
    range of sources for problem solving, decision making, and research.
    <P>
    With the increasing availability of information through conventional and new
    technologies, information literacy has quickly become one of the most vital
    sets of skills for the twenty-first century.  
<P>
<DT><A NAME="whatliblit"><STRONG>What is Library Literacy?</STRONG></A>
<P>
<DD>Library literacy is a very significant component of information literacy.  One could describe 
    library literacy as <STRONG>the ability to learn what library information can help you, 
    where and how to find it, and knowing how to retrieve and manipulate it in ways that are 
    useful to you once you do find it</STRONG>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="why"><DT><STRONG>Why should I care about Library Literacy?  Isn't
    it merely a buzzword for librarians?</STRONG></A>
<P>
<DD>Information has always been a vital resource conferring advantage on those able to make 
    intelligent use of it.  However, in the emerging information-based world economy of the late 
    twentieth century, information is becoming as valuable as traditional resources such as land, 
    labor, and capital.  In other words, information is gold.  This unprecedented growth in the 
    access to and value of information requires an information-literate work force.
    <P>
    Access to information technology such as the Internet does not confer 
    automatic information-literate status one the person fortunate enough to have such access.  
    Merely having access to information is not enough--to really flourish in the information age, one needs to 
    be library literate.
    <P>
    Library literacy is not an instantly acquired skill.  Instead, it's an ongoing process. 
    To survive, we really need to keep on learning--knowledge tools are changing and developing so 
    quickly that no one can ever afford to stop learning nowadays.  The ideal characteristics of a 
    library-literate person are: an inquiring mind, a sense of the interconnection and limitations 
    of all fields of knowledge, and a repertoire of learning skills.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="imp"><STRONG>Why is Library Literacy important in higher education
    and scholarship?</STRONG></A>
<P>
<DD>The amount and complexity of information with which people have to deal is
    growing exponentially. As a result, no course of study in higher education
    is adequate unless it helps to develop students' ability to deal with the
    burgeoning information in their fields. Faculty and librarians should work
    collaboratively to ensure that students graduating from Carleton College can
    recognize and use library tools and resources they're likely to encounter in
    graduate school, professional school, industry, and other vocations.
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="more"><H2>How to Become Library Literate</H2></A>
<P>
A way to initiate your commitment to library literacy is to take advantage of
<A HREF="index.html">instruction opportunities</A> offered by our library staff.
If you prefer the &quot;learn-on-your-own&quot; style, we suggest you
investigate the <A HREF="/resources.html">Library Resources</A> link on our main
library web page.  In addition, here are some additional links where you can
learn more about using our library:
<P>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="librarylingo.html">Library Lingo</A>
<DD>A glossary of library-related terms.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.geocities.com/Athens/8459/lc.html">Library of Congress Classification System</A>
<DD>A subject classification system for books devised by the 
    <A HREF="http://lcweb.loc.gov/homepage/lchp.html">Library of Congress</A>
    (LC) that divides knowledge into 21 subject areas and has a notation of 
    letters and figures that allows for expansion. It is used mostly in 
    academic libraries and special libraries.  This introduction to the LC
    classification system is maintained by Matt T. Rosenberg, a librarian at
    the University of California, Davis.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.geocities.com/Athens/8459/howto.html">Understanding Library of
     Congress Call Numbers</A>
<DD>Excerpt from a section in the resources listed above.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="sudocs.html">U.S. Superintendent of Documents Numbers</A> - 
<DD>Learn how U.S. government documents are arranged on our shelves.
</DL>
<BR>
<BR>
Here are links where you can learn more about the the issues of information and library literacy as
as well as digital scholarship: 
<P>
<UL>
    <DL>
    <DT><A HREF="http://arl.cni.org/index.html">ARL</A> - The Association of Research Libraries
    <DD>AARL is a not-for-profit membership organization comprising the libraries of North American 
        research institutions. The mission of ARL is &quot;...to shape and influence forces affecting 
        the future of research libraries in the process of scholarly communication.&quot;  
	<P>
    <DT><A HREF="http://cause-www.colorado.edu/">CAUSE</A> - The Association for Using
        and Managing Information Resources in Higher Education
    <DD>CAUSE's mission is &quot;...to be an indispensable partner in enabling the transformational 
        changes occurring in higher education through the effective management and use of 
        information resources--technology, services, and information.&quot; 
    <P>
    <DT><A HREF="http://www.cni.org/CNI.homepage.html">Coalition for Networked Information (CNI)</A>
        - Networked Information to Enrich Scholarship
    <DD>This organization's mission is &quot;...to help realize the promise of
        high performance networks and computers for the advancement of
        scholarship and the enrichment of intellectual productivity.&quot; The
        Coalition is a partnership of the
        <A HREF="http://arl.cni.org/index.html">Association of Research Libraries (ARL)</A>, 
	    <A HREF="http://cause-www.colorado.edu/">CAUSE</A>, and
	    <A HREF="http://www.educom.edu/">Educom</A>.
    <P>
    <DT><A HREF="http://www.dlib.org/dlib.html">D-LIB</A> - Digital Libraries Magazine
    <DD>D-LIB is a monthly electronic publication with stories, commentary, and briefings and
        a collection of resources for digital library research.
    <P>
    <DT><A HREF="http://www.educom.edu/">Educom</A> - Transforming Education through Information Technology 
    <DD>Educom is a nonprofit consortium of higher education institutions that &quot;...facilitates the introduction, 
        use, and access to and management of information resources in teaching, learning, scholarship, and research.&quot;
    <P>
    <DT><A HREF="http://www.texshare.edu/TexShareServices/Professional/digital.html">TexShare - Digital Libraries</A> TexShare is &quot;a Texas Library Resource Sharing Program&quot;
    <DD>This page provides links to information about hardware, software, vendors and current digital library projects.
    </DL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
