<html>

<head>
<title>Terry Metz Professional</title>
</head>

<body BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<IMG vspace=3 hspace=10 align=right SRC=terry.GIF border=2 ALT="Terry at his desk.">
<H2>Terry Metz</H2>
<H3>Loan Services & Instruction Librarian</H3>
<P>
<strong>Check out my <a href="/webtutorial/welcome.html">HTML</a> and 
<A HREF="/websearch/welcome.html">Web Search</A> resource pages.</strong>
<p>
Greetings.  As you can see, I have a dual title (not uncommon at small college libraries).  
<P>
<strong>Loan Services</strong> refers to all aspects of lending for the Gould Library.  My loan services responsibilities, which I began in January 1996,  include management and policy for:
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="/circ/circ.html">Circulation</A>, and
<LI><A HREF="/reserves/reserves.html">Reserves</A>
</UL>

<P>

<strong><A HREF="/instruction/index.html">Library Instruction</A></strong>, often referred to as <strong>Bibliographic Instruction</strong> or simply <strong>BI</strong>, is the education of library users to become effective information retrievers.  I share my instruction responsibilities with <A HREF="http://www.library.carleton.edu/staff/carolyn/carolyn.html">Carolyn Sanford</A>.  My instruction responsibilities include:
<UL>
<LI>serving in a scheduled on-call Information Services rotation (helping walk-in users) 
<LI>offering tailored in-class presentations for students and faculty (as needed for their course offerings)
<LI>holding one-on-one appointments with students and faculty (for in-depth consultation)
<LI>promoting general Internet competence as part of the library's mission to deliver electronic information to the Carleton Community (networked information "literacy") 
</UL>

From April 1992 through August 1996, I was also primarily responsible for Library <strong>Systems</strong>, which refers to the use and implementation of computerized information tools.  My systems responsibilities at that time involved managing the operation of electronic information products for the Carleton Library, including:
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="/muse/muse.html">Muse</A>, the
library's online catalog
<LI>Muse's "behind-the-scenes" components of circulation, reserves, cataloging, inventory, serials control, acquisitions, etc., which library users generally don't see
<LI>the Library's other <A HREF="/electronic/electronic.html">electronic resources</A>, such as locally mounted databases, CD-ROMs, and Internet resources
</UL>

<P>

Beginning with fall term 1996, I have handed over much of the day-to-day Muse responsibilities to our new colleague, <A HREF="/staff/scott">Scott Salzman</A>, so that I can focus my talents and energy on user instruction and devote more time to managing the library's other electronic resources.


<P>   
As you might expect, these are very exciting (and busy) times for librarians.  The rapid pace of technological change, as well as concepts such as "the information superhighway" and "the virtual library," are offering unprecedented opportunities and challenges for our profession.
<P>
I rely heavily on a 
<A HREF="/studentworkers/index.html">cadre of student workers</A>.  If you're interested in information technology, maybe you'd like to <A HREF="/studentworkers/jobs/jobs.html">work for me</A>.  
<P>
If you'd like to read more about my student workers, I recently authored a chapter in a book on this topic.  The chapter's entitled, 
"Student Employees Enhance Internet Expertise for a Liberal Arts
College Library." The chapter appears in <STRONG><CITE>The Internet Initiative:  Libraries
Providing Internet Services and How They Plan, Pay, and Manage</CITE></STRONG> published
in 1995 by the American Library Association.  It's located in our library under:  <KBD>Z674 .I59 1995</KBD>

<P>

My door is always open for your questions, comments, or information needs.  You can contact me: 

<UL>
<LI>in person at my office: Library 466
<LI>by phone: (507) 646-4530
<LI>by fax: (507) 646-4087
<LI>by e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:temetz@carleton.edu">temetz@carleton.edu</A>
</UL>
<p>
<HR>
<P>
