<HEAD>
<TITLE>
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H2>COLLECTION MANAGEMENT GUIDELINES FOR THE CARLETON COLLEGE LIBRARY</H2>
May 6th 1985</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<H3>Rationale</H3>

<P>Many members of the Carleton community are regularly involved in selecting
library
materials. In pursuing this task, they must deal with a universe of knowledge
that is
vast and constantly changing, along with a universe of publication that includes
an
annual production of over 200,000 monographs in Western languages alone. Given
the
magnitude of the task of determining the tiny fraction of available materials
that
our limited financial resources will allow us to acquire, it seems appropriate
that
we make an effort to agree on guidelines, establish functional working
relationships,
and list what needs to be agreed upon to come to a consensus of what our
objectives
are in managing our library collections.


<P>A stated program will clarify our collection development objectives to our own
constituency and to other institutions we cooperate with. This will help
eliminate
unwanted redundancy, permit more narrow purchasing in some areas and divestiture
of
others, and provide confidence that titles not purchased can be made available
through resource sharing. It will also help establish a framework of priorities
needed to allow systematic, equitable coordination of expenditures that will
permit
us to use available funds in the wisest possible way. We will be better able to
identify costs and alternatives for meeting goals, and to justify any increases
in
budget that may be needed. Other major benefits of a stated program are that it
will
provide a standard against which the effectiveness of our existing practices and
the
adequacy of existing collections can be measured, stimulate a heightened sense of
accountability in decision-making, and influence book selection more than ever
before
by a keen sense of community priorities.


<P>The process of constructing a written program will serve us as a planning tool
and
a communications device. By stating assumptions, using a systematic approach to
knowledge, and preserving the ideas and insights that emerge from the process, we
will be able to reduce uncertainty and ensure that we touch all of the subject
areas we have in the most equitable way possible within the constraints that we
have, and that no subject areas are overlooked. The intent is to define a living
program that will be subject to review and change as the needs and priorities of
the College change, not to set rigid rules. Deviation from standards and
guidelines
for good reason should be perfectly acceptable, so long as there is an
understanding that a deviation is being made and a consciousness of a purpose
that
justifies it.


<P>What we hope to accomplish is to define and to evaluate the status quo, to
develop a
perspective on selection that incorporates all areas of human knowledge, to
identify
new areas of research or new knowledge interests that need to be accomodated by
the
library, and to identify traditional biases in book selection. The process begs a
healthy questioning of selection practices that may make the responsibilities for
collection development more rigorous, but which will help us to do what we do
more
effectively.



<H3>Goal</H3>


<P>The goal of the library collection at Carleton should be quality, not necessarily
quantity. A collection may be said to have quality for its purpose to the degree
that
it is relevant and appropriate in quantity to each discipline taught, to the
level at
which it is taught, and to the number of faculty and students that use it.
Quality can
deteriorate either when appropriate new material is not added, or when unneeded
material is retained. We need the highest possible percentage of materials that
are
likely to be used by those working within the institution's current and
anticipated
academic program. We do not need the tiny fraction our financial and physical
resources can accomodate of the vast body of material that might possibly be of
use to
someone sometime, but for which no specific relevance to current needs can be
seen.


<P>Our purpose is to define what a quality collection for meeting the needs of
Carleton
is, and to establish guidelines for managing our collections in a manner
consistent
with our definition.


<H3>General Considerations
</H3>

<H4>Currency</H4> Emphasis should be on the collection of current materials, since we have
already reviewed and passed judgement on materials published during the past
several decades in the continuing process of book selection. This does not,
however, preclude our acquiring materials of historical interest pertinent to the
curriculum, filling in older materials in new areas of emphasis in the
curriculum, or obtaining materials that may have been overlooked or not purchased
because of personal biases of a selector or selectors in the past.


<H4>Completeness</H4> We should complete collections needed to support our academic
programs,
but we should not seek completeness for its own sake. Seldom-used earlier volumes
of
many periodicals, for example, are readily available from MINITEX. We should also
avoid succumbing to the collector's enthusiasm for assembling all the minor works
and all the variant editions of an author if the materials we have are sufficient
to
support the curriculum.


<H4>Duplication</H4> When the library purchases a duplicate of something it owns, it
forgoes
purchasing something it does not own, thus reducing the total resource available
to
users. Therefore, the purchase of duplicates is always discouraged, though the
following circumstances may justify limited duplication:
<ol>
<p><li>

Multiple demand and heavy continuous use are anticipated, i.e., users
would not have reasonable access without an additional copy.
<p><li>

<P>For extensive reserve assignments. However, library funds should
never be expended to provide a subsidy for avoiding the purchase
of required texts by students.
<p><li>

<P>When required for efficient operation of the library. There are,
for example, a few heavily used basic sources without which neither
the Science Library or the Main Library could effectively function.
</ol>

<P>Library funds will not be used to purchase duplicate copies or other materials
for the sole use of individuals, academic department offices, or administrative
offices.



<H4>Cooperative Development</H4> All collection management decisions will be made in the
context of cooperation with the St. Olaf library. The goal is to build
complementary
collections to expand the resources available to both college communities. An
entirely new level of cooperation will become possible when a union catalog,
including order, in-process, and circulation files becomes available. The
emphasis
will then shift from avoiding duplication of the occasional title to avoiding
duplication of most materials for which a substantial, continuing local need is
not
envisioned.


<H4>Preservation</H4> We must take all possible measures to preserve the materials we need
to have available for use. It is not part of our mission, however, to attempt to
preserve materials unlikely to be used here because they might be lost to the
world
of scholarship if we did not. If there is any question that material not relevant
to current or anticipated programs is unique, it should be offered to a research
library that collects comprehensively in the field, to be disposed of as they see
fit.


<H4>Language</H4> Since English is the language of instruction, the assumption is that
materials in English can be used by more members of the community than those in
other languages. We will normally favor text in English, with the exception of
materials needed to support foreign language curricula, materials where the
primary
interest is not the text, materials essential to a subject that are not available
in
English, and materials that are significantly superior in the original.


<H4>Geography</H4> The collection will generally focus on those geographic areas included
in current and anticipated curricula, or which we have agreed to cover through a
cooperative agreement with St. Olaf and/or other institutions.


<H4>Censorship</H4> The <U>Library Bill of Rights</U> statement of the American Library
Association
is considered part of this collection development document.




<H4>Gifts</H4> The library solicits and encourages gifts of useful material, provided
they meet our collection management criteria, and, provided that there are no
restrictions attached regarding their arrangement or disposition. Gifts provide
many valuable additions to the collection. The following conditions apply to
gifts:

<ol>
<p><li>
<P>Gift materials will be added under the same criteria that apply to
purchased materials. We will not add gift items simply because
they are available to us, or because we do not already hold them.
<p><li>

<P>The library will not accept gifts with conditions as to their
disposition or location except by express permission of the library
director.
<p><li>

<P>The library reserves the right to dispose of unneeded gifts in
whatever manner it sees fit.
<p><li>

<P>Duplicate copies received as gifts will be added only if the
circulation record of the existing copy suggests a single copy is
not sufficient to meet the demand. This does not preclude the
exchange of a gift copy in good condition for a worn or mutilated
existing copy.

<p><li>
<P>The library cannot legally appraise gifts for tax or inheritance
purposes, but it may assist donors in locating prices in book
auction records, etc.
</ol>


<H4>Classes of Material
</H4>

<H5>Paperbacks</H5> A book is purchased in paperback only when it is unavailable in hard
copy at a reasonable price, or a cost saving can be realized by purchasing a copy
in paperback of the same quality as the hardcover version. In general, paperback
books are bound before being added to the collection. Exceptions are the Hubbs
current reading paperback collection and added copies for reserve expected to be
needed for the current year only.


<H5>Textbooks</H5> The library will not normally add textbooks to the collection unless
they constitute a major reference or research work in the field that is not
otherwise available.


<H5>Juveniles</H5> Books for children, young adults, etc. will not be added to the
collection unless specifically needed for use in a course.


<H5>Editions</H5> Variant editions of a title will be added only if they are &quot;standard&quot;
editions or contain substantial changes. This does not apply to updated editions
in scientific and other fields where currency is of importance.


<H5>Rare Books</H5> The library does not normally purchase rare materials, but it does try
to acquire as many examples of various periods and styles of printing, binding,
book illustration, etc., as possible by gift. Materials that are not rare, but
are
fragile, of unusual format, or otherwise in need of special care and protection
are
kept with the rare books.


<H5>Periodicals</H5> The management of serials requires a higher degree of selectivity
than that of books. Initiating a serial subscription implies an ongoing and
costly commitment for many years to come in terms of payments, binding, and
storage. Responsibility for selecting periodicals is shared by faculty and the
library staff. The annual subscription list is essentially pre-selected, the
result of many decisions made over previous decades. The library staff
coordinates periodic reviews of titles of interest to the various departments to
identify items that might be dropped and to gather suggestions for titles to be
added. The results of these reviews are combined and reviewed by the library
staff, taking into account St. Olaf current and planned holdings, interlibrary
loan request records, etc. A list of all planned adds and drops is circulated to
the faculty for comment before changes are made. Because serials costs are
rising at a much faster rate than book costs, every effort is made to hold the
number of subscriptions to the minimum consistent with need, and to coordinate
holdings as much as possible with other Northfield libraries.


<P>The library will normally rely on interlibrary loan for periodical backfiles it
does not hold. Exceptions might be made for material in great demand, as
evidenced by interlibrary loan requests, limited backfiles needed to support a
new area of study, or needed backfiles that for some reason are not available
through interlibrary loan. Microform would be the normal medium for added
backfiles.


<P>Ordering of single issues/volumes, or scattered and incomplete sets of
periodicals
is generally discouraged. Copies of single issues of periodicals for reserves may
be freely ordered for use without cataloging, to be retained only as long as a
current need for them exists. In those rare instances where it appears that a
continuing need for a single periodical issue exists, the library will bind the
issue and add it to the periodicals collection.



<H5>Newspapers</H5> Approximately 40 current subscriptions to major national and
international newspapers are maintained. A few of the major indexed ones are also
received on microfilm. Most newspapers are retained 1-3 months, or until
microfilm
copy arrives. The titles received change little from year to year, but the
library
is happy to receive suggestions for substitute subscriptions that might better
serve the educational program of the college. Any titles suggested will be
reviewed with the periodicals lists. The only newspaper files permanently
retained
in print are Carleton publications.


<H5>Documents U.S.</H5> Government Documents are a special class of materials that are
acquired and maintained under Federal regulations. Management of this material
is covered in a separate policy statement. Documents other than those of the
U.S. Government are treated as books or periodicals, as the case may be.


<H5>Microform</H5> Microform is an invaluable means of storing and making available
material that is bulky and will receive relatively low use, that will deteriorate
rapidly, or that is rare, expensive, or otherwise unavailable. Examples are
newspapers and the American Cultural Series. Microform is normally avoided for
material that is expected to receive heavy use. Printed copies of materials we
hold on microform should not be ordered unless heavy use is anticipated or some
special feature that the film does not provide, such as color illustrations, is
needed.


<H5>Maps</H5> The library collects only those maps placed on deposit by U.S. Defense
Mapping Agency. U.S.G.S. quads are maintained in the Geology Department.


<H5>Other Materials</H5> This policy addresses only those materials--books, periodicals,
newspapers, microform, documents, maps, spoken word recordings--currently
comprising the library collections. Statements regarding the collecting of
other materials will be developed at such time as the library begins collecting
them.


<H4>Separate Collections
</H4>

<H5>Science Library</H5> No distinction is made between the Science Library and the Main
Library for the purpose of general collection management guidelines. Particular
needs of science disciplines will be covered by specific policies to be developed
for each discipline, as they are for other disciplines.


<H5>Archives</H5> Since the Archives is located in the Library and is administratively
under
the College Librarian, the Library/Bookstore Committee recognizes a
responsibility
to advise on policy for the Archives as a part of the Library. A separate policy
statement will be prepared for Archives.



<P>This document states the general goals and guidelines for the library and for
collection management at Carleton. It is the first of three stages in the
process of creating an instrument that will be a reflection of the nature of
the Carleton curriculum and an expression of faculty library needs. It is
intended to foster consistency and good communication between those engaged
in book selection. The completed policy will constitute a commitment of those
selecting library materials throughout the College to maintain the collecting
program described and to make periodic and carefully worked out adjustments
over the months and years ahead that will enable it to serve as a dependable
living instrument of College policy.
<P>
<hr>
<P>The next step will be for faculty in each department to prepare, with the
assistance of a librarian, a 2-3 page document outlining their overall program,
areas of common concern with other departments, points in the general collection
management guidelines that may need to be amplified for the discipline, other
concerns specific to the discipline, a brief overview of the broad fields of
interest to the discipline, and general levels of collecting for each field.


<P>The final stage will be a systematic department by department review that will
collectively touch on all fields of knowledge. The result of this review will
be a detailed profile listing the specific subject areas in which Carleton is
collecting library materials and the level at which collecting is being
carried on in each subject area.


<P>The completed document will enable members of the faculty to be aware of what
is being collected in each subject area of interest to them, whether or not
it falls within a field of general interest to their discipline. They will
also be able to suggest changes in the profile and to comment on all
contemplated changes before they are made.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
