<CENTER><H1>Library Instruction</H1></CENTER>
<STRONG>
CONTENTS: 
<A HREF="#what">What is Library Instruction</A> |
<A HREF="#course">Course Instruction Pages</A> |
<A HREF="#fac">Faculty and Staff Instruction Opportunities (anyone eligible)</A> |
<A HREF="#lib">Library Staff Instruction Opportunities (only library employees eligible)</A>
</STRONG>
<P>
<hr size=3>
<P>
<A NAME="what"><STRONG>What is Library Instruction:</STRONG>
<P>
<DL>
<DD><strong>Library Instruction</strong>, commonly referred to as <strong>Bibliographic Instruction</strong>
or simply <strong>BI</strong>, is the education of library users to become effective information retrievers 
and consumers.
<P>
<DD>As you might expect, the proliferation of information resources of all types as well as the rapid pace of technological 
change (including concepts such as the "information superhighway" and the "virtual library")
are offering unprecedented opportunities and challenges for our students and faculty.
<P>
<DD>Contact <A HREF="/staff/carolyn/carolyn.html">Carolyn Sanford</A> or
<A HREF="/staff/terry/terry.html">Terry Metz</A> (or <A HREF="/staff/charlie/">Charles Priore</A> 
if you teach in the natural sciences) to arrange for <A HREF="biarrange.html">tailored instruction</A>
for both fundamental skills and for keeping you and your students abreast of the latest information resources in your field.
</DL>
<P>
<hr size=3>
