<Title>Reserves Policy Summary</Title>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H2><Center>Reserves Policy Summary</Center></h2><p>

<STRONG>Telephone numbers</STRONG><BR><BR>  
<UL> 
<LI>Gould Library Reserves Desk: 646-4263 
<LI>Gould Library Circulation Desk: 646-4260
</UL>

<CENTER><H3>Reserves Resources and Policies:</H3><P>

<STRONG>
<A HREF="#ID">Library Barcodes/ID</A> |
<A HREF="#LOANS">Loan Policy</A> |
<A HREF="#FINES">Overdue Material Penalties</A> |
<A HREF="#ON">Placing Material on Reserve</A> |
<A HREF="#PHOTOCOPY">Photocopies on Reserve</A> |
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR><HR><BR>

<A NAME="ID"></a>
<IMG SRC="idcard.jpg" height=90 width=150 vspace=5 hspace=5 align=right> 
<BR CLEAR=left><H3>Library Barcode ID</H3>

Anone who would like to borrow material from the Carleton library must be
registered in the librarys circulation computer system and have been issued a
library barcode ID.<BR><BR>

You must present your library barcode ID for any circulation or reserve
transaction. No other form of identification is acceptable.<BR><BR>

Carleton students, faculty and staff are registered automatically and may
pick up their library ID card at the main library circulation desk. Students,
faculty & staff from St. Olaf may register the first time they use the
Carleton library. All others should inquire about their eligibility for a
library ID card at the circulation desk.  A form of identification, such as a driver's
license or campus food service card, may be required to secure the library card.
<BR><BR><BR>
<HR>

<A NAME="LOANS"></a>
<H3>Loan Periods for Reserve Items</H3><p>
There are two classifications of reserve material:<br>
<UL>
<LI><strong><A NAME="OPEN">Open Reserve</a></strong> Open reserve is for optional 
course-related reading. Materials circulate for <strong>two days.</strong> These materials may also be used
in the Library without checking them out.
<br>  
<LI><Strong><A NAME="CLOSED">Closed Reserve</a></strong> Closed reserve is for required 
course-related reading or for optional material needing greater security. Materials 
circulate for <strong>two hours</strong>, or on an overnight basis.<p>
</UL>
Items placed on reserve include Carleton and St. Olaf library materials as well as personal 
copies and photocopies. We do not place items on reserve such as periodicals, special 
collection books, and books from libraries other than Carleton or St. Olaf. Interlibrary 
services is not to be used for obtaining items for reserve.
</ul><br><br>


<HR>
<A NAME="FINES"></a>
<H3>Overdue Penalties for Reserve Items</H3>
The process for overdue open reserve material is similar to that for general
collection material, except the interval between overdue notices is three
days.<BR><BR>

The process for overdue closed reserve material is different because no
overdue notices are sent, and a system of fines applies:<BR><BR>

<table>
<td>10 minutes late to 60 minutes late:<td>$ 1.00<tR> 
<td>More than 1 hour but less than 2 hours late:<td>$ 2.00<tR> 
<td>More than 2 hours but less than 3 hours late:<td>$ 7.00<tR> 
<td>More than 3 hours but less than 4 hours late:<td>$12.00<tR> 
<td>More than 4 hours but less than 5 hours late:<td>$17.00<tR> 
<td>More than 5 hours but less than 6 hours late:<td>$22.00<tR> 
<td>More than 6 hours but less than 7 hours late:<td>$27.00</table><br><br>

In addition to the fine incurred, students who keep closed reserve material
overdue for more than 7 hours are referred to the Academic Standing Committee
automatically for disciplinary action.<BR><BR>
<HR><BR>

<A NAME="ON"></a>
<H2>Placing Material On Reserve</H2>
<br>
<br>
<STRONG>Plan Ahead</STRONG>--Requests for material to be placed on reserve should be 
made two weeks before the material will be needed.  Make sure your 
material is on reserve before making assignments.  <I><STRONG>Due to the volume of 
material placed on reserve, the library cannot offer same day or rush requests for placing
items on reserve.</STRONG></I>When bringing materials to the Reserve Office, indicate your 
name, the course name and number, and whether the materials should be on open or closed 
reserve.  If you wish the Library to purchase any materials to be placed on reserve, 
please notify the Library Acquisitions Department one full term in advance.

<!--THERE SHOULD BE A LINK FOR THIS--!>


</UL>


<HR>
<A NAME="PHOTOCOPY"></a>
<STRONG>Photocopying</STRONG>

<p>
The Library may place excerpts from copyrighted works on reserve for faculty members in 
accordance with copyright guidelines similar to those governing formal classroom 
distribution for face-to-face teaching. These guidelines apply to library reserves, which 
functions as an extension of classroom readings and reflects the student's right to 
photocopy for personal scholastic use. Photocopies may be placed on reserve for class 
assignments and other educational activities, such as advanced independent study and 
research.
<P>
All reserve photocopies must be submitted by the course instructor. <STRONG><I>The Library 
cannot photocopy articles for placement on reserve.</STRONG></I> Please include citation 
information on the first page. Reserve photocopies will be returned to you at the 
conclusion of each course, along with a list of all items on reserve for your course. 
Please save the list if you plan to place the items on reserve again. 
<P>
Examples of photocopied materials which may be placed on reserve include:
<UL>
<LI>a chapter from a book
<LI>an article from a periodical or newspaper
<LI>a short story, short essay, or short poem, whether or not from a collective work
<LI>a chart, diagram, graph, drawing, cartoon or picture from a book, periodical or newspaper
</UL>
You should follow these guidelines when submitting photocopies from copyrighted works for 
placement on reserve.
<UL>
<LI>The amount of material should be reasonable in relation to the total amount of material 
assigned for one term of a course, taking into account the nature of the course, its 
subject matter, and its level. Library reserves should not take the place of a purchased 
textbook, but rather supplement the other course material.
<BR>
<LI>The number of copies should be reasonable in light of the number of students enrolled, 
the difficulty and timing of assignments, and the number of other courses which may assign 
the same material. One copy per 10 -15 students is usually sufficient.
<BR>
<LI>Each copy of the material should contain a copyright notice on the first page. This 
notice consists of: "Copyright   [year], [name of copyright owner]". An example would be 
copyright  1983, Alice Walker. Such a notice is often already present on the first page 
of a journal article. The information needed to compose such a notice is usually available 
on the title page of the work.
<BR>
<LI>Only photocopy the material if doing so does not harm the market for the work. (In 
general, the Library should own at least one copy of the work.) The number of articles or 
chapters photocopied from a single journal issue or book should be limited. A collection 
of copies comprising an entire journal issue or book will not be accepted for reserve. The 
reserve use of the same photocopied materials in multiple courses or successive years 
usually requires advance permission from the owner of the copyright.
</UL>
<BR>
<P>Works in the public domain (not protected by copyright) may always be placed on reserve, 
within the space limitation of 5 copies per item.
<P>
Copyrighted works may also be placed on reserve in excess of the guidelines (but within 
the space limitations of 5 copies) when permission to engage in such practice has been 
obtained from the copyright owner.
<P><BR>



<STRONG>The U.S. Copyright Law is as follows:</STRONG><p>
<UL>
<LI>The copyright law of the United States (Title 17, United States Code) governs the
making of photocopies or other reproductions of copyrighted material.
<LI>Under certain conditions specific in the law, libraries and archives are authorized 
to furnish a photocopy or reproduction.  One of these specified conditions is that the 
photocopy or reproduction is not to be "used for any purpose other than private study, 
scholarship, or research."  If a user makers a request for, or later uses, a photocopy
or reproduction for purposes in excess of "fair use", that user may be liable for 
copyright enfringement.
<LI>This institution reserves the right to refuse to accept a copying order if, in its 
judgment, fulfillment of the order would involve violation of copyright law.
</UL><br>



<STRONG>How To Obtain Permission To Copy</STRONG>
<P>
It is the responsibility of the instructor to obtain permission from copyright owners to 
photocopy in excess of the guidelines described above. In some instances, the publisher 
may assess a fee for the permission. This fee would also be the instructor's 
responsibility. The American Association of Publishers suggests that the following 
information be included in a permission request letter to the copyright owner:
<UL>
<LI>title, author and/or editor, and edition of materials to be duplicated
<LI>exact material to be used, giving amount, page numbers, chapters, and, if possible, a 
photocopy of the material
<LI>number of copies to be made
<LI>purpose of duplicated materials
<LI>form of distribution (classroom, newsletter, etc.)
<LI>whether or not the material is to be sold
<LI>type of reprint (ditto, photography, offset, typeset)
</UL>
<P>
The request should be sent, together with a self-addressed return envelope, to the 
permissions department of the publisher in question. If the address of the publisher does 
not appear in the material, it may be obtained in The Literary Marketplace, published by 
the R. R. Bowker Company and shelved under call number PN161 .L5 in the Gould Library 
Reference collection.
<P>
The process of granting permission requires time for the publisher to check the status of 
the copyright and to evaluate the nature of the request. It is advisable, therefore, to 
allow enough lead time to obtain permission before the materials are needed. 
<P>
The Copyright Clearance Center also has the right to grant permission and collect fees for 
photocopying rights for certain publications. Dealing with the CCC, when applicable, can 
often prove more efficient than dealing directly with publishers.  Their address is:



<P><PRE>
Copyright Clearance Center, Inc.
222 Rosewood Drive
Danvers, MA 01923
Tel: (508) 750-8400
Fax: (508) 750-4744
<A HREF="http://www.copyright.com/">http://www.copyright.com/</A></PRE>
<BR><BR>

Vonnie Otte is the Reserve Coordinator. Items are placed on reserve during her office 
hours which are:
<ul>
<li>8 a.m. - 3 p.m. Monday - Thursday
<li>8 a.m. - 12 p.m. Friday
</ul><p>
Items are not placed on reserve between noon on Friday and 8 a. m. on Monday.

<BR>

Any questions should be addressed to <A HREF="mailto:votte@carleton.edu">Vonnie Otte</a>.
She may be reached at 646-4272 or in her office (Library 418).
<P>
<HR>
