 <HTML>
 <HEAD>
 <TITLE>Muse: Carleton College Online Catalog</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><H1>Muse</H1></CENTER>
<B>Contents:</B>
<A HREF="#whatis">What is Muse?</A> |
<A HREF="#whycall">Why Call it Muse?</A> |
<A HREF="#access">How to Access Muse</A> |
<A HREF="#usefor">What do I use Muse for?</A> |
<A HREF="#review">Reviewing Your Patron Information, Renewing Items, & Placing Holds on Checked-Out Items</A> |
<A HREF="#status">Status of Library Materials</A> |
<A HREF="#email">E-mail of Overdue Notices</A> |
<A HREF="#howtouse">How do I use Muse?</A> |
<A HREF="#getinfo">Getting Information & Making Subbestions</A> |
<A HREF="#word">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#author">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#title">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#author/title">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#subject">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#numbers">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#repeat">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#wilson">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#connect">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#view">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#reserve">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#view">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#quit">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
<A HREF="#connect">Basic Muse Searching</A> |
	 
<A HREF="#tips">Muse Tips</A> | 
<A HREF="#painting">Painting of the Muses</A> 
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><NAME="what is"><STRONG>What is Muse?</STRONG></A>
<DL>Muse is the pet name for Carleton Library's OPAC 
<A HREF="http://www.library.carleton.edu/catalogs/regionalcats.html">
(online public access catalog)</A>. 
More specifically, Muse is an integrated library computer system from 
<A HREF="http://herald.usask.ca/~scottp/iii.html">Innovative Interfaces Inc.</A> 
(referred to as III) running on a DEC Alpha 3000 computer.
<P>
<DT><NAME="whycall"><STRONG>What Call it Muse?</STRONG></A>
<DD>In classical mythology, the Muses were the daughters of Mnemosyne and Zeus. They were not only divine
singers, whose chorales and hymns delighted Zeus and other gods: they also presided over thought in all 
its forms:  eloquence, persuasion, knowledge, history, mathematics, astronomy.
<P>
From the classical period the number of Muses was standardized to nine, and the following list was 
generally accepted:  Clio, Polyhymnia, Euterpe, Terpsichore, Erato, Melpomene, Thalia, and Urania.<A HREF="#*">*</A>  
It was only gradually that each came to be attributed with a specific function, and these vary from 
one author to another.  
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Calliope, the first of them all in dignity, was said to be the Muse of epic poetry,
<LI>Clio of history,
<LI>Polyhymnia of mime,
<LI>Euterpe of the flute,
<LI>Terpischore of light verse and dance,
<LI>Erato of lyric choral poetry [and erotica],
<LI>Melpomene of tragedy,
<LI>Thalia of comedy, and
<LI>Urania of astronomy.
</UL>
<P>
<A NAME="*">*Grimal, Pierre, <STRONG>Dictionary of Classical Mythology</STRONG>, New York, NY : Blackwell, 1986</A> 
<P>
<DT><NAME="access"><STRONG>How to Access Muse</STRONG></A>
<DD>Muse is available at the College Library, or you can access it remotely via telnet:
<KBD><STRONG>muse.library.carleton.edu</STRONG><KBD>
<P>
Note: Most computers on the Carleton campus will connect to Muse via telnet if you supply the word:   
<KBD><STRONG>muse</STRONG><KBD>
<P>
However, you need the full address listed above to access Muse from outside the Carleton community.
<P>
<DT><NAME="usefor"><STRONG>What do I use Muse for?</STRONG></A>
<DD>Muse is the primary finding tool for materials owned by the Carleton Library, including:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>books (both owned and on order)
<LI>other book-like items such as subject bibliographies, indexes, encyclopedias, handbooks, dictionaries,
	almanacs, atlases, etc.
<LI>many U.S. government documents (1976- )
<LI>periodical titles (journals, magazines,  newspapers, etc.)
</UL>
<P>
These items are <CITE>not</CITE> found in Muse:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>full text of periodical articles
<LI>most video and films owned by the Media Center
<LI>most U.S. government documents published prior to 1976
<LI>scores and recording owned by the Music Department
</UL>
<P>
<DT><NAME="review"><STRONG>Reviewing Your Patron Information, Renewing Items, & Placing Holds on Checked-Out Items</STRONG></A>
<DD>At any time, you can check the status of items you have borrowed from the library and when they're due back. 
If you discover that you need more time to use a book you've already checked out, you can renew the loan on the item.  
If you discover that a book you want is checked out, you can place a hold on that book yourself.
<P>
<DT><NAME="status"><STRONG>Status of Library Materials</STRONG></A>
<DD>Not only is Muse a catalog, but it also controls circulation of library materials. This means that an item's 
status is displayed along with the call number.  If a book is checked out, you can see its due date.
<P>
<DT><NAME="email"><STRONG>E-mail of Overdue Notices</STRONG></A>
<DD>If you wish, you can request that library notices come to you in the form of e-mail messages. 
Ask at the Circulation Desk about how to arrange for this.
<P>
<DT><NAME="howtouse"><STRONG>How do I use Muse?</STRONG></A>
<DD>Muse employs a "menu-driven" search interface, which means that you never have to memorize 
confusing commands. All options available to you at any particular location within Muse are indicated 
on the screen.  Decide which option you want from the menu, and press the corresponding key.
<P>
<DT><NAME="getinfo"><STRONG>Getting Information & Making Suggestions</STRONG></A>
<DD><KBD><STRONG>I > Library INFORMATION</STRONG></KBD> contains answers to the most frequently asked 
questions about the library and its services. You can notify library staff about additional items 
the library should purchase by choosing  <KBD><STRONG>A > ADDITIONAL</STRONG></KBD> items the library 
should acquire.  If you wish to make suggestions about library services in general, select the option  
<KBD><STRONG>S > SUGGESTIONS</STRONG></KBD>.
</DL>
<P>
<H2>Basic Searching</H2>
<DL>
<DT><NAME="word"><STRONG>W > WORDS in the subjects, titles, and contents</STRONG></A> 
<DD>Use the WORD index to perform keyword searches when you don't have a specific Library of Congress 
    Subject Heading, title, or author in mind.  Example:  <KBD><STRONG>w movies</STRONG></KBD>
    <P>
    <STRONG>Truncation</STRONG>  Perform right truncation in the WORD index by using the * symbol:
	Example:  <KBD><STRONG>w cat*</STRONG></KBD> (retrieves the words <KBD><STRONG>cat</STRONG></KBD>, 
	<KBD><STRONG>catalog</STRONG></KBD>, <KBD><STRONG>catalogs</STRONG></KBD>, <KBD><STRONG>catacombs</STRONG></KBD>, 
	<KBD><STRONG>catastrophes</STRONG></KBD>, <KBD><STRONG>cats</STRONG></KBD>, etc.)
    <P>
    <STRONG>Boolean operators</STRONG>  Perform boolean word searches by using the operators 
    <STRONG>AND</STRONG>, <STRONG>OR</STRONG>, or <STRONG>NOT</STRONG> (or <STRONG>NO</STRONG>).
    <P>Examples:
    <P><UL>
       <LI><KBD><STRONG>w cat and dog</STRONG></KBD> (retrieves items that contain both words <KBD><STRONG>cat</STRONG></KBD> and <KBD><STRONG>dog</STRONG></KBD>) 
	   <LI><KBD><STRONG>w cat or dog</STRONG></KBD> (retrieves items that contain the word <KBD><STRONG>cat</STRONG></KBD> and items that contain the word <KBD><STRONG>dog</STRONG></KBD>)
	   <LI><KBD><STRONG>w cat not dog</STRONG></KBD> (retrieves items that contain the word cat, but not items that contain dog)
	Note:  Searching two words without an operator is the same as using <KBD><STRONG>AND (<KBD><STRONG>cat dog = cat and dog)

Nested searches - Use parenthetical expressions in WORD searches. Parenthetical expressions can contain 
the Boolean operators AND, OR, and NOT (or NO); they can also be nested.

	Examples:  sonata not (baroque or piano)	
		   sonata not baroque not piano
<P>
<DT><NAME="author"><STRONG>A > AUTHOR</STRONG></A> 
<DD>Use the AUTHOR index to find works written by a particular person or organization.  Note:  enter the last name 
first.  Example:  <KBD><STRONG>a silko, leslie marmon</STRONG></KBD>
<P>
<DT><NAME="title"><STRONG>T > TITLE</STRONG></A> 
<DD>Use the TITLE index when you know the exact title of the item you need. Examples:  
<KBD><STRONG>t almanac of the dead</STRONG></KBD> or <KBD><STRONG>t journal of geology</STRONG></KBD>
<P>
<STRONG>Tip on Using Initial Articles</STRONG> - You may choose to enter or not enter initial articles 
(e.g., <CITE>a</CITE>, <CITE>an</CITE>, <CITE>the</CITE>, <CITE>le</CITE>, <CITE>der</CITE>, etc.); either way, 
Muse will retrieve the same record(s). For example, you may input the title <KBD><STRONG>The New Yorker</STRONG></KBD> 
or <KBD><STRONG>New Yorker</STRONG></KBD>, or <KBD><STRONG>A farewell to arms</STRONG></KBD> or 
<KBD><STRONG>Farewell to arms</STRONG></KBD>; in either case, Muse will retrieve the correct record(s).
<P>
If you wish to retrieve titles beginning with a word which is normally considered to be an initial article, 
type the initial article twice when performing the search. Examples:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>To search for:  <CITE>A to Z, the Alphabet</CITE>
<LI>Enter:  </STRONG></KBD>a a to z, the alphabet</STRONG></KBD>
</UL>
<P>
<DT><NAME="author/title"><STRONG>B > AUTHOR/TITLE</STRONG></A> 
<DD>Use the AUTHOR/TITLE index for better precision if you already know the author and title of the work you need.

	Examples:  b silko, leslie <RETURN>
		      almanac
<P>
<DT><NAME="subject"><STRONG>S > SUBJECT (Library of Congress)</A>
<DD>Perform a SUBJECT search only when you know the precise Library of Congress subject heading you need. 
If you don't know the precise subject heading you need, do a WORD search on your topic and examine the 
subject headings of the items you retrieve. Or consult the four volume Library of Congress Subject Headings, 18th ed. near the Reference Desk. 

	Example:  s motion picture			s indians of north america

<DT><NAME="numbers"><STRONG>N > NUMBERS</STRONG></A>
<DD>Select the NUMBER index when you already have the number in one of these categories:
<P>
<STRONG>
<PRE>
		C > CALL numbers (Library of Congress) 
		I > ISBN, ISSN, Recording numbers
		G > GOVERNMENT Documents (U.S. Superintendent of Documents)
</PRE>
</STRONG>
<P> 
<DT><NAME="repeat"><STRONG>P > Repeat PREVIOUS Search</STRONG></A>
<DD>If you need to repeat the previous search, select this option. Up to <CITE>ten</CITE> of your 
most recent searches can be repeated: <KBD><STRONG>p [select from list]</STRONG></KBD>
<P>
<DT><NAME="wilson"><STRONG>J > Wilson JOURNAL Citation Indexes</STRONG></A>
<DD>Use this resource to identify journal articles which have been included in the following indexes since 1990- :
<P>
<UL>
<LI><CITE>Art Index
<LI><CITE>Biological & Agricultural Index
<LI><CITE>Social Sciences Index
<LI><CITE>General Science Index
<LI><CITE>Humanities Index
<LI><CITE>Business Periodicals Index
<LI><CITE>Reader's Guide to Periodical Literature
</UL>
<P>
<DT><NAME="wilson"><STRONG>J > Wilson JOURNAL Citation Indexes</STRONG></A>		
	 C > CONNECT to another resource

	Use this option to make automatic connections to  
	a select group of other online library catalogs and 
	databases of value to the Carleton community. 

 
<DT><NAME="wilson"><STRONG>J > Wilson JOURNAL Citation Indexes</STRONG></A>		
	 V > VIEW your circulation record

	This option allows you to retrieve the following 
	information: 

		C > Display CHECKED OUT items
								H > Display HELD items
								F > Display FINES
<DT><NAME="wilson"><STRONG>J > Wilson JOURNAL Citation Indexes</STRONG></A>
   R > RESERVE Lists
  
Select this item to identify materials being held 
on course reserve 

	P > Retrieve by PROFESSOR
	C > Retrieve by COURSE
 
<DT><NAME="quit"><STRONG>Q > QUIT</STRONG></A>
<DD>Use this feature to exit from Muse.
<P> 
<H2>General Muse Tips</H2>
<DT><NAME="caps"><STRONG>Capitalization</STRONG></A>
<DD>You may enter search statements in uppercase or lowercase (or mixed case). Muse is not sensitive to case, 
since it translates all search statements to lowercase.
<P>
<DT><NAME="punc"><STRONG>Punctuation</STRONG></A>
<DD>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Muse treats the ampersand (&) as if it were the word "and" spelled out.
<LI>Apostrophes are removed.
<LI>Most other punctuation marks are replaced by spaces.
<LI>Repeated punctuation marks or repeated spaces are treated as a blank space. Whether or not 
these punctuation marks are included has no effect on your search.
</UL>
<P>
<DT><NAME="return"><STRONG><RETURN> shortcut</STRONG></A>
<DD>Much of the time in Muse, you don't need to use the <RETURN> key. You really need to use 
it only when executing a search from the search screens, or when you make a menu selection 
from a menu which has more than 9 choices.
<P>
<DT><NAME="suptrunc"><STRONG>Suppressing Truncation</STRONG></A>
<DD>Searches performed in the AUTHOR, TITLE, AUTHOR/TITLE, or SUBJECT indexes are considered "phrase searches" 
(as opposed to keyword and number searches). Muse records containing a heading which  begins with a particular 
phrase may be retrieved by entering as much or as little of the phrase as desired.
<P>
For example, keying an AUTHOR search for <KBD><STRONG>smith</STRONG></KBD> will retrieve all the records containing 
<KBD><STRONG>Smithsonian</STRONG></KBD> as an author, as well as all those containing <KBD><STRONG>smith</STRONG></KBD>.
 Entering <KBD><STRONG>sm</STRONG></KBD> will retrieve all records containing authors whose names begin with 
<KBD><STRONG>sm</STRONG></KBD>, such as <KBD><STRONG>Smythe</STRONG></KBD>, <KBD><STRONG>Smart</STRONG></KBD>, etc. 
<P>
To instruct Muse to restrict a search to just the search statement entered (and not to expand it by searching the 
index for all headings beginning with the search statement), key a vertical bar (<KBD><STRONG>|</STRONG></KBD>) 
at the end of the search statement (e.g., the search for <KBD><STRONG>cat|</STRONG></KBD> will only retrieve 
records with the heading <KBD><STRONG>cat</STRONG></KBD>, not records containing headings <CITE>beginning</CITE> with 
<KBD><STRONG>cat</STRONG></KBD>, such as <KBD><STRONG>catalog</STRONG></KBD> or <KBD><STRONG>catch</STRONG></KBD>, 
or <KBD><STRONG>cat domestic</STRONG></KBD>, etc.).
<P>
The vertical bar, sometimes called a pipe, is ususally located on the key with the backslash on most keyboards. 
<P>
<DT><NAME="limit"><STRONG>Limiting a Search</STRONG></A>
<DD>Limit a searchby choosing <KBD><STRONG>L</STRONG></KBD> from the menu after performing  that search. 
You can limit your search by any several fields, including language, material format, location, and the other 
options illustrated here:
<P>
<STRONG>
<PRE>
                         L > LANGUAGE
                         M > MATERIAL type
                         B > BIBLIOGRAPHIC level
                         A > Words in the AUTHOR
                         T > Words in the TITLE
                         S > Words in the SUBJECT
                         P > PUBLISHER
                         W > WHERE Item is located
                         Y > YEAR of publication
                         R > RETURN to Browsing
</PRE>
</STRONG>
<P> 
<DT><NAME="browse"><STRONG>Browsing the Shelves & Finding Related Items</STRONG></A>
<DD>
<UL>
<LI><KBD><STRONG>Z > Show Items Nearby on Shelf</STRONG></KBD> - If you select this option, Muse displays 
    that portion of the call number index which includes the call number from your record. By moving forward 
    and backward from this point in the list, you can "browse" the other items nearby on the shelf. 
<LI><KBD><STRONG>S > SHOW SIMILAR items</STRONG></KBD>  If you select this option, Muse presents a display 
    of related subject, authors, and titles for which Muse will search.
</UL>
<P> 
<DT><NAME="export"><STRONG>Marking Records for Export or E-Mail</STRONG></A>
<DD><KBD><STRONG>E > Mark items for EXPORT</STRONG></KBD> - By selecting this option, you can 
    download Muse records to a file or send them to any e-mail address.
<P>
</DL>
Click on the image below to make a telnet connection to Muse.  Login as: <STRONG><KBD>muse</KBD></STRONG>
<P>
<A HREF=telnet://muse.library.carleton.edu><IMG Align=left SRC=muses.GIF ALT""></A><P>
The Muses Urania and Calliope, by Simon Vouet (1590-1649)
<br clear=left>
<br>
<br>
