<html>
<head>
<title>Carleton College Library - Electronic Resources</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<center><H1>Electronic Resources in the Carleton College Library</H1></center>

<P>
Here's your starting point for learning more about the electronic information resources
the Gould Library has to offer.
<P>
<hr size=3>
<P>
<DL>
<A NAME="opac">
<DT><STRONG><A HREF="/muse/muse.html">Online Catalog</A></STRONG>
<P>
<DD>Follow this link to find out more about, <STRONG>Muse</STRONG>, the online catalog for the
    Gould Library.
<P>
<A NAME="dbs">
<DT><STRONG>Electronic Databases</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>Look here to find out what electronic databases are available to you.  These databases
    are available in either one of two ways:
    <P>
    <UL>
    <LI><STRONG><A HREF="/electronic/online/index.html">Online Databases</A></STRONG> are
        resources which you may use from any Internet-accessible location (lab, office, 
        residence hall, library, etc.) on campus.  Most are indexes which lead you to books 
        and journal articles.  Some offer full text of original items.
    <P>
    <LI><STRONG><A HREF="/electronic/cd-rom/cd-rom.html">Stand-Alone CD-ROM Databases</A></STRONG>
        are <STRONG>not networked</STRONG> so you must come to the library to use them. Most are 
        indexes which lead you to books and journal articles.  Some offer full text of original items.  
        Still others are supplements to books in our collection or are multimedia tools.
    </UL>
<P>
<A NAME="ft">
<DT><STRONG><A HREF="/periodicals/fulltext.html">Full-Text Electronic Periodicals</A></STRONG>
<P>
<DD>This is where to learn about what full-text electronic periodicals are available to you.
    Most of these resources are online sources that you can use from any Internet-accessible location 
    (lab, office, residence hall, library, etc.) on campus.  Some are stand-alone CD-ROM products 
    available only in the Gould Library.
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<A NAME="caveat">
<DT><STRONG>Caution</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>Electronic tools have a certain seductiveness.  Although they 
<P>
<UL>
<LI>are generally faster to use,
<LI>are often available around the clock,
<LI>permit you to download oodles and oodles of citations, and
<LI>usually allow you to perform more sophisticated searching techniques than, say, a typical paper index,
</UL>
<P>  
the mere fact that information is available in digital form doesn't mean that such information is in some 
way inherently <STRONG>superior</STRONG> to information gleaned from non-electronic sources.
<P>
Please contact us if you'd like <A HREF="/instruction/index.html">instruction</A> on any 
of these electronic resources listed above, or if you'd care to <A HREF="/suggest.html">
suggest an electronic resource the library should acquire.</A>
</DL>
<P>
<hr>
<p>
<CENTER><a href="/resources.html">Return to the Information Resources</a></CENTER>
