<html>
<head>
<title>Carleton College Library Bibliographic Instruction - Arranging</title>
</head>
<body BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><H1>Arranging Library Instruction at Carleton College</H1></CENTER>
<P>
Here's your starting point for learning more about the electronic information resources
the Carleton Library has to offer.
<P>
<B>Contents:</B><CENTER>
<A HREF="#purp">Purpose</A> | 
<A HREF="#poss">Possibilities</A> | 
<A HREF="#proc">Procedures</A></CENTER> 
<P>
<hr size=3>
<P>
<DL>
<NAME="purp">
<DT><STRONG>Purpose</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>
Library instruction focuses on developing students' critical thinking skills to
find the information they seek.  The plethora of materials and formats can be
overwhelming for inexperienced library users.  An introductory session in
research strategy, online searching techniques, networking sources, and
electronic access to information can help your students become more productive
information seekers and reduce their anxiety about using an academic library.
<P>
Carleton's libraries contain wonderful resources that will greatly assist
students in research and general studying.  Many of these resources go untapped
for lack of knowledge; library instruction is one way to remedy this situation.
Nearly every discipline can benefit from some type of library instruction.
Please read on for descriptions of the different types of instruction
available.  Keep in mind that flexibility is our goal and the options may not
be limited to what is listed.  The library staff would be happy to tailor a
session to your specific needs.
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<A NAME="poss">
<DT><STRONG>Possibilities</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>We consult with a faculty member concerning the objectives
of the course, course content, materials covered, and course assignment.  The
program is then created specifically for the course to fit the instructor's
time frame and assignments.  Usually one instruction session is arranged during
the regular class period, although other arrangements can be made.
<p>
Programs and materials currently available for both group and individual
instruction are:
<P>
<UL>
<DL>
<DT><EM>Instruction Class in the Library or Computer Lab</EM>
<DD>The students spend one or more class sessions in the library or computer lab.  A
librarian explains how to use library resources in a particular field and
answers any questions the students might have.  Students are encouraged to make
individual research appointments to follow-up a class session.
<P>
<DT><EM>Focused Library Visits</EM>
<DD>Students come to the library to learn how to use one or just a few sources in
their field.  CD-ROM searching techniques often fall into this category.
<P>
<DT><EM>Bibliographies</EM>
<DD>Librarians will provide a customized bibliography (both paper and on the Web)
that highlights the library's sources relating to a course or subject area.
</DL>
</DL>
</UL>

<P>  

<HR>

<P>

<A NAME="proc">
<DT><STRONG>Procedures</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>Faculty are encouraged to schedule their classes as far in advance as possible.
At least two weeks' lead time between the date the request is made and the date
of the session is preferred.  <A HREF="/staff/carolyn/carolyn.html">Carolyn Sanford</A> 
will coordinate and schedule the sessions, but other librarians
may be involved in the actual teaching of the classes.  Carolyn can
be reached directly at x4266, or you may initiate a request via e-mail;
She can be reached as </kbd>csanford</kbd>.
<P>
If you think Library Instruction can benefit you and your students, please
don't hesitate to contact us.  We are eager to discuss
the possibilities with you.
</DL>
<p>
<hr>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/index.html">Return to the Library Instruction Page</A>
<P>
<A HREF="/index.html">Return to the Carleton Library Home Page</A></CENTER>
