<CENTER><H4>Quotes for the Term:</H4></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER>
&quot;I believe in God. I believe in General Gabriel, in Denmark Vesey, in Nat Turner, in John Brown, in every Negro who is willing to sacrifice his life to pull us out of the...chaos we live in and give us a full measure of liberty, liberty without strings, liberty without chains.&quot;<BR>
Arthur Schomburg to John Wesley Cromwell, July 5, 1912<BR>
Letter in Cromwell Family Papers<BR>
Moreland-Spingarn Research Center, Howard University<P>
&quot;Women must leave a record for their men; otherwise how will they know us?&quot;<BR>
Sherley Anne Williams, &quot;Meditations on History&quot; (1980)
</CENTER>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H4><A NAME="cdescription">Course Description</A></H4></CENTER>
<P>This course is a survey of the social, cultural, and intellectual history of people of African descent in the United States from 1619 through 1865. The years bracket the arrival of the first Africans in Virginia colony and in mainland British North America and the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment, which ended slavery and involuntary servitude. The Winter 1997 version of History 220 treats in greater detail the precolonial African background of American blacks and the involvement of black women in the struggle for freedom.</P>
<P>Slavery is the major core historical experience of black Americans. In the apt observation of the late Cornell University Professor and African American scholar J. Saunders Redding, an &quot;iron ring of historical circumstance&quot; unites American black people. The transfer of millions of people from Africa to the Americas and their experiences in the Atlantic World are sources of searching questions and debates among scholars and students of history. Slavery represents a subject of continuing vitality and fresh investigation. Its legacy informs the essential importance of African American history in revising the American master narrative. For reasons, then, that touch upon issues of scholarship and identity, the course is devoted in major part to the study of the origin, development, and destruction of the slave institution.</P>
<P>This course also treats another major group of people of color who were critically linked to the slave population: Free Negroes. This course examines the various strategies free blacks employed toward self-mastery, intra-group uplift, and the destruction of slavery. Finally, the course looks at the roles a distinct minority of  fearless and committed Euroamericans played in black liberation.</P>
<CENTER><H4><A NAME="ctheme">Major Theme and Tools of Analyses</A></H4></CENTER>
<P>The major theme is the transition of Africans from enslaved people to freed people. This transition involved both conflict and consensus among and between blacks and Euroamericans.</P>
<P>The quest for freedom from the degradation of racial enslavement and subjugation is studied in the larger background context of United States history, of which African American history is a major specialty.</P>
<P>Race, class, gender, tragedy, acculturation, resistance, and accommodation are concepts employed as major tools for interpreting black history.</P>
<P>In sum, the course strives for a rigorous study of black men and women as complex speaking and acting subjects and as people who were acted upon with tragic consequences. In essence, we study a people who both succeeded and failed in their long encounter with white supremacy before 1865.</P>
<CENTER><H4><A NAME="cmaterials">Teaching Materials and Strategies</A></H4></CENTER>
<P>Readings in primary documents and secondary sources in history, discussions, lectures, music, poetry, and an e-mail Notes Conference are the teaching materials and strategies employed to explore some of the important ideas, events, personalities, trends, and institutions that shaped black history before the Civil War.</P>
<P>The major teaching goal is to develop critical literacy in thinking, writing, and discussing African American history.</P>
<P>The main narrative or &quot;spine&quot; of the course is John Hope Franklin and Alfred A. Moss Jr., <U>From Slavery to Freedom: A History of African Americans</U>, 7th ed., (1994). It is the oldest black history survey text still in use; it is the standard in the field. Its authors are African American.</P>
<CENTER><H4><A NAME="corganization">Course Organization</A></H4></CENTER>
<P>The course has three units; each is divided into several topical sections with readings and primary source documents that require close reading and evaluation.</P>
<P><STRONG>Unit One</STRONG>, &quot;From African Origins through the American Revolution,&quot; addresses major experiences of Africans beginning on the African continent, continues through the American colonial period, and concludes with the era of the American Revolution. The unit begins with introductory matters, including essays that treat theoretical frameworks of tragedy, race, class, and gender. To facilitate understanding, a full week is spent discussing these concepts. Topics include the role Africans played in developing the Atlantic world, the origin of American slavery, slave systems in the English colonies, formative slave community and culture, the Great Awakening, and the paradox of American revolutionary ideology and black bondage.</P>
<P>In <STRONG>Unit Two</STRONG>, &quot;African Americans in the Ante-bellum South, 1830-1850,&quot; we move to an examination of select topics and issues that affected blacks under slavery as a mature institution. The racial messianism of David Walker and the rebellion led by Nat Turner are two such issues. The unit takes a detailed look at the nexus of race, class, and gender in the case study of Celia, a Missouri slave who murdered her master after years of sexual abuse.</P>
<P><STRONG>Unit Three</STRONG>, &quot;Free Negroes and the Coming of the Civil War,&quot; touches upon several topics. The opposition to colonize free blacks, their status as workers, and their social, religious, and antislavery activities come under review. The significant role of William Lloyd Garrison in the abolitionist movement raises interesting questions about whiteness, leadership, and the boundaries of racial egalitarianism. The Dred Scott case, with a Minnesota connection, was one of the controversial decisions of the decade of stress and strain leading to the Civil War. Harriet Beecher Stowe's <U>Uncle Tom's Cabin</U> is given a close reading to unravel its complexity beyond a simplistic treatment of its obvious melodrama and romanticism. The course ends, appropriately, with the black role in the Civil War, the Emancipation Proclamation, and the Thirteenth Amendment.</P>
<CENTER><H4><A NAME="crequirements">Course Requirements and a Word on Grading and Class Attendance</A></H4></CENTER>
<DL>
<DT>Written Work
<DD>
    <DL>
    <DT>A. <U>Short Papers</U>
    <DD>Two short papers of no more than five pages each and a final exam paper of between eight and 10 pages.<A HREF="#star">*</A> The papers are to be documented interpretive essays based on course readings, lectures, and discussions. The final paper covers the entire course. To prepare for the papers, you should immediately begin to make notes of everything to read, think, and hear that relates to History 220. No outside reading is required; in fact, outside reading works against the objective of the papers, which is for you to employ critical writing and other interpretive skills in responding to a historical problem, issue, or question based on texts studied in this course.<P>
        A draft of each paper must be reviewed by your Writing Assistant before it is turned in to me for assessment.  I do not read papers that have not been reviewed beforehand by a WA, nor do I read beyond the page limit. The WAs for History 220 are Andy Johnson '97 and Matthew Sanders '97. They are senior history majors who have taken my courses and are writing their comps theses under my supervision. Andy and Matthew will not be concerned with the &quot;correctness&quot; of your interpretations or ideas. Their sole goal is to work cooperatively with you in a friendly manner to help you present your interpretations and ideas in the most effective way possible. The essential writing reference for this course is Hacker, <U>A Pocket Style Manual</U>.<P>
        <CENTER>
        <H4>Paper due dates:</H4>
        Monday, Feb. 3, at beginning of class, short paper #1<BR>
        Friday, Feb. 28, at beginning of class, short paper #2<BR>
        Monday, March 17, 2 p.m. - 5 p.m., final exam paper/oral exam option<A NAME="star">*</A>
        </CENTER><P>
    <DT>B. <A NAME="emails"><U>E-Mail Personal Statement</U></A>. 
    <DD>An e-mail personal statement in which you respond to the following: &quot;What do you intend to accomplish in History 220? Why is your goal(s) important to you? How and when will you know if your goal(s)  has been accomplished?&quot;<P>
        <CENTER>
        <H4>Due date:</H4>
        Friday, Jan. 10, 5 p.m.; send statement to Hwilliam<BR>
        Be sure to make an electronic copy for yourself
        </CENTER><P>
    <DT>C. <U>Introduction: What's My Name?</U>
    <DD>Everyone's presence in this seminar is to be acknowledged and valued. To begin this important process, please introduce yourself to me and your classmates by completing the &quot;What's My Name?&quot; assignment before the beginning of class Monday, Jan. 13. If you do not have a vax account, go to the CMC student information desk. A  tutorial on how to use the notes conference created for this class will be held Thursday, Jan. 9, 4:15-5:15 p.m., in 102 CMC.
        <CENTER>
        <H4>Due date:</H4>
        Monday, Jan. 13, before beginning of class
        </CENTER><P>

    </DL>
<DT>Discussion and Teaching
<DD>The classroom is a communal place where learning and teaching is a collective project involving professor and student. Although I am more responsible than you for classroom dynamics because of my higher institutional position, we are partners. To help create and sustain an effective and successful learning community, History 220 utilizes the Socratic Method as the instructor's preferred teaching approach. Its goal is to foster learning by systematic questioning that encourages students to analyze, synthesize, and evaluate. For the Socratic Method to be effective and successful, vigorous and informed discussion is necessary. For the mechanics and philosophy of the Socratic Method that was employed in a popular film, see <A HREF="#appb">Appendix B</A>.
<DT>Reading History
<DD>The heart and soul of vigorous and informed discussion is careful reading of texts. To prepare for class, read the entire article critically, noting a series of questions along the way. What is the author's thesis? What is the evidence? Is it clear? Convincing? What might be left out? Do you detect negative bias? Try to relate the text to your own past thinking and experience and to other things you have read. Prepare a bibliographic note and precis. See Appendices <A HREF="#appa">A</A> and <A HREF="#appe">E</A>.
<DT>How to Analyze a Primary Source
<DD>There is a primary source to analyze for virtually every class meeting. To make this a successful experience, see <A HREF="#appd">Appendix D</A>, &quot;How to Analyze a Primary Source.&quot;
<DT><A NAME="notesconf">Vax Notes Conference</A>
<DD>The address for the Afam I Notes Conference for this class is <ADDRESS>Hst:[Hwilliam]Afam197.note</ADDRESS>
    It is another site where you may talk with your classmates about topics relevant to History 220. We will exhaust few, if any, topics during the run of the term. Classroom attention to each article and the questions it raises varies. Experience shows that provocative discussions in this course often take place on the Vax, and I strongly encourage you to use this teaching and learning opportunity beyond the four required postings. The four required postings include the &quot;What's My Name?&quot; assignment, discussed above. I will read the Conference each day, but will not participate in individual discussions.
<DT>Videos, Plays, Etc.
<DD>Attendance is required at an evening screening of &quot;Glory&quot; (1989). Time and place to be announced.<P>
    &quot;Off the Ice,&quot; a play by Twin Cities playwright Barbara Field, will be produced on campus this term under the direction of Professor Ruth Weiner.  The play explores what happens when Eliza from <U>Uncle Tom's Cabin</U> meets the <U>Little Women</U>. Wednesday through Saturday, Feb. 19th-22nd, at 8 p.m.  Attendance required.
    Sister Soljah is one of the featured speakers during the 1997 All-Campus Conversation. The rapper and activist has been invited to give a guest lecture in this class. You are encouraged to attend her scheduled events and to participate in other activities associated with the topic &quot;Violence and the Media.&quot; Violence against black people is a topic of particular relevance to African American history.
<DT><A NAME="attendance">Attendance</A>
<DD>Everyone influences the classroom dynamic because everyone contributes. Your contributions are resources. When you are absent, we miss the contribution of your resources. As Robin Williams's character states in <U>Dead Poets Society</U>, each day we have an opportunity to &quot;make our lives extraordinary.&quot;  Sorry, no more than one unexcused absence permitted.
