<CENTER><H4><A NAME="carticles">How to Obtain Articles Assigned in the Course</A></H4></CENTER>
A new feature this term is the History 220 Binder, a collection of all assigned readings.  The readings are cataloged by week. If more than three Binders are needed, please let me know. You should check out a Binder from Closed Reserve, copy relevant readings, and return it to Closed Reserve. It is a good idea to have your own individual copy of a text to refer to during class discussion. Be sure to return the original to the Binder for use by the next student. Copy cards are sold in Central Services.
<HR>
<A NAME="appa"><CENTER>Appendix A</CENTER></A>
<CENTER><H4>How to Creatively Read a Historical Work</H4></CENTER>
Pointers for engaging in careful, thoughtful, and analytical reading of a historical work <STRONG>or how to make reading a truly profitable experience rather than a passive attempt to absorb the contents without any analytical thought at all:</STRONG>
<UL>
<LI>I. Determine the basic structure of the work.<BR>
	<OL>
	<LI>Any book, article, or paper must attempt to establish a point or else it is useless except as a list of facts. The point or argument of the work is the <STRONG>thesis</STRONG>. The content of the work is the <STRONG>subject</STRONG>. <U>They are not the same.</U>
	<LI>Note any characteristic stylistic features of the author's writing. Is the topic sentence, the main emphasis of each paragraph, at the very beginning of the paragraph?
	<LI>If the book or article has an &quot;Introduction,&quot; does it either suggest in summary the contents of the book or article or else provide basic historical background for the main subjects to be discussed later?
	<LI>Read the concluding paragraph in each chapter to determine if the author summarizes the work at the end.
	</OL>
<LI>II. Now consider the main impact of the historical work on your attention. Read the rest of the work quickly. Skim.<BR>
    <OL>
    <LI>What are its arguments?
    <LI>What are its principle subsidiary points?
    <LI>What historiographical observations or value judgments can you make?
    </OL>
</UL>
<CENTER><H4>Words of Wisdom:</H4></CENTER>
&quot;If a student claims that he does not understand a certain book -- and how often have we heard this woebegone complaint from students who have given up in despair -- the probability is overwhelming that the fault lies in the student himself rather than in the book. The student has been waiting for the book to &quot;tell him the answer&quot; instead of using the book as a means of finding an answer. The chief use of a secondary historical source -- a book written to prove a point -- is to provoke, to stimulate, to lead the reader on to new insights of his own; and only thoughtful, analytical reading of secondary sources will make this possible.<BR>
&quot;Neither primary sources nor secondary sources will offer any significantly meaningful insights to a passive reader who seeks merely to recognize their contents. But the student who has acquired the basic principles of analyzing sources... will find himself fully prepared and well informed for the next major step in his development -- the writing of his own original historical papers.<BR>
<CITE>Norman F. Cantor, <U>How to Study History</U> (1986)</CITE>
<HR>
<A NAME="appb"><CENTER>Appendix B</CENTER></A>
<CENTER><H4>A Discourse on Teaching and Learning</H4></CENTER>
Given by Professor Kingsfield on the second day of class at Harvard Law:<BR>
&quot;The study of law is something new and unfamiliar to most of you; unlike any schooling you've ever been through before. We use the Socratic method here: I call on you, ask you a question, and you answer it. Why don't I just give you a lecture? Because through my questions you learn to teach yourselves. Through this method of questioning, answering, questioning, answering, we seek to develop in you the ability to analyze that vast complex of facts that constitute the relationships of members within a given society. Questioning and answering. At times you may feel that you have found the correct answer. I assure you that this is a total delusion on your part. You will never find the correct, absolute, and final answer. In my classroom there is always another question, another question to follow your answer. It's as if you're on a treadmill; my little questions spin the tumblers of your mind. You're on an operating table; my little questions are the fingers probing your brain. We do brain surgery here. You teach yourselves the law, but I train your mind. You come in here with a skull full of mush, and you leave thinking like a lawyer.&quot;<P>
From the 1973 film <I>The Paper Chase</I>, which starred Timothy Bottoms, Lindsay Wagner and John Houseman. Directed by James Bridges. Synopsis:<BR>
&quot;The trials and tribulations of being a first-year law student at Harvard University. Bottoms [whose character is a graduate of the University of Minnesota] is a young student [who] becomes obsessed with his tyrannical professor [Kingsfield (Houseman, who won an Oscar for best supporting actor)], but has an even bigger problem, when he discovers that his professor is also the father of his girlfriend.&quot;<P>
Substitute &quot;history&quot; and &quot;historian&quot; for &quot;law&quot; and &quot;lawyer&quot; and after &quot;facts&quot; insert &quot;and interpretations.&quot; Thence, you will have a statement on my teaching style and beliefs.
<HR>
<A NAME="appc"><CENTER>Appendix C</CENTER></A>
<CENTER><H4>A Conceptual Design for African American History</H4></CENTER>
<HR>
<A NAME="appd"><CENTER>Appendix D</CENTER></A>
<CENTER><H4>How to Analyze a Primary Source</H4></CENTER>
<P>Primary sources are those materials that were written or created during the
period under investigation. They are the documents or oral or visual artifacts
produced by the eyewitnesses of, or the participants in, the events the
historian is attempting to reconstruct. They are the records that make the study
of history possible.  In contrast, secondary sources are works of reconstruction
and interpretation based on the primary sources. Secondary sources attempt to
show <EM>how</EM> and <EM>why</EM> events happpened. The distinction between
primary and secondary sources is not always clear as the above definitions
imply. For instance, a newspaper is definitely a primary source for the period
in which it was published, but a newspaper also has many characteristics of a
secondary source. The journalist (a historian of sorts) constructs a narrative
based on primary sources -- documents and eyewitness testimony. (Furay and
Salevouris, <U>The Methods and Skills of History</U>, 1988.)</P>
<P>A convincing analysis of a primary source must be grounded in  (1) an
understanding of the document itself, and (2) knowledge of the era it
represents.</P>
<P>You should begin your analysis of a primary source by coming to grips with
your personal bias -- race, class, gender, sexual practice. Try to suspend your
beliefs; let the material &quot;speak&quot; to you. Keep an open mind. Later,
you will have to develop an argument or interpretation of the source.
<STRONG>Here are some questions that may be helpful to your analysis:</STRONG></P>
<OL>
<LI>What kind of source is it? Does it provide information about experience,
ideology, and/or behavior? Is it prescriptive literature that describes how
people should behave? Or is it evidence about lived experience? Does it tell us
about the experience or beliefs of &quot;typical&quot; people or elites? When
was the document made/published?
<LI>What do you know about the author and his/her purpose in writing? What is
the author's gender, race/ethnicity, class, religion, sexual and political
orientation? Does it matter?
<LI>Who is the intended audience? Was the source intended for public
consumption? How might this affect the presentation?
<LI>What can a close reading of the &quot;text&quot; tell you? Who are the
important people/characters? How does the language construct meaning? What are
the important metaphors or symbols? Pay special attention to the choice of
words. Think about the silences: what's not there may be just as important as
revealing what's there.
<LI>After you have understood the source on its own terms, you should evaluate
it as historical evidence. Is it a good source? Is it a common source for
historians in general? For historians of the African American experience in
particular? What other sources would supplement this one? Have other scholars
used this source? What is their interpretation?
</OL>
<P>Once you have used your analytic skills to understand the source and to
assess its historical significance, then develop your interpretation. Pick one
aspect of the document and discuss that. You can't cover every aspect in class
or in a short paper.</P>
