<H4>A Brief History of Black History Month</H4>
Carter G. Woodson<P>
In 1926, Carter G. Woodson (1875-1950) founded Negro History Week, now Black History Month, which is celebrated in February to coincide with the birthdays of George Washington, Abraham Lincoln, and Frederick Douglass.<P>
Woodson stated in 1926 on the reason for starting observance of Negro History Week:<BR> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>It is not so much a Negro History Week, as it is a History Week. We should emphasize not Negro History, but the Negro in history. What we need is not a history of selected races or nations, but the history of the world void of national bias, race hate, and religious prejudice. There should be no indulgence in undue eulogy of the Negro. The use of the Negro is well taken care of when it is shown how he has influenced the development of civilization.</BLOCKQUOTE>
W.E.B. Du Bois observed just after Woodson, founder of the Association for the Study of Negro Life and History (ASNLH), died in 1950 that Woodson's career &quot;illustrates what race prejudice can do to a human soul and also what it is powerless to prevent.&quot; Woodson, the son of sex-slaves, was born in poverty, worked as a youth in a West Virginia coal mine, and was not able to begin high school until he was twenty. Yet he went on to become the second black American (after Du Bois) to receive the doctorate in history (Harvard), and with his drive and vision was virtually single-handedly responsible for establishing African American history as a historical specialty.<P>
Seeking to preserve and to publicize among both blacks and whites the historical record of the race, he created the ASNLH, established a learned journal (Journal of Negro History, 1918), sponsored pioneering research, and had an influential role in encouraging the development of a whole generation of black scholars. On the other hand, while Woodson thus laid the foundations, he did not live to see African American history either recognized by the mainstream of white historians as anything more than a marginal specialty or to be embraced by Negroes themselves with the enthusiasm that he had envisioned. These things did not come to pass until nearly two decades perspectives after his death.<P>
For more on Woodson's career, see the catalog to &quot;Moving Back Barriers: The Legacy of Carter G. Woodson,&quot; a Library of Congress Traveling Exhibition, 1994; Jacqueline Goggin, <U>Carter G. Woodson: A Life in Black History</U> (1993); Lorenzo J. Greene, <U>Working with Carter G. Woodson, the Father of Black History</U>, ed. Arvarh E. Strickland (1989); and August Meier and Elliot Rudwick, <U>Black History and the Historical Profession, 1915-1980</U> (1986).
