<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="description"></A>Course Description</H4>

<P>This is a seminar in American social and intellectual history with Transcendentalism
as its subject of investigation. Transcendentalism was a movement of thought
that shaped the ideas and activities of a group of high-minded, mid nineteenth-century
intellectuals living in Concord and neighboring Boston. Among the principal
leaders were familiar authors such as Ralph Waldo Emerson, Bronson Alcott,
Margaret Fuller, Theodore Parker , and Henry David Thoreau. Although deeply
rooted in New England soil, the Transcendentalists were for America unprecedentedly
modern and cosmopolitan. They were widely associated with a potpourri of
democratic social movements while also producing among the most trenchant
critiques of American democracy ever written, and they vitally influenced
major thinkers and currents from philosophy, theology, social thought,
and politics to literature, painting, and music. Nathaniel Hawthorne and
Walt Whitman are among the American Renaissance writers whose works we
will read. </P>

<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="problem"></A>The Historical Problem</H4>

<P>Historians explore the past by asking and answering questions. The problem
of the seminar is Transcendentalism. How would we describe and explain
its distinctive features, its leaders, and their principle-minded actions?
What was the core meaning of the movement? What was the significance of
the Transcendentalists' religious consciousness in Unitarianism? What were
the broad cultural dimensions of the movement? What were their political
concerns: were the Transcendentalists democrats? Where did they stand on
such issues of their day as slavery, race, free white labor, and gender?
Finally, what is the Transcendentalists' legacy? </P>

<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="materials"></A>Teaching Materials and Strategies</H4>

<P>The texts will be readings in primary documents and secondary sources
in history, biography, and literature. Seminar discussions, student reports,
occasional lectures, and an e-mail notes conference are the teaching strategies
employed. The major teaching goal is to develop critical literacy in thinking,
writing, and discussing Transcendentalism. </P>

<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="organization"></A>Course Organization</H4>

<P>This seminar follows a chronological, topical, as well as biographical
approach. The second and third meetings of the seminar's Week One contextualizes
Transcendentalism within &quot;the hopefulness and fervency of the reform
fever&quot; that affected the United States in the wake of the Second Great
Awakening. Week Two's topic is &quot;Transcendentalism: Root and Branch,&quot;
and the seminar investigates ideas and movements that figured in the pre-history
of Transcendentalism. In addition, some New England intellectual forerunners
of the movement are considered. Selected key writings of Edward Everett
and William Ellery Channing are specifically included because of the authors'
impact upon the consciousness of Ralph Waldo Emerson. Emerson probably
was the most distinguished, if not the most famous, of the Transcendentalists.
Writing of Emerson in <U>Harvard English Studies</U> (1982), the critic
Joel Porte asserted that &quot;there is scarcely an American writer or
thinker of note who has not been moved to take the measure of this formidable
figure.&quot; His oracular eloquence frames the syllabus as it did Transcendentalism
itself. Robert Richardson's magisterial intellectual biography of Emerson
helps us cast an eye on the Sage's origins and development. Emerson's central
role in the Unitarian Controversy of 1838, during which the orthodox religionists
considered him a dangerous heretic, leads us to consideration of an ensemble
of his essays, addresses, and lectures. Selectivity also shapes the range
of prose essays produced by other major Concord intellectuals, including
Henry David Thoreau, Margaret Fuller, Theodore Parker, and Bronson Alcott.
During the final weeks the seminar turns its attention to prose fiction
and verse, of which we will read works by two major idiosyncratic geniuses
influenced by Emerson: Nathaniel Hawthorne and Walt Whitman. </P>

<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="requirements"></A>Course Requirements and a Word
on Grading and Class Attendance</H4>

<DL>
<DT>Written Work
<DD><DL>
    <DT>A. <U>Oral Report Paper</U>
    <DD>Complete one short oral report paper in which a first effort is made
        to sort out an idea or action of the Transcendentalists. The paper is to
        be 3-5 typed double-spaced pages. Footnotes are particularly important
        as you must demonstrate not only what sources were used, but how they were
        used. You should follow the research and writing strategy proposed by Wayne
        Booth's <U>The Craft of Research</U>, which is on Closed Reserve.<BR>
        The paper is to be given in a 20-minute seminar presentation during Week
        Six, Feb. 10-14. Another 10 minutes will be allowed for peer review. On
        the day before presentation, the presenter should make available to each
        classmate and to me either a Xerox or an electronic copy of his or her
        paper. It is the presenter's responsibility to make arrangements for paper
        distribution, and to inform the seminar of those arrangements. Dates for
        presentations will be selected by lottery.<BR>
        Please make an office appointment with me to discuss your paper topic and
        the initial status of your research no later than Monday, Jan. 20. It is
        strongly recommended that you select a topic from the <A HREF="#appe">list
        in the Appendix</A>.
    <DT>B. <A NAME="finalp"></A><U>Final Paper</U>.
    <DD>Complete a substantial paper in which you manifest a more sophisticated,
        knowledgeable perspective on the idea or action of the Transcendentalists
        than was possible in the first paper. You are expected to correct, buttress,
        critique, defend, and expand on arguments presented in the first paper.
        Where possible, in constructing the paper you may build upon the discussion
        and questions presented by other students in the seminar. Full credit must
        not only be given in written sources, but to the questions and ideas presented
        by students in the seminar. The final paper is due the last day of the
        term.
    <DT>C. <U>Introduction: What's My Name?</U>
    <DD>Everyone's presence in this seminar is to be acknowledged and valued.
        To begin this important process, please introduce yourself to me and your
        classmates by completing the &quot;What's My Name?&quot; assignment before
        the beginning of class Monday, Jan. 13. If you do not have a vax account,
        go to the CMC student information desk. A tutorial on how to use the notes
        conference created for this class will be held Thursday, Jan. 9, 4:15-5:15
        p.m., in 102 CMC.<P>

        <H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Due dates:</H4>
        <CENTER>
        <P>Thursday, Jan. 9, 4:15-5:15 p.m., Notes Conference Lesson, 102 CMC<BR>
        Friday, Jan. 10, 5 p.m., personal statement; send via e-mail to HWilliam<BR>
        Mon., Jan. 13, by 4A, &quot;What's My Name?&quot; posting on Concord97.Note<BR>
        Monday, Jan. 20, deadline to discuss paper topic and initial status of research<BR>
        Feb. 12-14, oral report presentations<BR>
        Fri., Feb. 21, seminar project: A Margaret Fuller-style transcendental conversation<BR>
        Wednesday, March 19, 5 p.m. 2 copies of final paper </P>
        </CENTER>
    </DL>
<DT>Discussion
<DD>The classroom is a communal place where learning and teaching is a
    collective project involving professor and student. Although I am more
    responsible than you for classroom dynamics because of my higher institutional
    position, we are partners. To help create and sustain an effective and
    successful learning community for History 324, this seminar utilizes two
    discussion formats:
    <DL>
    <DT>A. <U>Instructor-Led Discussion</U>
    <DD>The Socratic Method is the instructor's preferred teaching approach
        in this seminar. Its goal is to foster learning by systematic questioning
        that encourages students to analyze, synthesize, and evaluate. For the
        Socratic Method to be effective and successful, vigorous and informed discussion
        is necessary. For the mechanics and philosophy of the Socratic Method that
        was employed in a popular film, see Appendix, <A HREF="#appb">&quot;A Discourse
        on Teaching and Learning.&quot;</A>
    <DT>B. <U>Student-Led Discussion</U> </DT>
    <DD><P>Except for oral report dates and other &quot;special meetings,&quot;
        one or more students will be responsible for facilitating a segment of
        each seminar meeting. The number of student facilitators will depend on
        the final enrollment. At pre-registration, enrollment stood at five. Under
        a rotating cycle that begins alphabetically, this means that every student
        will lead discussion every sixth seminar meeting.<BR>
        Student-led discussion will be driven by questions posted on the vax. The
        vax notes conference for the seminar is:<BR>
        <TT>HST:[Hwilliam]Concord97.Note</TT><BR>
        At least 24 hours before seminar meeting, the student facilitator will
        post on Concord97.Note at least one question inspired by the assigned reading
        for the next class. Each student will post a response to the question and,
        if necessary, respond to her or his classmates' responses. The question
        and responses will frame the discussion at the next seminar meeting. Obviously,
        the facilitator will need to read ahead and to post the question early
        enough to allow sufficient time for peer response. Each student should
        bring a print out of the question and responses to class. The total number
        of postings per student should equal the number of class meetings this
        term.<BR>
        Here are some brief tips to make this aspect of seminar run smoothly:<BR>
        <OL>
        <LI>Questions should stimulate discussion and demonstrate that you have
            thought about the reading. Sometimes questions such as &quot;What did Emerson
            mean on page 287?&quot; enlighten the entire group, since interpretations
            vary. However, sparingly use this type of question. </LI>
        <LI>Both the student facilitator and the entire seminar must respond in
            Concord97.Note to the question. Jot down ideas, impressions, etc. It is
            not necessary to be profound (although that's welcome, too!) or to write
            a formal, coherent, reply. What we are trying to do is to move toward an
            understanding of Transcendentalism and its intersection with ante-bellum
            American society. Of course, some responses are better than others; vapid
            relativism does not suit the aims of an elite education in this classroom
            that seeks to transgress in the 1990s as much as the Transcendentalist
            project sought more than a century ago. </LI>
        <LI>Strive to keep questions and responses to one paragraph. At the end,
            please sign your full name. </LI>
        <LI>Before coming to class, read the responses of your classmates. </LI>
        </OL>
    </DL>
<DT><A NAME="conversation">Transcendental Conversation</A>
<DD>The group project for the term is the presentation on Friday, Feb.
    21, of a Margaret Fuller-style transcendental conversation. Seminar members
    as a group are to plan and execute the conversation. You are limited only
    by your imagination. You may write a script, converse from note cards,
    or talk <U>ex temporare</U>. Since each person in the seminar is equally
    responsible for the success of the conversation, an identical grade will
    be given all.<BR>
    The project's goals are threefold: (1) to investigate the educational objective,
    methodology, and historic significance of Fuller's transcendental conversations,
    (2) to continue to hone critical thinking and research skills, and (3)
    to stimulate the fine art of good conversation.<BR>
    In addition to major seminar texts that touch upon the topic, the following
    articles on Closed Reserve will help you shape the project.<BR>
    <UL>
    <LI>Margaret Fuller, &quot;Conversation&quot; (1839), in Anne Firor Scott, <U>Women in American Life</U> (1970), 35-38. </LI>
    <LI>Charles Capper, &quot;Margaret Fuller as Cultural Reformer: the Conversations in Boston,&quot; <U>American Quarterly</U> 39 (Winter 1987), 675-528. </LI>
    <LI>Margaret Fuller, &quot;A Transcendental Conversation,&quot; in Perry Miller, ed., <U>The American Transcendentalists: Their Prose and Poetry</U> (1957), 101-103. </LI>
    </UL>
<DT>Reading History
<DD>The heart and soul of vigorous and informed discussion is careful reading
    of texts. To prepare for seminar, read the entire item critically, noting
    a series of questions along the way. What is the author's thesis? What
    is the evidence? Is it clear? Convincing? What might be left out? Do you
    detect negative bias? Try to relate the text to your own past thinking
    and experience and to other things you have read. For the mechanics of
    reading history, see <A HREF="#appa">Appendix, &quot;How to Creatively
    Read a Historical Work.&quot;</A>
<DT>How to Analyze a Primary Source
<DD>There is a primary source to analyze for virtually every class meeting.
    To make this a successful experience, see <A HREF="#appc">Appendix C</A>,
    &quot;How to Analyze a Primary Source.&quot;
<DT><A NAME="attendance">Attendance</A>
<DD>Everyone influences the classroom dynamic because everyone contributes.
    Your contributions are resources. When you are absent, we miss the contribution
    of your resources. As Robin Williams's character states in <U>Dead Poets
    Society</U>, each day we have an opportunity to &quot;make our lives extraordinary.&quot;
    Sorry, no more than one unexcused absence permitted.
<DT>Grading
    <PRE>
    Oral paper report             15 percent
    final paper                   40 percent
    Transcendental conversation   15 percent
    participation                 30 percent
                          Total: 100 percent</PRE>
</DL>

