<DT>WEEK 3: <U>The Unitarian Controversy</U>
    <DL>
    <DT>Mon., Jan. 20: <U>Unitarianism and a Culture in Transition</U>
    <DD>Martin Luther King's Birthday Observed<BR>
        <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P>As I thought further I came to see that what we were really doing was
        withdrawing our cooperation form an evil system, rather than merely withdrawing
        our economic support from the [Montgomery] bus company. The bus company,
        being an external expression of the system, would naturally suffer, but
        the basic aim was to refuse to cooperate with evil. At this point I began
        to think about Thoreau's <U>Essay on Civil Disobedience</U>. I remembered
        how, as a college student, I had been moved when I first read this work.
        I became convinced that what we were preparing to do in Montgomery was
        related to what Thoreau had expressed. We were simply saying to the white
        community, &quot;We can no longer lend our cooperation to an evil system.&quot;
        </P>
        </BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P><CITE>Martin Luther King Jr., <U>Stride Toward Freedom</U> (1958)</CITE> </P>
        <UL>
        <LI><IMG SRC="/images/ltblueball.gif" ALT="**" HIEGHT="14" WIDTH="14">Rose, Chap. 1, &quot;Boston Unitarianism, 1790-1840,&quot; 1-37.
