<P>
<!-- ############### Indexes and Abstracts  -->
<a name="in-ab">
<h3>Indexes and Abstracts</h3>
<P>
Turn to indexes and abstracts to find more information on your topic.   If you want to know whether 
Carleton subscribes to a particular journal, perform a <STRONG><KBD>T > TITLE</KBD></STRONG> search in Muse 
using the exact title of the journal you're looking for.
<P>

<DL>

<DT><kbd>ML 156.4.J3 B6</kbd><br>
Blackstone, Orin. <strong>Index to Jazz, 1917-1944</strong>. [1944-48].
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 118 .M84</kbd><br>
<strong>The Music Index</strong>. v. 1-   1949-
<DD>A subject-author guide to music periodical literature.  Compiled from over 350 international sources,
offering the researcher access to a wealth of historiographic, enthnographic, and musicological data.  A
broad range of subjects is covered, including pas and present personalities, the history of music, form and
types of music, musical instruments from the earliest times to modern electronic instruments, plus computer
produced music.  In addition, book reviews, reviews of music recordings, tapes, and performances are indexed.
First performances and obituaries are noted.
<P>
A complete subject heading list with cross references is published annually with the monthly issues and
incorporated in the cumulations.

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 113 .R12</kbd><br>
International Repertory of Music Literature (Organization). 
<strong>RILM Abstracts of Music Literature</strong>.  v. 1- 1967-
<DD>RILM covers all aspects of music, including historical musicology, ethnomusicology, instruments and voice, dance, and music therapy.
They also include various other fields as they relate to music, including librarianship, literature, dramatic arts, visual arts, anthropology,
sociology, philosophy and physics.
<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 113 .R52 1976</kbd><br>
International Repertory of Music Literature (Organization). 
<strong>RILM Thesaurus : Subject Headings for Cumulative Index of RILM
Abstracts</strong>. 1976.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

</DL>

<!-- ###############put periodicals here  -->
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<a name="perio">
<H3>Annuals and Periodicals</H3>
To identify which music-related periodicals are owned by the Gould Library, perform the following steps on
Muse:
<P>
<OL>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>N > NUMBERS</KBD></STRONG>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>C > CALL numbers (Library of Congress)</KBD></STRONG> (use <STRONG><KBD>PER</KBD></STRONG>)
<LI><STRONG><KBD>L > LIMIT this Search</KBD></STRONG>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>S > Words in the SUBJECT</KBD></STRONG>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>music</KBD></STRONG>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>F > Find items with above limits</KBD></STRONG>
</OL>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>--Highlighted Annuals</STRONG><br>

<DL>


<DT><kbd>Main General ML   3505.8 .A56</kbd><br>
<strong>Annual Review of Jazz Studies</strong>,   no. 1- 
<DD>CONTINUES: <strong>Journal of Jazz Studies</strong>.

</DL>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>--Highlighted Periodicals</STRONG><br>

<DL>

<DT><strong>American Music</strong>, v. 1- 1983-
<DD>Scholarly, yet readable, exploring all the nooks and crannies of American musical life,
past and present, perhaps emphasizing serious music but not ignoring folk, jazz, and popular
music and dance.
    
<P>

<DT><strong>The Black Music Research Journal</strong>,  1980-  (Carleton has 1983- )
<DD>Scholarly publication covering a broad range of African-American genres, including such
classic styles as blue, as well as more contemporary forms such as rap.  Each issue features
five or six long articles, typically imbued with a sociohistorical prospective.
    
<P>

<DT><strong>The Black Perspective in Music</strong>,  v. 1-   spring 1973- ; Ceased with v. 18 published in 1990. (Carleton has  v. 1-18 1973-1990)
<DD>Publication aimed "to provide an opportunity for the free expression of ideas and opinions by
persons interested in Black-American and African performing arts..."

<P>

<DT><strong>Down Beat:  Jazz, Blues & Beyond</strong>, v. 1-   July 1934-  (Carleton has  v. 2 no.11-v. 24 no.2,v.36 no.8-  1935-1957,1969- INC)
<DD>While a background in music composition and notation is not necessary,
the contents presume a basic knowledge of jazz history and musicians.
Supposedly concerned with all aspects of jazz, the magazine in recent years
has slighted the more traditional forms (Dixieland, ragtime, swing, etc.)
in favor of electric and fusion styles.  Feature articles often 
incorporate enhaustive interviews with leading musicians and
generally are appended with selective discographies.  A lengthly 
record review section (25-30, approximately 500-1,00 words) is
also included.    

<P>

<DT><strong>Jazz Review</strong>,  Vol. 1, no. 1 (Nov. 1958)-v. 4, no. 1 (Jan. 1961)  (Carleton has  v. 1-4 no.1  1958-1961)
<DD>***comments***
    
<P>

<DT><strong>Journal of Jazz Studies</strong>,  v. 1-6, no. 1; Oct. 1973-fall/winter 1979. (Carleton has v. 1-6 no.1  1973-1979 INC)
<DD>ABSORBED: <strong>Studies in Jazz Discography</strong>. CONT'D BY: <strong>Annual Review of Jazz Studies</strong>.

<P>

<DT><strong>Metronome</strong>,  Began with: Vol. 48, no. 2 (Feb. 1932); ceased with: v. 75, no.
12 (Dec. 1958)  (Carleton has Microfilm: v. 48-75 1932-1958)
<DD>ABSORBED: <strong>Metronome (Orchestra ed.) and Metronome (Band ed.)</strong>
CONT'D BY: <strong>Metronome, Music U.S.A.</strong>   

<P>

</DL>	
