<H3>Sample Web Links for Jazz</H3>
<P>
<DL>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.altavista.digital.com/cgi-bin/query?pg=q&what=web&fmt=.&q=%22jazz+history%22">Alta Vista: Jazz History Links</A>
<DD>Alta Vista is one of the premier search engines on the Web.  Here is a list of links produced by a search using the
terms "jazz history".
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.easysource.com/musicjaz.html#composers">Easysource Jazz Links</A>
<DD>A very large source on jazz information available on the Internet. Claims, "If it has to do with Jazz and it's on 
the Net, then it's probably listed here!"
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.beatthief.com/greatday/">greatday in harlem</A>
<DD>A "documentary" about 57 of the finest jazz artists. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.ozemail.com.au/~jazclass/">Jazclass</A>
<DD>Learn how to play jazz from Australian instructor, Michael Furstner.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.tulane.edu/~lmiller/JazzHome.html">Hogan Jazz Archive</A>
<DD>The Hogan Jazz Archive at Tulane University is an internationally renowned resource for New Orleans Jazz research.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.vimages.com/vimages/hyperjazz.html">HyperJazz</A>
<DD>Information about a CD-ROM product called HyperJazz, an interactive multimedia tool celebrating
100 years of recorded Jazz History.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.ozemail.com.au/~jazclass/">Jazclass</A>
<DD>Learn how to play jazz from Australian instructor, Michael Furstner.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.rpa.net/jazz/">Jazz: A Brief History</A>
<DD>Created by Philips Douglas, a student at Florida State University.  Information at the site is based on notes taken
from a course at FSU entitled, "The History of Jazz, 1890 - 1950." 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://ie.uwindsor.ca/jazz/gloss.html">A Jazz Glossary</A>
<DD>This glossary is taken from Barry Ulanov's <CITE>A Handbook of Jazz</CITE> (New York: Viking, 1959). 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.j51.com/~jayl/jazz/jazzfacts.html">Jazz History and Facts</A>
<DD>Excerpted from from <CITE>The New York Times Magazine</CITE>.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://ie.uwindsor.ca/jazz/slang.html">The Slanguage of Swing</A>
<DD>Reprinted from the November 1935 issue of <CITE>Down Beat</CITE> magazine.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.nwu.edu/WNUR/jazz/styles/">The Styles of Jazz - A Map</A>
<DD>A chart of jazz styles derived from Joachim Berendt's <CITE>The Jazz Book</CITE>.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://town.hall.org/Archives/radio/Kennedy/Taylor/">What is Jazz?</A>
<DD>"In a four part ARTSEDGE lecture series, recorded live at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts in
Washington, D.C., Dr. Billy Taylor, noted jazz pianist, historian, and educator, shares glimpses of his extensive
knowledge of jazz music from its roots in the African-American slavery experience, through the early
days of ragtime, and onward through swing, bop, and progressive jazz."
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Entertainment/Music/Genres/Jazz/">Yahoo:Entertainment:Music:Genres:Jazz</A>
<DD>Yahoo is one of the primier directories of Internet resouces.  Here you'll find links to resources on jazz.
<P>
</DL>
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
<H2>Selected Paper Resources for Jazz</H2>
<P>
This list is intended to introduce you to some of the paper materials we have on jazz music.  
It is not a complete list, but merely a sampling.  All items listed below are located in the Reference
Collection on Level 4 unless otherwise noted.  Please don't hesitate to ask a librarian if your aren't
finding what you need here.
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#ency">Encyclopedias, Dictionaries, and Guides</A>
<LI><A HREF="#biblio">Bibliographies</A>
<LI><A HREF="#peop">People</A>
<LI><A HREF="#lit">Literature</A>
<LI><A HREF="#in-ab">Indexes and Abstracts
<LI><A HREF="#perio">Annuals and Periodicals</A>
</UL>


<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!--  ################ Dictionaries, Encyclopedias, and Guides.   -->
<a name="ency">
<h3>Background Sources - Encyclopedias, Dictionaries, and Guides</h3>

Use these sources at the beginning of your research to get an overview of a topic or to identify 
synonyms or related terms that will apply to your topic.  Later, return to these sources to clarify 
concepts or define new vocabulary.

<DL>
<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 156.4.J3 B66 1995</kbd><br>
ed. Kernfeld, Barry.<strong>The Blackwell Guide to Recorded Jazz</strong>. 1995.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 156.2 .D63 1969</kbd><br>
Godrich, John. <strong>Blues & Gospel Records</strong>. 1969.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 102.P66 S5 1982</kbd>
Shaw, Arnold. <strong>Dictionary of American Pop/Rock</strong>. 1982.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 105 .F36</kbd><br>
Feather, Leonard G. and Gitler, Ira <strong>The Encyclopedia of Jazz in the Seventies</strong>. 1976.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 105 .F35</kbd><br>
Feather, Leonard G. <strong>The Encyclopedia of Jazz in the Sixties</strong>. 1966.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 102.P66 T9 1985</kbd><br>
Tyler, Don. <strong>Hit Parade : An Encyclopedia of the Top Songs of the Jazz, Depression, Swing, and Sing Eras</strong>. 1985.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 102.J3 C34</kbd><br>
Case, Brian and Britt, Stan. <strong>The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Jazz</strong>. 1978.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 156.4.J3 T73</kbd><br>
Tudor, Dean and Nancy. <strong>Jazz</strong>. 1979.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 128.J3 M33 1995</kbd><br>
Meadows, Eddie S. <strong>Jazz Research and Performance Materials</strong>. 1995.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 102.J3 C32 1988</kbd><br>
Carr, Ian, et. al. <strong>Jazz : the Essential Companion</strong>. 1988.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 3561.J3 F39</kbd><br>
Feather, Leonard G. <strong>The New Edition of the Encyclopedia of Jazz</strong>. 1960.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 102.J3 N48 1988</kbd><br>
ed. Kernfeld, Barry. <strong>The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz</strong>. 1988.
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>ML 156.4.J3 C67 1992</kbd><br>
Cook, Richard, and Morton, Brian. <strong>The Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD, LP, and Cassette</strong>. 1992.
<DD>*** comments ***

</DL>

