<H3>Selected Web Links for Politics in America</H3>
<DL>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://AllPolitics.com/">AllPolitics</A>
<DD>The latest political news from CNN and Time. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.emf.net/~cr/finance.html">Charlotte's Web</A>
<DD>Links to many documents and sites related to campaign finance reform issues.  Maintained by
    Charlotte Roberts, a private citizen.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Government/Politics/Parties/Democratic_Party/
     1996_Presidential_Election/Candidates/Clinton_Gore/">Clinton/Gore '96</A>
<DD>Many links to sites both supporting (and opposing) the re-election of the Clinton/Gore ticket.
    Includes a link to the <A HREF="http://www.cg96.org/new/index.htm">official Clinton/Gore home page</A>. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/concord/">Concord Coalition</A>
<DD>The Concord Coalition is a nonpartisan, grassroots movement to eliminate the deficit and bring 
    entitlements down to a level that's fair to all generations. Founded by former Senators Warren B. 
    Rudman and Paul E. Tsongas.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.cq.com/">Congressional Quarterly's Web Site</A>
<DD>Congressional Quarterly is a leading publisher of magazines, 
    newsletters, books, and directories on politics and government.  Includes jump-off link to 
    <A HREF="http://voter96.cqalert.com/">American Voter '96</A> (CQ's election resource page). 
    CQ also offers the full text of the current issue of CQ's flagship publication, 
    the <A HREF="gopher://gopher.cqalert.com">Congressional Quarterly Weekly Report</A>.  
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.msnbc.com/news/dec_front.asp">Decision '96</A>
<DD>National Public Radio's (NPR) special election coverage Web site.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://republicans.vt.com/pe1996.html">Dole/Kemp '96</A>
<DD>Many links to sites supporting the re-election of the Dole/Kemp ticket.
    Includes a link to the <A HREF="http://www.dole96.com/">official Dole/Kemp home page</A>. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.npr.org/hotnews/election96.html">Election '96</A>
<DD>The latest political news from Microsoft Corporation and NBC News.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.nara.gov/nara/fedreg/ec/">Electoral College</A>
<DD>The National Archives and Records Administration's Electoral College Home Page. The Office of the Federal 
    Register coordinates the functions of the Electoral College on behalf of the Archivist of the United States, 
    the States, the Congress, and the American People. Provides links to a variety of information and statistics 
    on presidential elections, past and present.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/Fed-Agency/fedwebloc.html">Federal Web Locator</A>
<DD>The Federal Web Locator is a service provided by the Villanova Center for Information Law 
    and Policy and is..."intended to be the one stop shopping point for federal government information 
    on the World Wide Web."
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/aces/aaces001.html">GPO Access : Keeping America Informed
     Electronically</A>. U.S. Government Printing Office.
<DD>Provides a link to the <A HREF="http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/dpos/adpos400.html">Monthly Catalog of U.S.
    Government Publications</A>.  Also offers access to online databases such as campaign reform hearing, 
    congressional bills, and Congressional Record via the 
    <A HREF="http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/aces/aaces002.html">Connection to the Online Databases</A> link.  
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://hillaryshair.com/">Hillary's Hair</A>
<DD>This site is a salute to the ever-changing plumage of First Lady, Hillary Clinton. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.njdc.com/">National Journal Web Site</A>
<DD>Based in Washington, D.C., National Journal Inc. is a leading publisher of magazines, 
    newsletters, books, and directories on politics and government.  Includes a link to
    their <A HREF="http://www.njdc.com/nji/webguide.html">Webguide</A>.  
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.reformparty.org/">Perot/Choate Campaign</A>
<DD>Official World Wide Web site of the Reform Party. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.cais.com/fmg/fpac.htm">Political Action Committees on the Internet</A>
<DD>Divides sites into Left and Right Wing and lists them by subdivision (e.g., environmental,
    public interest, etc.).  Maintained by the Future Media Group, a Virginia-based public 
    relations firm. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.politicsnow.com/">Politics Now</A>
<DD>The latest political news from ABC News, The Washington Post, National Journal,
    Newsweek, and The Los Angeles Times. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.rollcall.com/">Roll Call</A>
<DD>Web Site for Roll Call, the newspaper of Capitol Hill since 1955. News and 
    information about Congress. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.realchange.org/">Skeleton Closet</A>
<DD>"The right place for dirt, attitude, and opinionated character reviews of
     all the presidential candidates."
     Maintained by the Real People For Real Change PAC.  
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.vote-smart.org/">Vote Smart Web</A>
<DD>A voter's "self-defense system" that provides voters with factual information on candidates and elected
    officials. Project Vote Smart is the major program of The Center for National Independence in Politics, 
    a national non-partisan organization focused on providing citizens/voters with information about 
    the political system, issues, candidates and elected officials. 
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Government/Politics/Parties/">Yahoo:Government:Politics:Parties</A>
<DD>Links to information on major and minor U.S. political parties.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Government/Politics/">Yahoo:Politics</A>
<DD>Links to major U.S. political information resources on the Web.       
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/headlines/politics/">Yahoo:Politics:[Xtra!]</A>
<DD>Headlines and news summaries about the upcoming U.S. elections from Reuters news service 
   (as provided by Yahoo). 
<P>
</DL>
</DL>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<H2>Selected Paper Resources for Politics in America</H2>
<P>
This list is intended to introduce you to some of the paper materials we have on American politics.  
It is not a complete list, but merely a sampling.  All items listed below are located in the Reference
Collection on Level 4 unless otherwise noted.  Please don't hesitate to ask a librarian if your aren't
finding what you need here.
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#ency">Encyclopedias, Dictionaries, and Factual Sources</A>
<LI><A HREF="#in-ab">Indexes and Abstracts</A>

</UL>


<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!--  ################ Dictionaries, Encyclopedias, and Factual Sources   -->
<a name="ency">
<h3>Encyclopedias, Dictionaries, and Factual Sources</h3>

Use these sources at the beginning of your research to get an overview of a topic or to identify 
synonyms or related terms that will apply to your topic.  Later, return to these sources to clarify 
concepts or define new vocabulary.

<DL>

<DT><kbd>Ref JK 1010 .B26</kbd><br>
<strong>The Almanac of American Politics</strong>.  1972- .
<DD>Published by the National Journal; annual; useful introductory material includes key
    bills and overview of the current state of Congress; gives overview of the politics in each state, state
    officials, key votes, 11 lobby group ratings, and National Journal ratings. 
<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref JK 1 .C66</kbd><br>
Congressional Quarterly, Inc. <strong>Congressional Quarterly Almanac; a Service for Editors and 
Commentators</strong>. Mar. 1945-
<DD>Summaries of Congressional sessions with analysis.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref JK 1 .C15</kbd><br>
Congressional Quarterly, Inc. <strong>Congressional Quarterly Weekly Report</strong>. 1956- Vol. 14, 
no. 1 (Jan. 6, 1956)- .  weekly.
<DD>Pending and recently enacted legistlation; most thorough day-to-day coverage of Congress; index
    in yellow issues.  <A HREF="gopher://gopher.cqalert.com:70//1D-1%A9163%A10WEEKLEREPORT">Gopher site</A>
    has table of contents of current issue with full-text of cover story.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref JK 1431 .C64 1993</kbd><br>
Congressional Quarterly, Inc. <strong>Congressional Quarterly's Congressional Districts in the 1990s: 
a Portrait of America</strong>.  1993.
<DD>Overview by district; notes limited election returns; demographics include race; lists
    educational institutions, newspapers, television stations, military bases, and major employers.
     
<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref JK 1010 .P64 1994</kbd><br>
Phil Duncan, editor. <strong>Congressional Quarterly's Politics in America</strong>: 1994- . Annual.
<DD>Overview of current members' careers in Congress, covering both Washington, D.C. and within their
    state; brief statement on redistricting; basic statistics about each state and its elections;
    list of committee members, seniority, and campaign finance information; includes a pronunciation
    guide and a list of close calls in the previous election.  See also the new
    <A HREF="/electronic/cd-rom/cd-rom.html#pol">CD-ROM version</A>.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref JK 1051 .S555 1988</kbd><br>
Sharp, J. Michael. <strong>The Directory of Congressional Voting Scores and Interest Group Ratings</strong>. 1988.
<DD>

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref JK 1967 .E44 1992</kbd><br>
<strong>The Election Data Book : a Statistical Portrait of Voting in America</strong>. 1992. Biennial.
<DD>

<P>

<DT><kbd>Periodical</kbd><br>
<strong>National Journal</strong>, 1971- . weekly.
<DD>Inside the Beltway/Washington D.C. who does what why; six months cumulative index in back of bound
    volume; supplements kept with current issues for one year then are withdrawn from our collection.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio JK 1991 .M26 1994</kbd><br>
Congressional Quarterly, Inc. <strong>Open Secrets : the Encyclopedia of Congressional Money and Politics</strong>. 1996. Annual.
<DD>Published by the Center for Responsive Politics; lists committees, leading contributors, sources, of
    funds, spending by candidates, etc.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref JK 1041 .V58 1995-96</kbd><br>
Congressional Quarterly, Inc. <strong>Vital Statistics on Congress 1995 - 1996</strong>. 1996.
<DD>

<P>

</DL>

<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!-- ############### Indexes and Abstracts  -->
<a name="in-ab">
<h3>Indexes and Abstracts</h3>
<P>
Turn to indexes and abstracts to find more information on your topic.   If you want to know whether 
Carleton subscribes to a particular journal, perform a <STRONG><KBD>T &gt; TITLE</KBD></STRONG> search in Muse 
using the exact title of the journal you're looking for.
<P>

<DL>

<DT><kbd>Ref Z 7554 .U5 A46</kbd><br>
<strong>ASI/American Statistics Index</strong>. Washington, Congressional Information Service. 1973 - .
<DD>Index to publications of government agencies.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref KF 49 .C62</kbd><br>
<strong>CIS/Congressional Information Service</strong>. Washington, D.C., Congressional 
Information Service. 1970- . Annual.
<DD>Index to publications of Congress.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref H 1 .P8 (1915-  )</kbd><br>
<strong>PAIS: Public Affairs Information Service/International</strong>, 1915-  .
<DD>Subject index to periodical articles, books, reports, governmental and intergovernmental 
    publications on issues of public policy. Also available on <A HREF="/electronic/cd-rom/cd-rom.html#pais">
    CD-ROM</A>.  The most recent 10 years, known as PAIS Decade, is available on
    <A HREF="/electronic/online/firstsearch.html">FirstSearch</A> 

</DL>

<P>

These <strong>Newspapers</strong> are retained in the Library's collection; all are on microfilm in the Microforms Room:
<DL>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>New York Times</STRONG>, 1850- .<BR>
<DD><kbd>Ref AI21 .N44</kbd> <STRONG>Index</STRONG>, 1850- .<BR>
<DT><STRONG>Wall Street Journal</STRONG>, 1958- .<BR>
<DD><kbd>Ref HG1 .W258</kbd> <STRONG>Index</STRONG>, 1958- .<BR>
<DT><STRONG>Washington Post</STRONG>, 1979-  .<BR>
<DD><kbd>Ref AI21 .W3</kbd> <STRONG>Index</STRONG>, 1979- .
</DL>
</DL>
<BR>
<BR>
To identify which political science periodicals are owned by the Gould Library, perform the following steps on
Muse:
<P>
<OL>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>N &gt; NUMBERS</KBD></STRONG>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>C &gt; CALL numbers (Library of Congress)</KBD></STRONG> (use <STRONG><KBD>PER</KBD></STRONG>)
<LI><STRONG><KBD>L &gt; LIMIT this Search</KBD></STRONG>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>S &gt; Words in the SUBJECT</KBD></STRONG>
<LI>(use <STRONG><KBD>politic* science</KBD></STRONG>)
<LI><STRONG><KBD>F &gt; Find items with above limits</KBD></STRONG>
</OL>
</DL>

<P>
