<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!--  ################ Dictionaries, Encyclopedias, and Guides.   -->
<a name="ency">
<h3>Background Sources - Encyclopedias, Dictionaries, and Guides</h3>

Use these sources at the beginning of your research to get an overview of a topic or to identify 
synonyms or related terms that will apply to your topic.  Later, return to these sources to clarify 
concepts or define new vocabulary.

<DL>
<DT><kbd>Ref CB 5 .D52</kbd><br>
<strong>Dictionary of the History of Ideas</strong>. 1973. 5 vols.
<DD>Discusses interdisciplinary causes for selected important ideas in history.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio BL 31 .E46 1986</kbd><br>
editor-in-chief, Mircea Eliade. <strong>Encyclopedia of Religion</strong>. 1987. 15 vols.
<DD>Emphasis on various religious traditions and comparative studies of themes; limited number of  references for further reading.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 31 .E4</kbd><br>
James Hastings, ed. <strong>Encyclopaedia of Religion and Ethics</strong>. 1908-1927.  13 vols.
<DD>Comprehensive articles written at the turn of the century.  Still useful for its historical detail.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 2525 .E53 1988</kbd><br>
eds. Charles H. Lippy & Peter Williams. <strong>Encyclopedia of the American Religious Experience: Studies of Traditions and Movements</strong>. 1988.
<DD>Articles arranged by broad topics or themes; includes bibliographies.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 80.2 .E415 1991</kbd><br>
Eliade, Mircea.  <strong>The Eliade Guide to World Religions</strong>. 1991.
<DD>Essays on international religious practices.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BM 50 .E496</kbd><br>
Cecil Roth and Geoffrey Wigoder, eds. <strong>Encyclopaedia Judaica</strong>. 1972. 16 vols.
<DD>This encyclopedia takes into account Jewish studies in the twentieth century  on topics such as the Holocaust as well as traditional historic studies.  Index is in the first volume not last.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BR563.N4 E53 1993</kbd><br>
Larry G.Murphy, J. Gordon Melton, Gary L. Ward, eds. <strong>Encyclopedia of African American Religions</strong>. 1993.
<DD>Many entries have brief bibliographies.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 31 .F33 1984</kbd><br>
 ed. by John R. Hinnels<strong>The Facts on File Dictionary of Religions</strong>. 1984.
 <DD>Includes a description of many religions and movements.  Synoptic Index is a listing of all terms related to a specific religion.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio BL 1005.B45 1990</kbd><br>
Bhattacharyya, Narendra.<strong> Glossary of Indian Religious Terms and Concepts</strong>. 1990.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref F1435.3.R3 M55 1993</kbd><br>
Miller, Mary and Karl Taube.<strong> The Gods and Symbols of Ancient Mexico and the Maya: an Illustrated Dictionary of Mesoamerican Religion</strong>. 1993.
<DD>Includes bibliographical references; many illustrations.

<P>

<DT><kbd>BM50 .J28 1995</kbd><br>
Jacobs, Louis. <STRONG>The Jewish Religion : a Companion</STRONG>. 1995
<DD>*** comments ***

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BX 841 .N44</kbd><br>
ed-in-chief, William J. McDonald. <strong>New Catholic Encyclopedia</strong>. 1967.
<DD>While focusing on Catholicism and how movements have affected Catholicism, the encyclopedia seems to have been meant to serve as a general encyclopedia and consequently there is a fair treatment on other religions,  as well as other topics such as philosophy  or psychology.  

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BQ 130.L492513 1991</kbd><br>
<strong>Shambhala dictionary of Buddhism and Zen</strong>. 1991.
<DD>Contains terms from Sanskrit, Chinese, Japanese and Tibetan languages on Buddhism, Tibetan buddhism and Zen.
</DL>

<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!-- ###############Bibliographies  -->
<a name="biblio">
<h3>Bibliographies</h3>

Bibliographies are lists of materials on a particular topic.  They should save you time because the author has done
the tedious work of searching catalogs and indexes to find information on the topic. Many bibliographies also contain 
evaluations of the works that they mention.  Listed here are several general titles, but note that we have
bibliographies soley on individual religions as well. (Try a keyword search on Muse to find some.  For example,
type: <STRONG><KBD>hinduism bibliography</KBD></STRONG> to find a bibliography on hinduism.)  
<a name="in-ab">

<DL>
<DT><kbd>Ref BL 48 .R46</kbd><br>
<strong>Religious Books, 1876-1982</strong>. 1983.  3 vols.
<DD>Lists over 130,000 books on all aspects of the world's religions.  Compiled from over one-hundred	 years of Library  of Congress cataloging on religious titles that were published or  distributed in the United States.  

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio BL 60 .R44 1983</kbd><br>
<strong>Religion and Society in North America: an Annotated Bibliography</strong>. 1983.
<DD>Access by subject, author, or classified indexes.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 80 .T87</kbd><br>
Turner, Harold W.  <strong>Bibliography of New Religious Movements in Primal Societies. 1977- </strong>. {1991...}
<DD>Vol. 1: Black Africa -- Vol. 2: North America -- Vol. 3: Oceania -- Vol. 4 Europe and Asia -- Vol. 5 Latin America.  Religious practices and beliefs of societies worldwide may be found in this series.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 458 .C395 1992</kbd><br>
Carson, Anne. <STRONG>Goddesses and Wise Women : Literature of Feminist Spirituality, 1980-1992</strong>. 1992.
<DD>Guide to Feminist Writings from 1980-1992 on issues confronting women in the Christian churches.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 1202 .D44</kbd><br>
Dell, David J. <strong>Guide to Hindu Religion</strong>. 1981.
<DD>Entries are divided into categories and include annotations.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL1802 .C548 1993</kbd><br>
Ching, Julia.  <strong>Chinese Religions : Publications in Western Languages 1981-1990</strong>. 1993.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 2018 .R34 1989</kbd><br>
Rai, Priya Muhar.  <strong>Sikhism and the Sikhs</strong>. 1989.
<DD>Annotated entries arranged by broad subjects.  The subject index is helpful.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BM 45 .S78 1991</kbd><br>
Starkey, Edward D. <strong>Judiasm and Christianity: a Guide to the Reference Literature</strong>. 1991.
<DD>Detailed compilation of reference books in Judeo-Christian religion with critical evaluations.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BM 535 .S48 1988</kbd><br>
Shermis, Michael.  <strong>Jewish-Christian Relations: an Annotated Bibliography and Resource Guide</strong>. 1988.
<DD>Annotated entries are arranged by subject.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BR 118 .K46 1981</kbd><br>
Kepple, Robert J.  <strong>Reference works for Theological Research.</strong> 2nd ed., 1981.
<DD>Contains about 800 detailed descriptions of references sources.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BT30.A438 Y68 1993</kbd><br>
Young, Josiah U. (Josiah Ulysses).  <strong>African Theology: a Critical Analysis and Annotated Bibliography</strong>. 1993.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BX 850 .C37 1990</kbd><br>
Carlen, Claudia.  <strong>Papal Pronouncements; a Guide: 1740-1978</strong>. 1990.
<DD>Contains summaries of and bibliographical references to papal acts and letters with citations to a complete print version.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BX 1795 .P43 M88 1987</kbd><br>
Musto, Ronald G. <strong>The Peace Tradition in the Catholic Church</strong>. 1987.
<DD>Annotated bibliography of articles and books arranged chronologically and by  subject.
</DL>

<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!-- ###############indexes and abstracts  -->
<a name="in-ab">
<h3>Indexes and Abstracts</h3>
<P>
Turn to indexes and abstracts to find more information on your topic.   If you want to know whether 
Carleton subscribes to a particular journal, perform a <STRONG><KBD>T > TITLE</KBD></STRONG> search in Muse 
using the exact title of the journal you're looking for.
<P>

<DL>
<DT><kbd>Ref BL 1 .A5</kbd><br>
<strong>Religion Index One: Periodicals</strong>. 1949- .
<DD>Access to over four hundred periodicals by subject and author with abstracts and book reviews.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 48 .R35</kbd><br>
<strong>Religion Index Two: Multi-Author Works</strong>. 1976- .
<DD>Covers articles from conference papers, Festschriften and other collections; access by subject, author, and editor with full contents.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 1 .R286</kbd><br>
<strong>Religious and Theological Abstracts</strong>. 1958- . 
<DD>Arranged by five main fields which are subdivided; access also by author, subject, and scripture.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BS 410 .O42</kbd><br>
<strong>Old Testament Abstracts</strong>. (Carleton has 1990- )
<DD>Abstracts over 300 periodicals and gives short book notices on topics such as archaeology, the prophet, biblical theology, etc.  The third issue each year has indexes.
 
<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref DS 133 .I5</kbd><br> 
<strong>Index to Jewish Periodicals</strong>. (Carleton has 1985- ) 
<DD>Author and Subject index to Jewish topics.  Coverage has grown with each year of publication.

<P>

<DT><kbd>lstSearch & Ref HM 1 .S67</kbd><br>
<strong>Sociology Abstracts</strong>. 1952- .
<DD>Arranged by classified subjects; includes journal articles, book reviews and conference papers.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref HQ 1111 .W65</kbd><br>
<strong>Women Studies Abstracts.</strong>. 1972- . 
<DD>Gives access to periodical articles in the field of women's studies.  Start with the keyword index in the back of the volume.  Reference numbers refer to entry #s not page #s.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref HQ 1180 .W683</kbd><br>
<strong>Women Studies Index</strong>. 1989- .
<DD>Straight alphabetical author and subject listing of bibliographic citations.  Comprehensive indexing of scholarly periodicals, selective indexing of popular titles.
</DL>

<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<a name="rev-ev">
<h3>Review and Evaluation</h3>

<p>When doing research you may  wish to find out more about the source of an article.  Here are a few guides to help identify authors' backgrounds,  find out how a book has been discussed, or determine what the editorial policy of the journal where an article was published.  </p>

<a name="peop">

<!--  ##################### biographical guides ************** -->

<a name="peop">
<h3>--People</h3>

<DL>
<DT><kbd>FirstSearch & Ref CT 104 .B5</kbd><br> 
<strong>Biography Index</strong>. 1946- .
<DD>Covers biographical material in 1,500+ periodicals and from the New York Times.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref PN 452 .C6</kbd><br>
<strong>Contemporary Authors</strong>. 1962- . 
<DD>Current information on writers; several series exist, but a cumulative index is published to provide access to all volumes.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio LA 2311 .C32 1982</kbd><br>
<strong>Directory of American Scholars</strong>. 8th ed. Vol. 4:  Religion.
<DD>Biographies of scholars in the U.S. and Canada.  Dated but still useful to identify information on authors.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL72 .M458 1991</kbd><br>
Melton, J. Gordon. <strong>Religious Leaders of America : a Biographical Guide to Founders and Leaders of Religious bodies, Churches, and Spiritual Groups in North America</strong>. 1991.
<DD>Biographical entries on more than 1000 people who have played leading roles in the diverse religions of North America and also includes people famous for rejecting religion: humanists, agnostics and atheists.
</DL>

<a name="book">
<h3>--Books</h3>

<DL>
<DT><kbd>Ref Z 1035 .A1 B62</kbd><br>
<strong>Book Review Index</strong>. 1969- .
<DD>A guide to citations of reviews from over 200 periodicals.  You should know when your book was originally published to find reviews.  Don't hesitate to ask a librarian if you need this information.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio BL 1 .I5</kbd><br>
<strong>Index to Book Reviews in Religion</strong>. 1986- .
<DD>Access by author, title, reviewer, series and classified indexes.  Before 1986 look for reviews in Religion Index One:  Periodicals  (described in "Index" section above).
</DL>

<!-- ###############put periodicals here  -->
<a name="perio">
<h3>--Periodicals</h3>


<DL>
<DT><kbd>Ref PN 4888 .R4 L5 1986</kbd><br>
ed. by Charles Lippy.<strong>Religious Periodicals of the United States</strong>. 1986.
<DD>Comprehensive analysis of current and defunct U.S. religious publications.  Contains references for further reading.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref BL 1 .A1 F53 1988</kbd><br>
Fieg, Eugene.  <strong>Religion Journals and Serials: an Analytical Guide</strong>. 1988.
<DD>Describes and evaluates English language, religious periodicals and related indexes.
</DL>
<P>
To identify which religion-related periodicals are owned by the Gould Library, perform the following steps on
Muse:
<P>
<OL>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>N > NUMBERS</KBD></STRONG>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>C > CALL numbers (Library of Congress)</KBD></STRONG> (use <STRONG><KBD>PER</KBD></STRONG>)
<LI><STRONG><KBD>L > LIMIT this Search</KBD></STRONG>
<LI><STRONG><KBD>S > Words in the SUBJECT</KBD></STRONG>
<LI>(use <STRONG><KBD>religion</KBD></STRONG>)
<LI><STRONG><KBD>F > Find items with above limits</KBD></STRONG>
</OL>
<BR>
<BR>
Here's an example of a full-text, online journal now available:
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/modern_judaism/">Modern Judaism</A>	
<DD>"...provides a distinctive, interdisciplinary
forum for discussion of the modern Jewish experience since
the Haskalah, the Jewish Enlightenment. Its contributors
address topics pertinent to the understanding of Jewish life
today and the forces that have shaped that experience,
including the Zionist movement and the establishment of the
State of Israel, the socio-political role assumed by literary
works of art, and the rise of modern anti-Semitism and its
devastating climax in the Holocaust."
</DL>
<hr>
<P>
