<H3>Selected Web Links for Anthropology</H3>
<P>
The Internet has many thousands of resources of interest to anthropologists. A
few selected links to major sites are provided below:
<P>
<DL>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.artsci.wustl.edu/~anthro/ca/papers/schwimmer/intro.html">
     Anthropology on the Internet: a Review and Evaluation on Networked Resources</A>
<DD>A superb guide by Brian Schwimmer from the University of Manitoba Department of Anthropology.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.n2h2.com/KOVACS/S0002s.html">Scholarly and Professional Electronic Discussions 
     in Anthropology, Cross-Cultural Studies, and Archaeology</A>
<DD>Compiled by Gladys Smiley Bell at Kent State University.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Social_Science/Anthropology_and_Archaeology/">Yahoo:Social Science:
     Anthropology and Archaeology</A>
<DD>The jumping off point to hundreds of WWW sites on anthropological and archeaological topics.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Social_Science/Anthropology_and_Archaeology/Indices/">Yahoo:Social Science:
     Anthropology and Archaeology:Indices</A>
<DD>Links to over +19 directories of anthropology and archeaology sites on the Web. Includes the
    <A HREF="http://www.usc.edu/dept/v-lib/anthropology.html">WWW Virtual Library on Anthropology</A>, 
    the <A HREF="http://galaxy.einet.net/galaxy/Social-Sciences/Anthropology.html">EINET Anthropology Page</A>, 
    and Allen Lutins' <A HREF="http://www.nitehawk.com/alleycat/anth-faq.html">Anthropology Resources on the Internet</A>.
<P>
</DL>
</DL>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<P>
<H3>Selected Anthropological Sources in the Reference Collection</H3>
<P>
This list is intended to introduce you to some of the paper materials we have on anthropology.  
It is not a complete list, but merely a sampling.  All items listed below are located in the Reference
Collection on Level 4 unless otherwise noted.  Please don't hesitate to ask a librarian if your aren't
finding what you need here.
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#ency">Encyclopedias, Dictionaries, and Guides</A>
<LI><A HREF="#in-ab">Indexes and Abstracts</A>
<LI><A HREF="#additional">Additional Sources</A>
<LI><A HREF="#govdocs">U.S. Government Publications</A>
</UL>

<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!--  ################ Encyclopedias, Dictionaries, and Guides   -->
<a name="ency">
<H3>Encyclopedias, Dictionaries, and Guides</H3>
<P>
Use these sources at the beginning of your research to get an overview of a topic or to identify 
synonyms or related terms that will apply to your topic.  Later, return to these sources to clarify 
concepts or define new vocabulary.
<P>

<DL>

<DT><kbd>General Collection GN 1 .A623</kbd><br>
<strong>Annual Review of Anthropology</strong>, 1972- . </strong>(continues <strong>Biennial 
Review of Anthropology</strong>, 1959-1971.)
<DD>Summarizes trends in subfields of anthropology.  Contains long bibliographies.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref GN 11 .W5</kbd><br>
Hunter D.E. & P. Whitten, eds. <strong>Encyclopedia of Anthropology.</strong> 1976.
<DD>

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio GN 281 .E53 1988</kbd><br>
Tattersall, Ian, & others. <strong>Encyclopedia of Human Evolution and Prehistory</strong>. 1988.
<DD>

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio GN 495.4 .E53 1993</kbd><br>
Gonen, Amiram, ed. <strong>The Encyclopedia of the Peoples of the World.</strong> 1993.
<DD>Useful index; select bibliography at the end of the book.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio GN 550 .E53 1991</kbd><br>
O'Leary, T. J. and David Levinson, eds. <strong>Encyclopedia of World Cultures.</strong> 1991- .
<DD>vol. 1. North America -- vol. 2. Oceania -- vol. 3. South Asia -- vol. 4. Europe -- vol 5. East and Southeast Asia -- vol. 6 Russia and Eurassia, China -- vol. 7.  South America.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Gov Docs Ref SI 1.20/2:</kbd><br>
Sturtevant, Willian C., ed. <strong>Handbook of North American Indians.</strong> 1972- .
<DD>Library has: -- vol. 4. History of Indian-White Relations -- vol. 5. Artic -- vol. 6. Subartic -- vol. 7. Northwest Coast -- vol. 8. Califorina -- vol. 9 & 10. Southwest -- vol. 11. Great Basin -- vol. 15 Northeast.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref H 40 .A2 I5</kbd><br>
<strong>International Encyclopedia of the Social Sciences.</strong> 1968. 19 vols.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref Folio E 75 .N397 1994</kbd><br>
<strong>The Native North American Almanac.</strong> 1994
<DD>An encyclopedia covering historical and contemporary information on topics such as religion, laws, biographies.

</DL>

<P>

<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!--  ################ Indexes and Abstracts   -->
<a name="in-ab">
<h3>Indexes and Abstracts</h3>
<P>
Turn to indexes and abstracts to find more information on your topic.   If you want to know whether 
Carleton subscribes to a particular journal, perform a <STRONG><KBD>T > TITLE</KBD></STRONG> search in Muse 
using the exact title of the journal you're looking for.
<P>

<DL>

<DT><kbd>Ref GN 1 .A15</kbd><br>
<strong>Abstracts in Anthropology. </strong><br>Carleton has: 1974-  (St. Olaf 
has: 1970-  )
<DD>Basic index in the field; covers books, articles, and papers.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref GN 1 .A67</kbd><br>
<strong>Anthropological Literature: an Index to Periodical Articles and Essays</strong>. 1983-<br>
<DD>Library has:  1983 & 1990- present in <EM>paper</EM> and 1984-1989 on <EM>microfiche</EM>.  See
also <A HREF="/electronic/online/anl.html">Anthropological Literature</A> online.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref GN 304 .I593</kbd><br>
<strong>International Bibliography of Social and Cultural Anthropology </strong>. 1955-1959; 1988- .
(continues: <strong>International Bibliography of the Social Sciences: Anthropology</strong>, 1960-1987.)
<DD>

<P>

<DT><kbd>Gov Doc Reference (1917- )</kbd><br>
<strong>Monthly Catalog of U.S. Government Publications</strong>. (GPO)
<DD>Basic index to U.S. government publications. The years July 1976-present of this resource are also 
    available online via <A HREF="/electronic/online/firstsearch.html">FirstSearch</A>.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref HM 1 .S67</kbd><br> 
<strong>Sociological Abstracts</strong>, 1952- .
<DD>Online version covering 1963-present is available on <A HREF="/electronic/online/firstsearch.html">FirstSearch</A>. 

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref HQ 1111 .W65</kbd><br>
<strong>Women Studies Abstract</strong>, 1972-  .
<DD>Indexes scholarly and popular publications not covered by more mainstream indexes.

<P>

<DT><kbd>Ref HQ 1181 .W683</kbd><br>
<strong>Women Studies Index</strong>, 1989-  .
<DD>Straight alphabetical author and subject listing of bibliographic citations.
Comprehensive indexing of scholarly periodicals, selective indexing of popular titles.
</DL>

<P>

<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!--  ################ Additional Sources   -->
<a name="additional">
<h3>Additional Sources</h3>

<DL>

<DT>Microfiche & CD-ROM (1995- )<br>
<strong>Human Relations Area Files</strong>.
<DD>Ethnographies are coded according to culture group (i.e. Ojibway) and topic (i.e. childrearing); 
good for cross-cultural topics; most material is pre 1950; see a reference librarian to use this file.
See also <A HREF="/electronic/CD-ROM/CD-ROM.html#ehraf">Electronic Human Relations Area Files</A>. 
</DL>

<P>

<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<!--  ################ U.S. Government Publications   -->
