<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Faculty Library Instruction Opportunities: FirstSearch</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H1>A World of Information Online:  Becoming a Sophisticated FirstSearch User</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3>Presenter:  Terry Metz, Instruction Librarian</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>DATES AND TIMES:</STRONG>
    <P>
    <PRE>
            	Thursday,  March 6          2:30-4:00
            	Friday,    March 7          1:30-3:00
            	Thursday,  March 13         2:30-4:00
            	Friday,    March 14         1:30-3:00
    </PRE>
<DD>All training sessions will be held in the Center for Mathematics and Computing (CMC) room #102.
    <BR>
    <BR>
<DT><STRONG>PURPOSE:</STRONG>
    <P>
<DD>The ability to locate and retrieve bibliographic information
    electronically can reduce significantly the leg work of scholarship and
    professional research.  Those who excell at these skills will maintain 
    more control over their work lives and save valuable time.
    <P>
    The purpose of this workshop is to give you hands-on experience in
    using FirstSearch, a service which gives you networked access to over 50
    databases covering many fields of knowledge, e.g., Worldcat (the world's
    largest database of books held in libraries), Books in Print, scholarly
    literature in many discipline, business information, news, etc.
    <P>
    FirstSearch is the library community's fastest growing online
    system.  In addition, FirstSearch is now the second most-used system in the
    entire information industry, ranking behind only LEXIS/NEXIS. Among
    academic and government libraries however, FirstSearch is the most-used
    online reference service.
    <BR>
    <BR>
<DT><STRONG>WHO SHOULD ATTEND:</STRONG>
    <P>
<DD>Faculty and staff who want to save time and effort by accessing 
    bibliographic and scholarly information from their homes, offices, 
    and labs should consider attending this workshop.  Attendees need not 
    have previous exposure to FirstSearch.  Novices are welcome and encouraged
    to attend. Previous experience using Telnet and the World Wide Web will
    be helpful, however.
    <BR>
    <BR>
<DT><STRONG>WHAT YOU WILL LEARN:</STRONG>
    <P>
<DD><UL>
    <LI>a conceptual understanding of FirstSearch and why
        it has become such a popular information tool among
        faculty and students
        <P>
    <LI>how to access FirstSearch in several different ways
        as well as understand which of FirstSearch's +50
        databases are of value to your specific needs
        <P>
    <LI>advanced FirstSearch features, including:
        <UL>
        <LI>how to e-mail and download citation information
        <LI>how to determine which libraries in the U.S. have
            resources you need
        <LI>how to place Interlibrary Loan requests online
        </UL>
    <LI>what are FirstSearch's strengths and weaknesses
    </UL>
    <BR>
    <BR>
<DT><STRONG>AFTER COMPLETING THIS WORKSHOP, YOU SHOULD BE ABLE TO:</STRONG>
    <P>
<DD><UL>
    <LI>navigate the FirstSearch interface with confidence
    <LI>retrieve information from FirstSearch databases more efficiently
    <LI>save time and effort in locating bibliographic and scholarly information
    <LI>identify print and electronic resources for learning more about
        FirstSearch
    </UL>
    <BR>
    <BR>
<DT><STRONG>TIME BUDGET:</STRONG> (subject to modification)
    <P>
<DD><DL>
    <DT>Part One - The Basics
    <DD><UL>
        <LI>FirstSearch overview (5 min.)
        <LI>connecting to FirstSearch (5 min.)
        <LI>search fundamentals (20 min.)
        </UL>
        <P>
    <DT>Part Two - The Bells & Whistles
    <DD><UL>
        <LI>advanced features and techniques (30 min.)
        </UL>
        <P>
    <DT>Part Three - FirstSearch on the WWW
    <DD><UL>
        <LI>highlights of the new FirstSearch WWW interface (20 min.)
        <LI>wrap up; how to learn more (10 min.)
        </UL>
    </DL>
    <BR>
    <BR>
<DT><STRONG>HOW TO REGISTER FOR THIS WORKSHOP:</STRONG>
    <P>
<DD><UL>
    <LI>notify Terry Metz
        <UL>
        <LI>in person at his office: Library 466
        <LI>by phone: (507) 646-4530
        <LI>by fax: (507) 646-4087
        <LI>by e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:temetz@carleton.edu">temetz@carleton.edu</A>
        </UL>
    </UL>
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/instruction/index.html">Return to the Library Instruction Page</A></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<CITE>
Maintained by <A HREF="/staff/terry/terry.html">Terry Metz, temetz@carleton.edu</A>
<BR> Last updated: February 12, 1997
</CITE>
