<HEAD>
<TITLE>Faculty Library Instruction Opportunities: Muse</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H1>I Didn't Know You Could Do That:  Becoming a Sophisticated Muse User</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3>Presenter:  Terry Metz, Instruction Librarian</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>DATES AND TIMES:</STRONG>
<P>
<PRE>
			Friday,    February 7      	1:30-3:00
			Thursday,  February 13  	2:30-4:00
			Friday,    February 14     	1:30-3:00
			Thursday,  February 20  	2:30-4:00
			Friday,    February 21     	1:30-3:00
			Thursday,  February 27  	2:30-4:00
 			Friday,    February 28     	1:30-3:00
</PRE>
<DD>All training sessions will be held in the Center for Mathematics and Computing (CMC) room #102.
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>PURPOSE:</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>The ability to locate and retrieve bibliographic information
electronically can reduce significantly the leg work of scholarship and
professional research.  Those who excel at these skills will maintain 
more control over their work lives and save valuable time.
<P>
The purpose of this workshop is to give you hands-on experience in
using Muse, the primary finding tool for materials owned by the 
Carleton Library.
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>WHO SHOULD ATTEND:</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>Faculty and staff who want to save time and effort by accessing 
bibliographic and scholarly information from their homes, offices, 
and labs should consider attending this workshop.  Attendees need not 
have previous exposure to Muse.  Novices are welcome and encouraged to 
attend. Previous experience using Telnet and the World Wide Web will 
be helpful, however.
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>WHAT YOU WILL LEARN:</STRONG>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>a conceptual understanding of Muse and its fundamental
	capabilities
<P>
<LI>how to access Muse in several different ways
<P>
<LI>many advanced Muse features, including how to:
<UL>
        <LI>refine your searching for more precise results
        <LI>find out what you have checked out under your name
        <LI>place a hold on an item you need
        <LI>find out which periodical titles Carleton owns
        <LI>find out which items the library has on order
        <LI>e-mail and download citation information
        <LI>suggest items the library should purchase as well
	        share suggestions for improving library services
        <LI>search the University of Minnesota's online catalog using Muse
            commands
        <LI>use the Wilson periodical indexes (built into Muse)
</UL>
</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>AFTER COMPLETING THIS WORKSHOP, YOU SHOULD BE ABLE TO:</STRONG>
<P>
<UL>
        <LI>navigate the Muse interface with confidence
        <LI>retrieve information from Muse more efficiently
        <LI>save time and effort in locating and managing
	        bibliographic information available from Muse
</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>TIME BUDGET:</STRONG> (subject to modification)
<P>
<DD>Part One - The Basics
<UL>
        <LI>Muse overview (5 min.)
        <LI>connecting to Muse (5 min.)
        <LI>search fundamentals (20 min.)
</UL>
<P>
<DD>Part Two - The Bells & Whistles
<UL>
        <LI>advanced features and techniques (30 min.)
</UL>
<P>
<DD>Part Three - Muse on the WWW
<UL>
        <LI>highlights of Muse's forthcoming WWW interface (20 min.)
        <LI>wrap up; how to learn more (10 min.)
</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>HOW TO REGISTER FOR THIS WORKSHOP:</STRONG>
<P>
   <UL>
        <LI>notify Terry Metz
        <UL>
<LI>in person at his office: Library 466
<LI>by phone: (507) 646-4530
<LI>by fax: (507) 646-4087
<LI>by e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:temetz@carleton.edu">temetz@carleton.edu</A>
</UL>
</UL>
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
