<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Faculty Library Instruction Opportunities: World Wide Web</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H1>Introduction to the World Wide Web:  World Wide Web "101"</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3>Presenter:  Terry Metz, Instruction Librarian</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>DATES AND TIMES:</STRONG>
<P>
<PRE>
            Wednesday, March 26     9:00-noon, CMC #102
            Thursday,  March 27     9:00-noon, CMC #102
            Friday,    March 28     9:00-noon, CMC #102
</PRE>
<DD>All training sessions will be held in the Center for Mathematics and Computing (CMC) room #102.
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>PURPOSE:</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    The ability to use the Internet is rapidly becoming a requirement for
    scholarly and professional advancement.  The purpose of this workshop is to
    give you hands-on experience in using the World Wide Web (WWW), the
    fastest growing service of the Internet.
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>WHO SHOULD ATTEND:</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    Faculty and staff who want to learn what the WWW is and how to use it at a
    basic level should consider attending this workshop.  Attendees need not
    have previous WWW experience.  Novices are welcome and encouraged to attend.
    Previous experience using Macintosh or Windows operating systems is helpful.
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>WHAT YOU WILL LEARN:</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    <UL>
    <LI>a conceptual understanding of the WWW and why it has become such a
        popular tool for information seekers and providers
    <LI>the basics of WWW use, including:
        <UL>
        <LI>WWW and Internet terminology
        <LI>fundamental techniques of WWW &quot;navigation&quot;
        <LI>examples of how the Carleton Library is using the WWW
        </UL>
    </UL>
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>AFTER COMPLETING THIS WORKSHOP, YOU SHOULD BE ABLE TO:</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    <UL>
    <LI>use WWW navigation techniques with confidence
    <LI>access WWW bibliographic tools (i.e., library catalogs, online indexes)
    <LI>identify print and electronic resources for learning more about the WWW
    </UL>
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>TIME BUDGET:</STRONG> (subject to modification)
<DD><P>
    <DL>
    <DT>Hour One - Conceptual
    <DD><UL>
        <LI>Internet overview (20 min.)
        <LI>WWW client/server model (20 min.)
        <LI>HTTP, HTML, & URLs (20 min.)
        </UL>
    <DT>Hour Two - Examples
    <DD><UL>
        <LI>Netscape orientation (60 min.)
        </UL>
    <DT>Hour Three - Searching and Surfing
    <DD><UL>
        <LI>Tour the Carleton Library web site (45 min.)
        <LI>wrap up; how to learn more (15 min.)
        </UL>
    </DL>
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>HOW TO REGISTER FOR A WORKSHOP(S):</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    <UL>
    <LI>notify Terry Metz
        <UL>
        <LI>in person at his office: Library 466
        <LI>by phone: (507) 646-4530
        <LI>by fax: (507) 646-4087
        <LI>by e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:temetz@carleton.edu">temetz@carleton.edu</A>
        </UL>
    </UL>
    </P>
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
