<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Faculty Library Instruction Opportunities: Searching The Web</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><H1>Using the World Wide Web for Information Retrieval</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3>Presenter:  Terry Metz, Instruction Librarian</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>DATES AND TIMES:</STRONG>
<P>
<PRE>
            Wednesday, March 26     1:00-4:00, CMC #102
            Friday,    March 28     1:00-4:00, CMC #102
</PRE>
<DD>All training sessions will be held in the Center for Mathematics and Computing (CMC) room #102.
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>PURPOSE:</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    To use the World Wide Web (WWW) to greater potential, you need to stop
    &quot;surfing&quot; and start searching.  The purpose of this workshop is to
    give you a fundamental understanding of what tools are available for
    searching the WWW as well as how you can use these tools to retrieve
    information relevant to your needs.
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>WHO SHOULD ATTEND:</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    Faculty and staff who want to learn how to retrieve information relevant to
    their teaching, research, and professional work needs should consider
    attending this workshop. Attendees must have previous WWW experience.
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>WHAT YOU WILL LEARN:</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    You will receive a basic exposure to WWW search tools, including:
    <UL>
    <LI>how they function
    <LI>how to use them effectively
    <LI>what are their strengths and weaknesses
    </UL>
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>AFTER COMPLETING THIS WORKSHOP, YOU SHOULD BE ABLE TO:</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    <UL>
    <LI>retrieve information on the WWW more efficiently and effectively
    <LI>understand which WWW search tool(s) to use in filling a particular
        information need
    <LI>identify print and electronic resources for learning more about
        WWW search tools
    </UL>
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>TIME BUDGET:</STRONG> (subject to modification)
<DD><P>
    <DL>
    <DT>Hour One - Directories
    <DD>comparisons and examples of Argus Clearinghouse, Magellan, Yahoo, etc.
    <DT>Hour Two - Search Engines
    <DD>comparisons and examples of Alta Vista, Excite, InfoSeek, etc.
    <DT>Hour Three - Advanced
    <DD>advanced searching concepts and techniques (45 min.)<BR>
        wrap up; how to learn more (15 min.)
    </DL>
    </P>
    
<DT><STRONG>HOW TO REGISTER FOR A WORKSHOP(S):</STRONG>
<DD><P>
    <UL>
    <LI>notify Terry Metz
        <UL>
        <LI>in person at his office: Library 466
        <LI>by phone: (507) 646-4530
        <LI>by fax: (507) 646-4087
        <LI>by e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:temetz@carleton.edu">temetz@carleton.edu</A>
        </UL>
    </UL>
    </P>
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
