<HEAD>
<TITLE>LEARNING HOW TO COMPOSE WEB PAGES</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H1>Introduction to HTML:  Fundamentals of Web Page Authoring</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3>Presenter:  Presentor:  Terry Metz</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>DATES AND TIMES:</STRONG>
    <P>
    <PRE>
            Monday,    February 24      1:00-4:00 (part #1)
            Monday,    March 3          1:00-4:00 (part #2)
    </PRE>
<DD>All training sessions will be held in the Center for Mathematics and Computing (CMC) room #102.
    <BR>
    <BR>
<DT><STRONG>PURPOSE:</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>
Few technologies have had as rapid and as wide an impact on information
services as the World Wide Web (WWW).  This is particularly true for
libraries.
<P>
The purpose of this workshop is to give you hands-on experience creating 
Hypertext Markup Language (HTML) documents and navigation structures for
use on the WWW.
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>WHO SHOULD ATTEND:</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>
Any library staff member who wants to learn how to author Web pages.  
Attendees must have previous experience navigating the World Wide Web.
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>WHAT YOU WILL LEARN:</STRONG>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>a conceptual understanding of HTML
<P>
<LI>the basics of using HTML for composing WWW documents, including:
<UL>
        <LI>fundamental HTML techniques
        <LI>WWW page stylistic principles and considerations
        <LI>awareness of HTML development tools
</UL>
</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>AFTER COMPLETING THIS WORKSHOP, YOU SHOULD BE ABLE TO:</STRONG>
<P>
<UL>

        <LI>create HTML documents
        <LI>employ principles of good WWW page design
        <LI>plan a Web site for your department or service
        <LI>identify print and electronic resources for learning more about HTML,
            WWW page design, and WWW site development
</UL>
</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>TIME BUDGET:</STRONG> (to be determined)
<P>
<DD>Hour One - Conceptual
<UL>
        <LI>
        <LI>
        <LI>
</UL>
<P>
<DD>Hour Two - 
<UL>
        <LI>
        <LI>
        <LI>            
</UL>
<P>
<DD>Hour Three - 
<UL>
        <LI>
        <LI>
        <LI>
</UL>
<P>
<DD>Hour Four - 
<UL>
        <LI>
        <LI>
        <LI>
</UL>
<P>
<DD>Hour Five - 
<UL>
        <LI>
        <LI>
        <LI>
</UL>
<P>
<DD>Hour Six - 
<UL>
        <LI>
        <LI>
        <LI>
</UL>
</DL>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>
