<HEAD>
<TITLE>MACINTOSH COMPUTING: INTERNET APPLICATIONS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H1>Macintosh Computing: Internet Applications</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3>Presentors:  Michael Current, Mark Heiman, and Terry Metz</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>DATES AND TIMES:</STRONG>
    <P>
    <PRE>
            No sessions currently scheduled.
    </PRE>
<DD>All training sessions will be held in the Center for Mathematics and Computing (CMC) room #102.
    <BR>
    <BR>
<DT><STRONG>PURPOSE:</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>Eudora is Macintosh &quot;client&quot; software for e-mail.
    NCSA Telnet is Macintosh &quot;client&quot; software for telnet.
    And Netscape and Internet Voyager are Macintosh software clients for the World Wide Web.
<P>
The purpose of this workshop is to give you hands-on experience and tips for using these Macintosh
software packages effectively and efficiently.
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>WHO SHOULD ATTEND:</STRONG>
<P>
<DD>Anyone who wants to improve their use Eudora, NCSA telnet, and Netscape/Internet Voyager software.  Attendees should
have fundamental knowledge of the Macintosh operating system; &quot;point-and-click&quot; skills, and previous
experience using e-mail, telnet, and the World Wide Web.
<BR>
<BR>
<DT><STRONG>TIME BUDGET:</STRONG> (subject to revision)
<P>
<DD>Hour One: (9:00-10:00) - Eudora Light (e-mail)
<UL>
        <LI>configuring
        <LI>mailboxes
        <LI>nicknames
</UL>
<P>
<DD>Hour Two: (10:00-11:00) - NCSA Telnet (telnet)
<UL>
        <LI>configuring
        <LI>aliases
</UL>
<P>
<DD>Hour Three: (11:00-noon) - Netscape & Internet Explorer (World Wide Web)
<UL>
        <LI>configuring
        <LI>managing bookmarks
</UL>
</DL>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<HR>
