<head>
<title>ILS Policy Summary</title>
<link rev="made" href="mailto:mcurrent@carleton.edu"> 
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Expires" CONTENT="01 Sep 1997">
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
</head>

<body>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Carleton College Library</h3>
<h2 align=center>INTERLIBRARY SERVICES</h2>

<h3 align=center>PURPOSE OF ILS</h3>
<p>
InterLibrary Services may be used to obtain library materials for study and research which are not available at Carleton or St. Olaf, but are available from other North American libraries willing to lend.

<h3 align=center>LOCATION OF ILS</h3>
<p>
InterLibrary Services information is available at both the Information Desk and the Reference Desk in the Library.
<p>
The ILS office is located in Room 448, Gould Library, just south of the east stairwell on the fourth floor.  The office is generally staffed from 8 to 5, Monday through Friday.  Telephone: x4257.

<h3 align=center>WHO MAY USE ILS</h3>
<p>
InterLibrary Services is available to current Carleton students, faculty and staff, and to retired Carleton faculty and staff living in Northfield.  A valid Library barcode number is also required.

<h3 align=center>MATERIALS AVAILABLE</h3>
<p>
Books, theses, music and some materials reproduced in microform, such as newspapers, can be borrowed.
<p>
Photocopies from non-circulating materials, such as journals, can be requested in accordance with the copyright law.
<p>
Items missing from the Library (marked "missing" on the Muse), and items sent temporarily to the bindery (also indicated on the Muse) can also be requested.

<h3 align=center>MATERIALS NOT AVAILABLE</h3>
<p>
The following types of materials cannot normally be obtained through ILS:
<ul>
<li>	books owned by the Carleton or St. Olaf libraries and temporarily in use
<li>	periodical volumes
<li>	recent, unmicrofilmed newspapers
<li>	materials for class, reserve, or group use
<li>	bulky or fragile items
<li>	reference books
<li>	rare or valuable material such as manuscripts
</ul>
<h3 align=center>COST</h3>
<p>

All requests are searched through the MINITEX Library Information Network and the Oberlin Group of libraries.  These are groups of libraries that do not charge us for interlibrary access to their materials.  Most filled requests are filled within MINITEX and the Oberlin Group.
<p>
To pursue requests beyond MINITEX and the Oberlin Group, you must agree in advance to pay whatever cost may be incurred.  Exact costs are not determined in advance, but charges of $10 or $15 are typical.


<h3 align=center>HOW ILS WORKS</h3>
<p>
All requests must be submitted either on request forms supplied by the Library, or electronically using certain online tools (i.e., the link from the FirstSearch service).
<p>
Students submitting requests on the paper forms must hand them in person to Information or Reference Desk staff for a quick review.
<p>
Faculty/Staff may drop off completed request forms at the ILS office, or they may send them via campus mail to "InterLibrary Services."
<p>
For speedy service, accurate and complete bibliographic citations should be supplied, along with the source of the citation.  Accurate personal information must be provided as well.  The online catalogs of Carleton (Muse) and St. Olaf (PALS) must be checked first to be sure the material is not already owned locally.
<h3 align=center>TIME</h3>
<p>
Plan ahead when requesting materials.  The time taken for ILS materials to arrive depends upon the seasonal workload in the ILS office, the difficulty of locating a library willing to lend the material, and the time taken for the material to travel from there to here.  7-10 days is a good average time to plan for.

<h3 align=center>NOTIFICATION</h3>
<p>
When loans arrive you are notified via campus mail that you may pick them up at the Library's circulation desk.
<p>
Photocopies are sent to you via campus mail.  They are yours to keep.

<h3 align=center>LOAN PERIOD</h3>
<p>
The loan period is determined by the lending library.
<p>
Loans obtained through MINITEX are not renewable.
<p>
Loans obtained outside MINITEX may occasionally be renewed.  Bring the book to the ILS office before the due date for details.

<h3 align=center>RESTRICTIONS</h3>
<p>
Lending libraries determine any conditions regarding the use of their materials.  Loans designated for "In Library Use Only" must be kept at the circulation desk when you are not in the Library using them.

<h3 align=center>RETURNING MATERIALS</h3>
<p>
All materials borrowed through ILS must be returned to the Library's circulation desk by the due date.  Please leave the book sleeve attached.
<p>
Late return, lost, or the poor care of materials jeopardizes the ability of the Library to borrow from other libraries in the future.

<HR>
