<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML: Introduction - Basic HTML Concepts
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>Introduction:  Basic HTML Concepts</H1></CENTER>

Note: This introduction and the associated exerecises assume knowledge of the fundamental features of Netscape 
or comparable World Wide Web (Web) browsing software.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
HTML stands for <STRONG>hypertext markup language</STRONG>, and is used to create hypermedia documents 
that can be viewed by World Wide Web browsers.
<P>
HTML describes a series of <STRONG>tags</STRONG> that tell browsers how to format, interpret, and 
display information in hypertext documents. By placing HTML tags around appropriate portions of text, 
you can create headlines, paragraphs, bold text, etc., as well as hypertext links to other information. 
Most (but not all) HTML tags are associated with a pair of tags; a <STRONG>starting tag</STRONG> and an 
<STRONG>ending tag</STRONG>. Both pair of tags are surrounded by "less-than" and "greater-than" brackets.  
However, the ending tag adds a forward slash (<KBD><STRONG>/</STRONG></KBD>) in front of the tag, e.g., 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;TAG&gt;</STRONG></KBD> and <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/TAG>&gt;</STRONG></KBD>.
<P>
The basic unit of HTML is called an <STRONG>element</STRONG>; the element <STRONG>name</STRONG> appears 
inside the tag brackets, and specifies the meaning associated with a block of text, e.g, 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;TITLE&gt;...&lt;/TITLE&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags containing the <STRONG>title</STRONG> element.  
There are rules about where elements can and cannot appear within an HTML document.
<P>
A specially defined property of an HTML element is called an <STRONG>attribute</STRONG>, e.g., 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;IMG SRC="image.gif"&gt;</STRONG></KBD> means that the element <STRONG><KBD>IMG</KBD></STRONG> 
has an attribute <STRONG><KBD>SRC</KBD></STRONG>, which is assigned the value 
<STRONG><KBD>"image.gif"</KBD></STRONG>.
<P>
While HTML is not case sensitive, many authors prefer to write HTML tags in capital letters to make 
them easier to see when editing a document. In this the associated exercises, all tags will appear in capital 
letters.
<P>
Just as text filenames often end in <KBD><STRONG>.txt</STRONG></KBD>, HTML filenames often end in 
<KBD><STRONG>.html</STRONG></KBD> or <KBD><STRONG>.htm</STRONG></KBD> (in the PC world). Both are 
accepted as identifiers for HTML documents. Filenames are generally in lower case letters, and contain 
no special characters or spaces. For example, the filename of the page you're currently reading is 
<KBD><STRONG>basic.html</STRONG></KBD>.
<P>

You don't need to have your documents on a World Wide Web (WWW) server to begin experimenting with HTML. 
In Netscape, you can use the <STRONG>Open File</STRONG> command under the <STRONG>File</STRONG> menu to 
locate and open a hypertext file. With this command, you can create files in any text editor (such as
a word processor) that can save its documents as ASCII text, and then open the files with your Web browser. 
Most HTML features will work without a Web server installed on your personal computer.
<P>
<UL>To open a file in Netscape:
<P>
	<LI>Select the <STRONG>Open File</STRONG> command under the <STRONG>File</STRONG> menu.
    <LI>Locate and select the document you wish to open.
    <LI>Click the <STRONG>Open</STRONG> button, and Netscape will open the file.
</UL>
<P>
<UL>After making changes in your HTML code, to view the changes in Netscape:
<P>
	<LI>Save your file in the text editor.
	<LI>Switch to the Netscape application.
	<LI>Click the <STRONG>Reload</STRONG> button or choose the <STRONG>Reload</STRONG> 
	    command from the <STRONG>View</STRONG> menu.
</UL>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<P>
<A HREF="exerciseabout.html">Go on to the Exercises</A> 
<p>
