<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML: Exercise 1 - Five Basic Elements
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>Exercise 1:  Five Basic Elements</H1></CENTER>

HTML uses formatting codes called "tags" to mark text with formatting instructions.  The tags
are identified by angle brackets around some text.  HTML tags are NOT case sensitive; 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;HTML&gt;</STRONG></KBD> will work the same way as <KBD><STRONG>&lt;html&gt;</STRONG></KBD>.  
(Some HTML authors prefer to use uppercase within HTML tags because it's easier to locate tags when scanning 
the document.)
<P>
This exercise includes use of <A HREF="#format">basic HTML document format</A>, <A HREF="#head">headers</A>, 
<A HREF="#title">title</A>,and <A HREF="#para">paragraphs</A> elements.
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<P>
It only takes four elements to create a basic HTML document. It'll be a very boring document--without the images 
and links that people have come to associate with the Web--but these four elements will provide a foundation in 
HTML on which to build.
<P>
Note that most (but not all) HTML tags are paired, e.g. <KBD><STRONG>&lt;TITLE&gt;</STRONG></KBD> goes in front 
of your title and <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/TITLE&gt;</STRONG></KBD> goes behind it.
<P>
<A NAME="format"><H3>Creating a Basic HTML Document Format:</H3></A>
<KBD><STRONG>
<DD>&lt;HTML&gt;<BR>
<DD>&lt;HEAD&gt;<BR>
<DD>&lt;TITLE&gt;<BR>
<DD>&lt;/TITLE&gt;<BR>
<DD>&lt;/HEAD&gt;<BR>
<DD>&lt;BODY&gt;<BR>
<BR><BR><BR>
<DD>&lt;/BODY&gt;<BR>
<DD>&lt;/HTML&gt;
</STRONG></KBD>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG><KBD>&lt;HTML&gt;...&lt;/HTML&gt;</KBD> - HTML document identifier</STRONG>
<DD>The <KBD><STRONG>&lt;HTML&gt;</STRONG></KBD> and <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/HTML&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags 
identify the beginning and end of an HTML document. While Netscape and many other browsers do not 
require the HTML tag, on some browsers your document may not load correctly if the 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;HTML&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag is absent.
<P>
<DT><STRONG><KBD>&lt;HEAD&gt;...&lt;/HEAD&gt;</KBD> - document header</STRONG>
<DD>Web browsers use the information between the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;HEAD&gt;</STRONG></KBD> and 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;/HEAD&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags to gather information about the document, such 
as its author, its title, and to what resources the document should be linked. For the scope of 
these exercises, the only tag used between the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;HEAD&gt;</STRONG></KBD> 
and <KBD><STRONG>>&lt;/HEAD&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags is the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;TITLE&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag. 
<P>
<DT><STRONG><KBD>&lt;TITLE&gt;...&lt;/TITLE&gt;</KBD> - document title</STRONG>
<DD>The <KBD><STRONG>&lt;TITLE&gt;</STRONG></KBD> element should only appear once in the head of an HTML document 
(between the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;HEAD&gt;</STRONG></KBD> and <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/HEAD&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags).  
The text that appears between the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;TITLE&gt;</STRONG></KBD> and <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/TITLE&gt;</STRONG></KBD> 
tags is used as the title of the document, and is displayed by most Web browsers in the browser window's title bar.
<P>
<DT><STRONG><KBD>&lt;BODY&gt;...&lt;/BODY&gt;</KBD> - document body</STRONG>
<DD>This is where all the action happens in an HTML document. With the exception of the above HTML elements, 
nearly every other tag must appear between the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;BODY&gt;</STRONG></KBD> and 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;/BODY&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags.
</DL>
<P>
<A HREF="#top">Return to Top</A>
<HR>
<A NAME="head"><H3>Creating HTML Headers:</H3></A>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG><KBD>&lt;Hx&gt;</KBD>...<KBD>&lt;/Hx&gt;</KBD> - heading</STRONG>
<DD>Headings are used to identify sections of a document. HTML provides six levels of headings, 
numbered I through 6. For the largest heading, you would use <KBD><STRONG>&lt;H1&gt;</STRONG></KBD> and 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;/H1&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags. For the smallest, you would use 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;H6&gt;</STRONG></KBD> and <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/H6&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags.
<P>
Note that most browsers will assume that white space should appear before and after a heading element, 
so you don't generally need to put a <A HREF="#para"><KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD></A> or 
<A HREF="exercise8.html#br"><KBD><STRONG>&lt;BR&gt;</STRONG></KBD></A> before or after a heading.
<P>
HTML headers work like this:
</DL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><KBD><STRONG>&lt;H1&gt;...&lt;/H1&gt;</STRONG></KBD> produces <CENTER><H1>A heading like this</H1></CENTER>
<LI><KBD><STRONG>&lt;H2&gt;...&lt;/H2&gt;</STRONG></KBD> produces <CENTER><H2>A heading like this</H2></CENTER>
<LI><KBD><STRONG>&lt;H3&gt;...&lt;/H3&gt;</STRONG></KBD> produces <CENTER><H3>A heading like this</H3></CENTER>
<LI><KBD><STRONG>&lt;H4&gt;...&lt;/H4&gt;</STRONG></KBD> produces <CENTER><H4>A heading like this</H4></CENTER>
<LI><KBD><STRONG>&lt;H5&gt;...&lt;/H5&gt;</STRONG></KBD> produces <CENTER><H5>A heading like this</H5></CENTER>
<LI><KBD><STRONG>&lt;H6&gt;...&lt;/H6&gt;</STRONG></KBD> produces <CENTER><H6>A heading like this</H6></CENTER>
</UL>
<A HREF="#top">Return to Top</A>
<HR>
<A NAME="para"><H3>Paragraph Tags</H3></A>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG><KBD>&lt;P&gt;...&lt;/P&gt;</KBD> - paragraph</STRONG>
<DD>In general,a Web browser starts a new paragraph only when it encounters a <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> 
tag.  Without <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags, the text in your HTML document will appear as one large, 
continuous paragraph.
<P>
Alas, life is always more complex that it seems, and this is the case with paragraphs in HTML.  Various 
<LINK>versions of HTML have defined paragraphs differently.  The only thing these versions agree on is that you 
indicate a plain text paragraph (not necessarily it's beginning or ending) by using the 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag.
<P>
Early versions of HTML specified the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> as a <STRONG>one-sided</STRONG> tag.  
There was no corresponding <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/P&gt;</STRONG></KBD>, and <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> 
tag was used to indicate the <STRONG>end</STRONG> of a paragraph (a paragraph break), not the beginning.  
So paragraphs in the early versions of HTML looked like this:
<P>
<PRE>
	The Civil War was the first conflict that was dominated by firearms.  
	Muskets employed in earlier wars were one-shot smoothbores, which were 
	inaccurate and extremely limited in range.
	&lt;P&gt;
	Reloading was a difficulty job; and the primitive flintlocks would not 
	work when wet, and only 80 percent of the time under ideal conditions.
	&lt;P&gt;
	Percussion caps for ignition soon replaced the unreliable flintlocks, 
	and experients with rifled muskets were initiated.  A revolution in 
	infantry warfare was sparked by Frenchman, Claude E. Minie, who in 1849 
	designed a bullet (not a "ball" as most Civil War participants referred 
	to it) that was smaller then the diameter of the gun barrel and could be 
	inserted easily.
	&lt;P&gt;
	When fired, the base of the projectile expanded to fit the rifling, 
	giving the bullet a stabilizing spin for greater accuracy and range.
	&lt;P&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
Most browsers that were created early on in the history of the Web--and many browsers--still assume that paragraphs
will be formatted this way.  When come across a <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag, they start a new line an 
add some extra vertical space between the line they just ended and the one that they just began.
<P>
In more recent versions of HTML, the paragraph tag has been revised.  In these versions, the paragraph tags are
<STRONG>two-side</STRONG> (<KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;...&lt;/P&gt;</STRONG></KBD>), but <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> 
indicates the <STRONG>beginning</STRONG> of the paragraph.  Also, the closing tag (<KBD><STRONG>&lt;/P&gt;</STRONG></KBD>) 
is optional.  So the "minie ball" story would look like this in the newer versions of HTML:
<P>
<PRE>
	&lt;P&gt;
	The Civil War was the first conflict that was dominated by firearms.  
	Muskets employed in earlier wars were one-shot smoothbores, which were 
	inaccurate and extremely limited in range.
	&lt;/P&gt;
	&lt;P&gt;
	Reloading was a difficulty job; and the primitive flintlocks would not 
	work when wet, and only 80 percent of the time under ideal conditions.
	&lt;/P&gt;
	&lt;P&gt;
	Percussion caps for ignition soon replaced the unreliable flintlocks, 
	and experients with rifled muskets were initiated.  A revolution in 
	infantry warfare was sparked by Frenchman, Claude E. Minie, who in 1849 
	designed a bullet (not a "ball" as most Civil War participants referred 
	to it) that was smaller then the diameter of the gun barrel and could be 
	inserted easily.
	&lt;/P&gt;
	&lt;P&gt;
	When fired, the base of the projectile expanded to fit the rifling, 
	giving the bullet a stabilizing spin for greater accuracy and range.
	&lt;P&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
It's probably a good idea to get into the habit of using <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> at the start of 
a paragraph because this will become important in subsequent versions of HTML--where you can define the alignment 
and other featuresof each paragraph.  Currently browsers will ingore this form of paragraphs just fine.
<P>
However, note that because many browsers still expect <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> to indicate the 
<STRONG>end</STRONG> of a paragraph, if you use it at the beginning you may end up with extra space in between 
the first paragraph and the element before it.  If this bothers you, you can do the following:
<P>
<UL>
	<LI>Go back to the old style of defining paragraphs.
	<LI>Use <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> as a paragraph separator, rather than indicating the beginning or
	    end of a paragraph.
	<LI>Leave off the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> in each set of paragraphs. 
</UL>
<P>
Some people like to use <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags to spread out the text on a page.  But beware.  
Some browsers may collapse multiple <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags into one, erasing all your careful 
formatting.
</DL>
<P>
<A HREF="#top">Return to Top</A>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<CENTER>Write HTML required to produce:</CENTER>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<H1>My First HTML Document</H1>
I'm composing my very first HTML document.
<P>
Soon I'll be creating a stop on the Information Superhighway!
<p>
<HR size=3>
