<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML: Exercise 2 - Unordered Lists
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>Exercise 2 - Unordered Lists</H1></CENTER>
This exercise includes use of <A HREF="exercise1.html#head">headers</A> and an <A HREF="#ul">unordered list</A>.<p>
<HR size=3>
<p>
<H3><A NAME="ul">Creating Unordered Lists:</A></H3>

HTML provides a variety of list formats to use in your HTML documents. Most of the lists use the following format:
<P>
<KBD>
&lt;<STRONG>LIST_TYPE</STRONG>&gt;<BR>
&lt;LI&gt;Item 1<BR>
&lt;LI&gt;Item 2<BR>
&lt;LI&gt;Item 3<BR>
&lt;<STRONG>/LIST_TYPE</STRONG>&gt;
</KBD>
<P>
Unordered are also referred to as "bulleted" lists.  To make an unordered list:
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Start with a <KBD><STRONG>&lt;UL&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag.
<LI>For each item on your list, enter an <KBD><STRONG>&lt;LI&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag followed by the item. 
    (No closing tag is needed.)
<LI>End with a closing tag: <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/UL&gt;</STRONG></KBD>.
</OL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>List items can contain more than one paragraph.
<LI>In later versions of HTML, you'll be able to specify the bullet type by adding the attribute 
    <KBD><STRONG>TYPE=DISC</STRONG></KBD>, <KBD><STRONG>TYPE=CIRCLE</STRONG></KBD>, or
    <KBD><STRONG>TYPE=SQUARE</STRONG></KBD> within the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;UL&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag.
</UL>
<P>
If you put a heading <EM>within</EM> an unordered list, it
will line up with the other list items.  By ending the unnumbered list and starting 
a new one below, a subsequent heading returns to the left margin.
<P>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<CENTER>Write HTML required to produce:</CENTER>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<p>
<H1>Three Colors are Found on the U.S. Flag</H1>
<UL>
<LI>red
<LI>white
<LI>blue
</UL>
<H2>The First Family Includes</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Bill
<LI>Hillary
<LI>Chelsea
<LI>Socks
</UL>
<P>
<HT SIZE=3>
<P>
