<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML: Exercise 3 - Ordered Lists
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>Exercise 3 - Ordered Lists</H1></CENTER>
This exercise includes use of a <A HREF="Exercise1.html#head">header</A> and a <A HREF="#ol">ordered list</A>.
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<H3><A NAME="ol">Creating Ordered Lists:</A></H3>
Ordered lists are used for information that needs to be presented with a preceding numeral.
To make an ordered list:
<OL>
<LI>Start with an <KBD><STRONG>&lt;OL&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag.
<LI>For each item on your list, enter an <KBD><STRONG>&lt;LI&gt;</KBD></STRONG> tag followed by the item. 
    (No closing tag is needed.)
<LI> End with a closing tag: <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/OL&gt;</STRONG></KBD>
</OL>
<UL>
<LI>With this type of list, you can <STRONG>reorder</STRONG> the items in your list without having to
    <STRONG>renumber</STRONG> them all.
<LI>In later versions of HTML, you'll be able to specify whether you want your list items marked with:
<UL>
<LI>capital letters <KBD><STRONG>&lt;TYPE=A&gt;</KBD></STRONG>
<LI>small letters <KBD><STRONG>&lt;TYPE=a&gt;</KBD></STRONG>
<LI>large Roman numerals <KBD><STRONG>&lt;TYPE=I&gt;</KBD></STRONG>
<LI>small Roman numerals <KBD><STRONG>&lt;TYPE=i&gt;</KBD></STRONG>
<LI>or arabic numerals <KBD><STRONG>&lt;TYPE=1&gt;</KBD></STRONG>
</UL>
<P>
These <KBD><STRONG>TYPE</KBD></STRONG> attributes are used within the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;OL&gt;</KBD></STRONG> tag.
<P>
<LI>In later versions, you'll be able to use a <KBD><STRONG>VALUE=x</STRONG></KBD> attribute in the 
    <KBD><STRONG>&lt;LI&gt;</KBD></STRONG> tag to change the count for that list item and all subsequent items.
<p></UL>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<CENTER>Write HTML required to produce:</CENTER>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<H1>Five State Capitals Which Begin with the Letter "A" - in Alphabetical Order</H1>
<OL>
<LI>Albany
<Li>Annapolis
<LI>Atlanta
<LI>Augusta
<LI>Austin
</OL>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<P>
