<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML: Exercise 7 - Logical and Physical Styles
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>Exercise 7 - Logical and Physical Styles</H1></CENTER>
<p>
This exercise includes examples of <A HREF="#log">logical</A> and <A HREF="#phys">physical</A> styles.  
(Note: there'll be more than one "right answer" to this exercise because different tags result in
identical output.)
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<P>HTML provides definitions for bold (<KBD><STRONG>&lt;B&gt;...&lt;/B&gt;</STRONG></KBD>) and 
italic (<KBD><STRONG>&lt;I&gt;...&lt;/I</STRONG></KBD>) text, but there is no guarantee 
that a browser will be able to display bold or italic text.  These formatting tags that are dependent on the 
browser's display capabilities are called <STRONG>physical styles</STRONG>.

For this reason, HTML provides emphasis (<KBD><STRONG>&lt;EM&gt;...&lt;/EM&gt;</STRONG></KBD>) and strong 
(<KBD><STRONG>&lt;STRONG&gt;...&lt;/STRONG&gt;</STRONG></KBD>) tags that are <STRONG>logical styles</STRONG>. These tags 
should be used instead of physical tags. If the browser has access to italics and bold, it will usually 
display the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;EM&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag as italic and the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;STRONG&gt;</STRONG></KBD> 
tag as bold. But if bold and italics are unavailable, the browser will provide another representation for these tags.

<P>
<H3><A NAME="log">Creating Logical Styles:</A></H3>
Logical styles tag text according to its <STRONG>meaning</STRONG>; these are all <STRONG>paired</STRONG> tags.  
Logical styles include:
<UL>
<DL>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;DFN&gt;...&lt;/DFN&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>Definition.  Typically displayed like <DFN>this</DFN>.<P>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;EM&gt;...&lt;/EM&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>Emphasize.  Typically displayed like <EM>this</EM>.<P>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;STRONG&gt;...&lt;/STRONG&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>Strong.  Typically displayed like <STRONG>this</STRONG>.<P>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;CITE&gt;...&lt;/CITE&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>Citation.  Typically displayed like <CITE>this</CITE>.<P>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;CODE&gt;...&lt;/CODE&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>Computer code.  Typically displayed like <CODE>this</CODE>.<P>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;KBD&gt;...&lt;/KBD&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>User keyboard entry.  Typically displayed like <KBD>this</KBD>.<P>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;SAMP&gt;...&lt;/SAMP&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>Computer status message.  Typically displayed like <SAMP>this</SAMP>.<P>
</DL>
</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<H3><A NAME="phys">Creating Physical Styles:</A></H3>
Physical styles specify how text is to <STRONG>appear</STRONG>; as with logical styles,
physical styles are also <STRONG>paired</STRONG> tags.
<UL>
<DL>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;B&gt;...&lt;/B&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>Bold text.<P>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;I&gt;...&lt;/I&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>Italic text.<P>
<DT><KBD><STRONG>&lt;TT&gt;...&lt;/TT&gt;</STRONG></KBD> <BR><P><DD>Typewriter text.<P>
</DL>
</UL>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<CENTER>Write HTML required to produce:</CENTER>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
The use of styles in HTML documents is important.  How else will
readers of your documents be able to tell when you're <b>SHOUTING</b>?<p>
In more refined circles (where people <i>whisper</i>) styles enable
one to look academically-inclined, like this:<p>
<blockquote>
In her work, <cite>HTML for Snobs</cite>, Professor Karen Mateer points
out the <em>importance</em> of using <strong>logical</strong>, rather than
<strong>physical</strong> styles. <dfn>Logical</dfn> styles are, as their name implies,
<em>stylish</em>, whereas <dfn>physical</dfn> styles are a matter of <kbd>brute force and
ignorance</kbd>.
</blockquote><p>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<A HREF="exercise1.html">Go to Exercise 1,</A> 
<A HREF="exercise2.html">2,</A>
<A HREF="exercise3.html">3,</A>
<A HREF="exercise4.html">4,</A>
<A HREF="exercise5.html">5,</A>
<A HREF="exercise6.html">6,</A>
<A HREF="exercise7.html">7,</A>
<A HREF="exercise8.html">8,</A>
<A HREF="exercise9.html">9,</A>
<A HREF="exercise10.html">10,</A>
<A HREF="exercise11.html">11</A><p>
<A HREF="answer7.html">Go to Answers for Exercise 7</A>
