<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML: Exercise 8 - Horizontal Rules, Line Breaks, Addresses, and Character Entities
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>Exercise 8 - Horizontal Rules, Line Breaks, Addresses, and Character Entities</H1></CENTER>
<p>
This exercise uses tags from Exercises 1 through 7 and adds use of 
<A HREF="#hr">horizontal rules</A>, <A HREF="#br">line breaks</A>, <A HREF="#add">addresses</A>, and 
<A HREF="#ch">character entities</A>.
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="hr">Creating Horizontal Rules:</A></H3>

The horizontal rule tag puts a line across the display, adjusted to the width of the browser window.
This tag is useful for visually dividing sections of text on a page.
<P>
<UL>
<LI>the tag is:  <KBD><STRONG>&lt;HR&gt;</STRONG></KBD>.  This is <b>not</b> a paired tag.
<LI><KBD><STRONG>&lt;HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=x%&gt;</STRONG></KBD> creates a centered line X percent of the 
window width.  You can also specify left or right alignment.
<LI><KBD><STRONG>&lt;HR size=X&gt;</STRONG></KBD>, where <KBD><STRONG>"X"</STRONG></KBD> is a 
number makes a thicker line.
</UL>

<H3><A NAME="br">Creating Line Breaks:</A></H3>
The <KBD><STRONG>&lt;P&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag adds a blank line to indicate the beginning of a paragraph.  
To force a line break with no extra space, use the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;BR&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag.  The 
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;BR&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag instructs the browser to begin the text on the next line. 
Consider the following Emilv Dickinson poem:
<P>
<PRE>
A word is dead&lt;BR&gt;
When it is said,&lt;BR&gt;
Some say.&lt;BR&gt;
I say it just&lt;BR&gt;
Begins to live&lt;BR&gt;
That day.
&lt;P&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
A word is dead<BR>
When it is said,<BR>
Some say.<BR>
I say it just<BR>
Begins to live<BR>
That day.
<P>


Since the poem should be displayed as a single stanza, the <KBD><STRONG>&lt;BR&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tag 
lets us avoid separating the lines.


<H3><A NAME="add">Creating Addresses:</A></H3>
<KBD><STRONG>&lt;ADDRESS&gt;</STRONG></KBD> and <KBD><STRONG>&lt;/ADDRESS&gt;</STRONG></KBD> tags can be used 
surrounding e-mail addresses.  Browsers generally format the address in italics.

<H3><A NAME="ch">Creating Characters Entities:</A></H3>
Some characters, such as <KBD><STRONG>&lt;</STRONG></KBD>, <KBD><STRONG>&gt;</STRONG></KBD>, 
<KBD><STRONG>&amp;</STRONG></KBD>, and <KBD><STRONG>&quot;</STRONG></KBD> have special meaning in HTML.  
To display them, you need to use a feature known as HTML <STRONG>character entities</STRONG>.
Each character is assigned an abbreviation, such as <KBD><STRONG>amp</STRONG></KBD> for the ampersand 
(<KBD><STRONG>&amp;</STRONG></KBD>).  To place the character in an HTML document, you place an ampersand 
(<KBD><STRONG>&amp;</STRONG></KBD>) before the abbreviation and a semicolon (<KBD><STRONG>;</STRONG></KBD>) 
after the abbreviation. These combinations are referred to as character entities 
collectively.
<P>
Note:  Most browsers interpret the quotation mark (<KBD><STRONG>&quot;</STRONG></KBD>) and thus do not require the 
<KBD><STRONG>&quot;</STRONG></KBD> entity. 
<P>
HTML also provides multinational character entities, such as <KBD><STRONG>&amp;uuml;</STRONG></KBD> for 
<STRONG>&uuml;</STRONG>, <KBD><STRONG>&amp;Egrave;</STRONG></KBD> for <STRONG>&Egrave;</STRONG>, etc. 
Note that unlike the rest of HTML, character entity names <STRONG>are case sensitive</STRONG>. 
A complete listing of HTML character entities is available at:
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="http://www.sandia.gov/sci_compute/symbols.html">http://www.sandia.gov/sci_compute/symbols.html</A></CENTER>
<P>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<CENTER>Write HTML required to produce:</CENTER>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
Wow, in seven short exercises, I've learned how to make an effective
page of text on the World Wide Web.  I know how to:<p>
<ol>
<li>Use basic HTML format.
<ul>
<li>&lt;HTML&gt; and &lt;/HTML&gt;
<li>&lt;HEAD&gt; and &lt;/HEAD&gt;
<li>&lt;TITLE&gt; and &lt;/TITLE&gt;
</ul><p>
<li>Make several kinds of lists.
<ul>
<li>unnumbered
<li>numbered (ordered)
<li>definition
<li>nested
</ul><p>
<li>Use different levels of headings, from
<ul>
<li><h1>Large</h1>
<li><h6>to small</h6>
</ul><p>
<li>Include extended quotations (like this one):
<blockquote>The Americans have need of the telephone, but we do not.<BR>
We have plenty of messenger boys.<BR>
--<i>Sir William Preece, chief engineer of the British Post Office, in 1876.</i>
</blockquote>
<p>
<li>Use logical and physical styles to make text appear:
<ul>
<li><b>bold</b>
<li><i>italic</i>
<li><tt>fixed-width font</tt>
</ul><p>              
<li>Use paragraph tags, special characters, and horizontal rules.
</ol>
<p>In addition to all <b>that</b>, you've learned several definitions.  You know that:<p>
<dl>
<dt>The <i>Internet</i>
<dd>is a collection of connected networks all over the world.
<dt>The <i>World Wide Web</i>
<dd>was started by CERN (the European Laboratory for Particle Physics) and seeks to build 
a distributed hypermedia system.
<dt><i>HTML</i>
<dd>stands for Hypertext Markup Language and is a tool for creating multi-layered and 
linked documents published on the Web.<p>
</dl>
<P>
Now maybe it's time to send e-mail to your boss at <ADDRESS>your_boss@work.com</ADDRESS>
and tell him or her how smart you are!?

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH="12%">
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH="30%">
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH="70%">
<HR size=3>
<P>
