<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML: Exercise 9 - Image Links
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>Exercise 9 - Image Links</H1></CENTER>
<p>
This exercise gives you practice using <A HREF="#url">URLs</A> in <A HREF="#image">image tags</A><p>
<i>Remember to add text for those without graphic interfaces!</i><p>
<P>
<HR size=3>
<H4><A NAME="url">URLs</A></H4>
URL is an acronym for Uniform Resource Locator.  URLs specify the location of files on servers.  
An URL includes three things:<OL>
<LI> the type of resource being accessed (e.g., http, gopher, ftp)
<LI> the address of the server
<LI> the location of the file
</OL><br>
You can learn more about URLs from <A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html">http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html.</A>
<p>
<H4><A NAME="image">In-line Image Tags</A></H4>
To include an image next to the text of your document (called "in-line images"), you provide a link to
any file in X-bitmap (XMB) or GIF (color) format.<p>
To include an in-line image, use &lt;IMG SRC="URL"&gt;, where URL is the URL of the image file.<p>
By default, the bottom of the image is aligned with the baseline of the current line.  You can also specify <br>
&lt;IMG ALIGN=top SRC="URL"&gt; or &lt;IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="URL"&gt;<p>
<b>Because some users do not have graphical browsers, you need to specify text to be displayed (if your image relays
information).  Use a tag like this one:  <br>&lt;IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="URL" ALT="text to be displayed"&gt;</b><p>
Changes coming soon (already in Netscape):<UL>
<LI>&lt;ALIGN=left&gt; &lt;ALIGN=right&gt; 
<LI>&lt;IMG WIDTH=x HEIGHT=x&gt; will allow you to specify the size of the image
<LI>&lt;IMG BORDER=x&gt; lets you control the thickness of the border
<LI>&lt;IMG VSPACE=x HSPACE=x&gt; allows you to control vertical and horizontal space around an image.  
</UL>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<CENTER>Write HTML required to produce:</CENTER>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<ol>
<li>an image (IMAGE.GIF) when the image is in the subdirectory named "GIF."<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>the same image with a different alignment of your choice.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<li>a graphic of a red bar across your screen.  Here is a URL:
http://www.cusd.claremont.edu:80/www/icons/redbar.gif<p>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<li>a graphic of an "under construction" image your screen.  Here is a URL:
http://www.library.carleton.edu/webtutorial/at_work.GIF<p>
</OL>
<HR size=3>
<P>
