<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Overview of HTML-Exercise 10
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H2>Exercise 10 - Hypertext Links</H2></CENTER>
<p>
This exercise gives you practice <A HREF="#link">linking</A> documents.
<p>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="link">Text Links</A></H4>
The tags used to link text together are called "anchors."  An anchor looks like this:<br>
&lt;A HREF="file.html"&gt;Highlighted text&lt;/A&gt;
<H4>Relative and absolute paths</H4><UL>
<LI>An absolute path is the entire address of a file, from the http:// (or equivalent) down to the file name.
<LI>A relative path means we're specifying the path from the current document to another document.
<LI>Use absolute paths if the linked documents are not directly related (e.g. not on the same web site).
<LI>Use relative paths whenever possible.
</UL>
<H4>Hot Image Links</H4>
A hot image link enables you to click on an image in order to move to a different HTML document.  (Images of 
buttons are often used this way.)  To do this, insert the image link inside the anchor tag, like this:<br>
&lt;A HREF="file.html"&gt;&lt;IMG SRC="file.gif" ALT="Alternate text"&gt&lt;/A&gt;<p>

<H4>Hot e-mail links</H4>
Some browsers support a "mail to" command.  To make it easier for most viewers of your page to send you e-mail, 
use a command like this: &lt;A HREF="mailto:name@address.net"&gt;name@address.net&lt;/A&gt;<p>

<H4>Links to specific places</H4>
Sometimes you want to use links to move back and forth inside one document or to move to a specific section of
a different document.  To do this:<ol>
<LI>Specify the place you want to link to by defining an anchor:  &lt;A NAME="place"&gt; &lt;/A&gt;
<LI>Specify a link at your origin point (the place you are linking from) by using a # in front of
the anchor name you specified in step 1: &lt;A HREF="#place"&gt;Highlighted text&lt;/A&gt;
<LI>To link from a different document, the tag looks like this: &lt;A HREF="file2.html#place"&gt;Highlighted text&lt;/A&gt;<p>
</OL>
<H4>Hypermedia links</H4>
To include animations and sounds, you use the anchor tag:<br>
&lt;A HREF="URL"&gt;Highlighted text&lt;/A&gt;, where URL is the URL of the media file.  The only difference
will be the file extension of the linked file.  (need link to page of common file extensions)
<p>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<CENTER>Write HTML required to produce:</CENTER>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<ol>
<li>a link tag that references a file called "linktags" in the same
directory as your HTML document.  Have the text on the screen say "Link Tags."
<p>
<li>a link tag for the same file if it is in a different subdirectory
named "HTMLdocs."
<p>
<li>a link tag to take people to the URL Primer (http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html).
Decide for yourself what the text on the screen will say.
<p>
<li>the pair of link tags that will take a viewer back to the words "Exercise 1"
in a document (like this one) from the end of Exercise 9.
<p>
<li>a link tag to use the image "image.gif" to link to a file called file.html.
</ol>
<P>
<HR size=3>
<P>
