<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML: HTML and Web Site Terminology
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>HTML and Web Site Terminology</H1></CENTER>

<p>
<hr size=3>
<P>
<DL>

<STRONG><DT>address</STRONG>
<DD>A unique name (or number) identifying a computer user or computer.  Addresses are used in network communications in transmitting messages for a particular person or machine.

<P>
<STRONG><DT>anchor</STRONG>
<DD>The location of a hypertext link in a document; it can be used to describe the link as it appears in text or graphics as well as the place that the link references.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>attribute</STRONG>
<DD>In HTML, a specially defined property of an HTML element.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>bookmark</STRONG>
<DD>A stored note telling how to get to a certain useful Web items.  A bookmark is a shortcut for getting to places you visit often in cyberspace.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>bookmark list</STRONG>
<DD>A customized listing of useful Web items, stored in memory so you don't have to retrace your steps every time you want access to an item.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/WWW/Clients.html">browser</A></STRONG>
<DD>A client program that interprets and displays HTML documents; Lynx, Mosaic, and Netscape are examples of browsers.
<P><STRONG><DT>clickable map</STRONG>
<DD>Unofficial name for image map, so called because to access a related URL, the user "clicks" the on a portion of the map (or graphic).  SEE <EM>imagemap</EM>.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>client</STRONG>
<DD>The program or computer that asks a server computer somewhere else on the network for information.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://aug3.augsburg.edu/library/aib/client.html">client/server model</A></STRONG>
<DD>The relationship in which a server computer (or server software) provides information to remote client computers (or client software).
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://hoohoo.ncsa.uiuc.edu/cgi/">common gateway interface (cgi)</A></STRONG>
<DD>A program for linking external applications Web servers.  HTML forms often rely in cgi.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/WWW/Tools/Filters.html">converter</A></STRONG>
<DD>In HTML, software programs which take files from word processing programs and convert them to HTML; also known as <EM>filters</EM>.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>default server</STRONG>
<DD>The Web server a user designates as the starting place for when launching a Web client.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>document</STRONG>
<DD>A catch-all term for anything that appears in the main window of a Web client.  More specifically, a Web document is an HTML document that the client displays.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>domain</STRONG>
<DD>A classification category used for identifying computers in a network.  The names of successive domains are used to form a unique name by which the particular computer is known to the network.
<P><STRONG><DT>domain name</STRONG>
<DD>A structured name for a computer in a network, consisting of a sequence of letters separated by dots, e.g., veblen.acns.carleton.edu.  Uniqueness is ensured by having a hierarchy of name authorities, each one responsible for approving the names in its immediate domain.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.boutell.com/faq/htedit.htm">editor</A></STRONG>
<DD>In HTML, a software program that helps you write HTML.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>element</STRONG>
<DD>In HTML, a basic unit of code.  The name of the element appears inside a tag and specifies the meaning associated with a block of text.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.boutell.com/faq/">FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions)</A></STRONG>
<DD>Common questions and their answers, assembled in one list for easy reading and quick information.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.webcom.com/~webcom/html/tutor/forms/intro.html">form (also fill-out form)</A></STRONG>
<DD>In HTML, a specially designed section of a document that accepts input from users; typically used for user feedback, product ordering, or document search.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>FTP (File Transfer Protocol)</STRONG>
<DD>A protocol, and programs to implement the protocol, which allow a user  on one system to access and transfer files over the Internet from another system.
<P>	<STRONG><DT>graphical browser</STRONG>
<DD>A Web client capable of displaying inline graphics, and which offers a mouse-based point-and-click hypertext interface.  
<P>
<STRONG><DT>graphics file</STRONG>
<DD>A file in graphics format that can be retrieved through the client's capabilities, but which usually cannot be displayed via the browser itself.  Graphics files are typically viewed through an helper file viewer associated with the client.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>helpers</STRONG>
<DD>Another term for viewers and players.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>home page</STRONG>
<DD>A designated entry point for access to a local Web.  Also, a page that a person designates as their own "main page" often presenting personal or professional information.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>host</STRONG>
<DD>The computer through which you gain Internet access.  Also, a computer on which you can hold an interactive session, or which is the source of network services.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.ucc.ie/info/net/htmldoc.html">HTML (HyperText Markup Language)</A></STRONG>
<DD>A collection of styles (indicated by markup tags) that define the various components of a World Wide Web document.  HTML was invented by Tim Berners-Lee while at CERN.  
Web browsers display HTML pages according to their coded format.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/WWW/Protocols/">HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)</A></STRONG>
<DD>The Web's primary protocol.  HTTP performs the request and retrieve functions necessary to display documents stored on remote computers.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>hyperlink</STRONG>
<DD>SEE <EM>link</EM>.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://wings.buffalo.edu/contest/awards/media.html">hypermedia</A></STRONG> 
<DD>An extension of hypertext that includes linking devices to other media--
<A HREF="http://www-swiss.ai.mit.edu/samantha/travels-with-samantha.html">text files</A>, 
<A HREF="http://rubens.anu.edu.au/">images</A>, 
<A HREF="http://soundprint.org/">sounds</A> and/or 
<A HREF="http://www.tns.lcs.mit.edu/vs/demos.html">animations</A>.  SEE <EM>hypertext</EM>.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>hypertext</STRONG>
<DD>Text linked across a potentially unlimited number of information sources.  One link takes the user to another document, which contains links to other documents (and so forth), and these documents can be located on any hypertext-capable system anywhere in the world.  
It's much like footnoting, but you get the referenced document instantly!  Hypertext is the basis for the World Wide Web.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://acwww.bloomu.edu/~wjgrun/maps/planetx-map.html">imagemap</A></STRONG>
<DD>Formal name for a clickable map.  Image maps are graphical elements that have embedded into them two or more hyperlinks, each hyperlink offering an individual jump to a linked document.  Frequently, imagemaps are in fact maps, but they can appear as any graphic.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.execpc.com/inp/inline.html">inline image</A></STRONG>
<DD>A graphic image that appears as part of a Web page.  In most graphical Web clients, inline images can be delayed or toggled off to improve retrieval speed.  SEE ALSO <EM>linked image</EM>.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.hcc.hawaii.edu/iss/macdos/mac/module1.htm">Internet</A></STRONG>
<DD>The worldwide network of networks, connected to each other through TCP/IP protocols.  The Internet makes file transfer, electronic mail, gopher, World Wide Web, and other services possible.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>IP</STRONG>
<DD>Internet Protocol.  The main protocol used on the Internet.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>IP address</STRONG>
<DD>A specially formulated number assigned to every computer directly connected to the Internet, e.g. <KBD>137.22.11.126</KBD>.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.execpc.com/inp/jpeg.html">JPEG (Joint Photographic Experts Group)</A></STRONG>
<DD>Pronounced "jay-peg."  Refers to a standards committee, a method of file compression, and a graphics file format; originated as an attempt to research and develop standards for the transmission of image data over networks.  JPEG files typically contain photographs, video stills, or other complex images.  Since Web browsers such as Mosaic and Netscape cannot display JPEG format files an "inline images," they launch a special viewer window in which images are displayed.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>jump</STRONG>
<DD>The act of retrieving a new document as the result of selecting a hyperlink.  The term "jump" is used because the user is often accessing a new computer somewhere in the world.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>launch</STRONG>
<DD>A synonym for start or load.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>link</STRONG>
<DD>A reference to another Web document, or another section of the same Web document.  Links are typically appear as highlighted or colored text when displayed in Web clients.  SEE ALSO <EM>anchor</EM>.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>linked image</STRONG>
<DD>A graphic image that appears in a file separate from the current hypertext page; it is displayed by selecting a link.  SEE ALSO <EM>inline image</EM>.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.cs.tufts.edu/lynx/Lynx_users_guide.html">Lynx</A></STRONG>
<DD>A character-based World Wide Web browsing program developed at the University of Kansas.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/SDG/Software/MacMosaic/MacMosaicHome.html">Mosaic</A></STRONG>
<DD>NCSA's graphical Web browser which was the precursor to Netscape.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.crs4.it/~luigi/MPEG/mpegfaq.html">MPEG (Motion Picture Experts Group)</A></STRONG> 
<DD>Pronounced "em-peg." Refers to a standards committee, a method of file compression, and a graphics file format; the main application for MPEG is the storage of audio and video data on CD-ROMs for use in multimedia systems.  Since Mosaic and Netscape cannot display MPEG format files as inline images, they launch a special viewer window in which the images are displayed.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.mcli.dist.maricopa.edu/authoring/mm.html">multimedia</A></STRONG>
<DD>A catch-all term for the integration of text, graphics, sound, animation, video, and communication technologies.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>name server</STRONG>
<DD>A computer in a network responsible for keeping track of domain names of other computers on the Internet and their numeric IP addresses.  When you refer to a computer by name, your name server translates that information appropriately into the numeric IP address necessary to make the connection. 
<P>
<STRONG><DT>navigation</STRONG>
<DD>The act of traversing the Internet.  Web clients typically offer navigation histories to help users find their way back along their paths.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/">NCSA (National Center for Supercomputing Applications)</A></STRONG>
<DD>NCSA produces a public domain version of the Mosaic browsing program and licenses the technology to developers.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>'net (or the 'net)</STRONG>
<DD>An abbreviation for the Internet.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://home.netscape.com/">Netscape</A></STRONG>
<DD>Currently, the most popular graphical Web browser.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>page</STRONG>
<DD>An HTML document displayed in a Web client's main window.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>player</STRONG>
<DD>A software program capable of playing sound or displaying video files retrieved through a Web client.  Players are separate programs from clients.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>point</STRONG>
<DD>The task of directing your gopher client software program to connect to a particular gopher server somewhere on the Internet.
<P><STRONG><DT>PPP (Point-to-Point Protocol)</STRONG>
<DD>A protocol that allows a computer to use the TCP/IP protocols with a standard telephone line and a high-speed modem.  Although PPP is less common than SLIP, its quickly increasing in popularity.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>protocol</STRONG>
<DD>A specific rule, or set of rules, defining how computers will act when talking to each other.  Protocol definitions range from how bits are placed on a wire to the format of an e-mail message.  Standard protocols allow computers from different manufacturers to communicate; the computers can use completely different software, providing that the programs running on both ends agree on what the data means.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>server</STRONG>
<DD>Software (or also commonly, the computer on which the server software runs) that allows a computer to offer a service to another computer, known as a client.  
<P>
<STRONG><DT>site</STRONG>
<DD>File section of a computer on which documents reside.  Typically used to refer to the specific organization that controls these documents (e.g., the Carleton College site, the White House site).
<P>
<STRONG><DT>subject tree</STRONG>
<DD>A method of organizing menus in which resources are listed by subject or topic, the menus in such an arrangement appearing as branches of a tree.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>sound file</STRONG>
<DD>A computer file containing digitized sound; can be retrieved by a Web client but can also be heard only player software associated with the client.
<P><STRONG><DT>surf</STRONG>
<DD>Term for navigating the Internet and browsing among its resources and services.  Typically refers to the technique of rapidly moving from one source to another, disregarding most content, in order to locate resources of value or interest to the user.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>SLIP (Serial Line Internet Protocol)</STRONG>
<DD>A protocol that allows a computer to use the Internet with a standard telephone line and a high-speed modem.  SLIP is being superseded by PPP, but is still in common use.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>system administrator</STRONG>
<DD>The person who runs your host machine or network. (Be very kind to this person.)
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.webcom.com/webcom/glossary/tag.html">tag</A></STRONG>
<DD>In HTML, tags are the codes that determine both the structure of information within a document and its presentation.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://aug3.augsburg.edu/library/aib/client.html">TCP/IP (Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol)</A></STRONG>
<DD>One of the protocols on which the Internet is based.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>text-base browser</STRONG>
<DD>A Web client which displays only text.  Lynx is a text-based client.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>telnet</STRONG>
<DD>An application program which allows you to log in to a remote computer on the Internet.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www-mipl.jpl.nasa.gov/~ndr/tiff/index.html">TIFF (Tag Image File Format)</A></STRONG>
<DD>A graphics file format developed by Aldus Corporation, which has become a standard format found in most paint, imaging, and desktop publishing programs.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>translator</STRONG>
<DD>SEE <EM>converter</EM>.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html">URL (Uniform Resource Locator)</A></STRONG>
<DD>The address of a document on the World Wide Web.  The address is contained in a link, which a client interprets in order to connect with the proper server. 
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.tns.lcs.mit.edu/vs/demos.html">video file</A></STRONG>
<DD>A computer file consisting of digitized video; can be retrieved by a Web client but can only be seen through a player or viewer associated with the client.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>viewer</STRONG>
<DD>A program launched by your World Wide Web browser to display a file in a format it cannot handle itself.  For instance, Mosaic or Netscape launches JPEG viewer to display a graphics file in a separate window because neither browser can interpret this format.  Viewers are separate programs from clients.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>visit</STRONG>
<DD>The process of accessing a World Wide Web document via a hypertext link.  The anchor of a document that you have visited recently has a different appearance than the anchor of a link you haven't accessed.
<P>
<STRONG><DT>web</STRONG>
<DD>A set of hypertext pages related to a particular topic or which may be located on a single host computer; a subset of the World Wide Web.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.boutell.com/faq/#servers">Web server</A></STRONG>
<DD>A computer on which Web documents reside, and which runs HTTP software to permit Web transactions.
<P>
<STRONG><DT><A HREF="http://www.boutell.com/faq/">World Wide Web</A> (also the Web, WWW, or merely W3)</STRONG>
<DD>A hypertext interface to information available from certain computers on the Internet.  One link takes the user to another document, which contains links to other documents (and so forth), and these documents can be located on any hypertext-capable system anywhere in the world.
The World Wide Web was started by CERN (the European Laboratory for Particle Physics) and seeks to build 
an international distributed hypermedia system.
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
