<HTML>

<HEAD> <TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML and Web Site Resource: Planning Your Web Site</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<A NAME="contents">
<HR SIZE=7>
<CENTER><H1>Planning Your Web Site</H1></CENTER>
<STRONG>
<OL>
<LI><A HREF="#purp">Discovering your purpose</A>
<P> 
<LI><A HREF="#who">Who needs to be involved? - service providers vs. do-it-yourself</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#onli">How online presence differs from print identity</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#grap">Online graphics considerations</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#plan">Planning site architecture</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#pub">Publicizing your site:  If you build it, will they come?</A>
</OL>
</STRONG>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="purp"></A>Discovering your purpose</STRONG>
<P>
It helps to clarify what you hope to gain by having a Web site.  Do you:
<P> 
<UL>
<P>
   <LI>want to share information with similar businesses or other offices of your business?
   <P>
   <LI>know your customers are on the Web and therefore want to:
       <UL>
          <LI>provide information about your products/services?
          <LI>provide customer service/trouble-shooting information?
		  <LI>collect information from your customers?
	   </UL>
   <P>
   <LI>want to gather support for your views?
   <P>
   <LI>want a regional, national and/or world-wide presence because it will impress:
       <UL>
       <LI>prospective customers
       <LI>prospective funders
       </UL>
</UL>
<P>
<EM><A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR>
<STRONG><A NAME="who"></A>Who needs to be involved?</STRONG>
<P>
In order to have a Web site you'll need to collect information and make decisions about:
    <P>
    <UL>
        <LI>Service Provider Issues:
            <P>
            <UL>
                <LI>your organizations' Internet connection...
                   <UL>
                       <LI>Will you have one?
                       <LI>What technology will you use? How fast will it be?
                       <LI>Who will have access?
                       <LI>What about security?
                   </UL>
                <P>
                <LI>your server space...
                    <UL>
                       <LI>Will you host your own server or rent space?
                       <LI>Which service provider will you use?
                    </UL>
                <P>
                <LI>your URL...
                    <UL>
                       <LI>Do you want or need your own domain name?
                       <LI>If so, what will it be?
                       <LI>Who will register it?
                    </UL>
                <P>
                <LI>Will you design, create, and maintain your site or hire someone?
            </UL>
            <BR>
            <BR>
        <LI>Internal Organizational Issues:
            <P>
            <UL>
               <LI>groups/people who may be involved:
                  <UL>
                      <LI>management
                      <LI>financial
                      <LI>technical
                      <LI>publications
                      <LI>marketing
                      <LI>graphic arts
                      <LI>customer service
                  </UL>
                <P>
                <LI>Who will lead the project?
                <LI>How much time will be required? Is such time available?
              </UL>
         </UL>
   </UL>
<P>
<EM><A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR>
<STRONG><A NAME="onli"></A>How online presence differs from print identity:</STRONG>
<UL>
   <LI>Sound bites and slogans yield to detailed information.
   <LI>People follow their interests.
   <LI>Netiquette requests useful information and generous links.
</UL>
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR>
<STRONG><A NAME="grap"></A>Online graphics considerations:</STRONG>
<P>
<UL>
   <LI>Is your logo appropriate for online use?
   <LI>How will the graphics on each page relate to each other?
   <LI>How will the graphics on the site relate to each other?
</UL>
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR>
<STRONG><A
NAME="plan"></A>Planning site architecture</STRONG>
<P>
Issues include:
<UL>
   <LI>Does each page clearly communicate its identity, purpose, and navigational options?
   <LI>Into what categories will your information be arranged?
   <LI>How will viewers find what they want?
   <LI>What navigational tools and links will you provide? (generally: more is better)
   <LI>How will your files be arranged on the server?
</UL>
Hints:
<UL>
   <LI>the "top" page in a directory is usually named <TT>index.html</TT> or <TT>index.htm</TT>
   <LI>UNIX machines <font size=+2>are case sensitive</font> for directories and file names!
   <LI>create a sketch of your architecture and keep it up-to-date
   <LI>either on that sketch or separately, list directory and file names (including "case")
</UL>
<P><EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR>
<STRONG><A NAME="pub"></A>Publicizing your
site</STRONG>
<P>
If you build it, will they come?  Only if they know you're there.
<UL>
<LI>Send announcements to online directories:
    <P>
    <UL>
        <LI><A HREF="http://ep.com/faq/webannounce.html">FAQ: How To Announce Your New Web Site</A> provides 
             information about how to publicize a new Web site.
        <P>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.submit-it.com/">Submit It!</A> offers a free service designed to make the process
             of submitting your URLs to a variety of WWW indexes and specialty directories faster and easier. It
             allows you to register with over 19 different services by completing just one form, including:
          <P>     
          <UL>
             <LI>Alta Vista                                  
             <LI>Apollo
             <LI>BizWiz
             <LI>ComFind
             <LI>Galaxy
             <LI>Infoseek
             <LI>InfoSpace                               
             <LI>LinkStar
             <LI>Lycos
             <LI>Mallpark
             <LI>METROSCOPE
             <LI>Nerd World Media
             <LI>New Rider's WWW YP
             <LI>Open Text
             <LI>Pronett
             <LI>Starting Point
             <LI>WebDirect!                          
             <LI>WebCrawler
             <LI>Whatsnew on the Internet
             <LI>What's New Too!
             <LI>Yahoo
             <LI>Yellow Pages Online                           
          </UL>
        <P>
        Submit It! also offers a variety of for fee services as well.
        <P>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.webpromote.com/">WebPromote(tm)</A> is a professional service which publicizes
             your Web site via a variety of promotional channels.  Programs start at $175.
        <P>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.netcreations.com/postmaster/">PostMaster(tm)</A> is a service which announce your 
             URL in as many places as possible (over 350).  The service costs $500 for a single use and $1,000 
             for four uses. 

     </UL>                     
     <P>
     <LI>Include your URL on printed material, including advertisements, stationery, brochures, business cards...
     <P>
     <LI>Make your site news and send press releases.
</UL>
<P>
<EM><A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="welcome.html">Main Menu</A></CENTER>
