<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Web Search Engines: Introduction</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#054BBB" VLINK="#006342">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H2>Web Search Engines: Introduction</H2></CENTER>
<P>
During the infancy of the World Wide Web, <A HREF="glossary.html#surf">surfing</A> was 
the primary means of finding information.  Starting with a particular Web page, you 
followed links from page to page, made educated guesses along the way, hoping sooner 
or later to arrive at the desired piece of information.
<P>
Surfing was fun when you had the 
time to explore, but when you needed to find a specific piece of information quickly, or 
needed to find that same information again, surfing and serendipity soon lost their charm.
<P>
You quickly learned to collect <A HREF="glossary.html#url">URLs</A>, or addresses of useful Web sites 
on your list of <A HREF="glossary.html#bookmark">bookmarks</A>, but this soon became a fairly 
unmanageable list.
<P>
Eventually you started to wonder if there wasn't some complete index of
the World Wide Web.  The answer, of course, was no, there is no <EM>complete</EM>&nbsp;
index to the Web.
<P>
But that was then and this is now...
<P>
During the last two years, a category of tools has been developed that enables information 
published on the Web to be searched and discovered more effectively.  
These tools are commonly referred to collectively as 
<A HREF="glossary.html#searchengine"><EM>search engines</EM></A>.  We'll be more 
precise so we'll refer to them broadly as <STRONG>Web search tools</STRONG> and then
make a  distinction between the two most common types of tools based upon their  
primary mechanisms: browsing through hierarchies, and keyword searching. 
<P>
As with the Web itself, these tools are constantly evolving.
<P>
Most of the early Web search tools were started as hobbies or projects by college 
students or computer scientists.  They grew in size or fame, and now have gained 
some of their designers great commercial success.  At times, many search 
tools suffer from overuse, resulting in difficutly in connecting to them.
<P>
Given all the hyperbole and heightened expectations surrounding the "information superhighway,"
users need to keep a balanced perspective of what is actually available via Web
search mechanisms.
<P>
While a flurry of activity is underway to create Web search tools for indexing the Web, it's 
unlikely that anyone can replace the knowledge, skills, and "street smarts" of humans anytime
soon.
<P>
<A HREF="glossary.html">World Wide Web glossary</A> contains useful definitions.
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="welcome.html">Web Search Tool Home Page</A></CENTER>
