<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Web Search Tools:  Directories</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#054BBB" VLINK="#006342">
<hr size=7>
<A NAME="contents">
<CENTER><H2>Web Search Tools:  Directories</H2></CENTER>
<P>
<STRONG>
<A HREF="#what">What is a Directory?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#work">How Do Directories Work?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#who">Who Does The Work?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#size">How Important is Size?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#advan">Advantages of Directories</A><BR>
<A HREF="#weak">Weaknesses of Directories</A><BR>
<A HREF="#examples">Examples of Directories</A><BR>
</STRONG>
<P>
<A NAME="what"><H4>What is a Directory?</H4></A>
<P>
A <STRONG>directory</STRONG> is often a good starting place if you are
interested in finding information on a broad topic or subject area.
Directories (also referred to as <EM>subject directories</EM>,
<EM>subject catalogs</EM>, <EM>subject trees</EM>&nbsp; or <EM>pick
lists</EM>&nbsp;) are collections of <A HREF="glossary.html#document">documents</A>
that maintain lists of <A HREF="glossary.html#link">links</A> organized by
their content.  They're usually very easy to navigate and use, since locating
information you need is simply a matter of trying the links under an
appropriate topic.  Well-maintained directories will often include a brief
summary, or <A HREF="glossary.html#abstract">abstract</A>, and other
information for each link to help users select the most useful materials.
Directories are also useful for people who have a general idea about the
information they are seeking, but just don't know where to start.
<P>
The size and complexity of subject directories are simplified by careful
organization, making them the most useful search tool for general subject
browsing.  Directories are commonly organized hierarchically to make it easy
to navigate from the general to the specific topic of interest. Well organized
directories also contain cross-references between related topics under
different headings such as "Business:Computer Sales" "Computers:Vendors".  Some
directories strive to be comprehensive, others aim to be selective, while
others are subject-specific.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="work"><H4>How Do Directories Work?</H4></A>
<P>
Most directories are organized hierarchically into layers from general to specific 
topics.  A user selects and navigates the links of a directory by their relation to the desired 
information. Since the documents are grouped by their content, once a suitable file is 
found, there are often many more useful links in the same section.
<P>
For example, <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com">Yahoo!</A> is a directory that is
organized into 14 general subject headings and about 50 sub-headings on the
first page. The user must navigate 3 or more index pages to actually find a
page of links, but such pages typically contain more than 20 references to
documents.  Like other well organized directories, this directory makes
abundant use of cross-references between related headings. 
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="who"><H4>Who Does the Work?</H4></A>
<P>
Because directories must be organized in some sort of meaningful way, they
require an administrative staff or dedicated contributors and guest editors to
locate useful documents and link them under the relevant subject heading.  New
documents are found by automated search tools, new service announcements, and
user suggestions. For each document, an administrator writes a descriptive
abstract and inserts the information into the directory under the appropriate
subject heading or headings.  Similarly, outdated documents or
<A HREF="glossary.html#deadlinks">dead links</A> must be removed by a human
administrator or editor, and is typically handled in response to user 
feedback.
<P>
As the number of indexed documents grows, administrators reorganize subject headings to 
accomodate and differentiate popular topics into smaller groups. Careful maintenance makes 
this process of growth and adjustment transparent to the users. 
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="size"><H4>How Important is Size?</H4></A>
<P>
The usefulness of a directory depends on the value of the links it contains. 
There are two approaches that administrators take to maximize the usefulness of their 
collections.
<P>
Services such as <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG> work hard to catalog as many Internet 
resources as possible--typically, hundreds or thousands of document collections a week. 
Resources are gathered by accepting URL suggestions from users, scanning mailing list and
newsgroups for WWW announcments, and scouting other directories for new links.
<P>
By including as many resources as possible, these services aim to provide a complete list of 
relevant documents for each subject area. In this model, the burden of selecting the "best" 
resources from this list is often left to the end user.
<P>
Rather than maximizing the number of links, other services follow a different philosophy. 
The links they recommend are hand-picked as the most valuable or complete within that particular 
subject area. Aging and dead links are quickly updated or removed by the staff. A user may not 
find <EM>all</EM>&nbsp; relevant documents in a field using such a tool, but she or he will almost certainly 
find something useful.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<A NAME="advan"><H4>Advantages of Directories</H4></A>
<P>
<UL>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>Simplicity</STRONG>
<DD>If you want to understand the territory around your subject of interest or to locate a few
    main Web sites specializing in a particular topic, a directory is all you need.
    <P>
    A directory is the right tool for people who aren't familiar enough with a subject
    to know exactly the right terms to search for, or who want the benefit from the expertise 
    of a human archiver.<P> 

<DT><STRONG>Quality</STRONG>
<DD>Those who don't have much time but are searching for a good resource, can consult with a
    directory that critically reviews the sites it includes.  This is a hot new trend 
    at directory sites.<P>
</DL>
</UL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="weak"><H4>Weaknesses of Directories</H4></A>
<P>
<UL>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>Lack of a Controlled Vocabulary</STRONG>
<DD>The subject-oriented organization of directories, while logical,
    can make it difficult to locate topics that are not easily categorized. The lack of
    a <A HREF="glossary.html#vocabcontrol">controlled vocabulary</A>, within
    and between different hierarchies, along with ad hoc
    additions of new categories, increases the difficulty of browsing directories
    effectively.  Increasingly, directories are sporting search mechanisms to relieve
    this problem so that users can <A HREF="glossary.html#keyword">keyword-search</A> the 
    contents of these sites.  This is equivalent to having an index for the directory.<P>
    
<DT><STRONG>Access to Fewer Documents</STRONG>
<DD>Because directories rely on humans for their overall design and maintenance, they
    typically provide links to a smaller number of documents than most automated search
    services. Thus, while directories are helpful when you're trying to find out what 
    the Web has to offer, they become less so as your questions become more specific...so the 
    results of browsing, or even searching an index to a directory, will
    not be comprehensive.  For these reasons, it's usually advisable to supplement your
    search by using a search <link> engine. 
</DL>
</UL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="examples"><H4>Examples of Directories</H4></A>
<UL>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com">Yahoo!</A>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.mckinley.com/">Magellan</A>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.einet.net/galaxy.html">Galaxy</A>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.clearinghouse.net/">The Argus Clearinghouse</A>  (Formerly known as the <STRONG>Clearinghouse for Subject-Oriented Internet Resource Guides</STRONG>)
        <LI><A HREF="http://chronicle.com//che-data/internet.dir/human4.htm">Chronicle of Higher Education's Scholarly Resources on the Internet</A>
</UL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="engines.html">On to Search Engines!</A><P>
<A HREF="welcome.html">Web Search Tools Home Page</A>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<CITE>
Maintained by <A HREF="/staff/terry/terry.html">Terry Metz, temetz@carleton.edu</A>
<BR> Last updated: December 8, 1996
</CITE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
