<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Web Search Tools: Search Engines</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#054BBB" VLINK="#006342">
<hr size=7>
<A NAME="contents">
<CENTER><H2>Web Search Tools: Search Engines</H2></CENTER>
<P>
<STRONG>
<A HREF="#what">What is a Search Engine?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#how">How Do Search Engines Work?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#work">Who Does the Work?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#size">How Important is Size?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#advan">Strengths of Search Engines</A><BR>
<A HREF="#weak">Weaknesses of Search Engines</A><BR>
<A HREF="#compare">Comparison of Features of Search Engines</A><BR>
<A HREF="#examples">Examples of Search Engines</A><BR>
</STRONG>
<P>
<A NAME="what"><H4>What is a Search Engine?</H4></A>
<P>
A search engine is a Web site which collects and organizes Internet resources using a 
large database of information and presents a way to select 
<A HREF="glossary.html#document">documents</A> based on certain words, phrases, 
or patterns within those documents. 
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="how"><H4>How do Search Engines Work?</H4></A>
<P>
Search engines work on the principle that the information content of a document can be 
summarized by extracting words already in the title or text.
<P>
Documents are found (usually by following <A HREF="glossary.html#link">links</A> from
other documents) and entered into a database (known as a <A HREF="glossary.html#index">
searchable index</A>) based on words extracted from the title or text of that document.
This is mostly an automated process.
<P>
Once a number of documents have been indexed, the user describes the desired information using 
selected words or phrases, called <A HREF="glossary.html#keyword">keywords</A>, that are entered 
into the computer. The search engine then examines the database for documents that match or are
related to the user's criteria, and returns to the user a list of the selected documents.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="work"><H4>Who Does the Work?</H4></A>
<P>
The vast majority of effort required to create search engines' document collections is
accomplished by automated processes.
<P>
A piece of software reaches out across the network and retrieves as many Web pages as it
can find and follows links embedded in those pages to find other Web pages.  At each page,
the program records the address, known as the <A HREF="glossary.html#url">URL</A>, and 
downloads part (or all) of the content for indexing in a searchable database.  Then the
software searches the document for <A HREF="glossary.html#link">links</A> pointing to
other documents that haven't been indexed yet.  Eventually almost every document on the web
is indexed.  These search-and-retrieve programs are often referred to as 
<A HREF="glossary.html#webickything">Web crawlers, robots, spiders, or worms</A>.
<P>
To make search-and-retrieve programs even more efficient, they can be split into two 
distinct parts:  a <A HREF="glossary.html#gather">gatherer</A> and a 
<A HREF="glossary.html#broker">broker</A>.  The gatherer resides at a remote site, 
retrieving documents to be indexed, while the broker stays on the home machine and builds 
the index.
<P>
Spiders start with a list of a dozen or so known sites.
They index these pages, then follow every link to every new page the sites contain and 
index those.  The process repeats until the spider can't find any links in the Web that
it hasn't visited.  Back when the Web was young, when it contained only a few 
thousand pages, this procedure took less than a day.  Now it takes even the quickest
spiders nearly a week to roam the entire Web. 
<P>
The database grows in size because the indexing software saves new links it discovers, 
as well as user suggested URLs, which can be explored and then indexed in the next cycle. 
<P>
Usually, very little human effort is involved in this process.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="size"><H4>How Important is Size?</H4></A>
<P>
Probably the most important, and certainly the most popular, comparison of search engines 
is based on the number of documents indexed in their databases. Search engines with larger
databases are typically much more likely to contain relevant results and 
larger result sets for given criteria. For this reason, most search engines strive for as large
a database as possible and advertise the number of documents they have indexed.
However, there are several ways to measure the number of documents in a database: 
<P>
	<UL>
		<LI>Documents for which the entire full text has been indexed. 
		<LI>Documents for which the URL, name, and headings or excerpts have been indexed. 
		<LI>Documents for which the URL and name have been indexed. 
		<LI>Documents for which some descriptive text has been indexed. 
	</UL>
<P>
Although each  method represents a count of "indexed" documents, they do not provide 
the same results!
<P>
For example, the <A HREF="http://inktomi.berkeley.edu">Inktomi</A> search engine site 
provides a link called "Truth in Document Counting," disputing the validity of Lycos' 
claim to have most of the Web "indexed."
<P>
The number of documents indexed by search engines are 
<EM>much</EM>&nbsp; larger than those listed by <A HREF="directories.html">directories</A>.
That's because a search engine's  
database describes every page in a collection to better represent the content of that 
collection, but a directory usually only points to the home page or key pages of a collection. 
Considering that collections of pages at a single site can number in the scores or hundreds or more, 
the actual number of documents indexed by a directory is significantly higher than the total links would 
indicate.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="advan"><H4>Strengths of Search Engines</H4></A>
<P>
<DL>
<DT>Size
<DD>Search engines often contain millions of links, as opposed to the hundreds of
    thousands contained by directories.
<P>
<DT>Keyword Searching
<DD>You supply the term(s) of interest to you, rather than searching through a hierarchy
    of lists created by someone else.
<P>
<DT>Search Refinement Capabilities
<DD>With millions of items available, you want your searching to be as precise as
    possible, and search engines allow this.
    You can read more about <A HREF="features.html">features 
    that improve search precision</A> in another section of this resource.
<P>
<DT>Currency
<DD>Since document gathering is usually performed by automated means, the searchable
    database is rebuilt regularly. This means that new or updated documents are often 
    indexed shortly after coming online, and that dead links are removed in timely fashion. 
</DL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="weak"><H4>Weaknesses of Search Engines</H4></A>
<P>
<DL>
<DT>No two search engines work quite the same.
<DD>The way you initiate a search differs dramatically from search engine to search engine.
    While some search engines are case sensitive by default, others allow you to choose 
    whether or not a search will be case sensitive. Many engines ignore words of three or 
    fewer letters. And some search only indexes of keywords, while others search the complete 
    text of pages.  The quantity and quality of results you get from individual search engines
    vary every bit as much as the interfaces and search forms themselves.
<P>
<DT>Search results often lack precision.
<DD>Quantity of results is not generally the problem.  But
    <A HREF="glossary.html#precision">precision</A> is another story entirely,
    and easily the most disappointing factor of all.  Many search engines will provide a large
    list of links, only a few of which contain the information that you were searching for.
    The more sophisticated engines demonstrate better precision.
<P>
<DT>Reviews and abstracts are seldom available.
<DD>The sheer magnitude of the number of documents contained in many search engine 
    databases prevents these services from including editorial judgment about the value 
    of the information in these documents.   
<P>
<DT>Popularity can slow performance.
<DD>A major problem inherent with successful search engines is that as soon as a
    particular search tool becomes useful and well known, it's flooded with users.  This
    in turn makes it less dependable, since the original server is unable to handle the
    increased load.
</DL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="compare"><H4>Comparison of Features of Search Engines</H4></A>
<P>
Selecting the right search engine does not necessarily have to be a trial and error
process. Connection difficulties, however, often make the choice for you. Lycos, one of
the biggest and most popular search engines, is legendary for its unavailability during
work hours. Webcrawler is more often available, and although considerably smaller,
is easy to use, and as a consequence, is often the first choice. The new kid on the
block, InfoSeek, has been favourably reviewed and rated number one in several
recent studies. Two other new search engines, Excite and Inktomi, are also worth exploring.
<P>

Not all search engines offer the same search options. Some of the engines use 'or'
as the default and rely on relevancy ranking algorithms to find and rank relevant
documents. Other search engines offer a choice between 'and', 'or', 'adjacent',
'near', and 'not' options. 
<P>
Different search engines have better precision for some searches than
others. For example, the lack of phrase or word adjacency capabilities with Webcrawler
makes it an inappropriate tool for an author or name search. Such a search will typically
retrieve a ranked result set, but as the first and last name have been considered to
be separate and unrelated search terms, the chance of a successful outcome is very low.
<P>
Each search engine varies significantly in the way the result sets are ranked and
presented, and this influences the success of a search. Scanning down a result set before
activating any of the links is a recommended strategy. The highest ranked documents in the
list are not necessarily those that will provide the desired information. Often the
best link is further down the ranked list.  The amount of information provided with each
link contributes to the ability to assess the individual links. Webcrawler, at one end of
the spectrum, presents a ranked list of links with no additional information. At the other
extreme, Lycos generates a lengthy computer-composed abstract for each link which is
useful for evaluating links. OpenText is an example of a search engine that goes even
further and suggests links to related sites.
<P>
These search engines, compared to OPACs and online periodical indexing tools, are 
still relatively limited in some respects.  The ability to combine results sets and limit
searches to specific fields has not been fully realized.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="examples"><H4>Examples of Search Engines</H4></A>
<UL>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.altavista.digital.com/">Alta Vista</A>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.excite.com/">Excite</A>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.infoseek.com/">InfoSeek</A>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.hotbot.com/">HotBot</A>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.lycos.com/">Lycos</A>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.opentext.com/">Open Text</A>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.webcrawler.com/">Webcrawler</A>
</UL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="metaengines.html">On to Metasearch Engines!</A><P>
        <A HREF="welcome.html">Web Search Tools Home Page</A></CENTER>
