<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Web Search Tools: Metasearch Engines</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#054BBB" VLINK="#006342">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H2>Web Search Tools: Metasearch Engines</H2></CENTER>
<P>
<STRONG>
<A HREF="#what">What is a Metasearch Engine?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#how">How Do Metasearch Engines Work?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#advan">Advantages of Metasearch Engines</A><BR>
<A HREF="#weak">Weaknesses of Metasearch Engines</A><BR>
<A HREF="#examples">Examples of Metasearch Engines</A><BR>
</STRONG>
<P>
<A NAME="what"><H4>What is a Metasearch Engine?</H4></A>
<P>
A metasearch engine is a Web search tool which which lets you access many different search engines from one site. 
<P>
These tools not only let you search across a variety of engines simultaneously, but they also let you specify which engines you'd like to use, as well as how long you're willing to wait for
the results.  This can be critical, because a complex multithreaded search can conceivably last for hours.  Some don't even force you to decide which engines to use.  Just select the resources and the number of engines to search, and it does the rest.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="how"><H4>How do Metasearch Engines Work?</H4></A>
<P>
Metasearch engines work in one of two different ways:
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>CUSI (Configurable Unified Search Index)</STRONG>
<DD>A metasearch engine which lets you launch searches to major
       search engines one at a time.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>SUSI (Simultaneous Unified Search Index)</STRONG>
<DD> A metasearch engine which simultaneously launches searches
        to several different search engines.
</DL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="advan"><H4>Advantages of Metasearch Engines</H4></A>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>One-stop shopping saves you time.
<LI>You avoid the effort of having to learn nuances of each engine's interface.
<LI>They're convenient for searches across search engines or when few results are expected.
</UL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="weak"><H4>Weaknesses of Metasearch Engines</H4></A>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Metasearch engine usually don't offer access to each engine's full range of query tools
(e.g., <A HREF="glossary.html#booleansearch">Boolean operators</A>) so searches are less refined.
<LI>Response times are slower than searching individual engines.
<LI>They may not indicate current availability of individual search engines, so you can't confirm that your search included all the engines you intended.
</UL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="examples"><H4>Examples of Metasearch Engines</H4></A>
<P>
<UL>
	<LI><A HREF = "http://www.albany.net/allinone/">All-in-One Search Page</A> (CUSI)
	<LI><A HREF = "http://metacrawler.cs.washington.edu:8080/">MetaCrawler</A>  (SUSI)
	<LI><A HREF = "http://guaraldi.cs.colostate.edu:2000/">SavvySearch</A>  (SUSI)
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="welcome.html">Web Search Tool Home Page</A></CENTER>
<BR>
