</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Features for Refining Search Engine Retrieval</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#054BBB" VLINK="#006342">
<hr size=7>
<A NAME="contents">
<CENTER><H2>Web Search Tools: Features for Refining Search Engine Retrieval</H2></CENTER>
<P>
<STRONG>
<A HREF="#truncate">Truncation</A><BR>
<A HREF="#boolean">Boolean Searching</A><BR>
<A HREF="#proximity">Proximity</A><BR>
<A HREF="#weight">Term Weighting</A><BR>
<A HREF="#relevancy">Relevancy Ranking</A><BR>
<A HREF="#concept">Concept Searching</A><BR>
<A HREF="#helpsite">A Useful Site for Learning More about Refining Search Engine Retrieval</A>
</STRONG>
<P>
Here is a very basic guide to some of the options that are available for search
engines.  Specific options are usually detailed in help pages associated with
each search engine. Here are a few general terms to watch for.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="truncate"><H4>Truncation</H4></A>
<P>
Most search services perform some sort of suffix management on 
<A HREF="glossary.html#keyword">keywords</A>. This helps users to get the most for
their queries by generalizing each keyword to its root, and expanding the search to 
include all forms of that root word. A query containing the keyword <CODE>computers</CODE> 
may actually return documents containing the words <CODE>compute</CODE>, <CODE>computed</CODE>, 
<CODE>computer</CODE>, <CODE>computes</CODE>, <CODE>computers</CODE>, and 
<CODE>computing</CODE>. Some services allow the user to choose which words are truncated, 
typically by appending an <CODE>*</CODE> character to the end of the root word, like 
<CODE>comput*</CODE>; most others, however, perform the truncation automatically according 
to their own rules.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="boolean"><H4>Boolean Searching</H4></A>
<P>
One of the most popular ways search engines handle multiple keywords is by
linking each with a <STRONG>Boolean</STRONG> command.  Examples of boolean
commands are AND (searching for all terms), OR (searching for at least one of
the terms), and NOT (excluding a term from the search).  To learn more about
Boolean search techniques, try these resources:
<P>
<OL>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.cnet.com/Resources/Tech/Advisers/Search/search3.html">
             Boolean Search Primer</A>
        <DD>By Elizabeth P. Crowe.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://users.why.net/redbear/scott/tutorial/sec2.html#boolean">
             Boolean Logic</A> and <A HREF="http://users.why.net/redbear/scott/tutorial/sec2.html#pseudo">
             Pseudo Boolean Logic</A>
        <DD>By Scott Nicholson.
</OL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="proximity"><H4>Proximity</H4></A>
<P>
A proximity capability allows you to specify that two or more words appear close to
one another in the original document.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="weight"><H4>Term Weighting</H4></A>
<P>
This feature allows you to tell the search engine that some terms are more important to
you than other terms. That is, you indicate that all terms are important, but one or more
terms are more important that the others.  Different engines have different techniques
for weighting.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="relevancy"><H4>Relevancy Ranking</H4></A>
<P>
Many search engines rank the results of your search based on a scoring algorithm; documents
with a higher score appear near the head of the ranked list.  As with term weighting,
different engines have different techniques for ranking, although some combination of
the following rules are often included:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>your terms appear in the first few words of the document
<LI>your terms are found close to one another in the document
<LI>the document contains more than one instance of your terms
</UL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="concept"><H4>Concept Searching</H4></A>
<P>
A few sophisticated search engines, such as <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG> and <STRONG>OpenText</STRONG>, offer concept searching.
They do this by trying to figure out how a word is being used in a document.  This is done by 
collecting statistics on which words commonly occur together.  This way, if the search engine 
sees the word "film" near the word "director," it can guess that the word is being used to 
refer to a motion picture.  This system still isn't perfect because some words may frequently 
occur together even if they aren't really related.  This is due to an important truth of 
information science:  no matter how good the technology, it can only work when the meaning of 
a document is directly correlated to the words it contains.  Fiction--or anything that relies 
on metaphor or allegory--causes difficulties.
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="helpsite"><H4>A Useful Site for Learning More about Refining Search Engine Retrieval</H4></A>
<P>
<OL>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://users.why.net/redbear/scott/tutorial/">Web Searching Tutorial</A>
<DD>By Scott Nicholson.  The author, a graduate student at the University of Oklahoma School 
    of Library and Information Science, has created a very useful guide to the features common
    to most search engines.  You may even take a quiz after completing the tutorial.
</DL>
</OL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="welcome.html">Web Search Tool Home Page</A></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<CITE>
Maintained by <A HREF="/staff/terry/terry.html">Terry Metz, temetz@carleton.edu</A>
<BR> Last updated: November 14, 1996
</CITE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
