</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Web Search Tools: Tips for Using Web Search Tools</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#054BBB" VLINK="#006342">
<hr size=7>
<A NAME="contents">
<CENTER><H2>Web Search Tools: Tips for Using Web Search Tools</H2></CENTER>
<hr size=3>
<P>
Web search tools are only as savvy as the person doing the searching.  Here are a few general 
guidelines that will help you increase your success:
<P>
<UL>
	    <LI>KNOW WHAT INFORMATION YOU ARE LOOKING FOR:  Do you want something that's being 
	        published on the Web, or information posted in newsgroups? Some search 
            sites concentrate on the Web, others focus on newsgroups, and still others give 
            you the option of both.
        <P>
		<LI>READ THE INSTRUCTIONS:  Most search engines provide their own set of 
		    operators, delimiters, and rules to help you search them efficiently.  
		    Read the instructions, and take advantage of each engine's advanced 
		    features (e.g. A HREF="glossary.html#booleansearch">boolean operators</A>
		    or <A HREF="glossary.html#proximitysearch">proximity searching</A>).
       
        <P>
		<LI>WATCH FOR VARIATIONS AMONG SERVICES:  No two search engines work quite the same. 
		    While some search engines are case sensitive by default, others allow you to
		    choose whether or not a search will be case sensitive. Many engines ignore words 
		    of three or fewer letters. And some search only indexes of keywords, while others 
		    search the complete text of pages.
        <P>		
		<LI>THINK BEFORE YOU TYPE: Is there a synonym for this word? Is there another, 
            less common word that would also be on the site I'm looking for? Can I insert 
            a modifier to narrow the search? If you can answer "yes" to any of these three 
            questions, you'll improve your search before you start.
        <P>
		<LI>CHOOSE THE UNUSUAL WORD:  Often, a more distinctive word will sharpen 
		    your search.  For instance, you'll get a more targeted search with "laptop" than 
		    with "computer".  You should also try to pick words that refine your idea (e.g., "PowerBook" or
		    "ThinkPad").
        <P>
		<LI>WATCH YOUR SPELLING:  Remember to search for legitimate spelling
		    variations (e.g., "color" and "colour").
        <P>
		<LI>REPEAT YOURSELF:  After the first pass, go to the some of the most 
		    promising-looking hits, and jot down other terms that you can use to 
		    narrow or broaden your search.
        <P>
		<LI>USE MORE THAN ONE SEARCH ENGINE:  There is surprisingly 
		    little overlap in the results from a single query performed on several 
		    different search engines.  So to make sure that you've got the best results, 
		    be sure to try your search with several sites.
        <P>
		<LI>TRY SPECIALIZED SITES:  You'll find many examples here:  <A HREF=
		    "http://www.yahoo.com/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/World_Wide_Web/Searching_the_Web/Directories/">Yahoo:
		    Computers and Internet: Internet: World Wide Web: Searching the Web: Directories</A> 
        <P>
		<LI>BE FLEXIBLE:  In the ever-changing landscape of the Internet, a critical skill 
		    is adjusting to new surroundings.  You must be prepared for formats to change, 
		    access methods to change, and a fluctuation in performance and the types of services 
		    offered.
</UL>
<P>    
<HR>
<P>
