<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selecting the Best Web Search Tool for Your Needs</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#054BBB" VLINK="#006342">
<A NAME="contents"></A>
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H2>Web Search Tools: Selecting the Best Tool for Your Needs</H2></CENTER>
<P>
<STRONG>
<A HREF="#best">What's the Best Web Search Engine?</A><BR>
<P>
<A HREF="#features">Features You Should Look for in a Web Search Engine</A><BR>
<P>
<A HREF="#compare">Resources that Compare Web Search Tools</A><BR>
<P>
<A HREF="#helpsite">A Site That Helps You Select the Appropriate Search Tool</A><BR>
</STRONG>
<P>
<HR size=3>
<P>
<A NAME="best"><H4>What's the Best Web Search Engine?</H4></A>
<P>
There isn't such a thing! At the current state of the technology, it's often 
necessary to repeat searches with different engines. This is because there are 
significant differences in the results that receive from these tools. 
<P>
The decision regarding the best search engine to start with depends partly upon a
thorough understanding and knowledge of the elements in a document that have been indexed
by each engine. For example, some tools index every word of a Web page, while others
are built with only selected words, such as the title, the headings, and
the most significant 100 words. These differences contribute to the very different
result sets that are returned by different search engines for the same query.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="features"><H4>Features You Should Look for in a Web Search Engine</H4></A>
<P>
Different types of searches and information needs require different types of
Web search tools.  You can't use the same Web search tool for all of your searching just like you can't 
use the same reference book for all of your questions. You need to select the proper tool for your searches.
Therefore, it's smart to be a discriminating user.  Here are some questions to ask yourself to help select the
right Web search tool for the job:
<DL>
<DT><STRONG>What type of resource am I looking for?</STRONG>
<DD>Do you want something that's being published on the Web, or information posted 
    in newsgroups? Some search sites concentrate on the Web, others focus on newsgroups, 
    and still others give you the option of both.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Is your search general or specific?</STRONG>
<DD>Searches on general topics imply the need for a directory.  You'll have more success with
    specific topics by employing search engines.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Do you want all pages on a topic, popular pages, or quality pages?</STRONG> 
<DD>Several search engines strive to be comprehensive, while several directories
    aim for popularity and/or quality. And some even offer reviews of the sites they list.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Would you rather pick from a list or type in your search?</STRONG> 
<DD>If you want to select choices offered from a list, you need a directory.  Typing
    in your search almost always requires a search engine.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>How sophisticated and usable is the search interface?</STRONG>
<DD>Some search tools are difficult to configure.  Others have interfaces that
    are too simplistic, and you won't be able to customize your query to 
    pinpoint the desired results.  A good search engine is simple to use and
    allows whatever type of search you want.
<P>    
<DT><STRONG>Is it speedy and reliable?</STRONG>
<DD>If the tool is painfully slow to respond to your queries or it's so busy you can't even
    begin a search when you need to, it's of little value.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Are your results usable?</STRONG>
<DD>You want quantity, precision, and readability of your search results.  It may seem
    exciting to get 500 hits, but not if 400 of them aren't really on target.
    And if all you get back is a hyperlinked-URL with no explanation, you're not likely to
    benefit much.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>How are the sites that are included in the search database chosen?</STRONG>
<DD>Are they submitted and edited by humans (implying some level of quality control) or are 
    they harvested by <A HREF="glossary.html#webickything">spider</A> software (which may retain
    both wheat and chaff)?
<P>
<DT><STRONG>How frequently are sites added to this collection?</STRONG>
<DD>In general, search engines will be more current than directories because search
    engines require little, if any, human intervention to build.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>What kind of intelligence is built into the mechanism?</STRONG>
<DD>Some directories offer cross-references and some directories offer various techniques
    to reduce synonym and homonym problems.
<P>
</DL>
<A HREF="#helpsite">A Site That Helps You Select the Appropriate Search Tool</A><BR>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="compare"><H4>Resources that Compare Web Search Tools</H4></A>
<P>
The following sources will help you compare and evaluate the
features and services of major Web search tools. Some of them
contain charts evaluating features and performance. 

<P>
<UL>
<DL>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.onlineinc.com/onlinemag/MayOL/zorn5.html">Advanced Web Searching:  Tricks of the Trade.</A>
        <DD>By Peggy Zorn, et al. <STRONG>Online</STRONG>, May/June 1996, pp. 14-28.
            This article (and accompanying chart) evaluates:  <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>, 
            <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Open 		
	        Text</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.chem.msu.su/eng/comparison.html">Best Search Engines for Finding  Scientific Information in the Net.</A>
        <DD>By Alexander Lebedev.  Includes a test with some scientific key words, and a useful 
            description of each engine.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://magi.com/~mmelick/it96jan.htm">Beyond Surfing: Tools and Techniques 
             for Searching the Web.</A>
        <DD>By Kathleen Webster & Kathryn Paul.  This article includes a section entitled "Search Tool 
            Comparisons & Evaluations: A Webliography." 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.dis.strath.ac.uk/business/search.html">Business Information Sources on the Internet:  
                 Reviews of Search Engines.</A>
        <DD>By Sheila Webber, University of Strathclyde, Department of Information Science.  Don't let the business label       
               dissuade you, because this source is useful for anyone interested in learning more about Internet search engines.
               Includes links to 17 sources of Internet search engine reviews, both paper and Web-based.
<P>                
        <DT>"Cool Tools For Searching the Web: A Performance Evaluation."  
        <DD>By Martin P. Courtois, et al.  <STRONG>Online</STRONG>, November/December 1995, pp. 14-32.
        In addition to providing and excellent explanation of how Web search tools work, this article describes and 
        contrasts the following services:  <STRONG>CUI W3 Catalog</STRONG>, <STRONG>Harvest</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, 
        <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>, <STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>, <STRONG>WWW Worm</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG>.
        The authors give <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG> the nod as the best overall search service.<BR>
	    Also contains a chart comparing the search engines.
<P>

        <DT>"Cool Tools for Web Searching: An Update."
        <DD>By Martin P. Courtois. <STRONG>Online</STRONG>, May/June 1996, pp. 29-36.
        An update of the author's previous article, this work describes and 
        contrasts the following services:  <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>, <STRONG>Excite</STRONG>, <STRONG>Inktomi</STRONG>,
        <STRONG>Magellan</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Point</STRONG>.  It also provides updated information on:  
        <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>,<STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>, and 
        <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG>.  <STRONG>Recommended</STRONG>.
<P>  
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.best.com/~mentorms/eureka.htm">Eureka!</A>
        <DD>By Mentor Marketing Services.  This site provides a consistent uniform user interface 
            to a host of search engines. Includes brief descriptions and reviews of major search 
            engines.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.tiac.net/users/hope/findqual.html">Evaluating Quality on the Net.</A>
        <DD>By Hope N. Tillman, Babson College Library. Despite its title, this article includes useful descriptions and 
                evaluations of many major Internet search services.  Although the original article dates from February 1996,
                it appears Tillman has continued to update the information included in it.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://lib-www.ucr.edu/pubs/navigato.html">General Internet Resource Finding Tools:
                 A Review and List of Those Used to Build INFOMINE.</A>
        <DD>By Steve Mitchell.  INFOMINE is a virtual library of close to 5,000 links to scholarly and educational
            resources created by librarians at the University of California, Riverside.  This article describes how
            the librarians used search engines to create this resource.  It also contains reviews of these engines
            based upon the librarians' experience in using them.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.iguide.com/insites/16/6/10/index.htm">iGuide:  Search Engines.</A>
        <DD>By iGuide.  Here are 36 search engine reviews posted on a search tool itself.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.boardwatch.com/mag/96/apr/bwm8.htm">Internet Search Engines.</A>
        <DD>By Chris Babb.  A <STRONG>BoardWatch </STRONG>magazine column with evaluations and
            reviews of the author's favorite search engines.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://sunsite.berkeley.edu/Help/searchdetails.html">Internet Search Tool Details.</A>
        <DD>By the University of California at Berkeley Digital Library SunSITE.  This resource contains comparative 
                information on the following six search engines:  <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG>, <STRONG>Galaxy</STRONG>, 
                <STRONG>AltaVista</STRONG>,  <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>,  
                and <STRONG>Lycos </STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://bingen.cs.csbsju.edu:80/~jwhausau/">Jacob Hausauer's Page for Search Engines.</A>
        <DD>By Jacob Hausauer.  Evaluations and reviews of search engines by a first-year college student
                in Minnesota.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.ub2.lu.se/desire/radar/lit-about-search-services.html">Literature About Search Services.</A>
        <DD>By Traugott Koch.  A lengthy bibliography composed of four sections:
				<UL>
					<LI>Search Service Comparisions 
					<LI>About Search Services and Retrieval 
					<LI>Indexing the Internet
          <LI>Collections, Bibliographies 
				</UL>
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.si.umich.edu/~fprefect/matrix/matrix.shtml">The Matrix of Internet Catalogs and 
                 Search Engines.</A>
        <DD>By Matt Slot.  A recent graduate of the University of Michigan School of Information (SI), Slot has created
                 (in my opinion) one of the best sites on the Web for comparing Internet search services.    
                 In addition to clear, concise evaluative information about specific search engines presented in an elegant,
                 easy-to-read format, Slot also includes useful "value-added information," such as a search engine FAQ and 
                 a glossary.  
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.onlineinc.com/database/JuneDB/nets6.html">On the Nets:
             Searching the Web with Alta Vista.</A>
        <DD>By Greg R. Notess. <STRONG>Database</STRONG>, June/July 1996, pp. 86-88.
        Although not a true comparison, the author gives a fine evaluation of <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.onlineinc.com/onlinemag/OL1995/JulOL95/notess.html">On the Nets:
             Searching the World-Wide Web: Lycos, WebCrawler, and More.</A>
        <DD>By Greg R. Notess.  <STRONG>Online</STRONG>, July/August 1995, pp. 48-53.
        This article offers an analysis and comparison of <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, <STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>, 
        <STRONG>WWW Worm</STRONG>, <STRONG>Harvest</STRONG>, and <STRONG>CUI</STRONG>, along with brief information
        about <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG> and <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://neal.ctstateu.edu:2001/htdocs/websearch.html">Quantitative Analysis of Five WWW 
                "Search Engines".</A>
        <DD>By Nicholas G. Tomaiuolo and Joan G. Packer, Central Connecticut State University Library.  This is
                a comparative study of the <STRONG>AltaVista</STRONG>, <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, 
                <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, <STRONG>Magellan</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Point</STRONG>
                search services.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.zdnet.com/pccomp/features/internet/search/sub1.html#rating">
             Rating Internet Search Engines.</A>
        <DD>By Neil Randall.  The chart, which appeared in Randall's <A HREF=
            "http://www.zdnet.com/pccomp/features/internet/search/index.html">
            September 1995 <STRONG>PC Computing</STRONG>
            article</A>, rates 14 search engines on various criteria.  Alta Vista is <EM>not</EM>&nbsp; included.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.accesscom.com/~ziegler/search.html#search_reviews">Reviews of Search
            Engines (From the Search Page).</A>
        <DD>By J. Marcus Ziegler.  Here are links to seven sources of search engine reviews.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.internetworld.com/1996/05/showdown.html">Search Engine Showdown.</A> 
        <DD>By Gus Venditto.  <STRONG>Internet World</STRONG>, May 1996, pp. 79-92.
            This article describes and evaluates seven search tools: 
            <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>, 
            <STRONG>Excite</STRONG>, <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, 
            <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>, <STRONG>Web Crawler</STRONG>, and <STRONG>WWW Worm</STRONG>.
            The print article also includes a chart.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.zdnet.com/pccomp/features/internet/search/index.html">The Search Engine that Could.</A>
        <DD>By Neil Randall.  <STRONG>PC/Computing</STRONG>, September 1995, pp. 165-168.  Comparisons and ratings of 
            14 major Web search services, including a guide to help you determine the best search service.  
            The author ranks <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG> as the best overall search service.  However, 
            <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG> was not examined. 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.cnet.com/Content/Reviews/Compare/Search/ ">Search Engines:  Where 
             to Find Anything on the Net.</A>
        <DD>By Andrew J. Leonard.  Reviews of 19 search engines based upon a study.  
            The graphical presentation is first rate.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.cnet.com/Content/Reviews/Compare/Search/ss3.html">Search Tools
             Compared.</A>
        <DD>By Andrew J. Leonard.  Includes a chart for both search engines and metasearch
            engines.  
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.internetworld.com/1996/05/guiding.html">Searching on the Net: Guiding Lights.</A>  
        <DD>By Ron Conte, Jr. <STRONG>Internet World</STRONG>, May 1996, pp. 41-44.  Includes brief comparisons
            of major search tools.                
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.leeds.ac.uk/ucs/docs/fur14/fur14.html">Searching the World Wide Web with 
             Lycos and Infoseek.</A>
        <DD>By Tracey Stanley.  An article comparing these two search engines.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.pcworld.com/reprints/lycos.htm">Special Report: Find It on the Net.</A>
        <DD>By Richard Scolville. <STRONG>PC World</STRONG>, January, 1996, pp. 124-130.
        This excellent article compares and rates the basic features of all the major 
        <STRONG>directories</STRONG>, <STRONG>search engines</STRONG>, and 
        <STRONG>metasearch engines</STRONG>. (Due to its date, it does not cover <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>.)  
        The author rates <STRONG>Excite</STRONG>, <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG> 
        are noted as the top three search engines and <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG> as the best Directory. 
        He also includes a generic list of tips for using search engines
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.indiana.edu/~librcsd/search/">Understanding WWW Search Tools.</A>
        <DD>By By Jian Liu, Reference Department, Indiana University Libraries.  A concise 
            comparison of <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>, 
            <STRONG>Excite</STRONG>, <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Inktomi</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, 
            <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>, <STRONG>Web Crawler</STRONG>, and <STRONG>WWW Worm</STRONG>.            
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.si.umich.edu/~fprefect/matrix/overview.html">Web Matrix: Overview Matrix
             Your Internet Service Shopping List.</A>
        <DD>By Matt Slot.  This document contains two charts comparing major search services.  
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.unn.ac.uk/features.htm">Web Search Tool Features.</A>
        <DD>By Ian R. Winship.  This resource consists of two tables listing
                some of the features of seven search engines:  <STRONG>AltaVista</STRONG>, <STRONG>Excite</STRONG>,  
                <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Inktomi</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, 
                <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>, and <STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>. 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://maxonline.com/webmasters/">The Webmaster's Guide to Search Engines and Directories.</A>
        <DD>By Danny Sullivan, General Manager, Maximized Online.  Sullivan's site contains a <EM>wealth</EM>&nbsp; of 
                information for anyone who wants to know more about the many aspects of Internet search tools.  In addition to a 
                listing of the primary search engines and directories,  you'll find:  a search engine comparison chart, a discussion 
                over the dispute concerning how search engine designers claim their tools function, information on the trend toward
                commercialization of Internet search tools, a study of search engine performance conducted by Maxonline, a 
                "webliography" of additional readings, and more.  You can even sign up to participate in a mailing list on the topic of 
                a search engines.<BR>
                Contains a <A HREF="http://maxonline.com/webmasters/chart.htm">Search Engine Comparison Chart.</A> 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.pcworld.com/reprints/lycos.htm#LYC">Which Gives You the Most?  
             Which Gives You the best?</A>
        <DD>By Richard Scoville.  <STRONG>PC World</STRONG>, January 1996, pp. 124-130.  Chart from this
            article.  There are many other good charts in this article, but they appear only in the
            print copy of the article.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.winona.msus.edu/services-f/library-f/webind.htm">World Wide Web Indexes:  A Study.</A>
        <DD>By H. Vernon Leighton.  This paper, written by a computer science graduate student, compares the  
                 performance of four major search engines:  <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>,
                 <STRONG>Infoseek</STRONG>, <STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>, and
                 <STRONG>WWWWorm</STRONG>. 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.bubl.bath.ac.uk/BUBL/IWinship.html">World Wide Web Searching Tools - An Evaluation.</A>
        <DD>By Ian Winship.  This evaluation compares four search engines:  <STRONG>Harvest</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, <STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>, and                                                           <STRONG>WWWWorm</STRONG>,  as well as two directories:  <STRONG>EiNet                                             Galaxy</STRONG> and <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT>"Yahoo: Profile of a Web Database."
        <DD>By Dan Lester.   <STRONG>Database</STRONG>, December 1995, pp. 46-50.
        Although not a true comparison, the author provides a fine explanation and analysis of 
        <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG>.
<P>        
        <DT>
<A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/World_Wide_Web/Searching_the_Web/Comparing_Search_Engines/">
Yahoo!:Computers and Internet:Internet:World Wide Web:Searching the Web:Comparing Search Engines</A>
        <DD>By Yahoo!.  Links to five resources.
</DL>
</UL>
<P>
<A HREF="#contents"><EM>Return to Contents</EM></A>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="helpsite"><H4>A Site That Helps You Select the Appropriate Search Tool</H4></A>
<P>
<UL>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://users.why.net/redbear/scott/">Scott Nicholson's WWW Search Engine 
     Selection Tool</A>
<DD>By Scott Nicholson.  The author, a graduate student at the University of Oklahoma School 
    of Library and Information Science, has created an automated "questionnaire" which guides you 
    to what he feels is the most appropriate search engine 
    or resource directory for your particular need (from a list of major search tools).  Beware: 
    this site may be somewhat confusing to navigate--and the graphics are somewhat garish--but 
    the end results are interesting.<P>
</DL>
</UL>               
<P>
