<TITLE>Web Search Tools: Web Search Tool "Webliography"</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#054BBB" VLINK="#006342">
<A NAME="contents">
<HR size=7>
<CENTER><H2>Web Search Tool "Webliography"</H2></CENTER>
<HR size=3>
<P>
If you're still in the exploring stage or want to keep on the lookout for the latest bells
and whistles in the Web search tool arena, you should expore some of the following sites:
<P>
<UL>
<DL>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.onlineinc.com/onlinemag/MayOL/zorn5.html">Advanced Web Searching: 
             Tricks of the Trade</A>  
        <DD>By Peggy Zorn, et al. This article evaluates:  <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>, 
        <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>.      
        <STRONG>Highly Recommended</STRONG>.  
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>Online</STRONG>, May/June 1996, pp. 14-28.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.internetworld.com/1996/05/agents.html">Agents of Change</A>  
        <DD>By Jeff Ubois.  Interviews with two computer industry experts on the topic of intelligent 
            agent development.
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>Internet World</STRONG>, May 1996, pp. 62-76.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.albany.net/allinone/all1www.html#WWW">All-In-One Search Page</A>
        <DD>By William Cross.  As noted on the home page, "This page is a compilation of various 
            forms-based search tools found on the Internet. They have been combined here to form 
            a consistent interface and convenient ALL-IN-ONE search point."
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.internetworld.com/1996/05/engine.html">Add an Engine</A>
        <DD>By Eric C. Richardson. This article identifies smaller cousins of search engines such as 
        <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG> and <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, which can be mounted at most any Web site.
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>Internet World</STRONG>, May 1996, pp. 88-90.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.chem.msu.su/eng/comparison.html">Best Search Engines for Finding                           Scientific Information in the Net.</A>
        <DD>By Alexander Lebedev.  Includes a test with some scientific key words, and a useful 
            description of each engine.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://magi.com/~mmelick/it96jan.htm">Beyond Surfing: Tools and Techniques 
             for Searching the Web</A>
        <DD>By Kathleen Webster & Kathryn Paul.  An excellent article accurately titled.  
            Appendices include:
				<UL>
					<LI>Browsing Tools: Subject Trees, Review Sites and Subject Guides 
					<LI>Keyword Searching Tools: Search Engines, Forms-Based Collections of Search
                             Tools, and Multi-Threaded Search Engines 
					<LI>Search Tool Comparisons & Evaluations: A Webliography 
				</UL>
<P>
       <DT><A HREF="http://www.dis.strath.ac.uk/business/search.html">Business Information Sources on the Internet:  
                 Reviews of Search Engines</A>
       <DD>By Sheila Webber, University of Strathclyde, Department of Information Science.  Don't let the business label       
               dissuade you, because this source is useful for anyone interested in learning more about Internet search engines.
               Includes links to 17 sources of Internet search engine reviews, both paper and Web-based.
<P>
       <DT><A HREF="http://www.dis.strath.ac.uk/business/engines.html">Business Information Sources on the Internet:  
                 Search Engines</A>
       <DD>By Sheila Webber, University of Strathclyde, Department of Information Science.  This source is useful for
       anyone needing to access a list of Internet search engines.  Includes links to 13 Internet search engine pages.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.interlog.com/~bxi/engines.htm">The BXI Inc. Search Engine Hotlink Page</A>
        <DD>From Brand X Internet Services Inc.  Here you'll find a list of links to major Internet search engines, as well as links
                to sources that help you get your home page indexed by these services.<P>
                <P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.best.com/~mentorms/eureka.htm">Eureka!</A>
        <DD>By Mentor Marketing Services.  This site provides a consistent uniform user interface 
            to a host of search engines. Includes detailed descriptions and reviews of major search 
            engines.  <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.tiac.net/users/hope/findqual.html">Evaluating Quality on the Net</A>
        <DD>By Hope N. Tillman, Babson College Library. Despite its title, this article includes useful descriptions and 
                evaluations of many major Internet search services.  Although the original article is more than six months old,
                it appears Tillman has continued to update the information included in it.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://lib-www.ucr.edu/pubs/navigato.html">General Internet Resource Finding Tools:
                 A Review and List of Those Used to Build INFOMINE</A>
        <DD>By Steve Mitchell.  INFOMINE is a virtual library of close to 5,000 links to scholarly and educational                    resources created by librarians at the University of California, Riverside.  This article describes how
                the librarians used search engines to create this resource.  It also contains reviews of these engines                    based upon the librarians' experience in using them.  <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.iinet.net.au/~heath/rhodes.html">How to Promote Your Business Web                              Page</A>
        <DD>By Jim Rhodes.  Here you'll find advice on how to get your Web page noticed, including some                            interesting comments on search engines, how they work, and what it takes to get your page to the top                 of the hit list.  <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.iguide.com/insites/16/6/10/index.htm">iGuide:  Search Engines</A>
        <DD>By iGuide.  Here are 36 search engine reviews posted on a search tool itself.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.boardwatch.com/mag/96/apr/bwm8.htm">Internet Search Engines</A>
        <DD>By Chris Babb.  A <STRONG>BoardWatch </STRONG>magazine column with evaluations and                         reviews of the author's favorite search engines.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.hop.man.ac.uk/staff/chukins/SEARCHEN.html">Internet Search Engines</A>
        <DD>By Celia Hukins.  A brief article reviewing various search engines.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://sunsite.berkeley.edu/Help/searchdetails.html">Internet Search Tool Details</A>
        <DD>By the University of California at Berkeley Digital Library SunSITE.  This resource contains comparative 
                information on the following six search engines:  <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG>, <STRONG>Galaxy</STRONG>, 
                <STRONG>AltaVista</STRONG>,  <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>,  
                and <STRONG>Lycos </STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://bingen.cs.csbsju.edu:80/~jwhausau/">Jacob Hausauer's Page for Search                                  Engines</A>
        <DD>By Jacob Hausauer.  Evaluations and reviews of search engines by a first-year college student
                in Minnesota.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.ub2.lu.se//desire/radar/lit-about-search-services.html">Literature About                          Search Services</A>
        <DD>By Traugott Koch.  A lengthy bibliography composed of four sections:
				<UL>
					<LI>Search Service Comparisions 
					<LI>About Search Services and Retrieval 
					<LI>Indexing the Internet
                       <LI>Collections, Bibliographies 
				</UL>
				<BR>
                <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.si.umich.edu/~fprefect/matrix/matrix.shtml">The Matrix of Internet Catalogs and 
                 Search Engines</A>
        <DD>By Matt Slot.  A recent graduate of the University of Michigan School of Information (SI), Slot has created
                 (in my opinion) one of the best sites on the Web for comparing Internet search services.    
                 In addition to clear, concise evaluative information about specific search engines presented in an elegant,
                 easy-to-read format, Slot also includes useful "value-added information," such as a search engine FAQ and 
                 a glossary.  <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.  
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.netskills.ac.uk/resources/searching/">Netskills:  Searching for Information on the Internet</A>
        <DD>By Walter Scales.  Although the author states, "This is not an attempt to offer a definitive list of every search device you'll ever need," 
        it's an <EM>incredibly</EM> &nbsp; rich (and lengthy) resource for anyone who uses the Internet for information retrieval.  
        It contains a wealth of information on Web search engines.  <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.onlineinc.com/database/DB1995/AugDB95/notess.html">On the Nets: 
             The InfoSeek Databases</A>
        <DD>By Gregg R. Notess.  Offers a description and analysis of <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>.
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>Database</STRONG>, August 1995, pp. 85+.   
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.onlineinc.com/database/JuneDB/nets6.html">On the Nets: 
             Searching the Web with Alta Vista</A>  
        <DD>By Gregg R. Notess.  An evaluation of <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>.
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>Database</STRONG>, June/July 1996, pp. 86-88.    
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.onlineinc.com/onlinemag/OL1995/JulOL95/notess.html">On the Nets: 
             Searching the World-Wide Web: Lycos, WebCrawler, and More</A>
        <DD>By Gregg R. Notess.  This article offers an analysis and comparison of <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, 
        <STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>, <STRONG>WWW Worm</STRONG>, <STRONG>Harvest</STRONG>, and 
        <STRONG>CUI</STRONG>, along with brief information
        about <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG> and <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>.
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>Online</STRONG>, July/August 1995, pp. 48-53.
    
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://neal.ctstateu.edu:2001/htdocs/websearch.html">Quantitative Analysis of Five WWW 
                "Search Engines"</A>
        <DD>By Nicholas G. Tomaiuolo and Joan G. Packer, Central Connecticut State University Library.  This is
                a comparative study of  the <STRONG>AltaVista</STRONG>, <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, 
                <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, <STRONG>Magellan</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Point</STRONG>
                search services.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.accesscom.com/~ziegler/search.html#search_reviews">Reviews of Search                      Engines (From the Search Page)</A>
        <DD>By J. Marcus Ziegler.  Here are links to seven sources of search engine reviews.<P>
        
        <DT><A HREF="http://users.why.net/redbear/scott/">Scott Nicholson's WWW Search Engine Selection                 Tool</A>
        <DD>By Scott Nicholson.  The author, a graduate student at the University of Oklahoma School of Library                  and Information Science, provides an outline of what search engines do, and asks a few simple                           questions to guide you to what he feels is the most appropriate search engine or resource directory                     for your particular need.  The graphics are somewhat garish, but the end result is amazing.     
                <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.<P>
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.internetworld.com/1996/05/showdown.html">Search Engine Showdown</A>
        <DD>By Gus Venditto.  This article describes and evaluates seven search tools: 
            <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>, 
            <STRONG>Excite</STRONG>, <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, 
            <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>, <STRONG>Web Crawler</STRONG>, and <STRONG>WWW Worm</STRONG>. 

            <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>Internet World</STRONG>, May 1996, pp. 79-92.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.zdnet.com/pccomp/features/internet/search/index.html">The Search Engine 
             that Could</A>
        <DD>By Neil Randall.  This article compares 14 search tools and includes a comparative chart. 
               <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>PC/Computing</STRONG>, September 1995, pp. 165-168.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/Web4Lib/archive/9604/0103.html">Search Engines Reference List</A>
        <DD>By Rowan Brownlee (from an April 1996 Web4Lib e-mail posting).  This message contains a list of                    "sites containing articles, papers, evaluations, and descriptions of various search engines."
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.cnet.com/Content/Reviews/Compare/Search/ ">Search Engines:  Where 
             to Find Anything on the Net</A>
        <DD>By Andrew J. Leonard.  Reviews of 19 search engines based upon a study.  
            The graphical presentation is first rate.   <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.<P>
            
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.cnet.com/Resources/Tech/Advisers/Search/index.html">Search the Net in                        Style:  Seek and Ye Shall Find</A>
        <DD>By Elizabeth P. Crowe.  A list of 8 brief tips for improving your Internet search technique.
                <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.<P>
                
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.search.com/">Search.Com</A>
        <DD>By C|net.  Links to most of the major search services.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.internetworld.com/1996/05/guiding.html">Searching on the Net: Guiding Lights</A>
        <DD>By Ron Conte, Jr. An excellent, concise introduction to Web search tools that includes recommendations.
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>Internet World</STRONG>, May 1996, vol. 7, no. 5, pp. 41-44. 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.leeds.ac.uk/ucs/docs/fur14/fur14.html">Searching the World Wide Web with                   Lycos and Infoseek</A>
        <DD>By Tracey Stanley.  An article comparing these two search engines.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.hotwired.com/wired/4.05/indexing/index.html">Seek and Ye Shall Find                             (Maybe)</A>
        <DD>By Steve Steinberg.  This is an article about 
            indexing the Web. The link above leads to a brief introduction to the print-only article, and 
            there are also links to some search engines. There is also an online discussion thread on the topic, 
            with various contributions (from some librarians/information scientists as well as non-information people).
            
            The highight of the article is the insight into how the people behind <STRONG>Yahoo</STRONG>, <STRONG>Inktomi</STRONG>, <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Oracle                            </STRONG>think about this problem.
            <P>
            <EM>Caution</EM>:  Librarians may find this article mildly annoying because it's written as if no 
            one did research into indexing, classification, information retrieval, etc., until the Internet came along.  
            <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>Wired</STRONG>, May 1996, pp. 110-114, 172,174,176,178,180, 182. 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.pcworld.com/reprints/lycos.htm">Special Report: Find It on the Net</A>
        <DD>By Richard Scolville. 
        This <EM>excellent</EM> article compares and rates the basic features of all the major 
        <STRONG>directories(link)</STRONG>, <STRONG>search engines(link)</STRONG>, and 
        <STRONG>metasearch engines(link)</STRONG>. (Due to its date, it does not cover <STRONG>Alta Vista</STRONG>.)  
        The author rates <STRONG>Excite</STRONG>, <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, and <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG> 
        are noted as the top three search engines and <STRONG>Yahoo!</STRONG> as the best directory. 
        He also includes a generic list of tips for using search engines.  <STRONG>Highly recommended.</STRONG>
        <P>
        This article appeared in print in <STRONG>PC World</STRONG>, January, 1996, pp. 124-130.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.hamline.edu/library/links/comparisons.html">Understanding and Comparing Web 
                Search Tools</A>
        <DD>By Karen Campbell, Hamline University Libraries.  Another list of useful links for anyone interested 
        in locating reviews and comparative analyses of learning more about comparative analysis of Internet search 
        tools.  Campbell also includes links to sources which lead users to major search engine sites. 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.indiana.edu/~librcsd/search/">Understanding WWW Search Tools</A>
        <DD>By By Jian Liu, Reference Department, Indiana University Libraries.  A concise 
            presentation of this topic, especially suitable to newbies. 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.si.umich.edu/~fprefect/matrix/answers.html">Web Matrix: What's 
             the Difference?  Some Answers about Search Engines and Subject Catalogs
</A>
        <DD>By Matt Slot.  A section of <A HREF="http://www.si.umich.edu/~fprefect/matrix/matrix.shtml">The Matrix of Internet 
            Catalogs and Search Engines</A>.  <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.  
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.unn.ac.uk/features.htm">Web Search Tool Features</A>
        <DD>By Ian R. Winship.  This resource consists of two tables listing
                some of the features of seven search engines:  <STRONG>AltaVista</STRONG>, <STRONG>Excite</STRONG>,  
                <STRONG>InfoSeek</STRONG>, <STRONG>Inktomi</STRONG>, <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, 
                <STRONG>Open Text</STRONG>, and <STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>. 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://maxonline.com/webmasters/">The Webmaster's Guide to Search Engines and Directories</A>
        <DD>By Danny Sullivan, General Manager, Maximized Online.  Sullivan's site contains a wealth of 
                information for anyone who wants to know more about the many aspects of Internet search tools.  In addition to a 
                listing of the primary search engines and directories,  you'll find:  a search engine comparison chart, a discussion 
                over the dispute concerning how search engine designers claim their tools function, information on the trend toward
                commercialization of Internet search tools, a study of search engine performance conducted by Maxonline, a 
                "webliography" of additional readings, and more.  You can even sign up to participate in a mailing list on the topic of 
                a search engines.  <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.  
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.winona.msus.edu/services-f/library-f/webind.htm">World Wide Web Indexes: A Study</A>
        <DD>by H. Vernon Leighton.  This paper, written by a computer science graduate student, compares the  
                 performance of four major search engines:  <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>,
                 <STRONG>Infoseek</STRONG>, <STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>, and
                 <STRONG>WWWWorm</STRONG>. 
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.netlinks.net/Netlinks/NEWBIE/NEWBIE3.html">World Wide Web Search Engines</A>
        <DD>By NETLiNkS.  This resource offers annotated links to nearly 170 Internet search tools, including scores of
                specialized tools on specific topics.  <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
<P>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.bubl.bath.ac.uk/BUBL/IWinship.html">World Wide Web Searching Tools - An Evaluation</A>
        <DD>By Ian Winship.  This evaluation compares four search engines:  <STRONG>Harvest</STRONG>, 
        <STRONG>Lycos</STRONG>, <STRONG>WebCrawler</STRONG>, and <STRONG>WWWWorm</STRONG>,  as well as two 
        directories:  <STRONG>EiNet Galaxy</STRONG> and <STRONG>Yahoo</STRONG>!
<P>               
        <DT><A HREF="http://maxonline.com/webmasters/whatsnew.htm">What's New</A>
        <DD>By Danny Sullivan, General Manager, Maximized Online.  A section of
            <A HREF="http://maxonline.com/webmasters/">The Webmaster's Guide to Search 
            Engines and Directories</A>, this resource posts recent news about Web search
            tools.<P>

        <DT><A HREF="http://lcweb.loc.gov/global/search.html">WWW Meta-Indexes and Search Tools</A>
        <DD>From the Library of Congress.  This site contains scores of useful links in the following categories:
				<UL>
					<LI>NCSA Meta-Index
					<LI>WWW Sites Organized by Subject
					<LI>Searching the Web
					<LI>Comparison Studies of WWW Search Engines
					<LI>WWW Search Engines: Collections of WWW Search Engines
					<LI>Individual WWW Search Engines
					<LI>Comprehensive Listings of WWW Servers
					<LI>New WWW Servers
				</UL><P>

        <DT>
<A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/World_Wide_Web/Searching_the_Web/">
Yahoo!:Computers and Internet:Internet:World Wide Web:Searching the Web</A>
        <DD>By Yahoo!.  Here you'll find a treasure trove of information, including categories on the following                           topics:
				<UL>
					<LI>Directories 
					<LI>All-in-One Search Pages
					<LI>Search Engines
                       <LI>Comparing Search Engines 
				</UL>
                 <STRONG>Highly recommended</STRONG>.
</DL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
