<TITLE>Web Search Tools:  Glossary</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#054BBB" VLINK="#006342">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H2>Web Search Tools:  Glossary</H2></CENTER>

This document describes some of the descriptive vocabulary used in the
evaluation of Web search tools. It's not intended as a basic glossary
for general Internet or World Wide Web concepts; for such information, you
should look at John December's <A HREF="http://www.december.com/net/tools/">
Internet Tools Summary</A> for relevant descriptions and tutorials.  If you
want to see another glossary somewhat like this one, look at Scott Weiss'
<A HREF="http://www.cs.jhu.edu/~weiss/glossary.html">Information Retreival
Glossary</A>.
<P>
<hr size=3>
<P>
<DL>

<DT><A NAME="abstract"></A><STRONG>abstract</STRONG>
<DD>A brief paragraph describing a <A HREF="#document"><EM>document</EM></A>,
    so that the user can decide to download the file based on more than the
    <A HREF="#link"><EM>link</EM></A> text. Abstracts are often written as part
    of the <A HREF="#url"><EM>URL</EM></A> submission process, or by server
	staff when added to a <A HREF="#directory"><EM>directory</EM></A>. Don't
	confuse an abstract, which is a summary separate from the original,
	with another term, document <A HREF="#extract"><EM>extract</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="anchor"></A><STRONG>anchor</STRONG>
<DD>Nothing more than another name for a <A HREF="#link"><EM>link</EM></A>, I
    think.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="bookmark"></A><STRONG>bookmark</STRONG>
<DD>A stored note telling how to get to a certain useful
    <A HREF="#www"><EM>Web</EM></A> item.  A bookmark 
    is a shortcut for getting to places you visit often in cyberspace.<P>
    
<STRONG><DT>bookmark list</STRONG>
<DD>Also referred to as a <EM>hotlist</EM>.  A customized listing of useful Web items, 
    stored in memory so you don't have to retrace your steps every time you want 
    access to an item.<P>
    
<DT><A NAME="booleansearch"></A><STRONG>boolean searching</STRONG>
<DD>A technique for finding documents that include or exclude data based
	on multiple criteria. By combining or restricting search keywords using
	Boolean operators <EM>AND</EM>, <EM>OR</EM>, and <EM>NOT</EM>, you can specify
	simple or complex formulas. Boolean searching provides a standard
	command interface for extracting matching data from a database.  Also see the
	<A HREF="features.html#boolean">Boolean Logic section</A> of the features of
	search engines page.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="broker"></A><STRONG>broker</STRONG>
<DD>That portion of the <A HREF="#webickything"><EM>Web spider</EM></A>
    software which builds the <A HREF="#index"><EM>index</EM></A> of a
    <A HREF="#searchengine"><EM>search engine</EM></A>. The broker works in
    conjunction with the <A HREF="#gather"><EM>gatherer</EM></A>, which gathers
    items to be indexed.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>concept search</STRONG>
<DD>A search for documents related conceptually to a word, rather than
    containing the word itself.  See also the
    <A HREF="features.html#concept">Concept Search section</A> of the features
    of search engines page.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>controlled vocabulary</STRONG>
<DD><DD>See <A HREF="#vocabcontrol"><EM>vocabulary control</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="client"></A><STRONG>client</STRONG>
<DD>A peice of software into which the user inputs information, and which then
    interacts with a <A HREF="#server"><EM>server</EM></A> to get the
    information that the user requests.  A web browser is an example of a
    client.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>crawler</STRONG>
<DD>See <A HREF="#webickything"><EM>Web crawler</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="#cusi"></A><STRONG> CUSI (Configurable Unified Search      
        Index)</STRONG>
<DD> A metasearch engine which lets you launch searches to major
        search engines one at a time.  See also
        <A HREF="#susi"><EM>SUSI</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="deadlinks"></A><STRONG>dead link</STRONG>
<DD>Because the Web consists of <A HREF="#document"><EM>documents</EM></A> authored and
    located at numerous network locations, the level of document support and
    maintenance varies.  Some collections are regulary used and incorrect
    information is updated; others may not be updated for weeks or months. As
    machine names change, users' documents move, or network connections fail,
    document <A HREF="#link"><EM>links</EM></A> become out of date. A dead link
    is a URL that leads to no existing document, indicated by the message
    "<CODE>404 Error</CODE>".
<P>
<DT><A NAME="directory"></A><STRONG>directory</STRONG>
<DD>A subject directory is a service that organizes linked
	documents by their content and subject matter. Organized into general
	categories (or alphabetically) at the top level, documents are layered
	hierarchically and collected with related pages. Although any subject
	index will be smaller than a searchable one, it's generally a much more
	reliable tool.  See also the <A HREF="directories.html">directories page</A>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="document"></A><STRONG>document</STRONG>
<DD>A catch-all term for anything that appears in the main window of a Web
    <A HREF="#client"><EM>client</EM></A>.  
    More specifically, a text file in HTML format that the client displays.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="engine"></A><STRONG>engine</STRONG>
<DD>See <EM><A HREF="#searchengine">search engine</A></EM>
<P>
<DT><A NAME="extract"></A><STRONG>extract</STRONG>:
<DD>A portion of a <A HREF="#document"><EM>document</EM></A>, typically returned as part
    of a match when using a <A HREF="#searchengine"><EM>search engine</EM></A>.
    New files are usually gathered in large amounts automatically by searching
    and indexing software, so it is rather inconvenient for an administrator
	to write a document summary or <A HREF="#abstract"><EM>abstract</EM></A>, 
	for each file. Search software generally saves sample text from a
	file with its <A HREF="#url"><EM>URL</EM></A> and indexed keywords, as a simple "preview".
<P>
<DT><A NAME="falsedrops"><STRONG>false drops</STRONG>
<DD>A document set returned from a <A HREF="#index"><EM>searchable index</EM></A>
    is characteristically filled with documents that match the user's criteria but don't 
    really contain the desired information.  These unwanted documents are referred to as
    false drops.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.boutell.com/faq/"><STRONG>FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions)</STRONG></A>
<DD>Common questions and their answers, assembled in one list for easy reading and quick
    information.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>full-text index</STRONG>
<DD>An <A HREF="#index"><EM>index</EM></A> containing every word of every
    document cataloged, including <A HREF="#stopwords"><EM>stop words</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>fuzzy search</STRONG>
<DD>A search that will find matches even when words are only partially spelled
    or misspelled.
<P>    
<DT><A NAME="gather"></A><STRONG>gatherer</STRONG>
<DD>The administrators of directories and search engines must
	not only maintain their collection of <A HREF="#url"><EM>URLs</EM></A>, but should
	continue to find more Internet documents to expand their collections. The
	process of gathering URLs can be done manually (by serendipity and scanning 
	the <A HREF="#whatsnew"><EM>what's new? lists</EM></A>) or by running 
	automated software (such as a <A HREF="#webickything"><EM>Web spider</EM></A>) 
	which returns a list of "discovered" resources.  The gatherer software of the
	spider works in tandem with a piece of software called the
	<A HREF="#broker"><EM>broker</EM></A>.  The gatherer resides at a remote
	site, retrieving documents to be indexed, while the broker stays on the
	home machine and builds the index.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="hit"></A><STRONG>hit</STRONG>
<DD>A document returned from a <A HREF="#index"><EM>searchable index</EM></A>
    which matches the users criteria and contains desired information.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="html"></A><A HREF="http://www.ucc.ie/info/net/htmldoc.html">
    <STRONG>HTML (HyperText Markup Language)</STRONG></A>
<DD>A collection of styles (indicated by markup tags) that define the various 
    components of a <A HREF="#www"><EM>World Wide Web</EM></A>
    <A HREF="#document"><EM>document</EM></A>.  HTML was invented by
    <A HREF=http://www.w3.org/pub/WWW/People/Berners-Lee/>Tim Berners-Lee</A> 
    while at <A HREF="http://www.cern.ch/">CERN</A>.  Web browsers display HTML
    pages according to their coded format.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/WWW/Protocols/"><STRONG>HTTP (HyperText 
     Transfer Protocol)</STRONG></A>
<DD>The Web's primary protocol.  HTTP performs the request and retrieve functions 
    necessary to display documents stored on remote computers.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>hyperlink</STRONG>
<DD>See <A HREF="#link"><EM>link</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>hypertext</STRONG>
<DD>Text linked across a potentially unlimited number of information sources.
    One <A HREF="#link"><EM>link</EM></A> takes the user to another document,
    which contains links to other documents (and so forth), and these documents
    can be located on any hypertext-capable system anywhere in the world.  It's
    much like footnoting, but you get the referenced
    <A HREF="#document"><EM>document</EM></A> instantly!  Hypertext is the
    basis for the <A HREF="#www"><EM>World Wide Web</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="index"></A><STRONG>index</STRONG>
<DD>The searchable catalog of <A HREF="#document"><EM>documents</EM></A> created
    by search engine software; it works with the search engine to allow a user
    to find documents by entering a <A HREF="#keyword"><EM>keyword</EM></A> or
    other criteria.  Also called "catalog."  Index is often used as a synonym
    for <EM><A HREF="#searchengine">search engine</A></EM>.
<P>
<DT><NAME="invertedindex"><STRONG>inverted index</STRONG>
<DD>An inverted index is simply a huge table, where rows 
    represent documents and columns represent words.  If document <CITE>x</CITE> 
    contains word <CITE>y</CITE>, there will be a binary <CITE>1</CITE> in row 
    <CITE>x</CITE>, column <CITE>y</CITE> of the table.  To find all 
    <A HREF="#document"><EM>documents</EM></A>&nbsp;  
    that contain a specific word, the computer simply scans for <CITE>1</CITE>s in 
    the appropriate column.  With a little added work, its possible to do more 
    complex searches:  Find all the documents that contain the word "apples" and not 
    the word "oranges."  The table helps speed up search engine performance because 
    only the appropriate columns, instead of the documents themselves, need to be examined.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="keyword"></A><STRONG>keyword</STRONG>
<DD>A word or phrase relevant to the information the user is seeking, entered
    by the user to tell the software how to identify the desired data. The
    database software then examines each record in the database for a match.
    Such matches, called <EM><A HREF="#hit">hits</A></EM>, are selected
    because they contain the entered word or phrase.
	Keyword searching can be improved by combining with other techniques:
	<EM><A HREF="#booleansearch">boolean searching</A></EM>, 
	<EM><A HREF="#proximitysearch">proximity searching</A></EM>, or 
	<EM><A HREF="#vocabcontrol">vocabulary control</A></EM>.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>keyword search</STRONG>
<DD>A search for documents containing one or more words specified by a user.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="link"></A><STRONG>link</STRONG>
<DD>A reference to another Web <A HREF="#document"><EM>document</EM></A>, or another
    section of the same Web document.  Links typically appear as highlighted
    or colored text when displayed in Web <A HREF="#client"><EM>clients</EM></A>.
<P>    
<DT><A NAME="loadbalancing"></A><STRONG>load balancing</STRONG>
<DD>Popular Web services can become too busy to run from a single computer,
	and administrators may choose to distribute the document collection 
	and processing across several networked computers. To reduce the 
	<EM><A HREF="#serverload">server load</A> </EM> that numerous users place
	place on critical resources, the server may be configured to perform
	automatic balancing between available computers. By passing off requests
	to alternating machines, the server can improve response time
	significantly.<P>

<DT><STRONG>metasearch engine</STRONG>
<DD> A metasearch engine is a Web search tool which which lets you access many
    different <A HREF="#searchengine"><EM>search engines</EM></A> from one
    site.  Metasearch engines are classified as either
    <EM><A HREF="#cusi">CUSI</A></EM> or <EM><A HREF="#susi">SUSI</A></EM>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="mirrors"></A><STRONG>mirrors</STRONG>
<DD>When a popular server becomes to busy to support the 
	<EM><A HREF="#serverload">server load</A> </EM>, other sites may volunteer
	to run a copy of the same software and database on their own computers.
	By duplicating, or mirroring, the original server's data, the new
	site can serve local users much faster and reduce the load on the
	first computer.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>multithreaded search</STRONG>
<DD><DD>See <A HREF="#cusi"><EM>CUSI</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="page"></A><STRONG>page</STRONG>
<DD>An <A HREF="#html"><EM>HTML</EM></A> document available for browsing in a
    Web <A HREF="#client"><EM>client's</EM></A> main window.  Some documents
    provide key access or information about a service or 
    organization on special pages, called "public pages" or "homepages".
<P>
<DT><STRONG>phrase search</STRONG>
<DD>A search for <A HREF="#document"><EM>documents</EM></A> containing an
    exact sentence or phrase specified by the user.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="precision"></A><STRONG>precision</STRONG>
<DD>The accuracy with which an information system retrieves relevant items.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="proximitysearch"></A><STRONG>proximity search</STRONG>
<DD>Another technique for improving the quality of 
	<A HREF="#keyword"><EM>keyword searching</EM></A>, a proximity search lets you
	identify documents with certain phrases or word combinations. Such tools
	let you specify multiple words that occur near to one another in the text
	of the original document, and thus a better chance of correspondence, 
	rather than two words that may be located anywhere in a single document.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>query-by-example</STRONG>
<DD>A search in which a user instructs an
    <A HREF="#searchengine"><EM>engine</EM></A> to find more documents that are
    similar to a particular <A HREF="#document"><EM>document</EM></A>.  Also
    called "find similar."
<P>
<DT><STRONG>recall</STRONG>
<DD>The ability of an information system to retrieve stored items.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>relevancy</STRONG>
<DD>How well a <A HREF="#document"><EM>document</EM></A> provides the
    information a user is looking for, as measured by the user.  See also the
    <A HREF="features.html#relevancy">relevancy ranking section</A> of the Web
    Search Tools Features page.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>robot</STRONG>
<DD>See <A HREF="#webickything"><EM>Web robot</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="searchengine"></A><STRONG>search engine</STRONG>
<DD>The software on a Web server that applies user criteria to a database
	of documents to build a match set. The speed of the engine is based
	on the size of the collection and the complexity of the search, as well
	as how the software is written.  Search engine is often used synonymously
	with <A HREF="#webickything"><EM>spider</EM></A> and
	<A HREF="#index"><EM>index</EM></A>, although these are separate components
	that work with the engine.  Popular search engines include
	<A HREF="http://www.altavista.digital.com/">Alta Vista</A>,
	<A HREF="http://www.lycos.com/">Lycos</A>,
	<A HREF="http://www.webcrawler.com/">Web Crawler</A>, and
	<A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo!</A>.  For more information see the
	<A HREF="engines.html">Search Engine Page</A>
<P>
<DT><A NAME="server"></A><STRONG>server</STRONG>
<DD>A computer connected to the internet which allows other computers to access
    certain <A HREF="#document"><EM>documents</EM></A> such as World Wide Web
    <A HREF="#page"><EM>pages</EM></A> from it.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="serverload"></A><STRONG>server load</STRONG>
<DD>The amount of work, such as networking or database searching, that a Web
    <A HREF="#server"><EM>server</EM></A> is performing at any given time. A
    server with a high load will not respond to user requests quickly, or may
    not work reliably.
	A site may choose to replace the server with a faster computer, or
	purchase a second computer to share the processing load and improve
	performance.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>spider</STRONG>
<DD>See <A HREF="#webickything"><EM>Web spider</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>stemming</STRONG>
<DD>See <A HREF="#truncate"><EM>truncation</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="stopwords"></A><STRONG>stop words</STRONG>
<DD>Conjunctions, prepositions, articles, and other words such as
    <EM>and</EM>, <EM>to</EM>, and <EM>a</EM> that appear often in documents,
    yet alone contain little meaning.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="surf"></A><STRONG>surf</STRONG>
<DD>Term for unstructured and serendipitous browsing.  
    It typically refers to the technique of rapidly moving from one Web resource to 
    another--disregarding most content--in order to locate resources of value or interest 
    to the user.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="susi"></A><STRONG> SUSI (Simultaneous Unified Search Index)</STRONG>
<DD> A metasearch engine which simultaneously launches searches
        to several different search engines.  See also
        <A HREF="#cusi"><EM>CUSI</EM></A>.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>thesaurus</STRONG>
<DD>A list of synonyms a search engine can use to find matches for particular
    words if the words themselves don't appear in documents.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="truncate"></A><STRONG>truncation</STRONG>
<DD>Also referred to as "root/suffix management" or "stemming," truncation
    allows some <A HREF="#searchengine"><EM>search engines</EM></A> to recognize and
    shorten long words such as "plants" or "boating" to their root words
    "<A HREF="http://phylogeny.arizona.edu/tree/eukaryotes/green_plants/green_plants.html">plant</A>" and
    "<A HREF="http://www.ten-io.com/clia/premier/">boat</A>." This makes
    searching for such words much easier because it isn't necessary to consider
    every permutation of that word when trying to find it.  See also the
    <A HREF="features.html#truncate">truncation section</A> of the page on
    refining search engine retrieval.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="url"></A><A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html">
    <STRONG>URL (Uniform Resource Locator)</STRONG></A>
<DD>The address of a document on the <A HREF="#www"><EM>World Wide Web</EM></A>.
    The address is contained in a <A HREF="#link"><EM>link</EM></A>, which a
    <A HREF="#client"><EM>client</EM></A> interprets in order to connect with the proper
    server.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>visit</STRONG>
<DD>The process of accessing a <A HREF="#www"><EM>World Wide Web</EM></A>
    <A HREF="#document"><EM>document</EM></A> via a <A HREF="#hypertext"><EM>hypertext</EM></A>
    <A HREF="#link"><EM>link</EM></A>.  
    The anchor of a document that you have visited recently has a different appearance 
    than the anchor of a link you haven't accessed.
<P>    
<DT><A NAME="vocabcontrol"></A><STRONG>vocabulary control</STRONG>
<DD>Vocabulary control means establishing a standard set of
    <A HREF="#keyword"><EM>keywords</EM></A> and identifying documents by these
    keywords, to improve the user's chances of finding every relevant document.
    As a user, selecting a suitable keyword for a search may be problematic
    when there are several related terms that have similar meanings. Unless
	the user's criteria reflect every relevant word in the language, matching 
	documents may be missed in a search.
<P>
<DT><A NAME="webickything"></A><STRONG>Web crawlers, robots, spiders, worms</STRONG>
<DD>Each of these terms are used to describe software that automatically
	downloads and catalogs Internet documents. By reading each document it
	discovers, the software builds a list of additional pages to visit.
	This is a popular method for creating a database suitable for a
	<EM><A HREF="#index">searchable index</A></EM>.<P>

<DT><A NAME="whatsnew"></A><STRONG>what's new? lists</STRONG>
<DD>As more document collections and cool homepages come online, Web 
	servers and other organizations regularly compile them into lists.
	By scanning a few What's New? lists, you can keep track of the 
	latest and greatest pages on the Web.<P>

<DT><A NAME="www"></A><A HREF="http://www.boutell.com/faq/"><STRONG>World Wide Web</A> (also the Web, 
     WWW, or merely W3)</STRONG>
<DD>A method of retrieving information available from certain computers on the
    Internet, making use of a <A HREF="#hypertext"><EM>hypertext</EM></A> interface.
    One <A HREF="#link"><EM>link</EM></A> takes the user to another
    <A HREF="#document"><EM>document</EM></A>, which contains
    <A HREF="#link"><EM>links</EM></A> to other documents (and so forth), and
    these documents can be located on any hypertext-capable system anywhere in
    the world.  The World Wide Web was started by
    <A HREF="http://www.cern.ch/">CERN</A> (the European Laboratory for
    Particle Physics) and seeks to build an international distributed
    hypermedia system.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>worm</STRONG>
<DD>See <A HREF="#webickything"><EM>Web worm</EM></A>.
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
