<html>
<head>
<title>CD-ROM Products in the Gould Library</title>
</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<center><H1>CD-ROM Products in the Gould Library</H1></center>

<P>
<DL>
<DD><STRONG>Reference Collection CD-ROM Resources:</STRONG>
   <P>
   <UL>
      <LI><A HREF="#am">America: History & Life</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#ehraf">Electronic Human Relations Area Files</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#english">English Poetry</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#ethnic">Ethnic News Watch</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#fbis">Foreign Broadcast Information Service</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#hist">Historical Abstracts</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#star">Minneapolis Star-Tribune</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#mla">Modern Language Association International Bibliography</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#pais">PAIS International</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#philo">Philosopher's Index</A>
      <LI><IMG SRC="/images/new.gif" ALT="[New!]"><A HREF="#pol">Politics in America</A>      
      <LI><A HREF="#psych">PsycLit</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#sci">Science Citation Index</A>
      <LI><A HREF="#ssci">Social Science Citation Index</A>
      <P>
      <LI><A HREF="#download">Downloading Your CD-ROM Searches</A>
   </UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<DD><STRONG>Government Documents Collection CD-ROM Resources:</STRONG>
   <P>
   <DL>
      <DD>The Government Documents department receives a large number of 
CD-ROM titles containing indexes, full text, and raw data. They are all 
described in a list of <a 
href=/govdocs/list/THELIST.html>Government Publications</A> on CD-ROM.
   </UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<DD><STRONG>Circulating Collection CD-ROM Resources:</STRONG>
   <P>
   <DL>
      <DD>You can display a list of CD-ROM titles owned by the Carleton Libraries
(excluding U.S. government document CD-ROM titles) by using Muse:
         <P>
	     <DL>
            <DD>select <KBD>N > NUMBERS</KBD> at the main Muse menu
            <DD>select <KBD>C > CALL numbers</KBD>
     	    <DD>type:  <KBD>cd rom</KBD>
     	 </DL>
      <P>
      <DD>Note:  This list will also include Reference Collection CD-ROM titles.
   </UL>
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
<A>
<DL>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="am"><STRONG>America: History & Life (1970- ) station #7 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>America: History & Life <STRONG>(AHL)</STRONG> contains article abstracts and citations of reviews and dissertations 
     covering the United States and Canada on CD-ROM. Searches may 
     be done by subject, author, title or reviewer.
     <P>
     There is a 26-page chapter on using AHL in the <STRONG>Electronic Library</STRONG>
     manual from ABC-CLIO, the publisher of AHL.  This manual is located near the AHL computer
     station.

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="ehraf"><STRONG>Electronic Human Relations Area Files (1995 - ) station #7 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>The Human Relations Area Files (HRAF) is a unique source of information
     pertaining to the cultures of the world. It contains primary source documents
     from books, journal articles, and unpublished manuscripts. HRAF is primarily
     a large microfiche set located on level 4 of the Gould Library in the
     microform room.  A smaller selection of the HRAF microfiche is also
     available on CD-ROM and is entitled "Electronic Human Relations Area
     Files" or "E-HRAF." It is available in the CD-ROM area on level 4. 
<P>
     The HRAF collection is a multicultural and interdisciplinary database. 
     For that reason, it is helpful to researchers in anthropology, psychology,
     political science and other fields. It covers areas of the humanities, 
     social sciences, health related areas, criminal justice and administration. 
     HRAF contains vast amounts of ethnographic information on various societies
     from around the globe.  Learn <A HREF="hraflong.html">more about HRAF</A>. 

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="english"><STRONG>English Poetry (600-1900) station #7 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>English Poetry is a full-text database that covers the works of 
1350 poets.  The index is based on volumes of the New Cambridge 
Bibliography of English Literature.  The database is a 5-CD set: 600-1603, 1603-1700, 1700-1800, 1800-1900 (Poets A-K), and 1800-1900 (Poets L-Z).

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="ethnic"><STRONG>Ethnic News Watch (1991-) station #7 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>Ethnic News Watch is a full-text database on CD-ROM of
     newspapers and magazines from the ethnic and minority press
     in America:  African-American, Arab/Middle Eastern, Asian-
     American, European/Eastern European, Hispanic/Latino,
     Jewish, and Native American publications.  This database also
     indexes articles written in Spanish.
     <P>
     There is a User's Guide to Ethnic NewsWatch in a large 3-ring binder.  This
     binder is shelved near the computer station.

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="fbis"><STRONG>Foreign Broadcast Information Service (1991-) (FBIS) station #7 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>This database provides an index to FBIS daily reports.  These are
     translations of foreign broadcasts, newspapers and major
     journals originating in countries around the world.  The 
     index can be searched as a whole, through a number of 
     bibliographic access points, or descriptive terms assigned by 
     NewsBank indexers.  Two levels of searching are available, to 
     accommodate both novice and experienced searchers.
<P>
     The microform reports are located in Government Documents,
     and the SUDOC number is <STRONG><KBD>PREX 7.10:</KBD></STRONG>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="hist"><STRONG>Historical Abstracts (1977- ) station #7 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>History Abstracts <STRONG>(HA)</STRONG> is a bibliography of the world's historical literature on CD-ROM.  
     It contains abstracts and shorter annotations from approximately 
     2,100 journals published in over 80 countries in almost 40 
     languages.  These are the major historical journals of the 
     world, including many journals of regional history, as well 
     as the most important titles in the related social sciences 
     and humanities.  It also indexes books and dissertations.
     <P>
     There is a 27-page chapter on using HA in the <STRONG>Electronic Library</STRONG>
     manual from ABC-CLIO, the publisher of HA.  This manual is located near the HA computer
     station.

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="mla"><STRONG>MLA International Bibliography (1963- ) </STRONG><BR>
<DD>The MLA International Bibliography, produced by the Modern 
     Language Association of America, is no longer available on CD-ROM.  It is, however, available on  
     <A HREF="/electronic/online/mla.html">the Web</A>.

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>     

<DT><A NAME="star"><STRONG>Minneapolis Star-Tribune (1986- ) station #8 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>Current full-text newspaper articles, including obituaries, 
     special sections, and early and late editions on CD-ROM. 

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="pais"><STRONG>PAIS International (1972- ) station #5 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>Public Affairs Information Service, Inc. includes 
     bibliographic records from the literature of public policy, 
     social policy, and the social sciences.

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>  

<DT><A NAME="philo"><STRONG>Philosopher's Index (1985- ) station #7 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>The Philosopher's Index provides indexing and abstracts from 
books and over 300 journals of philosophy and related 
interdisciplinary fields.  The Philosopher's Index database is 
produced by the Philosophy Documentation Center at Bowling 
Green State University and corresponds to the print publication 
"The Philosopher's Index." It is a major source of information in the 
areas of aesthetics, epistemology, ethics, logic, and metaphysics; it 
is also a rich source of material on the philosophy of various 
disciplines, such as education, history, law, religion, and science. 
The Philosopher's Index indexes philosophy books and journals in 
English, French, German, Spanish and Italian.
<P>
Includes book reviews.

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="pol"><STRONG>Politics in America 1996 - station #4 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>Politics in America 1996 on CD-ROM, produced by the Congressional Quarterly, 
is a guide to the 104th U.S. Congress. You'll find profiles for every member of the 
104th Congress, including each member's achievements, legislative priorities, and personal
style. Accompanying each profile are key facts on each member including their: address, 
phone number, biographical data, committee assignments, election results, key votes, 
campaign finance data, and more. Also, there's a profile of every congressional district, 
with demographic, economic and political
information.
<P>
The Politics in America 1996 CD-ROM includes all the information from the book version
(located in our reference collection at <STRONG><KBD>REF JK 1010 .P64 1996</STRONG></KBD>)
plus expanded district information from another reference book, CQ's <CITE>Congressional Districts 
in the 1990's</CITE> (<STRONG><KBD>JK1341 .C64 1993</STRONG></KBD>). Click your mouse on any state district 
description and you'll travel there instantly in maps, charts, and narrative that reveal the demographic, 
economic and political features of the area in the nation's political landscape.
     
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="psych"><STRONG>PsycLIT (1974- ) station #6 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>PsycLIT, produced by the American Psychological Association, 
     contains two databases. Journal Articles contains citations 
     and summaries of the world's serial literature in psychology 
     and related subjects database from 1974 to the present.  Book 
     Chapters & Books contains summaries of English-language 
     chapters and books in psychology and related disciplines 
     published worldwide from 1987 to the present.
     
<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="sci"><STRONG>SCI [Science Citation Index] (1995- ) campus network </STRONG><BR>
<DD>SCI indexes over 3,400 of the most important scientific and technical jouranals worldwide.  It covers
    every substantive item from these journals, including original research articles, corrections,
    discussions, editorial material, biographical items, chronologies, letters, meeting abstracts,
    and reviews.
    <P>
    The primary areas covered in SCI are:
    <P>
    <UL>
    <UL>
    <LI>agricultural, biological, and environmental sciences
    <LI>engineering, technology, and applied sciences
    <LI>medical and life sciences
    <LI>physical and chemical sciences
    </UL>
    </UL>
    <P>
    The SCI database is extremely powerful because it can be used to retrieve
    information about research that has been referenced (cited) in an earlier written
    work.
    <P>
    SCI can be confusing to a novice user, so we suggest you ask for
    assistance from our <A HREF="/staff/charlie/">Science Librarian</A> or 
    at the <A HREF="/reference/refdesk.html">Reference Desk</A>.

<P>
<HR ALIGN="center" WIDTH=50%>
<P>

<DT><A NAME="ssci"><STRONG>SSCI [Social Science Citation Index] (1981- ) station #4 </STRONG><BR>
<DD>SSCI is an index to the journal literature of the social sciences.  It fully covers
    over 1,400 journals spanning 50 social science disciplines.  In addition, SSCI
    also covers items relevant to the social sciences selected from 6,000 other
    multidisciplinary journals.  Includes book reviews.
    <P>
    The SSCI database is extremely powerful because it can be used to retrieve
    information about research that has been referenced (cited) in an earlier written
    work.
    <P>
    SSCI can be confusing to a novice user, so we suggest you ask for
    assistance at the <A HREF="/reference/refdesk.html">Reference Desk</A>.
</DL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="download"><STRONG>Downloading your Searches</STRONG></A><BR>
<P>
You can save your database searches on disk to browse through 
later.  Advantages to downloading are numerous:

<UL>
<LI>     Saving to disk is faster than printing.
<LI>     Saving to disk saves paper.
<LI>     You don't have to retype your citations; you merely cut and paste
them into your word processing document.
</UL>

To download, you will need to bring a 3 1/2" MS-DOS formatted disk 
to the
library.  Follow the directions at the individual 
CD-ROM search stations, because the downloading procedure 
varies from station to station.

To read what you've saved, you will need to use an MS-DOS or 
Windows word processor like WordPerfect, Write or Works.  Your 
searches are saved on disk as DOS TEXT. Ask for help in the 
computer center if you get stuck.

<p>
<hr>
<p>
