<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College Library - Full-Text Electronic Resources</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><H1>Full-Text Electronic Periodicals</H1></CENTER>
<P>
<B>Contents:</B>
<A HREF="#arl">ARL Directory</A> |
<A HREF="#cic-ejc">CIC-EJC</A> |
<A HREF="#e-doc">e-doc</A> |
<A HREF="#estand">Electronic Newsstand</A> | 
<A HREF="#english">English Server</A> | 
<A HREF="#pmuse">Project Muse</A> | 
<A HREF="#scp">Scholarly Communications Project</A> | 
<A HREF="#houston">Scholarly Web Journals</A>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Note:</FONT>  <A HREF="#pmuse">Project Muse</A> is the only resource listed on this page which 
the Carleton Library  takes as a paid subscription.  That is, the Carleton library underwrites access fees to the 
Project Muse online journals.  The other tools listed on this page are directories created by other libraries or 
agencies.  These guides offer access to publications which are available free of charge.
<P>
<hr size=3>
<P>
<P>
<DL>
<DL>
<A NAME="arl"><DT><A HREF="http://arl.cni.org/scomm/edir/index.html">Association of Research Libraries
Directory of Electronic Journals and Newsletters</A>
<DD>This resource contains descriptions and links to over 1,700 scholarly periodical publications.
<P>
The <A HREF="http://arl.cni.org/index.html">Association of Research Libraries (ARL)</A>
is a not-for-profit membership organization comprising the 
libraries of North American research institutions and operates as a forum for the exchange of ideas and as 
an agent for collective action. The mission of ARL is to shape and influence forces affecting the future of
research libraries in the process of scholarly communication.  ARL programs and services promote equitable access
to, and effective use of recorded knowledge in support of teaching, research, scholarship, and community service.
The Association articulates the concerns of research libraries and their institutions, forges coalitions, influences
information policy development, and supports innovation and improvement in research library operations.
<P>
<A NAME="cic-ejc"><DT><A HREF="http://ejournals.cic.net/toc.Topic.html">CICNet Electronic Journals Collection</A>
<DD>Links to +50 online journals from the <a href="http://www.cic.net/cic/cic.html">Committee on 
Institutional Cooperation</a> (CIC) Electronic Journals Collection (EJC), a prototype electronic journal management
system coordinated by the librarians of the CIC member universities, and the staffs of CICNet, Inc. and the CIC.  
Ultimately, this collection aims to be an authoritative source of electronic research
and academic serial publications -- incorporating all freely distributed scholarly electronic journals 
available online. The CIC-EJC serves as the electronic journal collection for the libraries of the
<a href=http://www.cic.net/cic/links.html>CIC member universities</a>. 
<p>
The CIC is the academic consortium of the members of the Big
Ten athletic conference and the University of Chicago. The
CIC-EJC is a collaborative initiative between the librarians
of the CIC member universities, CICNet, and the CIC Center
for Library Initiatives. For more information about the CIC,
see <a
href="http://www.cic.net/cic/cic.html">http://www.cic.net/cic/cic.html</a>
<P>
<A NAME="e-doc"><DT><A HREF="http://www.edoc.com/ejournal/">e-doc: WWW Virtual Library's Electronic Journal Listing</A>
<DD>This absolutely essential directory of electronic full-text publications exists as a portion of the WWW Virtual
Library, a worldwide project maintained by volunteers.  Types of publications included here are academicand
reviewedjournals, other college and university publications, email newsletters, magazines, and newspapers. 
<P>
<A NAME="estand"><DT><A HREF="http://www.enews.com/">Electronic Newsstand</A>
<DD>Here is the home to more than 200 magazine sites. It's also home to a list of links to 
magazine-related sites elsewhere on the Web: 2,000 in all! Newsstand host a variety of magazines, 
ranging from prestigious (The New Yorker, The New Republic, and The Economist, to name a few), to 
the obscure.
<P>
Note: When Newsstand "hosts" a publication, it may not provide <EM>precisely</EM> the same content as you'll
find in the paper versions of these publications.  That determination is made by the magazine publisher.
However, at the very least, you'll find sample articles, a table of contents, and some cover art.  Newstand
also compiles an archive of articles from their client publications, which
you can search by topic. 
<P>
<A NAME="english"><DT><A HREF="http://english-www.hss.cmu.edu/journals/">English Server Journals</A>
<DD>Links to +50 journals from the pioneering "English Server" at at Carnegie Mellon
University.  This resource is managed by students, faculty, and staff in the CMU English Department. 
It has been publishing humanities texts to readers online for seven years, today offering over ten
thousand texts in many disciplines.  
<P>
<A NAME="pmuse"><DT><A HREF="pmuse.html">Project Muse:  Scholarly Journals from Johns Hopkins University</A>
<DD>Not be confused with <A HREF="/muse/muse.html">Muse</A> (the online library catalog of the same name at 
Carleton College) Project Muse offers worldwide networked access to the full text of selected scholarly journals from
the Johns Hopkins University Press.    
<P>
<A NAME="scp"><DT><A HREF="http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/ejpage.html">Scholarly Communications Project</A>
<DD>Links to +20 online journals available to academic communities via the Internet. You can <A HREF="http://scholar.lib.vt.edu/scpabout.html">
learn more about the project</A>.
<P>
<A NAME="houston"><DT><A HREF="http://info.lib.uh.edu/wj/webjour.html">Scholarly Journals Distributed Via the World-Wide Web</A>
<DD>Here you'll find "links to established Web-based scholarly journals that offer access to English language
article files without requiring user registration or fees." From the University of Houston Libraries.
<P> 
</DL>
</DL>
<P>
<hr>
<p>
<CENTER><A HREF="/periodicals/index.html">Return to the Periodical Resources Page</A>
<P>
<A HREF="/electronic/electronic.html">Return to the Electronic Resources Page</A></CENTER>
<BR>
