<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Classics Page
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="marb.jpeg" text="#000000" Link="#FF0000" vLINK="#770077">

<center><IMG SRC="claspage.jpeg"></center><p><p><p>

<hr>
<center><img src="nbcc.jpeg"></center>
This page is Certified to be Content-Free by the National Board of Content Certification.  Please report
any actual content on this page to the NBCC if it should be discovered.
<hr>
<center><h3>Links to Classics Sites</h3></center>


<dl>

<dt><a href=http://rome.classics.lsa.umich.edu/welcome.html>UMich's Dept. of Classics & Mediterranean Archaeology Homepage</a><BR>
<dd>A really, really, REALLY comprehensive listing of sites concerning the study of Classics.<P><P>

<dt><A href=http://www.jura.uni-sb.de/Rechtsgeschichte/Ius.Romanum/english.html>Roman Law Homepage</a><br>
<dd>Everything you always wanted to know about Roman Law but were afraid to ask.  Check out the <a href="http://www.jura.uni-sb.de/Rechtsgeschichte/Ius.Romanum/origo.html">Latin version</a> of this homepage--wicked awesome.<p>

<dt><A href=http://the-tech.mit.edu/Classics/index.html>The Tech Classics Archive</a><br>
<dd>WOW! Hundreds of works in translation by many authors, in HTML format.  A must see for any classics type, and I mean MUST.<p>

<dt><a href=http://osman.classics.washington.edu/libellus/libellus.html>The Libellus Project</a><br>
<dd>An ongoing project dedicated to bringing <b>you</b> all the best Latin and Greek texts.  Unfortunately, the texts are in TeX, a Unix-based format.  But you can't have <b>everything,</b> can you?<p>

<dt><a href=http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/~www_sglah/homeclass.html>University of St. Andrews School of Greek, Latin and Ancient History</a><br>
<dd>These Brits are near and dear to my heart, since I spent the last year with them.  So they're on my page.<p>

<dt><a href=http://www.yahoo.com/Arts/Humanities/Classics/>The Yahoo Classics Page</a></br>
<dd>Yahoo is one of the first World Wide Web indices, still going strong.  Their classics page offers links to interesting classics sites.  Surprise, surprise.<p>

<dt><a href=http://ccat.sas.upenn.edu/~joef/vergil/home.html>Pagina Domestica P. Vergili Maronis</a><br>
<dd>Links to sites of interest for scholars of the Roman Epic poet, including online texts, translations, and commentaries.<p>

<dt>


</dl>

<p><p>
<p><p>

<H2>Newsgroup</h2>

<dl>

<dt><A href=news:sci.classics>Sci.Classics</a><Br>
<dd>There's always something new (or, perhaps, ancient!) and different in this group.  Discussion topics range from discussions of grammar to how to find true-type Greek fonts for your Mac.  A must see for a classicist. <P><P>
</dl></BODY>

