<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Anthropological Literature file (ANL)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<H1>Anthropological Literature</H1>
</CENTER>

Recognized as one of the most important research tools available in the fields of 
anthropology and archaeology, the <STRONG>Anthropological Literature (ANL)</STRONG> 
database contains records describing articles and essays in anthropology and archaeology of
two or more pages, from works published in English and other European languages.
The Gould Library continues to maintain its paper copy of this resource in the Reference Collection 
under the call number: <STRONG><KBD>GN1 .A67 (Vol. 11, no. 1- )</KBD></STRONG>    
<P>
<PRE>
 SUBJECT COVERAGE    Archaeology                   Geography
                     Art History                   Geology
                     Biological Anthropology       History
                     Cultural Anthropology         Linguistics
                     Demography                    Music
                     Economics                     Physical Anthropology
                     Ethnohistory                  Psychology
                     Folklore                      Religious Studies
                     Genetics                      Social Anthropology
                                                   Sociology

DATES OF COVERAGE    1984 to the present

         SUPPLIER    Tozzer Library, Harvard University

 UPDATE FREQUENCY    QUARTERLY

             SIZE    Nearly 100,000 records as of April 1995 with
                     approximately 2,000 added at each update
</PRE>
<HR>
<H3>Sample ANL Record</H3>
<PRE>
          AUTHOR: Marks, Jonathan.
           TITLE: What's old and new in molecular phylogenetics / Jonathan
                  Marks.
PHYSICAL DETAILS: ill.
              IN: American Journal of Physical Anthropology - New York,
                  ISSN 0002-9483 v. 85, no. 2, 1991. pp. 207-219.

        SUBJECTS: Phylogeny--Research.
                  DNA replication.
                  Molecular evolution--Research.
                  Primates--Speciation.
</PRE>
<HR>
