<html>
<head>
<title>Evaluating a Source</title>
</head>
<body>
<br>
<center><h2>Tips for Evaluating a Source</h2></center>


<DL>
<DT><strong>1. Author</strong>
<DD> Who is the author?  What is his/her background?  Is the author qualified to write the work?
<P>
<DT><strong>2. Intended audience</strong>
<DD>To what audience is the author writing?  Is it intended for the general public, for scholars, teacher, etc.?  Is this reflected in the authors style of writing or presentation?
<P>
<DT><strong>3. Author Bias</strong>
<DD>Does the author have any biases or make assumptions upon which the rationale of the article rests?  What are they?
<P>
<DT><strong>4. Research</strong>
<DD>What method of conducting the research was employed by the author?  Is the article based on personal opinion or experience, interviews, library research?
<P>
<DT><strong>5. Author conclusion</strong>
<DD>At what conclusion does the author arrive?
<P>
<DT><strong>6. Conclusion justification</strong>
<DD>Does the author satisfactorily justify the conclusion from the research or experience?  Why or why not?
<P>
<DT><strong>7. Relationship to other works</strong>
<DD>How does this article compare with similar works?  Is it in tune with or in opposition to other examples of scholarship?  Are there writings, schools of thought, or philosophies with which this one agrees or disagrees and that one should be aware?
<P>
<DT><strong>8. Attachments</strong>
<DD>Are there significant attachments such as appendices, bibliographies, illustrations, etc.?  If not should there be?
<P>
<DT><strong>9. Time Frame</strong>
<DD>Is the work current?  Is this important?  How does the time it was written reflect on the work?
</DL>

<hr>
<p>
<cite>
Maintained by <A HREF="/staff/terry/terry.html">Terry Metz, temetz@carleton.edu</A>
<br> Last updated: September 12, 1995
</cite>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
