<html>
<head>
<title>Library Instruction - Internet Citing</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<center><H2>Tips for Citing Internet Sources</H2></center>
Standards are not yet agreed upon for citing sources gleaned from the Internet.  A recent article in 
<A HREF = "#chron">The Chronicle of Higher Education**</A> discusses the debate over citing Internet 
resources.  Scholars and students of all kinds are finding and using Internet resources, but 
<strong>citing</strong> these sources is a challenge because the citation format differs significantly 
from formats developed for print resources. 
<P>
As a result, librarians and researchers have been adapting or creating guidelines for use 
in citing electronic sources, but they face some unique concerns, including:
<UL>
<LI>Creating a permanent citation for an online resource that has relocated or whose content has changed
<LI>Directing readers to a specific point in a cited document in the absence of page numbers
<LI>Citing mailing list documents that are not permanently archived for verification
</UL>
<P>
Standards for citing Internet sources will undoubtedly evolve.  In the meantime, 
however, you may refer to the guides below for help in citing your online resources:
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<DL>
<DT><STRONG><A HREF = "http://www.uvm.edu/~xli/reference/estyles.html">Bibliographic
Formats for Citing Electronic Information</A></STRONG> by Nancy B. Crane and Xia Li
<P>
<DD>This brief guide provides examples for APA and MLA styles that are illustrated further 
    in Li's and Crane's <cite>The Official Internet World Guide to Electronic Styles: 
    A Handbook to Citing Electronic Information</cite>.
    <P>
    <strong>[Note:</strong>  This book is on order for the Library.  In the meantime, 
    you may also consult the authors' book <cite>Electronic Style : a Guide to Citing 
    Electronic Information</cite> (Westport : Meckler, c1993) at 
    <strong><KBD>Reference PN171.D37 L5 1993]</KBD></strong> (It's a thin paperback.)
<P>
<DT><STRONG><A HREF="http://www.cas.usf.edu/english/walker/mla.html">MLA-Style
Citations of Electronic Sources</A></STRONG> by Janice R. Walker</A>
<P>
<DD>Endorsed by the Alliance for Computers & Writing, this style sheet is widely referenced 
    among authors and editors who seek to emulate Modern Language Association style.  It
    includes examples for citing a variety of networked sources (e.g., e-mail; telnet, FTP,
    gopher, and WWW sites; as well as discussion list and network news citations).
<P> 
<DT><STRONG><A HREF="http://www.nyu.edu/pages/psychology/WEAPAS/">Web 
Extension to American Psychological Association Style (WEAPAS)</A></STRONG>
<P>
<DD>Proposed standard for referencing online documents in scientific publications.  Presents 
    an alternative to the unweildy "path" statements suggested for online resources in the 1994 
    <cite>Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association</cite> (p.218-220).
<P>
<DT><STRONG><A HREF="http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/users/maw13/citation.html">Citation style for 
Internet Sources</A></STRONG> by Mark Wrainright (12 May 1995)
<P>
<DD>Suggestions from participants on the <KBD>alt.usage.english</KBD> newsgroup.  An attempt to 
    reconcile online documents with the published MLA guidelines.
<P>
<DT><STRONG><A HREF="http://www.nrlssc.navy.mil/meta/bibliography.html">How Do You Cite
URL's in a Bibliography?</A></STRONG> by Jeff Beckleheimer (1994, August 26) 
<P>
<DD>Biomedical emphasis, based on the <cite>National Library of Medicine
Recommended Formats for Bibliographic Citation</cite> (K. Patrias, 1991).
<P>
<DT><STRONG><A HREF="http://lamp.cs.utas.edu.au/citation.txt">Citing E-Texts Summary</A></STRONG>
<P>
<DD>Suggestions from participants on the LINGUIST Listserv.
<P>
<DT><STRONG><A HREF = "gopher://h-net.msu.edu:70/00/lists/H-AFRICA/internet-cit">A Brief
Citation Guide for Internet Sources in History and the Humanities</A></STRONG> by Melvin E. Page
<P>
<DD>Guidelines posted to the "H-AFRICA" discussion list.
</DL>
<P>
<A NAME = "chron">
<HR>
<P>
** Guernsey, Lisa.  "Cyberspace Citations." <cite>The Chronicle of Higher Education,</cite>
12 January 1996.
<P>
