<html> 

<head> 

<title>"Secrets" of Copyright Revealed</title> 

</head>


<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<cite>From <strong>Bookmark, a Newsletter of the <a href="/">Carleton Library</a></strong>, Volume 4, Number 2, Spring/Summer 1996<br>
Copyright &#169; 1996 by Michael D. Current</cite>
<hr>

<h4 align=right>Copyright</h4>
<h2>"Secrets" of Copyright Revealed</h2>
<p>
	It seems that many people in the academic community are concerned about copyright these days. This may be due in part to the recent explosion of information produced and made available in electronic format. Not only can networked electronic information be much easier to access, it can also be much easier to duplicate than information published in traditional paper media.
<p>	One might say that in an Information Age, it can only be more important than ever to be familiar with those pesky copyright laws. Luckily, for the most part the idea of copyright translates nicely into the electronic world.
<p>	So what should we know about copyright? First of all, let's back up a bit. Ideas, symbols, names, forms of expression...we can refer to all of these as intellectual property. Just as with other forms of property, there are certain sets of laws designed to protect intellectual property from being abused, stolen, etc.
<p>	There are three main kinds of intellectual property protection available under US law:
<ul>
<li><em>Copyright</em> protects original creative expressions, including writing, architectural design, software, graphic arts, motion pictures, and sound recordings.
<li><em>Patents</em> are available to protect novel and useful inventions. This includes machines, man-made products, compositions of matter, and processing methods.
<li><em>Trademarks</em> protect distinctive pictures, symbols or words from being used by competitors for identifying similar products.
</ul>


<p>

	Now back to copyrights. What rights do you get when you own a copyright for an original, creative work? You have the right to control:
<ul>
<li>the reproduction of your work,
<li>the production of works based on your work,
<li>the distribution of your work,
<li>the performance of your work,
<li>the display of your work.
</ul>
<p>
	Copyright protection begins from the moment of creation. That is, you don't have to register your work with the government, and you don't have to display a special copyright notice on your work to enjoy basic copyright protection. There are definite benefits to taking these two steps if you ever need to take someone to task for infringing on your copyright, but no registration or warning notice is required for protection.
<p>	When do copyrights expire? Works by a single author are protected for 50 years beyond the life of the author. Works by multiple authors: 50 years beyond the life of the last surviving author. Many works, though, are "works made for hire," or works created at the direction of someone else (like a company). Works made for hire are protected for 75 years from first publication or 100 years from creation, whichever is shorter.
<p>
	Copyright protection can also end if the copyright owner specifically gives up the rights to a work; the work then enters the "public domain." This term refers to any intellectual property that is not covered by any form of protection. Anyone may do anything with material in the public domain.
<p>	Thanks to several international treaties that the US has signed, works copyrighted in this country are also protected in most other countries around the world. Chief among these treaties is the <a href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/treaties/berne/overview.html">Berne Convention</a>, which the US finally agreed to join in 1989. As a member of Berne, the US is also obligated to honor copyrights held in other Berne member countries. The Berne Convention also mandates many of the features of copyright protection for member countries, so copyright laws (though not necessarily their enforcement) are relatively uniform.
<p>	While basic facts about copyright are often quite straight forward, some of the details quickly become fuzzy when examined closely. Fortunately there is plenty of reliable copyright information available. Your friendly librarians are here to help you find it, and maybe even help make some sense of it!

<h5 align=right><a href="/staff/michael/">MICHAEL CURRENT</a></h6>

<h5 align=right><a href="/ils/"><em>InterLibrary Services</em></a></h6>
<hr>
<h4 align=center>Copyright information can be found at the U.S. Copyright Office's Web site:
<p align=center><a href=" http://lcweb.loc.gov/copyright/"><IMG SRC="http://lcweb.loc.gov/copyright/header1.gif"
ALT="[U.S. Copyright Office Home Page]"></a>
<hr>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
