<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>HTML Exercises For Beginners - Exercise 8
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>Answers to Exercise 8</H1></CENTER>
<HR>
<PRE>
&lt;HTML&gt;
&lt;HEAD&gt;
&lt;TITLE&gt;Overview of HTML-Exercise 8
&lt;/TITLE&gt;
&lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;BODY&gt;
Wow, in seven short exercises, you've learned how to make an effective
page of text on the Net.  You know how to:
&lt;P&gt;
&lt;OL&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;Use basic HTML format.
&lt;UL&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;HTML&gt; and &lt;/HTML&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;HEAD&gt; and &lt;/HEAD&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;TITLE&gt; and &lt;/TITLE&gt;
&lt;/UL&gt;
&lt;P&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;Make several kinds of lists.
&lt;UL&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;unnumbered
&lt;LI&gt;numbered (ordered)
&lt;LI&gt;definition
&lt;LI&gt;nested
&lt;/UL&gt;
&lt;P&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;Use different levels of headings, from
&lt;UL&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;H1&gt;Large&lt;/H1&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;H6&gt;to small&lt;/H6&gt;
&lt;/UL&gt;
&lt;/OL&gt;
&lt;P&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;Include extended quotations (like this one):
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;The Americans have need of the telephone, but we do not.&lt;BR&gt;
We have plenty of messenger boys.&lt;BR&gt;
--&lt;L&gt;Sir William Preece, chief engineer of the British Post Office, in 1876.&lt;/I&gt;
&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;
&lt;P&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;Use logical and physical styles to make text appear:
&lt;UL&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;B&gt;bold&lt;/B&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;I&gt;italic&lt;/I&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;TT&gt;fixed-width font&lt;/TT&gt;
&lt;/UL&gt;
&lt;P&gt;              
&lt;LI&gt;Use paragraph tags, special characters, and horizontal rules.
&lt;/OL&gt;
&lt;P&gt;
In addition to all &lt;B&gt;that&lt;/B&gt;, you've learned several definitions.  You know that:&lt;p&gt;
&lt;DL&gt;
&lt;DT&gt;The &lt;I&gt;Internet&lt;/I&gt;
&lt;DD&gt;is a collection of connected networks all over the world.
&lt;DT&gt;The &lt;I&gt;World Wide Web&lt;/I&gt;
&lt;DD&gt;was started by CERN (the European Laboratory for Particle Physics) and seeks to build 
a distributed hypermedia system.
&lt;DT&gt;&lt;I&gt;HTML&lt;/I&gt;
&lt;DD&gt;stands for Hypertext Markup Language and is a tool for creating multi-layered and 
linked documents published on the Web.
&lt;/DL&gt;
&lt;P&gt;
Now maybe it's time to send e-mail to your boss at &lt;ADDRESS&gt;your_boss@work.com&lt;/ADDRESS&gt;
and tell him or her how smart you are!?
&lt;P&gt;
&lt;HR ALIGN=&quot;center&quot; WIDTH=&quot;12%&quot;&gt;
&lt;HR ALIGN=&quot;center&quot; WIDTH=&quot;30%&quot;&gt;
&lt;HR ALIGN=&quot;center&quot; WIDTH=&quot;70%&quot;&gt;
&lt;/BODY&gt;
&lt;/HTML&gt;
</PRE>
