<HEAD>
<TITLE>HTML Exercises For Beginners - Exercise 11
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="yourimage.gif"></CENTER>
<H1>This is your home page!</H1>
<H4>Some text explaining what this home page is, why it exists, who you are, or what
your organization does.
<P>
Not too much, just some general quick-to-read description that either (a) hooks people
into reading more or (b) tells them to move on 'cause this isn't what they wanted.
<P>
Now you may want to add a list (often of hyperlinks) to:
<UL>
<LI>Other pages in your (future) site
<LI>URLs for your favorite Web sites or
<LI>Other, related Web sites
</UL>
It's just this simple.</H4>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="welcome.html">Main Menu</A></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<CITE>
Maintained by <A HREF="/staff/terry/terry.html">Terry Metz, temetz@carleton.edu</A>
<BR> Last updated: February 5, 1997
</CITE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT20-B04-225</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA015-000159-B022-20</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.library.carleton.edu:80/webtutorial/graphicstop10.html 137.22.11.46 19970217154302 text/html 12133
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
