<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carleton College LiBRary HTML and Web Site Resource: Top 10 Rules for Creating Graphics for the Web
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<A NAME="contents">
<HR SIZE=7>
<CENTER><H1>Top 10 Rules for Creating Graphics for the Web</H1></CENTER>
<HR SIZE=3>
<OL>
<STRONG>
<LI><A HREF="#1">Design for the average user.</A>
<P> 
<LI><A HREF="#2">Smaller is Better.  Period.</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#3">Design for a computer screen, not the printed page.</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#4">Stop thinking in terms of inches.</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#5">You have two different format choices--GIF and JPEG.</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#6">Color is not color is not color.</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#7">An image is an image, but it may not save any words at all.</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#8">There is one thing you can do to make your image appear to<BR>
                 take less time to load than it really does.</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#9">You will need <EM>good</EM> graphics software.</A>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="#10">Get and read <EM>Designing Web Graphics</EM>.</A>
</STRONG>
</OL>
<P>
Adapted from Jurist, Susan, "Top 10 Rules for Creating Graphics for the Web," <CITE><STRONG>College & Research
Libraries News</STRONG></CITE>, July/August 1996, pp. 418-421, and used by permission of its author.
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<A NAME="1"><H3>1.  Design for the average user.</H3></A>
<UL>
<LI>The average user is:
    <UL>
	<LI>looking at a 14" monitor
	<LI>using the Netscape browser
    </UL>
</UL>
<P>
Unless you have a special audience in mind, don't design for the highest, or lowest, common denominator.
Go average and you should be save for most users.
<P>
<UL>
<LI>The average user is:
    <UL>
	<LI>using either a PC or a Mac
    </UL>
</UL>
<P>
While Macs are less than 10% of the installed personal computer user base, Mac users are proportionally more likely
to use the Net.  If you use only one system, and most of us do, always remember the other exists and the other is 
different.	
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR SIZE=2>
<A NAME="2"><H3>2.  Smaller is Better.  Period.</H3></A>
<UL>
<LI>Smaller is better because:
    <UL>
    <LI>smaller loads faster
	<LI>the average user is sitting in front of a 14" monitor
	</UL>
</UL>
<P>
Waiting for a large graphic to load isn't fun.  If some of your intended audience are sitting at home in front
of not-very fast machines connected by a 14.4 or 28.8 modem, they're going to be more than board.  They're not
going to wait to see what you have to show them.
<P>
Yes, some of us doing the designing are using 17" or 20" screens, but we're the minority.  You don't want to
design a graphic that takes up so much screen real estate that essential information is off the screen, or 
design one that can't be fully seen without scrolling.
<P>
Also remember, smaller for a digital image doesn't mean just two-dimensional size.  File format, bit-depth, 
and type of image are also important factors.  We'll talk about these issues in the following rules. 
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR SIZE=2>
<A NAME="3"><H3>3.  Design for a computer screen, not the printed page.</H3></A>
<UL>
<LI>Printed 8.5" x 11" pages are usually designed for a "portrait"; i.e., the height is greater than the width
<LI>Computer screens on the other hand are "landscape"; i.e., the width is greater than the height.
</UL>
<P>
Stop thinking horizontally.  The first screen someone comes to on a Web page is the most essential.  If it
doesn't grab them, they won't scroll down to see what else you're offering.
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR SIZE=2>
<A NAME="4"><H3>4.  Stop thinking in terms of inches.</H3></A>
From now on, you have to start thinking in pixels, the dots of light that make up an image on a screen.
<UL>
	<LI>The average screen has a resolution of 640 x 480 pixels.
	<LI>However, you need to create images that are no larger than 600 x 400 pixels.  Why?
	<LI>Because you don't have the whole screen as your canvas.
</UL>
<P>Both the browser software and the computer's operating system take up screen real estate, too.  With Netscape,
assuming you have both the square buttons for home, etc., and the locating bar showing, the loss is 124 pixels
in height and 21 pixels in width.  That means the maximum any image should be is 619 x 356.  But since the
Netscape browser defaults to an opening size of approximately 600 pixels, it's probably safer to create images
no larger than 600 x 400.  For banners across the top of the page, your goal should be 500 x 100 or less. 
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR SIZE=2>
<A NAME="5"><H3>5.  You have two different format choices--GIF and JPEG.</H3></A>
Choosing which graphics file format to use isn't that difficult if you consider the following:


										[PUT TABLE HERE]


<DL>
	<DT><STRONG>In-line Images</STRONG>
	<DD>In-line images are those that appear on the screen with the HTML-generated text.  All browsers
		can display GIF in-line images, and most, but not all, can display JPEG in-line images.  JPEG
		in-line images will crash some browsers.
    <P>
	<DT><STRONG>Bit-depth</STRONG>
	<DD>Bit-depth refers to how many bits each pixel has to describe a color:
	<P>
	<UL>
		<LI>2-bit images are black and white
		<LI>8-bit images can describe up to 256 colors (or shades of gray)
		<LI>24-bit images can display millions of colors
	</UL>
	<P>
	In the real world, the eye (and color film) can see millions of colors.  If you have a color photograph or
	a color painting, you would want millions of colors as well.
	<P>
	But our friend the average user has a monitor that can show only 8-bit color.  When an 8-bit monitor 
	displays a 24-bit image (or when you change a 24-bit image to 8-bit), the software "dithers" the 246
	allowable colors to approximate the colors it can't show you.  The dithering is a pattern tha combines
	two or more colors to simulate a third--and can be quite distracting.
	<P>
	All Net browser software will dither a 24-bit image for an 8-bit system, but they won't do as good  a
	job as graphics software like Adobe Photoshop.
	<P>
	<DT><STRONG>The overall characteristics of your image should also affect your choice of file types.</STRONG>
	<DD>The GIF compression algorithm works best with flat areas of color
	<P>
	JPEG, on the other hand, is not the best for images with flat areas of color or high contrast.  The JPEG
	compression algorithm tends to leave "artifacts" (small areas of off-color pixels) that become obvious
	in high-contrast pictures.
	<P>
	<DT><STRONG>Transparency</STRONG>
	<DD>The final, and often deciding reason to use GIF in-lin images is if you need the effect of 
	transparency where the background or background colors show through (used most often on decorative
	text.  <A HREF="http://www.gpo.ucop.edu/">See the GPO Gate example</A> from the University of 
	California Library System.)  The JPEG format doesn't support transparency.
</DL> 
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR SIZE=2>
<A NAME="6"><H3>6.  Color is not color is not color.</H3></A>
<UL>
	<LI>Different computers display colors differently.
	<LI>You can't guarantee that the colors you see are the colors someone else sees.
</UL>
<P>
You've created this gorgeous color scheme, for your Web pages on your PC.  You tell everyone you know the URL.
One of your friends is on a Mac and tells you it's the gaudiest thing she's ever seen.  Another friend, who uses
a PC, says the colors all clash.  Are they wrong?
<P>
No.
<P>
Every computer system displays colors differently.  Not only are Mac system colors (the default 256 color
palette) different from the PC system colors, but most of the browsers have default palettes that are 
different from both (and from each other!).  Even when using defined "safe" colors--colors that are
<EM>suppose</EM> to be the same on both platforms--you can get into trouble.
<P>
The best thing to do is to put some Web pages up and then look at them on both a Mac and a PC.  If you have
access to different browsers, you might want to check them, too.
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR SIZE=2>
<A NAME="7"><H3>7.  An image is an image, but it may not save any words at all.</H3></A>
There are times to use images and icons and there are times not to use them.  Although there are literally 
thousands of free icons available for the taking on the Web, that doesn't mean you should.  Almost every
iconic button in use on the Web has words next to it explaining what it is.  Which is not to say that you
should <EM>never</EM> use decorative buttons, arrows, bullets, etc., but use them with care and ask yourself
first if the image is worth waiting for.  Sometimes it is and sometimes it isn't--it's a judgment call, and
one that often separates the good pages from the bad.
<P>
If you'e going to use images as buttons, remember to consider the user who's on a Lynx browser with a VT100
connection and can't see the pictures at all.  Can that user still navigate your page without them? 
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR SIZE=2>
<A NAME="8"><H3>8.  There is one thing you can do to make your image appear to
                    take less time to load than it really does.</H3></A>
If you know the size <EM>in pixels</EM> of your image and you add that information as an attribute in your
in-line image tag, the text will be  able to load more quickly because the browser will know how much space
it has to leave for each picture.  For example:
<P>
<CENTER><KBD><STRONG>&lt;IMG WIDTH=300 HIGHET=75 SRC="IMAGE.GIF"&gt;</STRONG></KBD></CENTER>
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR SIZE=2>
<A NAME="9"><H3>9.  You'll need <EM>good</EM> graphics software.</H3></A>
<UL>
<LI>You want software that will:
<P>
<UL>
	<LI>let you modify and correct digital images.
	<LI>let you create images from scratch.
</UL>
<P>
<LI>You should be able to:
<P>
<UL>
	<LI>type text in it.
	<LI>be able to save files in either GIF or JPEG formats.
	<LI>(Some software now have built-in programs for creating transparent images<BR>
	    and creating interlaced GIFs (the images that come up in several passes,<BR>
	    gradually getting sharper), though there is shareware available which will<BR>
	    do those conversions as well.
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
Any image you create online, copy from a Photo-CD, or scan in on a consumer-level scanner will benefit from
simple modification with good software.  An good does <EM>not</EM> mean the pait software that comes with
Windows.  Adobe Photoshop is excellent, but there are other software packages with similar functionality that
you can choose from.
<P>
Whatever package you choose, take the time to learn and use it.  There's nothing that will replace the 
experience, and there's no shortcut you can take to get there.  A person without art background but with
a good understanding of the software can make better graphics than someone who knows art but doesn't
know the digital brush from the digital pencil.
<P>
Good luck.                
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR SIZE=2>
<A NAME="10"><H3>10.  Get and read <EM>Designing Web Graphics</EM>.</H3></A>
One of the best books available on this topic is:
<P>
<DL>
<DT>Weinman, Lynda.
<DD><CITE><STRONG><A HREF="http://www.lynda.com/dwg/dwg.html">Designing Web Graphics II:  
           How to Prepare Images and Media for the Web</A>.</STRONG></CITE> New York, NY : New Riders, 1997.
</DL>
<P>
<EM>
<A HREF="#contents">Return to Contents</A></EM>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="graphics.html">Back to Learning About Graphics</A>
<P>
<A HREF="welcome.html">Main Menu</A></CENTER>
