<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Carleton College Library HTML and Web Site Resource: Business Home Page Quiz</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<hr size=7>
<CENTER><H1>Business Home Page Quiz</H1> 
<STRONG><EM>...to help you think about creating a Web site...</EM></STRONG>
...whether you're hiring an <A HREF="http://www.delivery.com/webb/">outside consultant</A>
or are doing the work yourself.</CENTER>
<P><hr size=3>
<P><STRONG>The quiz...
<A NAME="top"></A>
<OL>
<LI><A HREF="#logo">Do you have a logo appropriate for use online?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#does">Explain, in three sentences, what your organization does.</A>
<LI><A HREF="#whol">How will your web site fit with your business as a whole?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#cats">What categories of service/product does your organization provide?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#cust">Who are your customers?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#acts">What actions do you want the viewer to take?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#info">What information will you provide?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#links">How will the various pages at your site relate to each other?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#graphics">How will the graphics on your page relate to each other?</A>
</OL>

The commentary...
<P>
<A NAME="logo">1.  Do you have a logo appropriate for use online?</A></STRONG>

Web graphics need to be in .gif format.  If your logo is in electronic form, you
should be able to convert it.  If it's not, you'll probably want to scan and convert 
it.<p>
Most logos will work online.  If your logo includes very fine lines, be aware that it
may not have a strong online presence.  You may want to consider using a bold 
graphic that incorporates your logo on your web pages.<p>
Right now, online graphics do not adjust their size to fit the viewer's window.  
Most browsers use windows 70 to 80 characters wide.  Size your logo to fit in
that space, or viewers will only see part of it.<p>
<A HREF="#top"><i>To top</i></A>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="does">2.  Explain, in three sentences, what your organization does.</A></STRONG>

You may already have a brochure describing your organization.  Web text is easiest 
to read when it consists of headings and short paragraphs.  Long text descriptions 
are hard to read on a screen.  If you have a mission statement or short description
of your organization, put it near the top of your page.  Net surfers will be able to
tell at a glance whether they're interested in your site.<p>
<A HREF="#top"><i>To top</i></A>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="whol">3.  How will your web site fit with your business as a whole?</A></STRONG>

You already have marketing materials, business strategies, and strategic plans (even
if you don't call them by those names).  How will the look and content of your
Web site fit (or be different from) already existing materials and strategies?<p>
<A HREF="#top"><i>To top</i></A>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="cats">4.  What categories of service/product does your organization provide?</A></STRONG>

Thinking in categories will make it easier for you to decide what groups of pages
to include in your Web site.  The first/home page should tell people enough about
you to make the viewer want to know more (or help them decide they're not interested).<p>
From there, buttons or linked lists will take them to other pages.  
<UL>
<LI>What questions will people be asking about you?
<LI>What different kinds of things do you do?
<LI>Will different types of viewers be interested in different parts of your organization?
</UL><p>
Answering these questions will help you decide how to cluster your information.<p>
<A HREF="#top"><i>To top</i></A>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="cust">5.  Who are your customers?</A></STRONG>

Whose attention are you hoping to attract?  What kinds of tools will they have available
to them?  What resources are they hoping to find?<p>
If your viewers are unlikely to have audio or video software, it won't make sense
for you to include those media in your Web pages.<p>
<A HREF="#top"><i>To top</i></A>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="acts">6.  What actions do you want the viewer to take?<A></STRONG>
</A>
Will they send you e-mail?  Order a catalog?  Order from an online catalog?  
Register for a class?  Get on your mailing list?<p>
Keep in mind that most interactive activities involve extra work for the people
putting your Web site on the server and the people doing the maintenance of your
pages.  Activities like placing online orders involve <i>lots</i> of extra work
(and using a commercial server and a computer security expert).  Be sure
you have the resources to follow through.<p>
<A HREF="#top"><i>To top</i></A>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="info">7.  What information will you provide?</A></STRONG>

The internet is a wonderful world-wide reference source.  My personal bias is that
being a good Web citizen includes providing information useful for folks who may not get
personally involved with your organization.  (Hence this page!)<p>
<A HREF="#top"><i>To top</i></A>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="links">8.  How will the various pages at your site relate to each other?</A></STRONG>
Practically speaking, which pages need to be linked to which pages?  If you chose three or
four "top level" pages, which would they be?  (Drawing what I call an "architecture"--a
kind of tree of branching pages can be helpful.)
<P>
Aesthetically speaking, will one design carry throughout the pages or will each one have
a different layout?  When you've got them linked the way you want them, cruise from one
to another to see if you can tell at a glance what each one is about.<p>
<A HREF="#top"><i>To top</i></A>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="graphics">9.  How will the graphics on your page relate to each other?</A></STRONG>

If you plan to use buttons or in-line graphics, think about
how they relate to each other and to the other graphics (photos, logos) on your pages.
(Some logos contain a graphic that can be used as a background shape for button graphics.  
If you're designing an online logo, you may want to consider including such a graphic.)<p>
<A HREF="#top"><i>To top</i></A>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="fromhere.html">Back to Where to Go From Here</A>
