<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>How to Download Files
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<hr size=7>

<CENTER><H2>How to download files from the Web</H2></CENTER>

FTP means "File Transfer Protocol" and is used as both a noun ("that file 
is available by FTP...") and verb ("FTP that file to me").  It's the way
to download all sorts of goodies from the Web.<p>
Anonymous FTP means you log into an FTP server (using an <A HREF="#FTPP">FTP program</A>),
enter the username <i>anonymous</i>
and your e-mail address (the whole thing) as your password.<p>

<H3>Resources Available</H3>
There are three types of resouces available on the Web:<p>
<DL)<DT><STRONG>Public Domain</STRONG>
<DD>The author has created the resource and released it for
any and every use.  There's no limit on distribution or sale and it can
be modified by anyone.<p>
<DT><STRONG>Freeware</STRONG>
<DD>The author retains the copyright but allows you to use the resource
for free.  Usually, you can give it away, but can't sell it.<p>
<DT><STRONG>Shareware</STRONG>
<DD>The author retains copyright and allows you to use the resource on
a trial basis for a short evaluation period.  At the end of that period,
you either pay for the resource or destroy all copies.<p>
</DL>
<H4>In order to keep the Web as information-rich as it is, please pay
fees for the shareware software you use.</H4>
<HR>
<p>
<H3>How to identify downloadable files:</H3>
If, when you put your browser on a linked sentence or word, you see a file
that ends with .hqx, .sit, .cpt, .sea, .seg, .pit, .dd, .zip, .lzh, .arc, .z,
.tar, you're looking at a downloadable file.  Those filename extensions
stand for the compression program used.  FTP programs will automatically determine
which transfer mode to use, based on the extension.<p>

<H3>How to download files:</H3>
In some cases, the URL of the downloadable file will be created so that your 
browser (if you're using Netscape or Mosaic) <B>automatically downloads it</B>.
The browser will put the file into whatever directory you specified when you
set preferences.<p>
<A NAME="#FTPP"></A>
Sometimes you need an FTP program in order to transfer files.  You can't FTP to get
an FTP program unless you have the software!<p>
To get FTP software:
<UL>
<LI>buy one of the several books on the market that come with an FTP program on disk
<LI>talk to your friends and find someone who has a (non-commercial) program
to give to you on disk, or
<LI>contact a distributor directly.
</UL>
If you're going to download files, you will also want to install a virus checker
on your computer.  (If you don't have one already.)
<p>
<A NAME="FTPP"><h4>For Macintosh users:</H4>
<STRONG>Fetch</STRONG> (FTP program)<UL>
<LI>licensed free of charge for use in educational and non-profit organizations
<LI>$25 individual license for users in for-profit organizations
<BLOCKQUOTE>Software Sales<BR>
Dartmouth College<BR>
6028 Kiewit Computation Center<BR>
Hanover, NH 03755-3523<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</UL><p>

Install and configure Fetch according to instructions and then download the current version
of <A HREF="ftp://acns.nwu.edu/pub/disinfectant/">John Norstad's Disinfectant</A>.
<p>
<h4>For Windows users:</h4>

<STRONG>WS_FTP</STRONG> (FTP program)<UL>
<LI>Freeware (please enclose formatted disk and return postage with your request)
<BLOCKQUOTE>John A. Junod<BR>
267 Hillwood Street<BR>
Martinez, GA 30907<BR>
<ADDRESS><A HREF="mailto:junodj@css583.gordon.army.mil">junodj@css583.gordon.army.mil</A></ADDRESS>
</BLOCKQUOTE></UL>

Install and configure WS_FTP and then download <A HREF="ftp://dorm.rutgers.edu/pub/msdos/virus/wscan109.zip">
McAfee's VirusScan</A> (a $35 shareware package). <p>


<hr size=7>
