<html>
<head>
<Title>Full-text Periodicals</Title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOr="FFFFFF">

<center><H1>Introducing Project Muse:<br>
Full-Text Journals via the World Wide Web</H1></center>

In one of the first ventures of its kind, the Carleton College Library is 
participating in an initiative that enables worldwide networked access to the full 
text of selected scholarly journals.  Along with other members of the <A HREF=
"/obegroup/obe.html">Oberlin Group</A>, a loose affiliation of over sixty highly 
selective liberal arts college libraries, the Carleton Library is a <EM>charter 
member</EM> of this venture.
<P>
This experiment in scholarly communication, known as <strong>Project Muse</strong> 
(not to be confused with <A HREF="/muse/muse.html">Muse</A>, the Carleton Library's 
online catalog), is a product of the Johns Hopkins University Press.  Within the next 
three years, Project Muse will publish online more than forty of the Press's journals 
in the humanities, the social sciences, and mathematics. 

<P>
<CENTER><STRONG>
<A HREF="http://muse.jhu.edu/information.html">More Information about Project Muse</A><BR>
<P>
<A HREF="http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/index.html">Browse the Project Muse Online Journals</A><BR>
<P>
<A HREF="http://muse.jhu.edu/cgi-bin/wwwwais">Search all Project Muse Journals by Subject</A><BR>
<P>
<A HREF="http://muse.jhu.edu">Jump to the Project Muse Home Page</A>
</CENTER></STRONG>
<p>
<hr>
