<html>
<head>
<Title>The Muenster's Lair</Title>
</head>
</html>

<body background="swimpool.jpeg" text="#ffffa0" link="#00ff00" vlink="#ooffff" alink="#ff00ff">

<html>
<center><img src="muenster.jpeg" alt="The Muenster's Lair"></center>
</html>
<p><hr>
<center><a href="http://www.eff.org/blueribbon.html"><img src="rib_bar_wh.gif"></a></center>
<hr><p>
<b><i>Deep in highlands of Scotland lies Loch Ness.  And deep in the murky waters of Loch Ness
waits a remnant of prehistoric times, an ancient creature of the depths.  Rarely seen, and even more
rarely photographed, this beast inspires awe, wonder, and a sense of mystery in visitors to its watery home.<p>
<p>
Imagine the scene: the creature sits at the bottom of the loch, waiting for its prey.  It senses movement 
in the water above, leaps from its hiding place, and pounces on the hapless fish, which promptly eats it.<p><p>

<center>I am speaking, of course, of the Loch Ness Muenster.</center>
<p><p>
Often eclipsed by its larger and slightly better-known neighbor, the Loch Ness Muenster is, in this author's humble
opinion, much more of a mystery than Nessie.  Shown below are some of the striking photographs purporting to show "Cheesie," as 
the Muenster is familiarly known.</i></b>

<table>
<tr><td align=right>This photo, snapped by a tourist, clearly shows Cheesie in the foreground, basking on the
surface, which is thought to have been a common behaviour in prehistoric aquatic cheeses.</td><td><img src="mun2.jpeg"></td></tr>
<tr><td align=right><img src="mun3.jpeg"></td><td>Another photo, similar to the one above, showing the Muenster floating
near the surface of the lake.</td></tr>
<tr><td align=right>Perhaps the most startling photo of Cheesie, this underwater shot shows it locked in what appears to be mortal combat with a large
plesiosaur-like creature.</td><td><img src="mun1.jpeg"></td></tr></table>
<p><hr><p>
<b><i>Will the Muenster ever be captured?  Ever be photographed up close? Ever be... eaten?  Only time will tell.</b></i>
<p><p><p>
<a href="josh.html"><IMG SRC=LEFTARROW.JPEG ALIGN=CENTER> Back to the Home Page</a>
<hr noshade>
<address>Maintained by Joshua Mitchell: <a href="mailto:mitchelj@carleton.edu">mitchelj@carleton.edu</a>
</DOC>
