<BODY>
<CENTER><H2>CD ROMS from the National Climate Data Center
</H2>
Carleton College Government Documents Electronic Media List</CENTER>
<HR SIZE="6">

<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC75">GLOBAL
DAILY SUMMARY Temperature and Precipitation 1977-1991
</A></H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC76">C
55.281/2:977-91
</A></H4>
<P>
National Climate Data Center, 1994
<P>
Daily temperature and precipitation from thousands of stations around the
world. The provided software only allows the data to be downloaded. No
facilities for analysis are available.
<UL><LI>File format: Fox Pro 
<LI>Compatible: DOS 
<LI>Documentation: On Line Documentation 
</UL>

<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC81">NATIONAL
ENVIRONMENT WATCH
</A></H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC82">C
55.281/2-2:EN8/CD/proto
</A></H4>
<P>
National Climate Data Center, 1994
<P>
This publication summarizes some of the NOAA-sponsored research that has
relevance to societal issues. Short articles and graphics which address a
variety of environmental topics are presented. The articles are hyper linked,
meaning the reader can jump within and between articles that address specific
problems. Each article begins with an abstract of the research on which it is
based. The next part explains the relevance of the research to societal issues
of concern, i.e., why the research is important in benefitting mankind.
Additional sections describe the research in more detail, provide illustrations
of results, and give references to related scientific articles. Finally, names,
addresses and phone numbers are provided for more information about the
research.
<UL><LI>File format: Hyper text(windows help file) 
<LI>Compatible: Windows; Use Windows help file.
<LI>Documentation:
</UL><P>
<P>

<HR><H3>
<A NAME="GGUAS">GLOBAL GRIDDED UPPER AIR STATISTICS</A></H3>
<H4>C 55.281/2-2:G 51/980-91/CD</A></H4>
<P>
National Climate Data Center, 1995
<P>
The CD provides a versatileinterface enabling the user to select and contour 
a nearlyunlimited variety of climatological charts covering the global
upper air environment.  Although export of the gridded data is
possible from within the CD, users requiring massive data export
preferred access to the GGUAS data base directly.  This CD-ROM
product is intended to provide this access.

The GGUAS data set describes the atmosphere for each month of the
year represented on a 2.5 degree global grid at 15 standard
pressure levels.  Mean and standard deviation values were compiled
for sea level pressure, wind speed, air temperature, dew point,
height and density.  Eight-point wind roses were also compiled.

<UL><LI>File Format: ASCII
<LI>Compatible: DOS, UNIX
<LI>Documentation: ON DISK
</UL><P>
<P>


<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC79">RADIOSONDE
DATA OF NORTH AMERICA 1946-1993
</A></H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC80">C
55.281/2-2:R11/v.4/CD
</A></H4>
<P>
National Climate Data Center.(Oct. 1994)<P>
274-F  94-047-E
<UL><LI>File format: Unknown 
<LI>Compatible: Software for Dos, Unix, VMS availible by order 
<LI>Documentation: None 
</UL><P>




<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC77">US
DIVISIONAL AND STATION CLIMATIC DATA AND NORMALS
</A></H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC78">C
55.281/2-3:v.1/994
</A></H4>
National Climate Data Center<P>
Item:274-F-1  95-005-E
<P>
This CDROM contains a collection of ASCII data files and associated
documentation that pertains to U.S. climatic normals and byproducts of the
normals.  Climatic variables include temperature, precipitation, degree days,
and Palmer Drought Index.  The information is derived from the archive files at
NOAA's National Climatic Data Center.  The current normals period is 1961-90;
the earlier data are provided for comparison and research applications.
<UL>
<LI>File format:ASCII
<LI>Compatible: 
<LI>Documentation: On line Assistance and small manual 
</UL>





<HR><H3>
<A NAME="DAYSUM">Cooperative Summary of the Day
</A></H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="DAYSUM">C
55.281/2-4:993
</A></H4>
<P>
National Climatic Data Center, 1994
<P>
These CD-ROMs are a set containing ASCII data files and associated inventory and station history files for the Cooperative
Summary of the Day (Tape Deck 3200) data set.  The data set is a compiliation of daily observations from cooperative observers
in the United States, U.S. Caribbean Islands, U.S Pacific Islands, and Puerto Rico.  It includes air and soil temperatures, 
rainfall, snowfall, and evaporation elements.  The period of record varies among stations but falls with the period from the 
1850s through 1993. 
<UL><LI>File format: DOS ASCII
<LI>Compatible: DOS
<LI>Documentation:
</UL><P>

