<HEAD>

<TITLE>US Department of Education CD ROM Index</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2>
CD ROMS from the US Department of Education
</H2>
Carleton College Government Documents Electronic Media List</CENTER>
<HR SIZE="6">

<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC93">
SCHOOL AND STAFFING SURVEY 1987-88.
</A>
</H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC94">
ED 1.332:SC6.
</A>
</H4>
<P>
Department of Education, National Center for Education Statistics, 1992.
<P>
Data from a survey conducted by the National Center for Education Statistics to update information on teachers, 
school administrators, schools, and local education agencies.
<P>
The Teacher Survey provides data on teachers regarding education and training, teaching assignments, experience, 
certification, workload, perceptions and attitudes, job mobility and workplace conditions. The School Survey includes 
student characteristics, staffing patterns, student-teacher ratios, types of programs and services offered, length of 
school day and year, graduation and college application rates, and teacher turnover.
<P>
The School Administrator Survey provides information on the training, experience, professional background, and job
activities of school principals/headmasters. The Teacher Demand and Shortage Survey includes public local education
agencies (LEAs) and private schools, with information about enrollment, number of teachers, position vacancies, new
hires, teacher salaries and incentives, hiring and retention, etc.
<UL>
<LI>
File format: ISO 9660.
<LI>Compatible: PC.
<LI>Documentation: Technical Documentation Printed from Disc
<UL>
<LI>TECHNICAL DOCUMENTATION printed from disc
</UL>
</UL>



<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC95">
NATIONAL POST SECONDARY STUDENT AID STUDY 1986-87.
</A>
</H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC96">
ED 1.333:980-86/CD; 986-87/CD; 989-90/CD/table
</A>
</H4>
<P>
Department of Education, 1992.
<P>
Contains data collected in the 1986-87 school year on how students and their families pay for post-secondary 
education. Sources of the data included institutional records, a student survey, and a parent survey. The student
 sample was composed of full- and part-time students attending either public or private institutions providing less 
 than two-year and four-year programs. The CD-ROM includes a table generating system.
<UL>
<LI>File format: ISO 9660.
<LI>Compatible: PC.
<LI>Documentation: on disc.
</UL>

<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC97">
NATIONAL EDUCATION LONGITUDINAL STUDY of 1988
</A>
</H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC98">
ED 1.334/2:ED 8/994-2/CD
</A>
</H4>
<P>
This CD contains the NELS:88 Base-Year and First and Second Follow-Up data for the National Educational Study of 
1988. This is the first nationally representative longitudinal study of eighth grade students in publiuc and private 
schools. It is designed to provide longitudinal data about critical transitions experienced by young people as they 
develop, attend school, and embark on their careers.
<P>
The study was conducted in 1988 with some 25,000 eigth gradeers, their parents, teachers, and principals. Follow-up
 surveys were conducted in 1990, 1992 and 1994. This disc contains only the first two follow-ups.
<P>
<UL>
<LI>File format:SPSS files
<LI>Compatible: DOS.
<LI>
Paper Copy:
<LI>
Access by:ECB system included does allows access to weighted and unweighted frequenceys and precents for each 
variable. It also diplays the questions text for each variable. Statistical software such as SAS or SPSS can be used 
to do further analysis.
<LI>
Documentation:A WordPerfect manual and technical documentation for each part of the study is included, also in WP 
format. These electronic versions lack the many of the tables and charts included in the printed form. The 
documenation suggests that all users order the paper copies
</UL>

<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC99">
NATIONAL LONGITUDINAL STUDY OF THE HIGH SCHOOL CLASS OF 1972 (NLS&nbsp;72)
</A>
</H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC100">
ED 1.334/2:H53/CD
</A>
</H4>
<P>
Department of Education
<P>
This Compact Disc (CD) contains ALL available NLS-72 data and an electronic codebook system for using it. For more
information see the on-disc documentation.
<UL>
<LI>File format: ASCII
<LI>Compatible: PC.
<LI>Access by: All of the NLS-72 data may be extracted using the ECB software (with the exception of the \FICE data). 
The ECB will create fully labeled SPSS-PC and SAS-PC (&amp; SPSS for WINDOWS) program code for building extract files
on your fixed disc.
<LI>Documentation: on disc.
</UL>
<HR>


<H3>
<A NAME="HSB1992">
HIGH SCHOOL and BEYOND FOURTH FOLLOW-UP(Sophomore Cohort) HS&B:1992
</A>
</H3>
<H4>

ED 1.334/2:H53/2/CD

</H4>
<P>
Department of Education
<P>
This CD contains data from the High School and Beyond Longitudinal Study Fourth
Followup - HS&B:92 - in the form of a public release Data Analysis System (DAS). 
This DAS does not contain all variables collected as part of HS&B, but does
contain most of those which are of interest to analysts for descriptive purposes.
This CD also contains the original surveys from HS&B and the four follow up
studies for each cohort(sophmore Senior) it also contains the NLS-72 data for
comparison.

<UL>
<LI>
File format: Unknown
<LI>
Compatible: DOS; DAS system included.
<LI>Documentation: Readme file and DAS documentation on disc.
</UL>
<HR>


<H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC101">
EDUCATION STATISTICS ON DISK
</A>
</H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC102">
ED 1.334/2:ST2/CD
</A>
</H4>
<P>
National Center for Education Statistics (Aug. 1994)
<P>
EDsearch: Education Statistics on Disc is a computerized search and retrieval system designed to provide an easy way
to locate and display specific information contained in the wealth of statistical tables produced by the National 
Center for Education Statistics (NCES). This version of the program includes the complete contents (except as noted) 
of the following NCES publications:
<UL>
<LI>
1993 Digest of Education Statistics (412 tables, 34 figures, chapter introductions, and supporting materials);
<LI>
1993 Condition of Education (the text, tables, charts, and supplemental tables and notes for all 60 indicators,
 plus chapter introductions and supporting materials);
<LI>
1992 Condition of Education (the text, tables, charts, and supplemental tables and notes for 29 indicators not 
included in the 1993 edition);
<LI>
Projections of Education Statistics to 2004 (44 tables, 62 figures, chapter introductions, and technical appendixes);
<LI>
Historical Trends: State Education Facts 1969 to 1989 (41 tables, chapter introductions, and supporting charts and 
appendices; the state charts accompanying the tables are not available);
<LI>
120 Years of American Education: A Statistical Portrait (37 tables, 21 figures, chapter introductions, and supporting
 materials);
<LI>
Education in States and Nations: Indicators Comparing US. States with the OECD Countries in 1988 (the text, tables, 
and notes for 16 indicators; the figures accompanying the indicators are not available);
<LI>
1993 Youth Indicators (the tables and charts for all 63 indicators, and supporting text)
<LI>
Glossary and Guide to Sources (the Glossaries and Guides to Sources for the publications have been merged).
</UL>
<UL>
<LI>File format: Compressed files, tables can be downloaded in ASCII or Lotus 1-2-3 format. Graphics can be output 
in GIF, PCX, or PS Format
<LI>Compatible: DOS; Searching Software provided.
<LI>Documentation: On disc
<UL><LI>EDSEARCH USER MANUAL printed from disc
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR><H3>
<A NAME="SORCG">
1991 Survey of Recent College Graduates</A>
</H3>
<H4>
ED 1.334/2:SU7/CD
</A>
</H4>
<P>
Office of Eduactional Research and Improvement
<P>
This is the public release of the 1991 survey of college graduates. It contains such data as race, major, grade point averavge, number of languages, etc.
<UL>
<LI>
File format: dBase Files.
<LI>
Compatible:DOS; A electronic codebook program and extract are provided
<LI>
Documentation: None.
</UL>

<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC103">
VOCATIONAL EDUCATION ELECTRONIC TABLE LIBRARY
</A>
</H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC104">
ED 1.334/2:V85/Floppy
</A>
</H4>
<P>
National Center for Education Statistics
<P>
The Vocational Education Electronic Table Library (ETL) provides users with immediate access to a comprehensive 
set of more than 100 vocational education tables that have been published by the US. Department of Education over 
the last several years
<UL>
<LI>
File format: Self Extracting archive of files with access software
<LI>
Compatible: PC; Loaded on CD-ROM works Station Display and analyses software provided, also data can be downloaded 
in Excel or Lotus 1-2-3 format
<LI>
Documentation: Documentation printed from Disc
<UL>
<LI>USERS MANUAL printed from Disc
</UL>
<LI>Disk(s): 1 high density floppy
</UL>
.
<P>
<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC105">
PUBLIC LIBRARY DATA: 1991 and 1992
</A>
</H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC106">
ED 1.334/3:991;992 v.1-2
</A>
</H4>
<P>
National Center for Education Statistics
<P>
The Public Libraries Survey is conducted annually by the National Center for Education Statistics (NCES) through 
the Federal-State Cooperative System for Public Library Data (FSCS). The survey file includes 8,946 public libraries 
in the 50 states and the District of Columbia identified by the state library agencies. A total of 44 data items 
were collected for each library--33 basic data items and 11 library identification items. (The basic data items for 
multiple-outlet libraries are provided to NCES as aggregated data.) Included are the library's name, address, number 
of service outlets, number of full-time equivalent staff, operating income, operating expenditures, capital outlay, 
size of library collection, annual public service hours, attendance, number of reference transactions, total annual 
circulation transactions, number of interlibrary loans, circulation of children's materials, and children's program 
attendance. The survey also collected 12 data items on each public library outlet and state library agency outlet; 
11 identifying items on state library agencies, federations, systems, and cooperatives; and 4 data items on 
characteristics of the state data submission.

<UL>
<LI>File format: Self Extracting archive of ASCII files
<LI>Compatible: PC; No software provided
<LI>Documentation: Documentation printed from Disc
<UL><LI>1991 TECHNICAL DOCUMENTATION printed from disc
</UL>
<LI>Disk(s): 1 high density floppy
</UL>
<P>

<HR>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC107">INTEGRATED POST SECONDARY EDUCATION DATA SYSTEM 1990</A>
</H3>
<H4>

ED 1.334/4:990

</H4>
Office of Education Research and Improvement
<P>
The Integrated Post Secondary Education Data System is a system designed to collect data from primary providers 
(institutions) of post secondary education. It is a single, comprehensive data collection system developed to 
encompass all institutions and organizations that provide secondary education as their primary goal. The IPEDS 
system is built to collect institution-level data in such areas as enrollment, program completion, faculty and 
staff, and financing.
<P>
This disc contains an analysis file that includes variables extracted from the five IPEDS surveys. The data has been 
combined into a single file with each record on the file representing a single institution. The file does not 
contain all of the variables in each file; rather it contains those variables (nearly 5000) considered to be the 
most useful to the user community. This CD contains an ASCII file version of the analysis data file along with the 
individual data files and documentation for the following surveys: Institutional Characteristics (90/91), Fall 
Enrollment(90/91), Compilations(89/90), Finance(89/90), and Salaries and Tenure (90/91).
<UL>
<LI>
File format: ASCII
<LI>Compatible: DOS and Windows; Software on disc
<LI>Documentation: On-disc documentation
</UL>


<HR><H3>
<A NAME="RTFToC109">
NATIONAL HOUSEHOLD EDUCATION SURVEY
</A>
</H3>
<H4>
<A NAME="RTFToC110">
ED 1.334/5:991 &amp; 993
</A>
</H4>
<P>
US Department of Education
<P>
The National Household Education Survey (NHES) is an ongoing project of the National Center for Education Statistics.
The NHES use random digit dial (RDD) sampling and computer-assisted telephone interviewing (CATI) to conduct studies 
of important education issues. This disc contains four NHES components:
<P>
1991 Adult Education: Focuses on participation in a broad range of adult education activities by persons 16 and older.
Both an Adult file and a Course file are provided.
<P>
1991 Early Childhood Education: Focuses on child care, early childhood education programs, early school experiences, 
and home activities of children age 3 to age 8. Both a Preprimary file and a Primary file are provided.
<P>
1993 School Readiness: Focuses on the characteristics and experiences of children age 3 through age 7 or second grade.
<P>
1993 School Safety and Discipline: Focuses on school environment, discipline, and safety. The Parent file represents 
grades 3 through 12, and the Youth file represents grades 6 through 12. A combined file is also provided.
<P>
The software allows the user to:
<OL>
<LI>Search the names and labels of variables in the NHES:91 and NHES:93 databases (called catalogs) to select 
variables for analysis (see section on the Variable List Window, p. 13).
<LI>Examine the question wording, response categories, and frequencies of responses for variables you choose (see 
Viewing CodeBook Information for a Variable, p. 13).
<LI>Create a list of variables you want extracted from the catalog, save your list for later use, print your list, 
or use a predefined list (see the Tagged Variables Window, p. 17).
<LI>Write a SAS-PC or SPSS-PC program to extract selected variables from the whole dataset or for a subset of the 
cases you define (see Extracting Data, p. 21).
</OL>
<UL><LI>File format: ASCII
<LI>Compatible: PC; Software provided on disc.
<LI>Documentation: On-disc documentation
</UL>

