<H3><A NAME="RTFToC122"></A>HEALTH DATA ON OLDER AMERICANS, United States:
1992 </H3>
<H4><A NAME="RTFToC123"></A>HE 20.6209/4-4/:3/1 </H4>
Health and Human Services Department, National Center for Health Statistics,
<BR>
<BR>
This diskette contains 170 tables from &quot;Health Data on Older Americans,
United States: 1992&quot;. These tables are in Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet files.
The spreadsheets look like the printed tables. Another spreadsheet, AGEGUIDE.WK1,
contains a guide to the tables. 
<UL>
  <LI>File format: Self-Extracting Compressed Lotus 1-2-3 files 
  <LI>Compatible: DOS 
  <LI>Documentation: Printed from disk on disk 
  <UL>
    <LI>README FILE printed from disk in folder. 
  </UL>
</UL>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC124"></A>NATIONAL HOSPITAL AMBULATORY MEDICAL CARE SURVEY
</H3>
<H4><A NAME="RTFToC125"></A>1990--HE 20.6209/4-5:13/2/Corr. <BR>
1991--HE 20.6209/4-3:10/5/995<BR>
1992--HE 20.6209/4-5:13/5 </H4>
Health and Human Services Department, National Center for Health Statistics
<BR>
<BR>
These files comprise the data collected by the National Ambulatory Medical
Care Survey (NAMCS), conducted by the National Center for Health Statistics
(NCHS). The National Ambulatory Medical Care Survey provides data from samples
of patient records selected from a national sample of office-based physicians.
These national estimates describe the utilization of ambulatory medical
care services in the United States. 
<UL>
  <LI>File format: SETS 
  <LI>Compatible: DOS 
  <LI>Documentation: Complete on Line Documentation 
  <UL>
    <LI>Use Sets Manual 
  </UL>
</UL>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC126"></A>BIRTH COHORT LINKED BIRTH/INFANT DEATH DATA
SET </H3>
<H4><A NAME="RTFToC127"></A>HE 20.6209/4-7:20/1;20/2;20/3;20/4 </H4>
Item:500-E-7 95-005-E;95-012-E;95-014-E <BR>
<BR>
US Department of Health and Human Services <P8 THERE ARE CURRENTLY FOUR LINKED BIRTH="Infant" DEATH DATA SET CD="s:" ONE FOR 1985="1986,1987" AND 1988="each" 
CONTAINS THREE SEPARATE DATA FILES="<ul"> <LI>The first file includes linked
records of live births and infant deaths for the year's birth cohort --
also referred to as the numerator file. This file is comprised of deaths
to infants born in that year who died in that year or before their first
birthday. Infant death records were extracted from the the file year and
the following year's National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS) mortality
statistical files. This file includes linked records for births and deaths
that occurred in the United States to U.S. residents and to U.S. nonresidents.
Excluded are deaths that occurred outside the United States to infants born
in the U.S.; deaths that occurred in the United States to foreign-born infants;
and births and deaths that occurred outside the United States to U.S. residents.
<LI>The second file contains the live birth file for the file year, with
a few minor modifications (described in the introduction to the documentation)
-- referred to as the denominator-plus file. The files are offered as a
numerator/denominator data set to give users the means to compute infant
mortality rates. Linked birth records were extracted from a denominator
file that contained the file year's NCHS natality statistical file and a
small number of late-filed birth certificates. Refer to the Methodology
section for a more detailed explanation of records added to the statistical
file. The denominator file is not identical with the NCHS natality statistical
file. <LI>The third file contains information from the death certificate
for all infant death records which could not be linked to their corresponding
birth certificates -- referred to as the unlinked death file. </UL>
<UL>
  <LI>File format:SETS 
  <LI>Compatible: DOS 
  <LI>Documentation: On line Assistance and small manual 
</UL>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC128"></A>1990 NATIONAL DISCHARGE SURVEY </H3>
<H4><A NAME="RTFToC129"></A>HE 20.6209/7-2:13/1 </H4>
Health and Human Services Department, National Center for Health Statistics,
<BR>
<BR>
Contains more than 266,000 records collected from an annual survey of medical
and demographical information from a sample of hospital discharge records.
<UL>
  <LI>File format: SETS 
