<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>US Government Publications Depository</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="GPO.small.GIF">
<H2>US Government Publications</H2>

<A HREF="#intro">Introduction</A><BR>
<A HREF="#searching">Searching for Government Documents</A><BR>
<A HREF="#check_out">Check-Out Policy</A><BR>
<A HREF="#electronic_media">Electronic Media</A><BR>
<A HREF="#internet">Government Documents Resources on the Internet:
</A><BR></CENTER>
<HR>

<A NAME="intro"><H3>Introduction</H3></A>
Carleton College Library is a selective U.S. government publications library.  We
receive approximately 25% of the titles that come through the depository program.
In addition to offering many primary historical and Congressional resources,
current
titles provide statistical data, census data, environmental reports, and much
more.

<A NAME="searching"><H3>Searching for Government Documents</H3></A>
Government publications are not listed in <A HREF="../muse/muse.html">Muse</A> at present. 
A project is under way to add titles published since 1976 to the online catalog. 
General access is through the CD-ROM index<A HREF="http:/electronic/cd-rom/cd-rom.html#gpo"> Marcive's
GPO CAT/PAC</A>.  It is available on one of
the work stations in the Reference Room electronic area.  Titles held at Carleton
are listed by the Superintendent of Documents number in the Documents Shelf List
in the Documents microform area.  Periodical titles are also listed in the
Carleton List of Periodicals.
<A NAME="check_out"><H3>Check-Out Policy</H3>
</A>Government publications may be checked out unless they are published before
1910
or have a notation that they can not leave the library.
<A NAME="electronic_media"><H3>Electronic Media</H3></A>
Many publications arrive on <A HREF="list/THELIST.html">CD-ROM or
discs</A>.  The government documents work station is dedicated to these titles. 
Magazine 6 offers access to NTDB/The National Trade Data Bank, NESE/National
Economic, Social & Environmental Data Base, the 1993 Statistical Abstract, and
U.S. Foreign Relations.  There are 5 additional magazines with titles loaded and
ready to use.  If you need to use one of these, ask at the <A HREF="../reference/infodesk.html">General Information &amp; Referral
Desk</A> for assistance.  Other titles are kept in the CD-ROM cabinet.  See the
Documents Librarian, Carolyn Sanford, to use these cd's.
<P>
<A NAME="internet"><H3>Government Documents Resources on the Internet:</H3></A>
A wide variety of information about the <A HREF="bookmarks.html">Federal
Government</A> is available on the Internet.  The Government itself maintains
several sites, including a virtual tour of the White House.  Many servers also
have searchable archives of Government related information.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
