<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
HRAF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<H2>Human Relations Area Files (HRAF)</H2>
</CENTER>

The <STRONG>Human Relations Area Files</STRONG>, commonly known as <STRONG>HRAF</STRONG>, is special collection of 
articles and essays on the cultures of the world.  This unique organization by culture and by subject
allows cross-cultural research, especially useful for students in the social sciences and humanities.
About 360 cultural groups exist in the Files now, with a few added every year.  Much of the field 
research was conducted during the first half of the 20th century. Carleton, one of two libraries in 
Minnesota that subscribes to HRAF, makes this microfiche collection available in the Microforms Room
in the Gould Library.  There are three volumes which serve as guides and are shelved near the microfiche:
<STRONG>Outline of World Cultures</STRONG>, <STRONG>Outline of Cultural Materials</STRONG>, and 
<STRONG>HRAF Source Bibliography</STRONG>.
<P>
Recently, HRAF began producing data on a CD-ROM, known as <A HREF="cd-rom.html #ehraf">E-HRAF</A>.  
The Gould Library has this resource mounted on a CD-ROM workstations. The first CD includes fifteen cultures
with a commitment to yearly expansions of fifteen additional cultures.  The first 60-culture sample to be converted
is known as the <STRONG>Probability Sample File</STRONG>, which is composed of groups that have been the subject of
long and in-depth study.  Included with this group will be two or three North American ethnic cultures not already
covered in the microfiche collection.  The database also contains photographs, drawings, illustrations, charts,
graphs, and other data.
<P>
Images from E-HRAF Screen Display:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="ehraffiles.gif">List of Cultures on E-HRAF</A>
<LI><A HREF="ehraffulltext.gif">Example of E-HRAF Full Text Document</A> 
<LI><A HREF="ehrafsearch.gif">Sample Search for Topic in the <CITE>Outline of Cultural Materials</CITE></A>
</UL>
<P>
For more information or <A HREF="/instruction/index.html">an instruction session</A>, 
see a <A HREF="/staff/pro_staff.html">librarian</A>.
</UL>
<P>
<hr>
