<html>
<head>
<TITLE>What is the Oberlin Group?</TITLE>
</head>
<body BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H2>What's the Oberlin Group?</H2></CENTER>
<P>
The Oberlin Group is an affiliation of library directors from over sixty highly-competitive 
liberal arts colleges in the United States.  This affiliation was nurtured by 
<A HREF="moffett.html">Bill Moffett</A>, former library director at Oberlin College in 
Oberlin, Ohio, hence the name of the group.  Mr. Moffett believed it would be benefitial 
for library directors at these various institutions to share common interests and concerns 
in order to better fulfill their missions.
<P>
The first meeting of Oberlin Directors took place at Oberlin College in 1986.
<P>
<CENTER><H2>Why Maintain an Oberlin Group Web Site?</H2></CENTER>
<P>
Since the Web is rapidly becoming the basis for the prototype "virtual library," 
it seemed natural that the Oberlin Group begin staking its own claim in cyberspace.   
For the time being, consider this resource as a mechanism whereby member libraries may 
share their accomplishments and ideas about using the Web for liberal arts library uses.
<P>
The Oberlin Group Home Page was initially developed in celebration of the 1994 Oberlin Group 
Conference held in Minnesota.  That conference was sponsored by the five Minnesota Oberlin 
Group members:
<P>
<STRONG>
<DL>
<DD><A HREF="http://www.library.carleton.edu/index.html">Carleton College</A>, Northfield
<DD><A HREF="http://www.gac.edu/Academics/Resources/Library/">Gustavus Adolphus College</A>, St. Peter

<DD><A HREF="http://www.macalstr.edu/~library/">Macalester College</A>, St. Paul

<DD><A HREF="http://www.csbsju.edu/library/">St. John's University</A>, Collegeville

<DD><A HREF="http://www.stolaf.edu/library/">St. Olaf College</A>, Northfield
</DL>
</STRONG>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="obe.html">Return to the Oberlin Group Home Page</A></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<CITE>
Maintained by <A HREF="/staff/terry/terry.html">Terry Metz, temetz@carleton.edu</A>
<BR> Last updated: October 3, 1996
</CITE>
</BODY>

